insert  into `rs_key_concepts_27062015`(`kc_id`,`topic_id`,`kc_text`) values (1,1,'&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Averages&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The term Average refers to the sum of all observations divided by the total number of observations. Average is used quite regular in our day to day life. For example to calculate the average marks of the students, Average height of a particular group etc. The term average is also referred to as &amp;lsquo;Mean&amp;rsquo;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Basic formula to calculate the average is &lt;em&gt;Average =&amp;nbsp;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Notes/Averages/11.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;52&quot; height=&quot;42&quot; /&gt;&lt;/em&gt; &amp;nbsp;where &amp;nbsp;denotes the &amp;nbsp;term of the series.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Examples&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1. Find the average of the series 8, 9, 12, 13&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Average is equal to &lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq2&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/D0C1BBD7-0510-C00B-5914-2689B5455DA0.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Different cases for problems&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Case 1:&lt;/strong&gt; if the terms of the series are in &lt;strong&gt;AP&lt;/strong&gt; and the number of terms is:&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;odd, then the &lt;strong&gt;middle value&lt;/strong&gt; is the mean of the series.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;even, then the &lt;strong&gt;mean of the two middle values&lt;/strong&gt; is the mean.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Example&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;2. The average of seven consecutive numbers is 15. Find the highest number.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Since the terms are in AP, the middle most number or the 4&lt;sup&gt;th&lt;/sup&gt; number is the mean.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the highest number will be 15 + 3 = 18.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Case 2:&lt;/strong&gt; if all the terms of series are added/subtracted a constant k, then the new mean of the series is the old mean added/subtracted by a constant k.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Example&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;3. The average marks for all the students in a class in Mathematics is 55&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;. Later, 5 grace marks are added to every student. What will be the new average?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Since the marks of each and every student increased by 5, the average also will increase by 5. The new average will be 55 + 5 = 60 marks.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Case 3: Weighted average&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If there are two groupseach consisting of &lt;em&gt;a&lt;/em&gt;&amp;nbsp; and &lt;em&gt;b&lt;/em&gt; elements respectively and if the means of the two groups is &lt;em&gt;x&lt;/em&gt; and &lt;em&gt;y&lt;/em&gt; respectively, then the average of the total groups is &lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq3&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/72D769A3-1AFB-D87E-213E-00DE64C17EE2.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Examples&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;4. There are 2 sections in tenth class in a school. Section A has 40 students and Section B has 30 students. The average marks in Mathematics is 45&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt; for section A and&amp;nbsp; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;80 for section B. Calculate the average marks in Mathematics for Class 10 students in the school.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total marks for Section A is 45 x 40 = 1800.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total marks for Section B is 80 x 30 = 2400.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total marks for the entire class is 1800 + 2400 = 4200.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total number of students in the class is 40 + 30 = 70.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Average for the entire class is &lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq4&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/FBE68765-995E-27C1-6F46-283B28690CD3.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;5. A group of 10 persons whose average age is 15 years come to a picnic. Another group of 20 persons with average age 30 also come to the picnic. Calculate the average of all the persons who have come to picnic.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total age of the first group is 15 x 10 = 150.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total age of the second group is 20 x 30 = 600.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total age for both the groups is 150 + 600 = 750.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total number of persons is 10 + 20 = 30.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Average age for the entire group is&amp;nbsp; &lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq5&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/D4EB439B-7923-4A32-40E7-CC4CCC5572C7.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Case 4:&lt;/strong&gt; If one of the values&amp;nbsp;&lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq7&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/B36671F9-F94F-D1E4-BAE8-2C9F35FDBA2E.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt; in the group is replaced with a new value &lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq8&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/2E94BED9-6FFF-ADC9-A85E-BF7D833E77F2.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;, then the change in the average is &lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq9&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/080EF694-2BB5-991C-2BBC-C75661CED194.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;, where n is the number of elements in the group.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Case 5:&lt;/strong&gt; If the average of a group of n elements is x. A new element is added and the group average becomes y. Then the value of the new element is k = y + n(y-x).&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Examples&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;6. The average age of a jury of 5 is 40. If a member aged 35 resigns and a man aged 25 becomes a member, then find the average age of the new jury.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total change in the age is 25 - 35 = - 10 years difference.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Number of members remain the same.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the new average is 40 +&amp;nbsp;&lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq10&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/BCEDD4B8-B4D3-7070-BF62-13F4714B3E55.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;= 38 years.&lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq1&quot; src=&quot;../../assets/images/DA582F8C-0E7C-523C-EF1D-ACB73379AAE6.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;7. The mean of 50 numbers is 30. Later it was discovered that two entries were wrongly entered as 82 and 13 instead of 28 and 31. Find the correct mean.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Number of entries remain the same. Change in the total value is (28 - 82) + (31 - 13) = -36.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the new average is &lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq13&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/E98AC932-B8AA-916C-7A14-0B69F736F6FC.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt; marks.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;8. The average of 6 observations is 45.5. If one new observation is added to the previous observation, then the new average becomes 47. Find the new observation.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Here x = 45.5, y = 47, n = 6.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the new observation is y + n(y-x) = 47 + 6(47-45.5) = 56.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;9. The average of the first 100 positive integers is&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The numbers are in AP and the number of terms is even. The middle terms are 50 and 51.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the mean required is&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq12&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/11BE444D-AB63-3796-1BC5-51E748361F60.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt; .&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;10. The average of the runs made by Raju, Sam and Harry is 4 less than that made by Sam, Harry and Kishore. If the number of Kishore&#039;s runs is 35, what is the number of runs scored by Raju?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Sam and Harris are common in both the groups. The total runs made by the first group 4 x 3 = 12 is&amp;nbsp;less than the second group. So, we can say that Kishore made 12 runs more than Raju.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, number of runs scored by Raju is 35 - 12 = 23.&lt;/p&gt;'),(2,2,'&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Speed, Distance and Time&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Distance travelled is always equal to the product of the time taken and the average speed.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The speed is expressed in either &lt;em&gt;m/s&lt;/em&gt; or &lt;em&gt;km/hr&lt;/em&gt;. The usage of the correct units is very important.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Conversions form &lt;em&gt;m/s&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;to &lt;em&gt;m/s&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;and vice versa&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq1&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/70FB76E4-F2B8-E616-7C18-BEE189BFCDE0.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq2&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/BFC50BD5-3331-CAF3-2044-93AC7DE04FE5.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Average speed concept&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The general formula to calculate the average speed is &lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq4&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/5A1CEFDB-E152-3954-C7B2-BEB0C1309533.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If a journey can be broken down to two different steps, then the average speed, if d&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; and d&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;&amp;nbsp; are the two distances and t&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; and t&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; are the time periods, is given by &lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq5&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/0A006FE6-8542-5193-81D7-6AB7ECCB10A5.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Case 1:&lt;/strong&gt; if d&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; = d&lt;sub&gt;2 &lt;/sub&gt;= d and the average speed for the two parts of the journey are v&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; and v&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;&amp;nbsp; respectively. Then&amp;nbsp;&lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq6&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/A877710B-D255-6C94-48CF-35CD0EBF88C6.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt; and &lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq7&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/1867DEF7-74BD-3BDD-A1A7-C86ED64A6E76.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;. So, &lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq9&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/64CB5DEC-FD94-5109-A1D7-C0A7CE940FFE.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Case 2:&lt;/strong&gt; if t&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; = t&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; = t and the average speed for the two parts of the journey are v&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; and v&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; respectively. Then d&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; = v&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt;t and d&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; = v&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;t. So, &lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq10&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/9AB973E4-FD58-BFA2-DA5C-A5DA1BF64065.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Examples&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1. &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A motor cyclist travels for 6 hours, the first half at 30 km/hr. and the other half at 50 km/hr. Find the distance travelled.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Here the time taken for each part is the same.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, average velocity is &lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq11&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/AB0C4F8E-835C-6106-8DE3-108794659061.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total time taken is 6 hours.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total distance is 40 x 60 = 240 Km.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;2. &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A car runs at the rate of 40 km/hr. during the first 20 km and 60 km/hr. during the second 20 km. The average speed of the car in km/hr. is&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Here the distance is same. So average speed is&amp;nbsp;&lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq12&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/3D4249E9-D643-A3AB-8CDD-E3551AD8677D.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;3. &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A man walks a certain distance at 8 km/hr. and returns at 6 km/hr. If the total time taken by him is 7 hours &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;, find the total distance walked. &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Here the distance is same. So average speed is &lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq13&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/A53165C5-38A3-3BDC-1518-B5B4F109EA88.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Time taken is 7 hours.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the total distance walked is &lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq14&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/DB34BA90-56D2-7F9F-56E8-0961B2BFFE78.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;4. If a man reduces his speed to &lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq15&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/91AD1C65-4C4F-8420-DD56-AF88EF62DF40.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;of the normal speed&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;, he takes 1 hour more to walk a certain distance. Find the time (in hours) taken to cover the distance with his normal speed.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The difference in the two times is 1 hour.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, &lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq16&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/88C55161-F6FB-475A-8E1D-159F9DDD6B8B.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, he normally takes 4 hours to travel the distance.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;5. A walks at 6 km an hour, and 4 hours after his start, B bicycles after him at 12 km an hour. Find out how far from the start does B catch up with A.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Let B overtake A after a time of x hours.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, A is travelling for (x + 4) hours and both have travelled the same distance.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, 12x = 6(x + 4) =&amp;gt; 6x = 24 =&amp;gt; x = 4 hours&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the distance that is to be travelled is 4 &amp;times; 12 = 48 Km.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;6. A student walks from his house at the speed of 4 km/hr. and thus reaches the school 10 minutes late. If his speed had been 5 km/hr. he would have reached 10 minutes earlier. Find the distance of the school from his house.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The difference in the two times is 20 minutes or 1/3 hours.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So,&amp;nbsp;&lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq17&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/2C899CBB-DE41-02B3-F35A-6B506C824FD6.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt; .&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Problems on Trains&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;Distance to be covered by a train to cross a man is equal to the length of the train.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;Distance to be covered by a train to cross the bridge is the sum of lengths of the train and the bridge.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;Distance to be covered by a train to cross a pole is equal to the length of the train.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;Distance to be covered by a train to cross another train is the sum of lengths of the two trains.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;If two trains or two bodies are moving in the same direction at &lt;em&gt;u Kmph&lt;/em&gt;&amp;nbsp; and &lt;em&gt;v Kmph&lt;/em&gt; such that &lt;em&gt;u&lt;/em&gt; &amp;gt; &lt;em&gt;v&lt;/em&gt;, then their relative speed is &lt;em&gt;(u - v) Kmph&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;If two trains or two bodies are moving in opposite directions at &lt;em&gt;u Kmph&lt;/em&gt;&amp;nbsp;and &lt;em&gt;v Kmph&lt;/em&gt;&amp;nbsp;such that &lt;em&gt;u&lt;/em&gt; &amp;gt; &lt;em&gt;v&lt;/em&gt;, then their relative speed is &lt;em&gt;(u + v) Kmph&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;If two trains or two bodies are moving in the same direction at &lt;em&gt;u Kmph&lt;/em&gt;&amp;nbsp;and &lt;em&gt;v Kmph&lt;/em&gt;&amp;nbsp;such that &lt;em&gt;u&lt;/em&gt; &amp;gt; &lt;em&gt;v&lt;/em&gt; , then the time taken to cross each other is &lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq18&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/E50B695D-EEF1-5F31-FD75-AB5A215D2831.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;hours where &lt;em&gt;x&lt;/em&gt; and &lt;em&gt;y&lt;/em&gt; are the lengths of the trains in &lt;em&gt;Km&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;If two trains or two bodies are moving in opposite directions at&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;u Kmph&lt;/em&gt;&amp;nbsp;and &lt;em&gt;v Kmph&lt;/em&gt;&amp;nbsp;such that &lt;em&gt;u&lt;/em&gt; &amp;gt; &lt;em&gt;v&lt;/em&gt; , then the time taken to cross each other is &lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq19&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/242BB06D-E106-5FA7-F688-84DC86FAACF7.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;hours where &lt;em&gt;x&lt;/em&gt; and &lt;em&gt;y&lt;/em&gt; are the lengths of the trains in &lt;em&gt;Km&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;Two trains start at the same time from two points &lt;em&gt;A&lt;/em&gt; and &lt;em&gt;B&lt;/em&gt; towards each other and after crossing they take &lt;em&gt;a&lt;/em&gt; hours and &lt;em&gt;b&lt;/em&gt; hours in reaching &lt;em&gt;B&lt;/em&gt; and &lt;em&gt;A&lt;/em&gt; respectively. Then, the ratio of the speeds in the same order is &lt;em&gt;&amp;radic;b&lt;/em&gt; : &lt;em&gt;&amp;radic;a&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Examples&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1. &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;How long will it take for a train 200 m long running at 50 km/hr. to cross a bridge 100 metres long?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Distance to be covered to cross the bridge is the sum of lengths of the train and the bridge.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Speed is&amp;nbsp;&lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq20&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/9B6DD20A-5D3C-4ABC-FA47-6F7C1C615A4F.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt; and the distance is 100 + 200 = 300m.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, time taken will be&amp;nbsp;&lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq21&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/84B0BD7F-BA87-A908-CD40-5CFE40FCDE6C.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt; .&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;2. &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A train running at 40 m/s takes 30 seconds to cross a platform of 800m long. Find the length of the train in metres.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Distance to be covered to cross the platform is the sum of lengths of the train and the platform.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Let the length of the train be L meters . Speed is 40 m/s. Distance is (800 + L) m.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Time taken will be&amp;nbsp;&lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq22&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/D9051518-558D-C457-595B-B725C5D85E8A.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt; .&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the length of the train is 400 m.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;3. &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A person standing on a platform of length 300 metres observed that a train takes 10 seconds to pass him, and pass completely through the platform in 30 seconds. find the length of the train.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Distance to be covered to cross the man is the lengths of the train.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Distance to be covered to cross the platform is the sum of lengths of the train and the platform.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Let the length of the train be L and its speed be V. It crosses the man in 10 seconds. So, L = 10V&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;It crosses the 300 m platform in 30 seconds. So, L + 300 = 30V&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, 20V = 300 =&amp;gt; V = 15 m/s .&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Length of the train is L = 10V = 150 m.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;4. &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A train running at uniform speed takes 60 seconds to pass a platform of 500 m long and 40 seconds to pass another platform of 300 m long. Find the length of the train in metres.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Distance to be covered to cross the platform is the sum of lengths of the train and the platform.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Let the length of the train be L and its speed be V.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, for the first platform, L + 500 = 60V and for the second platform, L + 300 = 40V .&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Subtracting the second eqn. from the first, we get&amp;nbsp; 20V = 500 - 300 = 200 =&amp;gt; V = 10 m/s.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Substituting it we get L = 60V - 500 = 600 - 500 = 100 m.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;5. &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A train 240 metres long, takes 24 seconds to cross a man running at 18 km/hr in the same direction as the train. Find the speed of the train.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Distance to be covered to cross the man is the lengths of the train.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Since both are moving in same directions, relative velocity of the train will be u - v.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;v = 18 x (5/18) m/s = 5 m/s.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Distance to be covered will be 240 m. Time taken is 24 seconds.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, speed is u - 5 = (240/24) = 10 =&amp;gt; u = 10 + 5 = 15 m/s.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Boats and Streams&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;In water, the direction along the stream is called downstream and the direction against the stream is called upstream.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;If speed of a boat in still water is u Kmph and the speed of the stream is v Kmph , then the speed downstream is (u + v) Kmph and speed upstream is (u - v) Kmph.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;If the speed downstream is a Kmph and the speed upstream is b Kmph, then speed in still water is (a + b)/2 and the rate of stream is (a - b)/2 .&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Examples&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1. &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A person can row downstream at 10 Kmph&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt; and upstream at 8 Kmph &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;. Then, find the person&amp;rsquo;s rate in still water.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If the speed of upstream is u and that of downstream is v, then the speed of the boat in still water is (u + v)/2. So, speed required is (10 + 8)/2 = 9 Kmph.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;2. &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;If a person&#039;s rate down the current is 16 km/hr. and the rate of the current is 2 km/hr., then find the person&#039;s rate against the current (in km/hr.).&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Let the velocity of the boat is u kmph and that of the stream is v = 2 kmph.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Speed downstream is u + 2 = 16 =&amp;gt; u = 14 kmph.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Speed upstream is u - 2 = 14 - 2 = 12 kmph.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;3. If a person can row upstream 14 km/hr. and downstream at 20 km/hr., then find the rate of the current. &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If the speed of upstream is u and that of downstream is v, then the rate of current is (v-u)/2.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, speed required is (20 - 14)/2 = 3 Kmph .&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;4. The speed of a boat in still water is 10 Kmph&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt; and the rate of the current is 2 Kmph&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;. Find the distance travelled downstream in 15 minutes.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The velocity of the boat is 10 Kmph and that of the stream is v = 2 Kmph.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Speed downstream is 10 + 2 = 12 Kmph.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Distance travelled in 15 minutes is 12 &amp;times; (15/60) = 3 Km.&lt;/p&gt;'),(3,3,'&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Time and work&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;In these problems, we always treat the whole work to be done as 1 and use the fractions to indicate the percentage of work done. So, if there is 50% of the work to be completed, we simply say that the work to be completed is 1/2.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Different cases for problems&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;If A takes x days to do a work, then it means that he does 1/x of the work each day.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;If A takes x days to complete a work and B takes y days to do the same work, then the number of days that &lt;strong&gt;A and B together take to complete is &lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq1&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/E060A629-86C9-5D30-CE1F-F9F44291B75A.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;days&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Proof:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Work done by both in a day is &lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq2&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/C09DDC85-F5EC-D992-992D-EBA5AB259684.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;. Total work to be done is 1. So, time taken is &lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq3&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/9C2E8309-4E68-3CE1-0EEB-912067F8C988.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;days.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;If A alone can do a work in x days and A and B together do it in y days, then the number of days taken by B to complete the work alone is &lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq4&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/1592FF46-69DC-EEA4-2881-7EE8C2015AF3.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;days.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Proof:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Work done by both in a day is &lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq5&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/EC4EDE15-C5BB-C154-C667-44CEBFC8F035.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;. Of this A does &lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq6&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/F2A90391-7316-30F6-BA87-73551A452C1B.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;of the work. So, work done by B in a day is &lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq7&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/CC35712A-1C53-1036-02D5-9D26BE337135.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;. So, he takes &amp;nbsp;days to complete the work alone.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;If A takes x days to complete a work, B takes y days&amp;nbsp; and C takes z days to do the same work, then the number of days that &lt;strong&gt;A, B and C together take to complete is &lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq8&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/060CF7EB-5841-DA98-D472-997D55326876.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;days&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;Number of men working on a project and the time taken to complete the project are inversely proportional to each other.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Examples&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1. &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Ramesh alone does a piece of work in 10 days and Suresh does it in 15 days. In how many days will the two do it together?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Work done by Ramesh in a day is 1/10 and the work done by Suresh in a day is 1/15.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If both work together, work done in a day will be &lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq9&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/D2679406-6073-C27F-48CF-6D6CE747BA4C.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, number of days required to complete the work is &lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq10&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/74C79E19-D74C-7015-6EAB-8B084A54427D.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;days.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;2. X and Y can finish a work in 24 days while X can do the same work in 36 days. In how many days can Y alone finish the same work?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Work done by X in a day is 1/36 . Let work done by Y in a day be 1/x.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Both worked and completed the job in 24 days. So, they completed 1/24 of the work in one day.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, &lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq11&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/F2F59B71-C649-42A2-97D4-4DF6E5A57D3A.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, Y can complete it alone in &lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq12&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/85CE1CD1-F3BB-9BEE-DE34-F7B1D6BF3F62.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;days.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;3. A can do a work in 20 days, B in 30 days and C in 40 days. How long will they take to do the work if they work together?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Work done by A in a day is 1/20.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Work done by B in a day is 1/30.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Work done by C in a day is 1/40.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If the three work together, work done in a day will be &lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq13&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/42371C0A-FEC6-1AE7-AD89-95D884DED8F6.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, number of days required to complete the work is &lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq15&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/C5F0D349-EF18-AE15-EADE-76AF848DBD23.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;days.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;4. If A, B and C together can finish a piece of work in 6 days, A alone in 18 days and B in 27 days, then C alone can do it in&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Work done by A in a day is 1/18, Work done by B in a day is 1/27. Let the work done by C in a day be 1/x.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If the three work together, work will be completed in 6 days. So, the amount of work done in a day is equal to 1/6. So, .&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, number of days required for C to complete the work alone is 13.5 days.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;5. &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Some persons can do a piece of work in 40 days. Two times the number of those persons will do half of that work in how many days?&lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq16&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/473CFE84-D683-676C-5709-852FA7D013A9.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Those persons can do half the work in 40/2 = 20 days.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If the number of persons is doubled, the time taken will be halved.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the number of days required is 20/2 = 10 days.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;6. &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;4 men can do a work in 12 days. After 2 days, 4 more men joined them. How many days will they take to complete the remaining work?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Work done by 4 men in one day is 1/12 . So, work done by a man in a day is 1/48.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;For two days, there are 4 men and from then, for the next x days, there are 8 men until the work is completed. So total work done is &lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq17&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/68B032EE-4DBB-71C0-9967-AE48BB8CC878.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, 5 days are required.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;7. &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A can do a piece of work in 15 days and B can do the same work in 10 days. They work together for 3 days and then A leaves. B will finish the remaining work in how many days?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Work done by A in one day is 1/15.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Work done by B in one day is 1/10.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If both work together, work done in 3 day is 3(A + B) = 3/6 = 1/2.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Work remaining that is to be completed by B is 1 - 1/2 = 1/2 .&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, number of days B will work alone is &lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq18&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/C0273045-52EE-097B-0B9A-EA968E1D05D1.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;days.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;8. &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;An army of 1000 men had enough food to last for 30 days. After 6 days 200 more men joined them. How long did the food last then?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Just before 200 men joined, the food remaining is enough for 1000 men for 24 days.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If there is single man, it would last for (1000 x 24) days, but there are 1200 men right now.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the food will last for &lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq19&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/6C0B4105-D7BD-6F5B-A78B-651D648CEDBE.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;days.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;9. A certain job was assigned to a group of men to do in 40 days. But 18 men did not turn up for the job and the remaining men did the job in 58 days. Find the original number of men in the group.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Let the initial number of men be x.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, x men complete the work in 40 days and (x-18) men do the work in 58 days.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Since no. of persons is inversely proportional to the time taken to get the work done,&amp;nbsp;&lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq20&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/AFD3DD46-DACE-2EC3-4216-F5F80A10B472.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Pipes and Cisterns&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Problems involving pipes and cisterns are solved in the same way as time and work problems but there is one important exception. There are inlet pipes and outlet pipes. Inlet pipes fill a tank and outlet pipes empty it. &lt;strong&gt;Inlet pipes do positive work and outlet pipes do negative work.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Different cases for problems&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;If pipe A takes x hours to fill a tank and pipe B takes y hours to fill a tank, then the number of hours that &lt;strong&gt;A and B working together take to fill the tank is &lt;strong&gt;&lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq1&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/E060A629-86C9-5D30-CE1F-F9F44291B75A.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;hours&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;If pipe A takes x hours to fill a tank and pipe B takes y hours to empty a completely filled tank, then the number of hours that &lt;strong&gt;A and B working together take to fill the tank is &lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq21&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/E35AEC2C-D366-B862-4847-B276E5B478AA.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;hours&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;If pipe A takes x hours to fill a tank, pipe B takes y hours to fill a tank&amp;nbsp; and pipe C takes z hours to empty a completely filled tank, then the number of hours that A, B and C together take to completely fill the tank is &lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq22&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/FCE89767-DFF1-DD10-FB81-97EEB143601E.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;hours.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Examples&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1. Two pipes can fill a tank in 15 hours and 30 hours respectively. In how much time will they fill the tank when opened together?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Work done by A in one hour is 1/15. The work done by C in one hour is 1/30.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If A, B are working together, then the work done in one hour is A + B = 3/30 = 1/30.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the time required is &lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq23&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/2AA70173-4F4C-7451-DB35-033D92527CBB.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;hours.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;2. A tap can fill a tank in 10 hours and another can empty it in 20 hours. If both the taps are opened simultaneously, find the time (in hours) taken to fill the tank.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Work done by A in one hour is 1/10. The work done by C in one hour is -1/20. (negative because it empties the tank).&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If A, B are working together, then the work done in one hour is A + B = 1/20.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the time required is &lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq24&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/F7554816-113B-2291-2B3C-71EAFE18CF6C.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;hours.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;3. A cistern can be filled by a pipe in 30 hours. But due to a leak in the bottom the cistern is just full in 40 hours. When the cistern is full, the leak can empty it in how many hours?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Work done by A in one hour is 1/30 . Let the work done by B in one hour be - 1/x . (negative because it empties the tank).&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Given that A and B are working together, work done in one hour is A + B = 1/30 - 1/x&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;It is given that A + B = 1/40 +&amp;gt; 1/x = 1/120.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, B on working alone will empty a full tank in 120 hours.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;4. A cistern can be filled by pipes A and B in 10 hours and 15 hours respectively. When full, the tank can be emptied by pipe C in 30 hours. If all the taps be turned on at the same time the cistern will be full in how many hours?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Work done by A in one hour is 1/10. Work done by B in one hour is 1/15. Work done by C in one hour is -1/30. (negative because it empties the tank).&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If A, B and C working together, then the work done in one hour is A + B + C = 4/30.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the time required is &lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq25&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/7ACDCA17-75A5-8D4C-088C-13F618DF977F.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;hours.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;5. Two pipes A and B can separately fill a tank in 12 minutes and 15 minutes respectively. Both the pipes are opened together but 2 minutes after the start, pipe A is turned off. How much time will it take to fill the tank?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Work done by A in one minute is 1/12. Work done by B in one minute is 1/15.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If both work together, work done in one minute is A + B = 9/60.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Work done in four minutes by both the taps will be (A + B) x 2 = 3/10.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Work left is 1 - 3/10 = 7/10.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Now, only tap B is open.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the extra time taken by B to fill the tap is &lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq26&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/24F788D1-740A-8D2E-8C58-A2AB00E38C79.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;minutes.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total time taken to fill the tank is 2 + 10.5 = 12.5 minutes.&lt;/p&gt;'),(4,4,'&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Ratio&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Ratio is the relation which one quantity bears to another of the same kind. The ratio of two quantities a and b is the fraction &lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq1&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/FD69EAE7-3466-B46B-75EE-4528C21861AC.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;and we write it as a: b. In the ratio a:b, we call a as the first term or antecedent and b as the second term or consequent. &lt;strong&gt;While the value of b&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;in thew fraction &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;can never be zero, in the ratio &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;, a&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;can have the value 0&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The multiplication or division of each term of a ratio by the same non - zero number does not affect the ratio.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Types of ratios&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1. Compound Ratio&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;It is the ratio where the numerator is the product of all the numerators and denominator is the product of all the denominators.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;If the ratios are 4:3, 2:1, 5:3 and 3:1, the compound ratio will be &lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq2&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/40017327-01E9-C45E-7E3F-6BF1C2B02B6F.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;which is equal to 40:3.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;2. Duplicate ratio&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The duplicate ratio of a:b is a&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;:b&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;. Similarly &amp;radic;a:&amp;radic;b&amp;nbsp;will be the sub-duplicate ratio of a:b.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;If the ratio is 4:9, then the duplicate ratio will be 16:81 and the sub-duplicate ratio will be 2:3.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;3. Triplicate ratio&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The triplicate ratio of a:b is a&lt;sup&gt;3&lt;/sup&gt;:b&lt;sup&gt;3&lt;/sup&gt;. Similarly &lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq3&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/87197644-E752-7F0A-B523-C59E3CCC3623.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;will be the sub-triplicate ratio of a:b.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If the ratio is 8:27, then the triplicate ratio will be 512:19683 and the sub-triplicate ratio will be 2:3&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Examples&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1. Divide 3241&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;into two parts such that they are in ratio 3:4&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Sol: &lt;/strong&gt;let the two numbers be 3x and 4x respectively.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the sum of them is 3x + 4x = 3241.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, 7x = 3241 =&amp;gt; x = 463.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the numbers are 3x = 1389 and 4x = 1852 respectively.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;2. If the ratio between two numbers is 6:4 and their difference is 20, find the bigger number.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;If the numbers are 6x and 4x, then the difference is 6x - 4x = 20.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, 2x = 20 =&amp;gt; x = 10.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the bigger number is 6x = 6 x 10 = 60.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;3. Two numbers are in the ratio 3:5. If 5 is added to each of them, the ratio becomes 2:3. Find the numbers.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;Let the numbers be 3x and 5x.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If 5 is added to each of them, the numbers become 3x + 5 and 5x + 5.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, (3x + 5):(5x + 5) = 2:3 =&amp;gt; x = 5 &amp;nbsp;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the numbers are 3x = 15 and 5x = 25.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;4. The ratio of the ages of Ravi and Ashok is 4: 3 at present. The ratio will be 9:7 after four years. Find Ravi&amp;rsquo;s present age in years.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;Let the present ages be 4x and 3x. After 4 years, the ages will be 4x + 4 and 3x + 4.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, (4x + 4):(3x + 4) = 9:7 =&amp;gt; x =8.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the present age of Ravi is 4x = 32 years.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Continued Ratio&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If the ratio of the first and second numbers is a:b and the ratio of the second and third numbers is c:d, then the continued ratio of the first, second and third numbers is ac:bc:bd .&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;5. If the ratio of the runs scored by A and B is 3:5 and the runs scored by B and C is 4:7, then find the ratio of runs scored by A and C.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;Since the runs scored by B has a ratio 5 when compared with A and the ratio 4 when compared with C, the runs scored by B should be a multiple of both 4 and 5 or 20.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, let B = 20k.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Then runs scored by A = 3/5 x 20k = 12k and the runs scored by C = 7/4 x 20k = 35k.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the required ratio is 12:35.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Proportion&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Four quantities a, b, c and d are said to be in proportion if and only if a/b = c/d. It is denoted by :: and is written as a:b::c:d. a and b are called the extremes and b and c are called means.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;In any proportion, Product of Extremes = Product of means&lt;strong&gt;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Three numbers a, b and c are said to be in proportion if and only if b&lt;sup&gt;2&amp;nbsp;&lt;/sup&gt;= ac. In this case, b is called the mean proportion of a and c.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Examples&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1. Find the last term of the proportion 2:3:6&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt; The fourth term of a proportion is given by d = bc/a = 9.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;2. Find the mean proportion of 3&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;and 27&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution: &lt;/strong&gt;The mean proportion of two numbers a and c is &amp;radic;(ac).&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the mean proportion of 3 and 27 is 9.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Types of proportion&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1. Direct proportion&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Two quantities are said to be in direct proportion if the increase (decrease) in one quantity causes a corresponding increase (decrease) in the other quantity.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;If the cost of 5 pens is Rs. 50, then the cost of 10 pens is Rs. 100.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;2. Inverse proportion&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Two quantities are said to be in direct proportion if the increase (decrease) in one quantity causes a corresponding decrease (increase) in the other quantity.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;If 3 men can complete a work in 7 days, then 7 men will complete it in 3 days.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Examples:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1. If the work done by x&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;men in (x + 1)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;days &lt;strong&gt;is in the ratio 5:6&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt; to the work done by (x + 2)&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;men in x&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;days &amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;, then the value of x&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;is&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;Number of man hours in the first case is x(x + 1).&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Number of man hours in the second case is x(x + 2).&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Since the number of man hours is directly proportional to the work done, &lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq4&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/76FD3FC8-1EB1-E061-6F04-3564A501D0BF.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;2. If 15 workers can complete 1/5&lt;sup&gt;th&lt;/sup&gt; of a work in 4 days, how many workers are required to complete the remaining work in 8 days?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;Total number of man days required to complete (1/5)&lt;sup&gt;th&lt;/sup&gt; of the work is 15 x 4 = 60.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the remaining (4/5)th work requires &lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq5&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/6F908914-9750-982D-43A0-0BE207EFA015.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;man days.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;There are 8 days available to complete the work.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, number of workers required is 240/8 = 30 workers per day.&lt;/p&gt;'),(5,5,'&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Interest&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If a person borrows some money from another person for a certain period, then after that specified period, the borrower has to return the borrowed money with some additional money. This additional money that the borrower has to pay is called &lt;strong&gt;Interest&lt;/strong&gt;. The actual borrowed money is called &lt;strong&gt;Principal&lt;/strong&gt; or &lt;strong&gt;Sum&lt;/strong&gt;. &lt;strong&gt;The Sum and interest together is called amount&lt;/strong&gt;, and the time for which the borrower has borrowed money is called the &lt;strong&gt;time&lt;/strong&gt;. The interest that the borrower has to pay for every 100 rupees borrowed each year is called rate percent per annum.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Interests are of two types.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1. Simple Interest&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If the interest on a sum borrowed for a certain period is reckoned uniformly, then it is called Simple Interest and it is denoted by S.I.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;2. Compound Interest&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If the interest for one time period gets added to the sum after the time period and the amount becomes the new principal, then the interest type is called compound interest.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The time period can be either yearly, or half-yearly or quarterly etc..&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If the amount borrowed is Rs. 10,000 at an interest of 10% per annum for four years, then the interest for first year will be same in SI and CI.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Interest is equal to &lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq1&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/1845AF66-2CED-09FE-D9E1-8D35D59A73AF.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;In the case of simple interest, the principal is always fixed at the initial principal and so the interest to be paid for the second year also remains the same at Rs. 1000.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;However, in the case of Compound Interest, the principal for the second year will be &amp;nbsp;and the interst for second year will be &lt;img id=&quot;MathMLEq2&quot; src=&quot;../assets/q_images/D7AED31B-BE64-8FB4-E130-97CAE2BBA497.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The principal for the third year will be 11,000 + 1100 = Rs.12,100.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;value of CI is never less than the value of SI&lt;/strong&gt; if the total time period and the rate of interest in both the cases remain the same. For the first time period, both of them are equal.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Formulae for Simple Interest&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;P = Principal, r% = annual rate of interest, T = time in years.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;S.I. = (PxTxR)/100.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;If the two rate of interests are r&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt;% and r&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;%, then the difference in the value of simple interest over T years is P x T x (r&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; - r&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt;)/100.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;Final amount after T years will be A = P + SI = P(1 + Tr/100).&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Examples&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1. At what rate percent per annum will a sum of Rs. 6000 become Rs. 9000 in 10 years at simple interest?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If the principal is P, then the simple interest at the end of T years at a rate of r% per annum is PTR/100.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Here P = 6000, S.I. = 3000, T = 10&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, 6000 x 10 x r/100 = 3000 =&amp;gt; r = 5%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;2. A sum of Rs. 4000 lent at simple interest at 10 % per annum will become double in how many years?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If the principal is P, then the simple interest at the end of T years at a rate of r% per annum is PTR/100.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Here r = 10% and S.I. = P&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, P x T x 10/100 = P =&amp;gt; T = 10 years.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;3. The difference in the interests received from two different banks on Rs. 1000 for 2 years is Rs. 20. Find the difference in their rates. &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If the two rate of interest are r&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt;% and r&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;%, then the difference in simple interest over n years is PT(r&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;-r&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt;)/100.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, given that 1000 x 2 x (r&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;-r&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt;)/100 = 20 =&amp;gt; (r&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;-r&lt;sub&gt;1) = 1%&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;4. Find out the capital required to earn a quarterly interest of Rs. 900 at 12% simple interest.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Rate of interest per quarter is 12/4 =&amp;gt; 3%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Interest is Rs. 900. So, P x 3/100.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;5. If a certain sum of money given at simple interest for 8 years doubles itself, then how many more years will it take for the amount to be 4 times the sum?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;It will take 8 years for the interest to be equal to the sum.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the interest will be three times the sum in &amp;nbsp;years.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, it will take 16 more years.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Formulae for Compound Interest&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;, , ,&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;, if the interest is compounded annually.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;, if the interest is compounded 2 times annually.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;, if the interest is compounded quarterly.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;Population increase follows the logic of compound interest.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;Money invested in compound interest becomes &lt;strong&gt;double in &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;years&lt;/strong&gt;, where &amp;nbsp;is the annual rate of interest.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Examples&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1. What will be the compound interest on Rs. 1000 at 10% per annum for 3 years, compounded annually?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;. Here, , , .&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So,&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;2. What is the difference between the simple and compound interest on Rs. 7,300&amp;nbsp; at the rate of 6% per annum, in 2 years?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the required difference is .&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;3. The simple interest accrued on an amount of Rs. 30,000 at the end of 3 years is Rs. 9000. What would be the compound interest accrued on the same amount at the same rate of interest at the end of two years?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;, , , . So, &amp;nbsp;per annum.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the compound interest for this principal will be .&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, .&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;5. If a certain sum of money given at compound interest for 8 years doubles itself, then how many more years will it take for the amount to be 4 times the sum?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;It will take another 8 years for the amount to be 4 times the sum.&lt;/p&gt;'),(6,6,'&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Profit and Loss&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The chapter profit and Loss is related to selling and buying things. Shopkeepers generally buy articles at a lower price and then sell them to customers at a higher price.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Some important terms involved are&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Cost Price&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;:&lt;/strong&gt; it is the price at which the article is purchased.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Selling Price&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;: &lt;/strong&gt;it is the price at which the article will be sold.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Profit: &lt;/strong&gt;If the selling price of an article is &lt;strong&gt;more&lt;/strong&gt; than the cost price, then the article is sold at a profit.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The value of the profit is the difference between the selling price and cost price.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Loss: &lt;/strong&gt;If the selling price of an article is &lt;strong&gt;less&lt;/strong&gt; than the cost price, then the article is sold at a loss.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The value of the loss is the difference between the cost price and selling price.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Profit percentage: &lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Loss percentage: &lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;Profit percentage and loss percentage are always calculated on the cost price.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Cases for different problems&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Case 1: If the gain percentage is given and the cost pr