;Permutations and Combinations&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Mathematical principal of counting&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;There are 2 basic methods used to count the number of possibilities to complete a work. They are addition and multiplication. The most important point is to know absolutely when addition is required and when multiplication is required.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Multiplication is used when 2 or more works should be done in a particular order to finish a work. Addition is used when a work can be completed in more than one ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;An example would make the concept very clear.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Example&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1. In how many ways can you go from Town A to Town B and return to Town B, if there are 6 connecting roads between the two towns?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;While going from Town A to Town B, he can select any one of the six roads available. So, he can complete this part in 6 ways. Now, coming back, he can select any one of the six roads again. So, the entire work can be completed in . We have used multiplication here because, in order to complete the work, he must do the two things in order.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;In some situations where we collect some elements, we also need to arrange the things. In such cases, the total number of arrangements that we can make is called &lt;strong&gt;permutations.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;e.g. if we are posing for a photograph, then the order becomes very important. Similarly, the spelling of any word also requires that we maintain a particular arrangement. WRONG is not the same as WORNG.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;In some situations where we collect some elements, we need not arrange the things. In such cases, the total number of selections that we can make is called &lt;strong&gt;combinations.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Permutations&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Here, the order is very important. There are 2 very critical types of permutations. Repetition may either be allowed or not be allowed.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Rule:&lt;/strong&gt; The number of ways in which we can arrange r objects in n places, &amp;nbsp;where repetition is allowed is . If repetition is not allowed, the number of arrangements is .&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Proof:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If repetition is allowed, then for each object, there are n choices. The work will not be completed until all the &amp;nbsp;objects are filled. So, total number of ways is .&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If repetition is not allowed, there are &amp;nbsp;possibilities for the first object. There will only be &amp;nbsp;objects for the second object. There will only be &amp;nbsp;choices for third object. There will be &amp;nbsp;choices for the last one.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the total number of choices is .&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Permutations with conditions&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The number of ways in which you can arrange r items in n places when&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;There is no condition is .&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;One of the objects is never included is .&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;One of the objects is always included is .&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Examples&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1. In how many ways can 4 letters be placed i