ong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;In order to be divisible by 5, the only possibility for the units place is . So, the units place can be filled in only 1 way. There is no condition for the remaining places. So, the 3 places can be filled from the remaining 4 numbers in &amp;nbsp;ways. So, the total number of arrangementsis .&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;8. The number of ways in which the letters of the word &lt;em&gt;MOTHER&lt;/em&gt; be arranged without changing the relative positions of the vowels and consonants is&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The 2 vowels can only move within their positions. So, they can be arranged in &amp;nbsp;ways. Similarly, the 4 consonants can only move within their positions. So, they can be arranged in &amp;nbsp;ways. So, total number of arrangements is .&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Permutation of things when some are identical&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If we have &amp;nbsp;things in which &amp;nbsp;are exactly of one kind, &amp;nbsp;of second kind, &amp;nbsp;of third kind and the rest are all different, then the number of permutation of &amp;nbsp;things taken all at a timeis .&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Examples&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;9. In how many ways can we arrange the letters of the word ALMANAC?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;In this case, there are 7 letters out of which the letter A is repeated 3 times.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, number of words that can be formed is .&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;10. &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Find the number of arrangements that can be made by taking all the letters of the word &lt;em&gt;ALGEBRA&lt;/em&gt; such that no two A&amp;rsquo;s are together.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;First arrange the other 5 letters in 5! ways. This will leave 6 gaps among them. Now, we can arrange the two A&amp;rsquo;s in these gaps in &amp;nbsp;Ways, because A has repeated twice. So, the total number of arrangements is .&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;11. In how many ways can we arrange 10 identical black balls and 5 identical blue balls such that no two blue balls are together?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;First arrange the 10 identical black balls in &amp;nbsp;way, because they are all identical. Now this will leave 11 gaps in between them. We can put 5 identical blue balls in these gaps in &lt;sup&gt;11&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;5&lt;/sub&gt;ways. So, total number of ways required is&lt;sup&gt;11&lt;/sup&gt;P&lt;sub&gt;5&lt;/sub&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Circular permutation&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If we fix one of the objects around the circumference of a circle then number of permutation of n different thing taken all at a time is ways because a circle does not have starting point.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, we first must select one item as the starting point. Now the remaining &amp;nbsp;items can be arranged in &amp;nbsp;ways. If we do not consider the direction i.e. if the clockwise and anticlockwise orientation does not make any difference, then the number of permutationsis .&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Examples&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;12. In how many ways can 10 guest be seated around a circular table for dinner?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Since it is a round table, the number of ways is .&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;13. In how many ways can 10 guest be seated around a circular table for dinner such that no person will have the same two neighbors?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Since it is a round table, the total number of arrangements is . In half of these, the orientation is clockwise. The remaining half are the same arrangements, but the orientation will be anti-clockwise. So, total number of required arrangements is &amp;nbsp;ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;14. In how many ways can 4 gentlemen and 3 ladies be seated around a table such that no two ladies are together?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;First arrange the 4 gentlemen. This can be done in &amp;nbsp;ways because it is a circular table. Now, there will be 4 gaps &amp;lt;5 only if the arrangement is linear&amp;gt; and 3 ladies can be arranged in these gaps in&lt;sup&gt;4&lt;/sup&gt;P&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt;&amp;nbsp; ways. So, total number of arrangements is &lt;sup&gt;4&lt;/sup&gt;P&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt; .&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Combinations&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;In these cases, arrangement is not needed. Just selection is enough. It is used when we are selecting committees, cricket squads etc&amp;hellip;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The number of ways in which r objects can be selected from n objects &amp;nbsp;is&lt;sup&gt;n&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;r&lt;/sub&gt; .&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Combinations with conditions&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The number of ways in which you can select r items out of n places when&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;There is no condition is&lt;sup&gt;n&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;r&lt;/sub&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;One of the objects is never included is.&lt;sup&gt;(n-1)&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;r&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;One of the objects is always included is .&lt;sup&gt;(n-1)&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;(r-1)&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Examples&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1. In how many ways can you select 5 members for a committee from 12 members if &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;a)&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Member A is always selected?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;b)&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Member B is never selected?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;c)&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Member C refuses to be selected if A is part of the committee.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;d)&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Member D refuses to be selected unless A is part of the committee.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;a)&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; Since Member A is always selected, there are only 4 vacancies which can be filled by the remaining 11 persons. It can be done in &lt;sup&gt;11&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;4&lt;/sub&gt; ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;b)&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; Since Member B is never selected, there are 5 vacancies which can be filled by the remaining 11 persons. It can be done in&amp;nbsp; &lt;sup&gt;11&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;5&lt;/sub&gt;ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;c)&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; If A is selected, then there are only 4 vacancies which can be filled by the remaining 10 persons, because C will never be part of this committee. It can be done in&amp;nbsp; &lt;sup&gt;10&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;4&lt;/sub&gt;ways. If Member A is not selected, there are 5 vacancies which can be filled by the remaining 11 persons. In this case, C does not have any problem. It can be done in&amp;nbsp; &lt;sup&gt;11&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;5&lt;/sub&gt;ways. So, total number of ways of forming the committee is&lt;sup&gt;10&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;4&lt;/sub&gt;+ &lt;sup&gt;11&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;5&lt;/sub&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;We use addition here because these two represent two different ways to complete a same job. We use multiplication for sequential jobs and addition for parallel jobs.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;d)&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; If A is not selected, then there are 5 vacancies which can be filled by the remaining 10 persons, because D will never be part of this committee. It can be done in &lt;sup&gt;10&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;5&lt;/sub&gt;ways. If Member A is selected, there are 4 vacancies which can be filled by the remaining 11 persons. In this case, D does not have any problem. It can be done in &lt;sup&gt;11&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;4&lt;/sub&gt; ways. So, total number of ways of forming the committee is &lt;sup&gt;10&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;5&lt;/sub&gt;+ &lt;sup&gt;11&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;4&lt;/sub&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;2. &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;In how many ways can a committee consisting of 4 men and 6 women be formed from a group of 10 men and 7 women?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;We can select 4 men out of 10 men in &lt;sup&gt;10&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;4&lt;/sub&gt; ways and 6 women out of 7 women in &lt;sup&gt;7&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;6&lt;/sub&gt; ways. So, the total number of ways to select the committee is &lt;sup&gt;10&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;4&lt;/sub&gt;x &lt;sup&gt;7&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;6&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;3. &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;In how many ways can 4 scholarships of equal value be awarded among 6 M.P.C., 5 Bi.P.C and 4 C.E.C. students so as not to exclude any group? &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;There are 3 ways. 2 medals for one particular group and 1 each for the remaining two groups.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the total number of ways is.&lt;sup&gt;6&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;&amp;times;&lt;sup&gt;5&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt;&amp;times;&lt;sup&gt;4&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt;+&lt;sup&gt;6&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt;&amp;times;&lt;sup&gt;5&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;&amp;times;&lt;sup&gt;4&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt;+&lt;sup&gt;6&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt;&amp;times;&lt;sup&gt;5&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt;&amp;times;&lt;sup&gt;4&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;4. &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A person wishes to make as many parties of 6 persons as possible from his friend group of 12. In how many of these parties is a particular friend found?&amp;nbsp; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;A particular friend is always included. So, he needs to select another 5 fried from the remaining batch of 11 friends. He can do it in&lt;sup&gt;11&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;5&lt;/sub&gt;&amp;nbsp; ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;5.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt; There are 5 ladies and 6 gentlemen. The number of ways of selecting a lady and a gentleman so that the youngest lady may not be with the oldest gentleman is&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;One lady and one gentleman can be selected in &amp;nbsp;ways. In one of these, the youngest lady is with oldest gentleman. So, the number of required ways is .&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Selection of any number of things out of distinct things&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;There are 2 ways to select anything i.e. either it will be selected or not. Therefore number of ways to select n things is . In these selections, one selection is where no item is selected. So, the total number of selections where at least one item is selected is .&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;&lt;sup&gt;n&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;0&lt;/sub&gt;+&lt;sup&gt;n&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt;+â‹¯+&lt;sup&gt;n&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;n&lt;/sub&gt;=2&lt;sup&gt;n&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Selection of any number of things out of identical things&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Since all the objects are now identical, we have &amp;nbsp;choices only. We can select &amp;nbsp;items, or &amp;nbsp;item, or &amp;nbsp;items and so on until &amp;nbsp;items.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Examples&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;6. &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Find the number of ways in which a person can invite one or more of his 4 friends for dinner.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Here, there are 4 different friends. He invites at least one. So, the number of ways of selecting at least one is .&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;7. Find the total number of signals that can be made with 7 different coloured flags.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;At least 1 colour is to be used. We can use any number of colours. So, the total number of flags that can be made with 7 colours is .&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;8. A box contains 2 white balls and 3 black balls and 4 red balls. In how many ways can 3 balls be drawn from the box if at least one black ball is to be included in the draw?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;3 balls can be drawn from the available 9 balls in &lt;sup&gt;9&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt; ways. The number of ways in which there is no black ball is&lt;sup&gt;6&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt;. So, the required number of ways is&lt;sup&gt;9&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt;-&lt;sup&gt;6&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt;=84-20=64.&lt;/p&gt;'),(10,10,'&lt;h1&gt;Table Graphs&lt;/h1&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;A table is the easier form used to summarise data in a meaningful way, it presentsthe data systematically in the form of rows andcolumns.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;In the tabular form of the data, information orthe facts are arranged in alphabetical or thechronological order.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example of a general table graph.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The following table lists the profits of three companies A, B, C over the four quarters for last year in Rs. crore.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table border=&quot;1&quot; cellspacing=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;0&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;125&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Company&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;125&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;125&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;B&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;125&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;C&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;125&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Quarter 1&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;125&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;42&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;125&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;35&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;125&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;48&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;125&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Quarter 2&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;125&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;53&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;125&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;30&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;125&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;42&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;125&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Quarter 3&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;125&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;40&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;125&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;29&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;125&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;52&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;125&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Quarter 4&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;125&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;38&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;125&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;45&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;125&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;50&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Points to Remember&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;Study the title of the table carefully that givesyou a description of the contents of the table,kinds of data and the period for which itoccurred.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;A dash or the blank indicates that corresponding data is not available.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;If you are arranging data in the form of a table,remember that the zero is always indicated by 0.A dash or the blank should never be indicated aszero.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Examples&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;I. Observe the table given below and then answer the questions that follow.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The table gives the data about the number of boys and girls in six different junior colleges.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table border=&quot;1&quot; cellspacing=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;0&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;148&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;College&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;148&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Boys&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;148&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Girls&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;148&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;P&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;148&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;300&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;148&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;200&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;148&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;Q&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;148&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;420&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;148&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;480&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;148&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;R&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;148&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;540&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;148&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;350&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;148&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;S&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;148&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;210&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;148&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;320&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;148&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;T&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;148&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;340&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;148&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;420&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;148&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;U&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;148&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;500&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;148&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;460&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1. What is the difference between the total number of boys and girls in all the colleges put together?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total number of boys is 300 + 420 + 540 + 210 + 340 + 500 = 2310.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total number of girls is 200 + 480 + 350 + 320 + 420 + 460 = 2230.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The required difference is 2310 &amp;ndash; 2230 = 80.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;2. In how many colleges is the number of boys greater than their average?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The average number of boys in a college is 2310/6 = 385&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the number of boys is greater than the average in 3 colleges.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;3. What is the ratio of the number of boys in college R to the number of girls in college P?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The required ratio is 540: 200 = 27: 10.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;4. Which college has the highest number of boys and girls?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The strength for college P is 300 + 200 = 500.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The strength for college Q is 420 + 480 = 900.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The strength for college R is 540 + 350 = 890.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The strength for college S is 210 + 320 = 530.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The strength for college T is 340 + 420 = 760.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The strength for college U is 500 + 460 = 960.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the college with the most number of boys and girls is college U.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;II. Observe the table given below and then answer the questions that follow.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The table gives the data about the number of products manufactured in various plants of a company in various months.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table border=&quot;1&quot; cellspacing=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;0&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;104&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Month/Plant&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;90&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;I&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;90&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;II&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;90&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;III&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;90&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;IV&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;91&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;V&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;104&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;April&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;90&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;180&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;90&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;170&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;90&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;120&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;90&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;140&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;91&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;150&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;104&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;May&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;90&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;175&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;90&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;180&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;90&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;140&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;90&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;140&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;91&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;165&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;104&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;June&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;90&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;160&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;90&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;175&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;90&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;135&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;90&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;135&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;91&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;170&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;104&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;July&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;90&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;170&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;90&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;160&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;90&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;125&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;90&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;145&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;91&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;160&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;104&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;August&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;90&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;165&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;90&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;165&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;90&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;150&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;90&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;130&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;91&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;155&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1. What is the difference between the total production in July and April?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total production in July is 170 + 160 + 125 + 145 + 160 = 760.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total production in April is 180 + 170 + 120 + 140 + 150 = 760.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The required difference is 760 &amp;ndash; 760 = 0&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;2. What is the difference between the total production in the first and third plants?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total production in the first plant is 180 + 175 + 160 + 170 + 165 = 870.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total production in the third plant is 120 + 140 + 135 + 125 + 150 = 670.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The required difference is 870 &amp;ndash; 670 = 200&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;3. What is the ratio of the total production in the second and fifth plants?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total production in the second plant is 170 + 180 + 175 + 160 + 165 = 850.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total production in the fifth plant is 150 + 165 + 170 + 160 + 155 = 800.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The required ratio is 850:800 = 17: 16.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;'),(11,11,'&lt;h1&gt;Bar Graphs&lt;/h1&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;A bar graph is a well-defined diagram of various bars depended on the given data. Generally, the respective figures are written at the end of each bar to facilitate the interpretation easily, otherwise the figures are written only on the parallel axis.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The height of each bar is always proportional to the value that is being represented.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The bar graphs are of three types. These are&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;1. Simple Bar Graphs&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;2. Component Bar Graphs&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;3. Multiple Bar Graphs&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Simple Bar Graph&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;In simple bar graph, one bar represents only one variable or one component, viz., one bar for only one item or matter or the number. Each and every bar remains separate to the other one.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;A simple bar graph is shown in the example below.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Component Bar Graph&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;In Component Bar Graph, the total magnitude of a bar is to be divided into two or more than two parts of sub-classes. The bars are drawn proportional in length to the total and divided in the ratios of their components, viz., one bar for two or more than two items, or the matters, but each and every bar remains separate to the other one. Component Bar Graph is also called sub-divided Bar Graph.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;A component bar graph is shown in the example below.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Multiple Bar Graph&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;In Multiple Bar Graph, two or more than two bars make a unit compound of bars of the different items or the components by meeting each other with their respective magnitudes. A unit compound of bars remains a definite separation to another unit of compound.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;A multiple bar graph is shown in the example below.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Examples&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;I. Observe this graph and answer questions that follow&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1. What is the maximum change in the profit shown in the figure?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The change over the years is - 5, 6, 0.5, - 5.5, 4 crore over the years.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the maximum change is 6 crore and it came during 2010 to 2011.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;2. What is the ratio of the maximum loss to the maximum profit?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Maximum profit is 4 crore during the year 2011.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Maximum loss is Rs. 2 crore during the years 2010 and 2013.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the required ratio is 2: 4 or 1: 2.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;3. In how many years is the profit above the average profit?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Average profit is [3 &amp;ndash; 2 + 4 + 3.5 &amp;ndash; 2 + 2]/6 = 8.5/6 = Rs. 1.4 crore.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the profit is more than the average in 4 years: 2009, 2011, 2012, 2014&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;II. Observe this bar graph and answer questions that follow&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1. What is the difference in profit during the years 2009 and 2012?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Profit during 2009 is 60 &amp;ndash; 40 = 20 lakh rupees.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Profit during 2012 is 70 &amp;ndash; 45 = 25 lakh rupees.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the required difference is Rs. 5 lakh.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;2. What is the percentage change in income from 2010 to 2013?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Income in 2010 is Rs. 80 lakh and in 2013 is Rs. 10 lakh.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the required percent change is [90-80]/80 x 100% = 100/8% = 12.5% increase.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;3. In which year is the profit maximum?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Profit during 2009 is 60 &amp;ndash; 40 = 20 lakh rupees.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Profit during 2010 is 80 &amp;ndash; 65 = 15 lakh rupees.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Profit during 2011 is 100 &amp;ndash; 60 = 40 lakh rupees.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Profit during 2012 is 70 &amp;ndash; 45 = 25 lakh rupees.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Profit during 2012 is 90 &amp;ndash; 60 = 30 lakh rupees.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Profit during 2012 is 80 &amp;ndash; 55 = 25 lakh rupees.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, it is the highest in the year 2011.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;'),(12,12,'&lt;h1&gt;Line Charts&lt;/h1&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Line Graph represents a pictorial presentation of the given data. It is also called a Cartesian graph of pictorial representations. Generally, a line graph indicates the variation of a quantity or a magnitude with respect to two parameters calibrated on the axes X and Y respectively.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If it is drawn with the help of only a single line, it is called a Single Line Graph or a Simple Line Graph.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example of a single line chart&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If the graph has at least two or more than two lines, it is called a Multiple Line Graph.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example of a multiple line chart&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Examples&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;I. Observe the chart carefully and then answer the questions that follow.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1. What is the price difference between the products in May?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The required price difference is 600 &amp;ndash; 550 = Rs. 50.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;2. What is the difference in the average prices if the two products over 5 months?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The average price of product A is [650 + 600 + 550 + 700 + 750]/5 = Rs. 650&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The average price of product B is [700 + 550 + 500 + 650 + 800]/5 = Rs. 640&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the required difference is Rs. 10.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;3. What is the percentage increase of the value of product B from April to August?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The value of product B increased from Rs. 700 to Rs. 800.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the percentage increase is [800 &amp;ndash; 700]/700 x 100% = 100/7% = 14.3%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;II. Observe the chart carefully and then answer the questions that follow.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1. What is the difference between the total number of students from the discipline of Physics from all the colleges together and the total number of students from the discipline of Chemistry from all the colleges together?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total number of Physics students in all colleges is 500 + 550 + 600 + 450 + 400 = 2500&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total number of Chemistry students in all colleges is 600 + 500 + 400 + 550 + 450 = 2500&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the required difference is 0.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;2. What is the respective ratio of the number of students from Mathematics and Physics together from college C to the number of students from Physics and Chemistry together from college B?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total number of mathematics and physics students from college C is 600 + 550 = 1150&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total number of Chemistry and physics students from college B is 500 + 550 = 1050&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The required ratio is 1150: 1050 = 23: 21.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;3. Which college has the least number of students from Mathematics?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;It is college D with 400 students.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;4. The number of students from Physics from college D are approximately what percent of the number of students from Chemistry from college A?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Number of physics students from college D is 450 and the number of chemistry students from college A is 600.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the required ratio is 450/600 x 100 = 75%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;'),(13,13,'&lt;h1&gt;Pie Charts&lt;/h1&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Pie chart&amp;mdash;Pie chart or the Pie graph is a complete circle or a Pie in which the total quantity or the magnitude of the given question is distributed over the various parts of an angle of 360&amp;deg;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;In the Pie chart or the pie graph, the data can be plotted with respect to only one parameter, therefore its usage is restricted. It is useful to show the shares of various parties having a particular quantity for the distribution among themselves in various parts or the percentage. &lt;strong&gt;The share of each item is proportional to the angle that the corresponding item submits at the centre.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Example of a general Pie chart.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Examples&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;I. Observe the pie chart given below and answer the questions that follow.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1. What is the total number of students enrolled in Stitching and Drama together?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The percent of students enrolled in stitching and drama together is 18 + 17 = 35%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, number of students enrolled is 35/100 x 400 = 140.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;2. How many students are enrolled in cooking classes?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Number of students enrolled in cooking classes is 15/100 x 400 = 60.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;3. How many fewer students enrolled in singing compared to drama?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The percent of students enrolled in singing is less than those enrolled for drama by 17 &amp;ndash; 12 = 5%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, number of fewer students is 5/100 x 400 = 20.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;4. Find the ratio of students enrolled in Painting and Singing to those enrolled in Dancing and Stitching.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The percent of students enrolled in painting and singing is 14 + 12 = 26%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The percent of students enrolled in Dancing and stitching is 24 + 18 = 42%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the required ratio is 26: 42 = 13: 21.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;II. Observe the pie chart given below and answer the questions that follow.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1. What is the total amount that is spent on bread and milk together?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total percent of money spent on bread and milk together is 25 + 17 = 42%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total amount spent is 5000 x 42/100 = Rs. 2100.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;2. Amount spent on Non-veg is what percent of the amount spent on Vegetables?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Percent of money spent on Non-veg is 20%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Percent of money spent on Vegetables is 15%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, required percentage is 20/15 x 100% = 133.33%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;3. What is the ratio of the amounts spent on fruits and non-veg?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The required ratio is 10: 20 = 1: 2.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;'),(14,14,'&lt;p&gt;Synonyms:&lt;br /&gt; &lt;br /&gt; Words with similar meanings. These words can be used interchangeably to convey the same meaning.&lt;br /&gt; &lt;br /&gt; Eg: Anger = Fury&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;In great anger he replied &amp;ldquo;Damned be you and all your sons!&amp;rdquo;&lt;br /&gt; In his fury, he cursed him and his children.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;'),(15,15,'&lt;p&gt;Analogy:&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ol&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;A&amp;nbsp;form&amp;nbsp;of&amp;nbsp;reasoning&amp;nbsp;in&amp;nbsp;which&amp;nbsp;one&amp;nbsp;thing&amp;nbsp;is&amp;nbsp;inferred&amp;nbsp;to&amp;nbsp;be&amp;nbsp;similar&amp;nbsp;to another&amp;nbsp;thing&amp;nbsp;in&amp;nbsp;a&amp;nbsp;certain&amp;nbsp;respect,&amp;nbsp;on&amp;nbsp;the&amp;nbsp;basis&amp;nbsp;of&amp;nbsp;the&amp;nbsp;known&amp;nbsp;similarity between&amp;nbsp;the&amp;nbsp;things&amp;nbsp;in&amp;nbsp;other&amp;nbsp;respects.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;A&amp;nbsp;similarity&amp;nbsp;between&amp;nbsp;like&amp;nbsp;features&amp;nbsp;of&amp;nbsp;two&amp;nbsp;things,&amp;nbsp;on&amp;nbsp;which&amp;nbsp;a&amp;nbsp;comparison may&amp;nbsp;be&amp;nbsp;based.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ol&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Analogy tests are a way of testing Vocabulary, Understanding relations and a measure of accuracy and deduction.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The following Relations will help you understand the possible questions you may be quizzed upon:&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Animal and Offspring:&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table border=&quot;0&quot; cellspacing=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;0&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;36&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;1&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;282&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Horse : Foal&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;36&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;2&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;282&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Tiger : Cub&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;36&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;3&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;282&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Goat : Kid&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;36&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;4&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;282&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Butterfly : Caterpillar&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;36&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;5&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;282&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Insect : Larva&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Be careful. The masculine or feminine form of animals can be used to confuse you.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Eg: The parent of a Foal can be a Horse (gender neutral), Stallion (masculine) or a Mare (feminine)&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;It is also possible that specific animals and their class can be given as options. The appropriate choice must be made based upon available options.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Eg: Caterpillar is a better answer than Larva when &amp;ldquo;What is the offspring of a Butterfly?&amp;rdquo; is the question. If Caterpillar is not available, Larva is an acceptable answer.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Male and Female:&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table border=&quot;0&quot; cellspacing=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;0&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;36&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;1&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;282&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Horse : Mare&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;36&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;2&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;282&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Tiger : Tigress&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;36&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;3&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;282&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Goat : Nanny&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;36&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;4&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;282&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Bee : Drone&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;36&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;5&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;282&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Bear : Sow&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Individual and Collective Noun:&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table border=&quot;0&quot; cellspacing=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;0&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;36&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;1&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;282&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Horse : Herd&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;36&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;2&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;282&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Tiger : Ambush&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;36&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;3&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;282&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Goat : Herd&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;36&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;4&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;282&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Bee : Colony&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;36&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;5&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;282&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Bear : Sloth&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Individual and Class:&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table border=&quot;0&quot; cellspacing=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;0&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;36&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;1&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;282&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Horse : Mammal&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;36&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;2&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;282&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Tiger : Mammal&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;36&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;3&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;282&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Goat : Herd&lt;/p&gt;\r