andmother&amp;rsquo;s son&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;161&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Father or Uncle&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;321&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Grandfather&amp;rsquo;s or grandmother&amp;rsquo;s only daughter&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;161&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Mother&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;321&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Grandfather&amp;rsquo;s or grandmother&amp;rsquo;s daughter&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;161&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Mother or Aunt&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;321&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Only son of paternal grandfather&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;161&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Father&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;321&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Only daughter of maternal grandfather&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;161&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Mother&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;321&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Uncle&amp;rsquo;s wife&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;161&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Aunt&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;321&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Father of father or mother&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;161&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Grandfather&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;321&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Mother of father or mother&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;161&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Grandmother&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;321&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Wife of father&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;161&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Mother&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;321&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Husband of mother&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;161&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Father&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Examples&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1. Pointing to a man, a woman said, &amp;ldquo;He is the brother-in-law of the only son-in-law of my mother&#039;s husband.&quot; How is the man related to the woman?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Woman mother&#039;s husband =&amp;gt; Woman&#039;s father&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Only son-in-law of woman&#039;s father =&amp;gt; Women&#039;s husband&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Woman&#039;s husband&#039;s brother-in-law =&amp;gt; Women&#039;s brother.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the man is the brother of the woman.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;2. A woman walking with a boy meets another woman and on being asked abouther relationship with the boy. She says, &quot;My maternal Uncle and his maternaluncle&#039;s maternal uncle are brothers&amp;rdquo;.How is the boy related to the woman?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Boy&amp;rsquo;s maternal uncle will be brother of boy&#039;s mother. Maternal uncle of mother&#039;s brother and maternal uncle of lady are brothers means lady is sister to mother&#039;s brother i.e., lady is the mother of the boy. So the boy is woman&#039;s son.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;3. A party consists of grandmother, father,mother, four sons and their wives and oneson and two daughters of each of thesons. How many females are there in all?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Grandmother is one female, mother is another, wives of four sons are the four females and two daughters of all four sons are eight females. So, in all there are 1+1+4+8=14 females.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;4. Pointing to a photograph, Shanti said,&quot;She is the mother of my brother&#039;s uncle&#039;sson&quot;. How is Shanti related to the personin the photograph?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Shanti&#039;s brother&#039;s uncle&#039;s son =&amp;gt; Shanti&#039;s cousin&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Hence, the lady in the photograph is Shanti&#039;s aunt.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;5. Pointing to a photograph Ramesh said, &quot;She is the wife of my grandfather&#039;s only son.&quot; How is the person in the photographrelated to Ramesh?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Grandfathers only son =&amp;gt; father.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the person is the wife of his father i.e., his mother.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;6. Rani&#039;smotheristhedaughterofVishnu&#039;ssister.HowisVishnu&#039;smotherrelatedto Rani&#039;s mother?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Rani&amp;rsquo;s mother is the daughter of Vishnu&#039;s sister. So, Rani&amp;rsquo;s mother will be the granddaughter of Vishnu&amp;rsquo;s sister&amp;rsquo;s mother i.e., Vishnu&amp;rsquo;s mother.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Therefore, Vishnu&#039;s mother is the grandmother of Rani&#039;s mother.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;7. Chris isthesonof Daniel. Sam isthedaughterof Robert. Rachel isthemotherof Sam. Bob is thebrotherof Sam.Howis Bob relatedto Rachel? &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The mother and father of Sam are Rachel and Robert respectively.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Since Bob is the brother of Sam, he will be the son of Rachel.&lt;/p&gt;'),(19,19,'&lt;h1&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Study Material&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/h1&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Coding is the process of converting a word into another language by using letters and numbers while decoding is to convert the coded value back into the normal language.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Knowledge of English alphabets and their corresponding number values is very essential to maser this topic.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table border=&quot;1&quot; cellspacing=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;0&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;46&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;A=1&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;46&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;B=2&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;45&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;C=3&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;46&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;D=4&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;46&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;E=5&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;45&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;F=6&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;45&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;G=7&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;46&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;H=8&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;46&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;I=9&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;50&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;J=10&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;45&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;K=11&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;45&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;L=12&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;49&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;M=13&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;46&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;N=14&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;46&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;O=15&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;45&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;P=16&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;46&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;Q=17&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;46&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;R=18&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;45&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;S=19&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;45&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;T=20&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;46&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;U=21&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;46&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;V=22&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;50&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;W=23&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;45&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;X=24&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;45&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;Y=25&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td width=&quot;49&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;Z=26&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The questions on coding and decoding can be broadly divided intofour broad types as given below.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Type-1: Letter Coding &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;In these questions, the real alphabets in the word are replaced by other alphabets according to a certain rule. We must find out that rule and then apply it to other words to get the coded words.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Examples&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1. If the word CARE is coded as DBSF, then find the code for the word NIGHT.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Solution&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;All the letters in the word are moved 1 step to the right in the alphabet.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the code for NIGHT is OJHIU.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;2. If the word CARE is coded as DCUI, then find the code for the word FLOWER.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Solution&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;All the letters in the word are moved &amp;nbsp;steps to the right in the alphabet.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the code for FLOWER is GNRAJX.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;3. If the word CARE is coded as DZSD, then find the word for which the coded form isGREAT.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Solution&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;All the odd letters in the word are moved 1 step to the right in the alphabet.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;All the even letters in the word are moved 1 step to the left in the alphabet.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, if the code is GREAT, then for the original word, all even letters should be shifted 1 to the right and all the odd letters are to be shifted 1 step to the left.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the required word is FSDBS.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Type-2: Number Coding &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;In these questions, the alphabets in the word are replaced by numbers according to a certain rule. We must find out that rule and then apply it to other words to get the coded words.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Examples&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1. If the code for the word CARE is 27, then find the code for the word NIGHT.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Solution&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Use the rule A = 1, B = 2, C = 3&amp;hellip;, Z = 26 and then add all the numbers to get the code.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, for NIGHT, the code will be 14 + 9 + 7 + 8 + 20 = 58.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;2. If the word CAT is coded as 60 and the word BAN is coded as 28, then find the code for the word BOAT.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Solution&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Use the rule A = 1, B = 2, C = 3&amp;hellip;, Z = 26 and then multiply all the numbers to get the code.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, for BOAT, the code will be 2 x 15 x 1 x 20 = 300.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Type-3: Substitution &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;In these questions, some objects are assigned code names. We must apply the code when answering any questions.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Examples&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1. If &amp;lsquo;black&amp;rsquo; is called &amp;lsquo;blue&amp;rsquo;, &amp;rsquo;blue&amp;rsquo; is called &amp;lsquo;orange&amp;rsquo;, &amp;lsquo;orange&amp;rsquo; is called &amp;lsquo;violet&amp;rsquo;, &amp;lsquo; violet&amp;rsquo; is called &amp;lsquo;red&amp;rsquo; and &amp;lsquo;red&amp;rsquo; is called &amp;lsquo;black&amp;rsquo;, what is the colour of blood ?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Solution&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;As the colour of blood is red and red is called black in the given coded language. So the colour of blood is black in the given coded language.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Type-4: Mixed Letter Coding &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;In these questions, some words are assigned code names. Three or four statements will be given to ascertain some words and then the code for a particular word will be asked.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Examples&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1. In a certain code &amp;lsquo;432&amp;rsquo; means &amp;lsquo;she is beautiful&amp;rsquo;; &amp;lsquo;26&amp;rsquo; means &amp;lsquo;very beautiful&amp;rsquo;; and &amp;lsquo;3267&amp;rsquo; means &amp;lsquo;flower is very beautiful&amp;rsquo;. What number will indicate the word &amp;lsquo;flower&amp;rsquo;?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Solution&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Flower is the only word which only occurs in third statement. So, the code corresponding to flower is 7.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;2. In a certain code language, &amp;lsquo;how many runs scored&amp;rsquo; is written as &amp;lsquo;6418&amp;rsquo;, &amp;lsquo;five teams play&amp;rsquo; is written as &amp;lsquo;193&amp;rsquo; and &amp;lsquo;he scored five&amp;rsquo; is written as &amp;lsquo;214.&amp;rsquo; How is &amp;lsquo;scored&amp;rsquo; is written in that code?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Solution&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Five is represented by 1. Scored is common for the first and third statement and so, scored is represented by 4.&lt;/p&gt;'),(20,20,'&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Venn Diagrams&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;In this chapter, we deal with certain groups of items and try to find the relationship between these groups. We use Venn diagrams for this purpose. If we are dealing with 3 groups of items, then we have the following 9 cases.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Type 1&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;When three items are completely unrelated to each other, then they are represented as shown in the figure given below.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;There is no area that will be common to any two of the items.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;E.g. Goats, Cats and Dogs.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Type 2&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;When one of the items is completely a part of the second item, which in turn is a part of the third item, then they are represented as shown in the figure given below.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;There are three circles such that each circle completely lies in the other.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;E.g. Animals, Canines, Dogs.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Type 3&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;When one of the items is partially related to the second item and both these items are completely a part of the third item, then they are represented as shown in the figure given below.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;There are two intersecting circles within a bigger outer circle.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;E.g. Intelligent persons, Graduates, Human Beings.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Type 4&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;When one of the items is completely unrelated to the second item and both these items are completely a part of the third item, then they are represented as shown in the figure given below.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;There are two non-intersecting circles within a bigger outer circle.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;E.g. Doctors, Teachers, Professionals.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Type 5&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;When only one of the items is partially related to the other two items, then they are represented as shown in the figure given below.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;There are three intersecting circles, out of which two are non-intersecting.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;E.g. Vegetables, Fruits, Food.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Type 6&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;When each one of the items is partially related to the other two items, then they are represented as shown in the figure given below.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;There are three intersecting circles.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;E.g. Graduates, Government Employees, Men.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Type 7&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;When one of the items is completely a part of the second item and these two items are partially related to the third item, then they are represented as shown in the figure given below.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;There are two concentric circles, both of which are intersecting third circle.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;E.g. Males, Brothers, Spouses.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Type 8&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;When one of the items is completely a part of the second item and these two items are unrelated to the third item, then they are represented as shown in the figure given below.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;There are two concentric circles, both of which are non-intersecting with the third circle.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;E.g. Males, Brothers, Mothers.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Type 9&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;When one of the items is partially related to the second item and these two items are unrelated to the third item, then they are represented as shown in the figure given below.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;There are two intersecting circles, both of which are non-intersecting with the third circle.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;E.g. Fathers, Brothers, Mothers.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Problems on Venn Diagrams&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The given Venn diagram shows three figures. The triangle represents those students who cleared EAMCET. The rectangle represents those students who cleared IIT JEE MAINS. The circle represents those students who cleared IIT JEE ADVANCED.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;In this figure,&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;The region C represents those students who cleared all the three examinations because the region is enclosed by rectangle, triangle and circle also.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;The region D represents those students who cleared only EAMCET and IIT JEE MAINS because the region is enclosed by rectangle, triangle,but not by circle.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;The region A represents those students who cleared only IIT JEE ADVANCED because the region is enclosed only by the circle.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The region F represents those students who cleared only IIT JEE MAINS because the region is enclosed only by the rectangle.&lt;/p&gt;'),(21,21,'&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;SYLLOGISM&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The word &quot;syllogism&quot; means &#039;inference&#039; or &#039;deduction&#039;. The example given below is a typical question of syllogism.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Directions:&lt;/strong&gt; In the following questions, two statements are given followed by two conclusions. You have to study the two statements and then decide which of the conclusions follow from the statements. Mark the right answer from (1), (2), (3), (4) and (5)&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Statements:&lt;/span&gt; All plants are trees. No trees are green.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Conclusions: &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;I. Some plants are green. &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;II. No plants are green.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;1) Only I follows&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;2) Only II follows&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;3) Both I and II follow&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;4) Either I or II follows&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;5) Neither I nor II follows&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Solution:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Since all the plants are trees and no trees are green, we can clearly say that no plant is green. So, &lt;strong&gt;conclusion I is wrong and conclusion II is right.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Proposition&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;A proposition is a sentence that makes a statement and gives a relation between two or more terms.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Examples &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;1) All windows are rods.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;2) No cloth is a shirt.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;3) Some teachers are professors.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;4) Some blues are not greens.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The parts of proposition are given below.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Subject&lt;/strong&gt;: A subject is the part of the proposition about which something is being said.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Predicate&lt;/strong&gt;: Predicate is the part of the proposition denoting that which is affirmed or denied about the subject.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;e.g. In the proposition &lt;strong&gt;All scientists are teachers&lt;/strong&gt;, something is being said about scientists. So scientists is the subject. Teachers is the predicate here because it affirmed about the subject.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;CLASSIFICATION OF PROPOSITIONS&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Universal positive proposition:&lt;/strong&gt; A proposition of the form &lt;strong&gt;All A are B&lt;/strong&gt; is called a universal positive proposition. A universal positive proposition is denoted by A.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Universal negative proposition:&lt;/strong&gt; A proposition of the form &lt;strong&gt;No A is B&lt;/strong&gt; is called a universal negative proposition. It is usually denoted by E.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Particular positive Proposition:&lt;/strong&gt; A proposition of the form &lt;strong&gt;Some A are B&lt;/strong&gt; is called a particular positive proposition. It is usually denoted by I.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Particular negative Proposition:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;A proposition of the form &lt;strong&gt;Some A are not B&lt;/strong&gt; is called a particular negative proposition. It is usually denoted by O.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Tricks for solving syllogisms&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ol&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;If the proposition is of type A, then the conclusion will be of type I.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ol&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; 2. If the proposition is of type E, then the conclusion will be of type E.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; 3. If the proposition is of type I, then the conclusion will be of type I.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; 4. If the proposition is of type O, then the conclusion will vary according to the situation.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Tricks for solving syllogisms based on conclusion&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;nbsp;1.&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;If the conclusion is &lt;strong&gt;NO&lt;/strong&gt;, then we have to show &lt;strong&gt;at least one common element&lt;/strong&gt;to show that the &lt;strong&gt;conclusion is wrong.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;2.&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;If the conclusion is &lt;strong&gt;ALL&lt;/strong&gt;, then we have to show &lt;strong&gt;at least one not common element&lt;/strong&gt;to show that the &lt;strong&gt;conclusion is wrong.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;3.&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;If the condition is &lt;strong&gt;SOME&lt;/strong&gt;, then we have to show &lt;strong&gt;at least one common element&lt;/strong&gt;to show that the &lt;strong&gt;conclusion is right.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;4.&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;If the conclusion includes the words &lt;strong&gt;&amp;lsquo;possibility&amp;rsquo;&lt;/strong&gt; or &lt;strong&gt;&amp;lsquo;may-be&amp;rsquo;&lt;/strong&gt;, then we have to show that there is &lt;strong&gt;at least a rare chance for the conclusion to be right.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Solved Examples&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;1. &lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Statements:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; All lions are cows. All cows are insects.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Conclusions:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;I. All those insects which are cows are also lions.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;II. All lions are insects.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;a) Only conclusion I follows.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;b) Only conclusion II follows.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;c) Either conclusion I or conclusion II follows.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;d) Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;e) Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Cows is a bigger set than lions and so, &lt;strong&gt;conclusion I is NOT right.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Lions is a subset of cows, which in turn is a subset of insects. So, all lions will be insects and &lt;strong&gt;conclusion II is right.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;2. &lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Statements:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; All foxes are jackals. Some jackals are elephants.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Conclusions:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;I. All elephants being jackals is a possibility.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;II. All foxes being elephants is a possibility.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;a) Only conclusion I follows.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;b) Only conclusion II follows.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;c) Either conclusion I or conclusion II follows.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;d) Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;e) Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If elephants is a subset of jackals, then still some jackals will be elephants and so, there is a chance that this might happen. So, &lt;strong&gt;conclusion I is right, but only because of the inclusion of the word &amp;lsquo;possibility&amp;rsquo;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Since foxes is a subset of jackals, expanding on the hypothesis above, we can see that there is a possibility of all foxes being elephants. So, &lt;strong&gt;conclusion II is right, but only because of the inclusion of the word &amp;lsquo;possibility&amp;rsquo;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;3. &lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Statements:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; No shoe is a sock. All socks are legs.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Conclusions:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;I. No leg is a shoe.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;II. All legs being shoes is a possibility.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;a) Only conclusion I follows.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;b) Only conclusion II follows.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;c) Either conclusion I or conclusion II follows.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;d) Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;e) Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;He did not say that all legs are socks. So, there will be some legs which are not socks. Some shoes which are not socks may be included in this category. So, conclusion I &lt;strong&gt;may be wrong&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Second conclusion is &lt;strong&gt;conclusively wrong&lt;/strong&gt; because we know that socks, which are not shoes, are legs.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;4. &lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Statements:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; Some clubs are spades. Some hearts are clubs.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Conclusions:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;I. No spade is a heart.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;II. All hearts being spades is a possibility.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;a) Only conclusion I follows.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;b) Only conclusion II follows.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;c) Either conclusion I or conclusion II follows.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;d) Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;e) Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;There can be some clubs, who are both hearts and spades. So, statement I is wrong.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If all hearts are spades, then there may be some spades who are not hearts but clubs and also some hearts that are clubs. So, &lt;strong&gt;conclusion II is valid, but only because of the word &amp;lsquo;possibility&amp;rsquo;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;5. &lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Statements:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; Some beasts are monsters. No beast is a mammoth.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Conclusions:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;I. No mammoth is a monster.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;II. Some monsters are definitely not beasts.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;a) Only conclusion I follows.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;b) Only conclusion II follows.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;c) Either conclusion I or conclusion II follows.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;d) Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;e) Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Since only some beasts are monsters, there may be some beasts which are not monsters and these may be mammoths. So, &lt;strong&gt;conclusion I is wrong&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If we consider that all monsters are beasts, the statement some beasts are monsters is still true and so &lt;strong&gt;conclusion II may NOT always be right.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;6. &lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Statements:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;Some gels are liquids. All fluids are liquids.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Conclusions: &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;I. All fluids being gels is a possibility.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;II. No fluid is a gels.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;a) Only conclusion I follows.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;b) Only conclusion II follows.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;c) Either conclusion I or conclusion II follows.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;d) Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;e) Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solution:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If we consider that the fluids is a subset of gels, then there is every chance that the two statements are still satisfied. So, &lt;strong&gt;conclusion I isright because of the inclusion of the word &amp;lsquo;possibility&amp;rsquo;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Some gels which are charts can also be fluids. So &lt;strong&gt;conclusion II is wrong.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;'),(22,22,''),(23,23,''),(24,24,''),(25,25,''),(26,26,''),(27,27,''),(28,28,''),(29,29,''),(30,30,''),(31,31,''),(32,32,''),(33,33,''),(34,34,''),(35,35,''),(36,36,''),(37,37,''),(38,38,''),(39,39,'');

