ine is estimated to be decreasing at the rate of 10% every year. If it costs Rs. 5000 now, what will be the estimated value of the machine after 2 years?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4100&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4050&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4150&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;The decrease in cost of the machine is equivalent to compound interest because the decrease is proportional to the present amount instead of initial amount.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, after 2 years, the amount of water left will be &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/155.24.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;286&quot; height=&quot;45&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(463,5,'4','','&lt;p&gt;Find out the capital required to earn a monthly interest of Rs. 1000 at 10% simple interest.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 1 lakhs&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 1.2 lakhs&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 1.1 lakhs&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 1.3 lakhs&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Rate of interest per month is 10/12%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Interest is Rs. 1000. So, &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/155.25.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;260&quot; height=&quot;42&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(464,5,'4','','&lt;p&gt;What is the simple interest on a sum of Rs. 1500 if the rate of interest for the first 2 years is 4% per annum and for the last 4 years is 6% per annum?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;585&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;495&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;540&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;555&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Total interest is the sum of the two interests because this is simple interest.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total interest is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/155.26.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;496&quot; height=&quot;45&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(465,5,'4','','&lt;p&gt;Find the compound interest on Rs. 2500 at the rate of 10% per annum for 18 months when interest is compounded half yearly.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;395&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;375&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;385&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;415&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Since the money is compounded half yearly, the effective rate is 10/2 = 5%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;There are 3 such periods in 18 months.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, compound interest is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/155.27.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;439&quot; height=&quot;41&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(466,5,'4','','&lt;p&gt;What is the rate of simple interest for the first 3 years if the sum of Rs. 3600 becomes Rs. 5148 in 10 years and the rate of interest for the last 7 years is 5%?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;3%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5%&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Let the rate of interest required be r%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total interest is the sum of the two interests because this is simple interest.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total interest is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/155.28.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;433&quot; height=&quot;41&quot; /&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/155.28.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;402&quot; height=&quot;47&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(467,5,'4','','&lt;p&gt;Raju borrows Rs. 25000 from two money lenders. He pays interest at the rate of 10% per annum for one loan and at the rate of 14% per annum for the other. The total interest he pays for the entire year is Rs. 3100. How much does he borrow at the rate of 14%?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;15000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;12500&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;17500&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Let us assume he borrowed x on 10% interest and (25000-x) on 14% interest.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, interest will be &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/155.29.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;546&quot; height=&quot;48&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, money borrowed on 14% interest is Rs. 15000.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(468,5,'4','','&lt;p&gt;Divide Rs. 10,000 into two parts so that simple interest on the first part for 3 years at 6% p.a. may be equal to the simple interest on the second part for 2 years at 8% p.a. the value of the first part is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4300&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4500&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4700&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4100&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Let the two parts be x and (10000 - x) respectively.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The interest in both the cases is equal.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/155.30.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;518&quot; height=&quot;48&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the first part is Rs. 4705.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(469,6,'1','','&lt;p&gt;I sold two watches, for Rs. 300 each, one at a loss of 10% and the other at a profit of 10%. What is the percent loss (-) or the percent profit (+) that resulted from the transaction?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1% loss&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1% profit&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2% profit&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;No Profit, no loss&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;If the selling price of two items is same and one is sold at x% profit and the other at x% loss, then the overall loss is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/162.1.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;31&quot; height=&quot;42&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(470,6,'1','','&lt;p&gt;I sold two watches each costing Rs. 300 each, one at a loss of 10% and the other at a profit of 10%. What is the percent loss (-) or the percent profit (+) that resulted from the transaction?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1% loss&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1% profit&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2% profit&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;No Profit, no loss&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;If the cost price of two items is same and one is sold at x% profit and the other at x% loss, then there is no overall loss or profit.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(471,6,'1','','&lt;p&gt;A loss of 5% was suffered by selling a plot for Rs. 4,085. The cost price of the plot was&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 4350&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 4259.25&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 4200&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 4300&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;Since there is a loss of 5%, the selling price is 0.95x where x is the cost price. So, the cost price will be equal to 4,085 &amp;times; &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/162.3.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;30&quot; height=&quot;42&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 4300.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(472,6,'1','','&lt;p&gt;A machine costs 2000. If it is sold at a loss of 20%, what will be its cost price as a percentage of its selling price?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;120%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;125%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;80%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;100%&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;If the loss is 20% and the cost price is C, then the selling price will be S = 0.8C.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, required ratio is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/162.4.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;151&quot; height=&quot;34&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 125%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;This value does not depend on the actual value of C.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(473,6,'1','','&lt;p&gt;A shopkeeper sold an item for Rs. 2400 and made a profit of 60% in the process. Find his profit per cent if he had sold his goods for Rs. 1800.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;20%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;25%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;No Profit, no loss&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;His profit percentage in the first case is 60%. So, if the cost price of the article is C, then the selling price is 1.6C.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, 1.6C = 2400 =&amp;gt; C = 2400/1.6 = 1500.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, profit percentage in the second case is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/162.5.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;205&quot; height=&quot;43&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 20%.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(474,6,'1','','&lt;p&gt;A feeding bottle is sold for Rs. 450. Sales tax accounts for one-fifth of this and profit one-third of the remainder. Find the cost price of the feeding bottle&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 300&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 210&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 250&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;RS. 360&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;We know that the selling price is the sum of cost price, the sales tax and the profit.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/162.6.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;248&quot; height=&quot;35&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= Rs.210.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(475,6,'1','','&lt;p&gt;The cost price of a cup and a bottle is Rs. 428. If the bottle costs 14% more than the cup, find the cost price of the cup.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;200&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;228&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;240&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;258&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Let the cost of the cup be x. So, the cost of the bottle is 1.14x.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total cost is x + 1.14x = 2.14x = 428 =&amp;gt; x = 200.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, cost of the bottle is 1.14 &amp;times; 200= Rs. 228.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(476,6,'1','','&lt;p&gt;A tradesman&amp;rsquo;s prices are 20% above C.P. He allows his customers some discount on his bill and makes a profit of 8%. The rate of discount is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;12%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;14%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;16%&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;His mark-up price is 1.20C where C is the cost price.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Given that his mark-up price is 1.08C as there is only 8% profit.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the rate of discount is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/162.8.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;213&quot; height=&quot;46&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 10%.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(477,6,'1','','&lt;p&gt;A dealer sold a mixer for Rs. 420 at a loss of 12.5%. At what price should he have sold it to gain 12.5%?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 620&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;RS. 540&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 650&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 750&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Since there is a loss of 12.5%, the selling price is 7x/8 where x is the cost price.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the cost price will be equal to 420 &amp;times; (8/7)= 480.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;To get a profit of 12.5%, the selling price should be &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/162.9.3.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;156&quot; height=&quot;42&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= Rs.540&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(478,6,'1','','&lt;p&gt;On selling 33 meters of cloth, a person gained an amount equivalent to the S.P. of 11 meters of cloth. The profit in the deal is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;50%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;20%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;70%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;30%&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Let the selling price of 1 meter of cloth be S and its cost price is C.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, 33(S-C) = 11S =&amp;gt; 33C = 22S =&amp;gt; S = (3/2) C.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Profit percentage is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/162.10.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;47&quot; height=&quot;43&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;times; 100% = 50%.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(479,6,'1','','&lt;p&gt;A dishonest dealer claims to sell his goods at cost price, but he uses a weight of 960 gram for the kg weight. His gain percent is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4 1/6%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2 1/2%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;3 3/4%&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Since he uses 960 grams for every 1000 grams sold, his gain is 40 grams for the cost of 960 grams.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, profit percentage is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/162.11.4.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;253&quot; height=&quot;43&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(480,6,'1','','&lt;p&gt;Ravi buys a radio at three-fourth of its value and sells it for 20% more than its value. What will be the profit percent?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;50%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;40%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;60%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;70%&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Let the original price be Rs. 100.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, cost price is (3/4) &amp;times; 100 = 75.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Selling price is 1.20 &amp;times; 100 = 120.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, profit percentage is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/162.12.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;229&quot; height=&quot;48&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 60%.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(481,6,'1','','&lt;p&gt;A man buys pencils at 10 for Rs. 3 and sells at 8 for Rs. 3. His gain percent is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;20&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;25&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;30&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;27&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Cost price is Rs. 3/10 and selling price is Rs. 3/8.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Gain percent is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/162.13.3.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;186&quot; height=&quot;54&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 25%.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(482,6,'1','','&lt;p&gt;An article was sold at a loss of 5%. If it were sold for Rs. 30 more, the gain would have been 1.25%. The cost price of the article is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 488&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 480&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 460&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 420&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Let the cost price be C.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If it is sold at 5% loss, then selling price is S&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; = 0.95C.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If it is sold at 1.25% profit, then selling price is S&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; = 1.0125C.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Given S&lt;sub&gt;2&amp;nbsp;&lt;/sub&gt;- S&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; = 30 =&amp;gt; 0.0625C = 30 =&amp;gt; C = 30/0.0625 = Rs. 480.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(483,6,'1','','&lt;p&gt;Amar purchased a bag with 25% discount on the labelled price. At what percentage profit on the price he bought should he sell it to make 20% profit on the labelled price?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;60%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;40%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;45%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;50%&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Let the labelled price be Rs.100.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If it is bought at 25% discount, then cost price is S&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; = Rs.75.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If it is sold at 20% profit on labelled price, then selling price is S&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; = Rs.120.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Profit percentage is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/162.15.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;208&quot; height=&quot;44&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 60%.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(484,6,'1','','&lt;p&gt;Listed price of an article is Rs. 65. A customer pays Rs. 56.16 for it. He was given two successive discounts. If the first discount is 10%, find the second.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;8%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4%&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;Final discount is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/162.16.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;215&quot; height=&quot;35&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 13.6 %.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If two successive discounts are x% and y%, then effective discount is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/162.16.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;92&quot; height=&quot;33&quot; /&gt;%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/162.16.3.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;288&quot; height=&quot;43&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 4%.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(485,6,'1','','&lt;p&gt;A single discount equivalent to a discount series of 20%, 10% and 25% is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;55%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;54%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;46%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;42%&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;The final price after the discounts is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/162.17.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;376&quot; height=&quot;38&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the effective discount percentage is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/162.17.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;73&quot; height=&quot;46&quot; /&gt;X 100% = 46%.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(486,6,'1','','&lt;p&gt;A trader allows two successive discounts of 20% and 10%. If he sells an article for Rs. 108, then the market price of the article is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 140&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 142&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 148&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 150&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;If two successive discounts are x% and y%, then effective discount is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/162.18.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;97&quot; height=&quot;37&quot; /&gt;%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, discount in this case is 30 + 10 - (200/100) = 28%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If the market price of the article is C and the discount is x%, then the selling price is C - (xC/100).&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, C - 0.28C = 108 =&amp;gt; C = 1.08/72 = Rs.150.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(487,6,'1','','&lt;p&gt;How many kilograms of sugar worth Rs. 3.60 per kg should be mixed with 8 kg of sugar worth Rs. 4.20 per kg such that by selling the mixture at Rs. 4.40 per kg, there may be a gain of 10%?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;8&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;The selling price is Rs. 4.4 and there is gain of 10%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the actual price of the mixture is 4.4 &amp;times; (100/110) = Rs.4.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Let x kgs of Rs. 3.60 variety be mixed with 8 kg of Rs. 4.20 variety to get an average price of Rs. 4 per kg.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, 3.6x + (8 &amp;times; 4.20) = 4(x + 8) =&amp;gt; 0.4x = (8 &amp;times; 0.2) =&amp;gt; x = 4.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, 4 kg should be used.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(488,6,'1','','&lt;p&gt;Ramesh purchased four old cycles at the rate of Rs. 625 for each. He spent Rs. 175 on each cycle for repairing and painting. At what price should he sell each cycle in order to make 35% profit on the money he spent?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 1,019&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 1,000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 1,080&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;RS 844&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Total cost price for each cycle is 625 + 175 = Rs.800.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;He wants a profit of 35%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, selling price should be 1.35C = 1.35 &amp;times; 800 = Rs.1080.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(489,6,'2','','&lt;p&gt;Mr. Smith decides to sell both his cars. He sells the first car at a loss of 20%. He marks the second car up by 100% and then gives a discount of 40%. What is the percentage loss or gain in the transaction, given that the selling prices of both the cars are the same?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2.5% profit&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2.5% loss&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5% profit&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10% profit&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Let the cost price of first car be C&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; and that of second car be C&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Selling price of first car is S&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; = 0.8C&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Selling price of second car is 2C&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;(1 - 0.4) = 1.2C&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Given S&lt;sub&gt;1&amp;nbsp;&lt;/sub&gt;= S&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;. So, C&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; = (1.2/0.8)C&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; = 1.5C&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total profit is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/163.1.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;353&quot; height=&quot;46&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= -2.5%. So, there is 2.5% loss.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(490,6,'2','','&lt;p&gt;When John and David went for shopping, initially John had twice the money than David. They together bought things amounting to Rs.250, out of which David&amp;rsquo;s share was 60%. At the end John was left with thrice the amount that David had. What was the amount with David at the beginning?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;350&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;700&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;175&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;200&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Let the amount of money with David be x, then the amount with John is 2x.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;In Rs. 250, David&amp;rsquo;s share is 60% which is (60/100) &amp;times; 250 = 150.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Final ratio of money left with David and john is 1: 3.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/163.2.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;94&quot; height=&quot;43&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;=&amp;gt; 3x - 450 = 2x - 100 =&amp;gt; x = 350&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(491,6,'2','','&lt;p&gt;An article costs Rs.1000 to a manufacturer who lists its price at Rs.1200. He sells it to a trader at a discount of 10%. The trader gets a further discount of 5% on his net payment for paying in cash. Calculate the amount that the trader pays to the manufacturer.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 1100&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 1080&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 1020&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 1026&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;Total discount that the trader gets is given by &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/163.3.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;114&quot; height=&quot;40&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= (10 + 5 - 0.5) = 14.5%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the amount that he pays is 1200 &amp;times; (85.5/100) = Rs.1026.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(492,6,'2','','&lt;p&gt;A publisher printed 3,000 copies of a book at a cost of Rs. 2,400. He gave 500 copies free to heads of institutions. He allowed a discount of 25% on published price and gave one extra copy when a customer buys 24 copies at a time. He sold all the copies in this scheme. If the published price is Rs. 3.25, find his gain or loss percentage.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;100%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;143.75%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;157.5%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;163.25%&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Total cost is Rs.2400.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total price she got is (500 &amp;times; 0) + &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/163.4.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;170&quot; height=&quot;42&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= Rs.5850 if we assume that each and every customer bought 24 copies and so got one free.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, his profit percentage is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/163.4.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;91&quot; height=&quot;41&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;times; 100 = 143.75%&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(493,6,'2','','&lt;p&gt;There are two consecutive discounts of 35% and 10% on a watch. If a person paid Rs. 1170 for that, then what was the original price of the watch before the discounts?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 2000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 1800&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 1900&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 1700&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Equivalent discount in case of 2 successive discounts of x% and y% is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/163.5.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;111&quot; height=&quot;33&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Here, the final discount is 35 + 10 - (350/100) = 41.5 %.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If the original price is C, then discounted price is 0.585C = 1170 =&amp;gt; C = 1170/0.585 = Rs.2000&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(494,6,'2','','&lt;p&gt;Raghu bought 10kg. of sugar at the rate of Rs. 14 per kg and 15kg. of sugar at the rate of Rs. 16 per kg. He mixed the two varieties and sold the mixture at the rate of Rs. 18 per kg. What was his total gain by doing so?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 50&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 70&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 40&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 80&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Total cost price is C = (10 &amp;times; 14) + (15 &amp;times; 16) = 380.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total selling price is S = 25 &amp;times; 18 = 450.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, gain is equal to S - C = Rs.70.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(495,6,'2','','&lt;p&gt;A man buys an article and sells it at a profit of 20%. If he bought at 20% less and sold it for Rs. 75 less, he would have gained 25%. What is the cost price?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 375&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 425&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 350&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Data inadequate&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Let the cost price be C.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;In the first case, selling price is 1.2C.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;In the second case, cost price is 0.8C and the selling price is 1.2C - 75.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Profit in the second case is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/163.7.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;119&quot; height=&quot;38&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;times; 100% = 25%&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;=&amp;gt; 4(0.4C - 75) = 0.8C =&amp;gt; 0.8C = 300 =&amp;gt; C = Rs.375.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the cost price is Rs.375.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(496,6,'2','','&lt;p&gt;A person bought 20 litres of milk at the rate of Rs. 8 per litre. He got it churned after spending Rs. 10 and got 5 kg. of cream and 20 litres of toned milk. If he sold the cream at Rs. 30 per kg. and toned milk at Rs. 4 per litre, his profit in the transaction is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;25%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;35.3%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;37.5%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;42%&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Total cost for him is (20 &amp;times; 8) + 10 = Rs.170.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;He got 5 kg, of cream and 20 kg of toned milk.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Selling price is (5 &amp;times; 30) + (4 &amp;times; 20) = Rs.230.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Profit percentage is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/163.8.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;190&quot; height=&quot;44&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 35.3%.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(497,6,'2','','&lt;p&gt;The cost of production of a cordless phone set in 2011 is Rs. 1800 divided between material, labour and overheads in the ratio 3: 4: 2. If the cordless phone set is marked at a price that gives a 20% profit on the component of price accounted for by labour and 10% profit on other segments, what is the marked price of the set?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 2000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 2160&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 1980&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 2060&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;Price of the materials is (3/9) &amp;times; 1800 = Rs.600.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Price of the labour is (4/9) &amp;times; 1800 = Rs.800.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Price of the overheads is (2/9) &amp;times; 1800 = Rs.400.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, marked price is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/163.9.4.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;222&quot; height=&quot;44&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 1100 + 960 = Rs.2060.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(498,6,'2','','&lt;p&gt;A man sells 6 articles for Rs. 20 and makes a profit of 33.33%. Find his gain or loss percent if he sells 10 such articles for Rs. 25.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;20%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;25%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;40%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10%&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Cost price of each article is C, then the selling price is 4C/3 because the profit percentage is 33.33%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, 6 &amp;times; (4C/3) = 20 =&amp;gt; C = 20/8 = 2.5.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, cost price of 8 articles is 8 &amp;times; 2.5 = 20.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, profit percentage is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/163.10.4.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;169&quot; height=&quot;43&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 25%.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(499,6,'2','','&lt;p&gt;A makes an article for Rs. 200 and sells it to B at a profit of 25%. B sells it to C, who sells it to D for Rs. 345 making a profit of 15%. What profit percent did B make?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;20%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;25%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;30%&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Cost price of B is (120/100) &amp;times; 200 = Rs.240.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If C sells it for Rs.355, he would get a profit of 15%. So, if S is the selling price of B, then 1.15S = 355&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;=&amp;gt; S = 355/1.15 = 300.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Profit percentage for B is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/163.11.3.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;184&quot; height=&quot;42&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 25%.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(500,6,'2','','&lt;p&gt;A shopkeeper sells sugar in such a way that the selling price of 950 grams is the same as the cost price of one kilogram. Find his gain percent.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5.2%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6.25%&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;It is given that 0.95S = C =&amp;gt; S = C/0.95 = 1.052 C.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Profit percentage is (0.052C/C) &amp;times; 100% = 5.2%&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(501,6,'2','','&lt;p&gt;A sold a table to B at a profit of 20%. B sold the same table to C for Rs.600 thereby making a profit of 25%. Find the cost price of the table, if A bought the table from X and it is known that X gained 25% in the transaction&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 320&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 400&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 480&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 250&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Let cost price be x. There are three phases and 3 profits involved. The final price is Rs.600.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Final price will be x &amp;times; &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/163.13.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;119&quot; height=&quot;41&quot; /&gt;= 600&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;=&amp;gt; x = 600 &amp;times; (16/30) = Rs.320.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(502,6,'2','','&lt;p&gt;A man sells a plot of land at 6% profit. If he had sold it at 10% profit, he would have received Rs. 3000 more. What is the selling price of the land?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 60,000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs.75,000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 79,500&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 78,500&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;If the cost price is C, then the selling price to get a 6% profit is 1.06C and 10% profit is 1.1C.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The difference in two cases is 0.04C = 3000 =&amp;gt; C = 3000/0.4 = Rs.75000.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the selling price of the land is (106/100) &amp;times; 75000 = Rs.79,500&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(503,6,'2','','&lt;p&gt;A man buys two cycles for a total cost of Rs. 1000. By selling one for 4/5th of its cost and other for 5/4th of its cost, he makes a profit of Rs. 70 on the whole transaction. Find the cost price of lower priced cycle.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 470&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs.400&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs .350&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 450&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Let the cost prices of the two cycles be x and y.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;so, x + y = 1000; &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/163.15.3.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;57&quot; height=&quot;38&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 1070.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;25x + 16y = 21400; 16x + 16y = 16000 =&amp;gt; 9x = 5400 =&amp;gt; x = 600.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the cost of lower priced cycle is Rs.400.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(504,6,'2','','&lt;p&gt;A merchant bought two transistors, which together cost him Rs. 1000. He sold one of them at a loss of 25% and other at a gain of 12.5%. If the selling price of both the transistors are equal, find the cost of the higher priced transistor.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 600&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 650&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 550&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 575&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;If the cost prices if the two transistors are x and y, then the two selling prices are 0.75x and 1.125y.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/163.16.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;60&quot; height=&quot;44&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;=&amp;gt; 2x = 3y.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the cost of higher priced transistor is (3/5) &amp;times; 1000 = Rs.600.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(505,6,'2','','&lt;p&gt;Two dealers X and Y selling the same model of refrigerator mark them under the same selling prices. X gives successive discounts of 25% and 6% and Y gives successive discounts of 16% and 15%. From whom is it more profitable to purchase the refrigerator?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;X&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Y&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Both offer the same price&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Data inadequate&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Effective discount when the individual discounts are x% and y% is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/163.17.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;113&quot; height=&quot;36&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;For X, the discount is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/163.17.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;116&quot; height=&quot;42&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 29.5%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;For Y, the discount is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/163.17.3.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;117&quot; height=&quot;36&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 28.6%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, it is better to buy the product near X.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(506,6,'2','','&lt;p&gt;A watch dealer pays 10% custom duty on a watch that costs Rs. 1000 abroad. For how much should he mark it, if he desires to make a profit of 20% after giving a discount of 25% to the buyer?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 1500&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 1760&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 1860&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 1680&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;His actual cost is 1000 + [(10/100) &amp;times; 1000] = Rs.1100.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Let the marked price be M. Since discount is 25%, the selling price is 0.75M.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Since profit percentage is 20%, the selling price will be 1.2 &amp;times; 1100 = 1320.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, 3M/4 = 1320 =&amp;gt; M = 1320 &amp;times; (4/3) = Rs.1760.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(507,6,'2','','&lt;p&gt;A sells a car priced at Rs. 100,000. He gives a discount of 10% on the first Rs. 40000 and 6% on the remaining Rs. 60000. His competitor B sells a car of the same make, priced at Rs. 110,000. If he wants to be competitive what percent discount should B offer on the marked price?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;17%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;15%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;18%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;20%&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Total discount offered is [(10/100) &amp;times; 40000] + [(6/100) &amp;times; 60000] = Rs.7600.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, in order to be competitive, his selling price should be 100000 - 7600 = 92400.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, his discount percentage should be 17600/1100 % = 17%.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(508,6,'2','','&lt;p&gt;The cost of manufacturing an article is made up of materials, labour and overheads in the ratio 2:4:3. If the cost of labour is Rs.400, find the profit percent if the article is sold for Rs.1200.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;33.33%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;25%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;20%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;30%&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Labour cost is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/163.20.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;98&quot; height=&quot;44&quot; /&gt;th of the total cost.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total cost is (9/4) &amp;times; 400 = 900.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, profit percentage is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/163.20.3.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;83&quot; height=&quot;39&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;times; 100% = 100/3 % = 33.33%.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(509,6,'3','','&lt;p&gt;A rectangular plot of area 900 sq. m is to be fenced: two adjoining sides with bricks and two others with wooden fence. One metre of the wooden fence costs Rs. 10 and one metre of the brick fence costs Rs. 25. The contractor has been given Rs. 3,000 to complete the task. The maximum profit that the contractor can get is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 1000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 900&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 800&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 700&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;If the length is l and the breadth is b, then one length and one breadth are to be fenced with wood and the other two sides is to be fenced with brick walls.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the cost to the contractor is (l + b) &amp;times; (10 + 25) = 35(l + b).&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;He will get the maximum profit when the value of l + b is the lowest. Since the area is fixed, the value of (l + b) will be lowest when l = b.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;But lb = 900 =&amp;gt; l = b = 30.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the minimum cost to the contractor is 35 &amp;times; (30 + 30) = 35 &amp;times; 60 = 2100.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the maximum profit is 3000 - 2100 = Rs.900.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(510,6,'3','','&lt;p&gt;Price of food grains have risen by 10% and of other items of consumption by 15%. If the ratio of an employee&#039;s expenditure on food grains and other items is 2:5, by how much should his salary be increased so that he may maintain the same level of consumption as before, assuming that his present salary is Rs. 3500?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 450&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 400&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;RS. 425&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 475&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;Average increase of all items is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/164.2.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;187&quot; height=&quot;42&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the new salary should be &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/164.2.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;62&quot; height=&quot;39&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;times; 3500 = 795 &amp;times; 5 = Rs.3975.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the increase in the salary should be Rs. 475.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(511,6,'3','','&lt;p&gt;Mona makes 750 articles at a cost of 60 paise per article. He fixes the selling price such that if only 600 articles are sold, he would have made a profit of 40% on the outlay. However, 120 articles got spoilt and he was able to sell 630 articles at this price. Find his actual profit percent as the percentage of total outlay assuming that the unsold articles are useless.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;49.22%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;49%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;49.44%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;49.66%&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Total cost is 750 &amp;times; (60/100) = Rs. 450.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;For the profit to be 40%, the selling price should be 1.4C = 1.4 &amp;times; 450 = Rs.630.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, cost of each article will be (630/600) = Rs.1.05 because he assumes only 600 will be sold.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;630 items are sold at that cost, so the total selling price is 630 &amp;times; 1.05 = Rs. 661.50. Since the remaining articles are useless, money from them is 0.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, his final profit percentage is (221.5/450) &amp;times; 100 = 49.222.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(512,6,'3','','&lt;p&gt;A manufacturer estimates that on inspection, 12% of the articles he produces will be rejected. He accepts an order to supply 22,000 articles at 7.50 each. He estimates the profit on his outlay including the manufacturing of rejected articles, to be 20%. Find the cost of manufacturing each article.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 5&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 5.5&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs 5.75&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 5.25&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;If he produces 100 articles, only 88 will be accepted.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, In order to supply 22000 articles, he must manufacture 22000 &amp;times; (100/88) = 25000 articles.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The total money he earns is 22000 &amp;times; (15/2) &amp;nbsp;= 165000.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;His profit ratio is 20%. So, the total cost for him is 165000 &amp;times; (100/120) = Rs.137500.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, his cost of production of each article is (137500/25000) = Rs.5.50 per each article&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(513,6,'3','','&lt;p&gt;The cost of setting up the type of a magazine is Rs. 1000. The cost of running the printing machine is Rs. 120 per 100 copies. The cost of paper, ink and so on is 60 paise per copy. The magazines are sold at Rs. 2.75 each. 900 copies are printed, but only 784 copies are sold. What is the sum to be obtained from advertisements to give a profit of 10% on the cost?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 646&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;RS. 726&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 784&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;RS. 824&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Total cost to print all the magazines is 1000 + &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/164.5.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;160&quot; height=&quot;45&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= Rs.2620.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;To get a 10% profit, the total return from sales should be 1.1C = 1.1 &amp;times; 2620 = Rs. 2882.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Only 784 magazines are sold, so money from the magazines is 784 &amp;times; 2.75 = Rs. 2156.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, money that should come from advertisements is 2882 - 2156 = Rs. 726.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(514,6,'3','','&lt;p&gt;A dishonest dealer marks up the price of his goods by 20% and gives a discount of 10% to the customer. He also uses a 900 gram weight instead of a 1 kilogram weight. Find his percentage profit due to these manoeuvres.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;17%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;19%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;20%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;22%&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;He buys 1000 grams for every kilogram and sells 900 grams for every kilogram. So, he saves 100 grams for every 900 grams sold.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, his profit percentage with false weights is (1/9) &amp;times; 100% = 11.11%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;His price on each good is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/164.6.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;79&quot; height=&quot;44&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 1.08 times the original price.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, if the original cost is Rs. 100, his selling price is Rs.111.11 &amp;times; 1.08 = Rs.120.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, his profit percentage is 20%.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(515,6,'3','','&lt;p&gt;A dishonest dealer marks up the price of his goods by 20% and gives a discount of 10% to the customer. Besides, he also cheats both his supplier and his buyer by 100 grams while buying or selling 1 kilogram. Find the percentage profit earned by the shopkeeper.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;22%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;30%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;32%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;36%&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;He buys 1100 grams for every kilogram and sells 900 grams for every kilogram. So, he saves 200 grams for every 900 grams sold.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, his profit percentage with false weights is (2/9) &amp;times; 100% = 22.22%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;His price on each good is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/164.7.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;72&quot; height=&quot;40&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 1.08 times the original price.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, if the original cost is Rs. 100, his selling price is Rs. 122.22 &amp;times; 1.08 = Rs.132.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, his profit percentage is 32%.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(516,6,'3','','&lt;p&gt;The cost of 20 apples, 20 bananas and 20 oranges is Rs. 220. A boy had Rs. 19 for which he could buy an apple, two bananas and three oranges. But he wanted to buy three apples, two bananas and one orange by paying some more money. How much more money will he fall short of?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;7&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;8&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;A + 2B + 3O = 19.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;20A + 20B + 20O = 220 =&amp;gt; A + B + O = 11.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;3A + 2B + O = 4(A + B + O) - (A + 2B + 3O) = 44 - 19 = Rs.25.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;He will fall short of 25 - 19 = Rs.6.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(517,6,'3','','&lt;p&gt;A whole-seller allows a discount of 20% on the list price to a retailer. The retailer sells at 5% discount on the list price. If the customer paid Rs. 380 for an article, what profit is made by the retailer?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 40&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 50&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 60&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 80&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Let the marked price be C. Then he sells it at a cost 0.95C and buys it at a cost 0.8C.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the profit percentage is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/164.9.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;150&quot; height=&quot;44&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The customer bought it for Rs.380. So, 0.95C = 380 =&amp;gt; C = 400.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the profit for the shopkeeper is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/164.9.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;72&quot; height=&quot;42&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= Rs.60.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(518,6,'3','','Which is the better deal from the below?\na) A straight discount of 60%\nb) Two successive discounts of 30% each\nc) Three successive discounts of 20% each\nd) Four successive discounts of 15% each','Sraight discount of 60%','Two successive discounts of 30%','Three successive discounts of 20%','Four successive discounts of 15%','1','If the sum of the values is the same, it is always better to have a straight discount. The effective value decreases with each successive discount.','Hard'),(519,6,'3','','&lt;p&gt;A watch dealer sells watches at Rs. 600 per watch. However, he is forced to give two successive discounts of 10% and 5% respectively. However, he recovers the sales tax on the net sale price from the customer at 5% of the net price. What price does a customer have to pay him to buy the watch?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;RS. 513&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;RS. 538.5&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 540&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;RS. 543.5&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Total effective discount is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/164.11.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;243&quot; height=&quot;36&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 14.5%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, if C is the marked price, then the selling price would be C - (14.5C/100) = 0.855C.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The sales tax is collected on the net amount. So, the price after the sales tax is 1.05 &amp;times; 0.855C = 0.8975C.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the final cost price is 0.8975 &amp;times; 600 = Rs.538.5&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(520,6,'3','','&lt;p&gt;A carpenter wants to sell 80 articles. If he sells them at Rs. 100 per article, he would be able to sell all the chairs. But for every Rs. 10 increase in price, he will be left with one additional unsold article. At what selling price would he be able to maximise his profits (assuming unsold articles remain with him)?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;RS. 450&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;RS. 360&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 400&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;RS. 420&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Since all the articles are already made, the cost price will not change.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The selling price must be made such that the total selling price is maximum.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If the selling price is (100 + 10n), then the number of articles sold are (80 - n).&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the total selling price is S = (100 + 10n)(80 - n).&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;It is maximum when &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/164.12.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;246&quot; height=&quot;42&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 0 =&amp;gt; 20n = 700 =&amp;gt; n = 35.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, in order to get maximum profit, the selling price should be Rs. 450.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(521,6,'3','','&lt;p&gt;A shopkeeper makes a profit of x% by selling an object for Rs. 32. Had the cost price and selling price been interchanged, it would have led to a loss of 0.8x%. With the latter cost price, what should be the new selling price to get a profit of x%?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 40&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 38.4&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 41.6&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;RS. 35.2&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;His selling price is Rs.32 and he gets x% profit. So, the cost price is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/164.13.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;135&quot; height=&quot;57&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If the cost price and selling prices are reversed,, then the loss is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/164.13.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;215&quot; height=&quot;61&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 0.8x.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, x = 25%. If the new cost price is Rs. 32, then to get a profit of 25%, the selling price should be 32 &amp;times; (125/100) = Rs.40.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(522,6,'3','','&lt;p&gt;A shopkeeper calculates percentage profit on the buying price and another on the selling price. What will be their difference in profits if both claim a profit of 10% on goods sold for Rs. 3000?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 27&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;RS. 30&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;RS. 32&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;RS. 33&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;The profit for the first person is 10% on the buying price.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, to get 10% profit, if his cost price is C, the selling price should be 1.1C.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, 1.1C = 3000 =&amp;gt; C = 3000/1.1 = 2727.27.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, his profit is 3000 - 2727 = Rs. 273.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The profit for the first person is 10% on the selling price.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, to get 10% profit, if his selling price is C, the cost price should be 0.9C.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, his cost price is 0.9 &amp;times; 3000 = Rs.2700.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, his profit is 3000 - 2700 = Rs. 300.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, difference in the profits is Rs. 27.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(523,6,'3','','&lt;p&gt;A merchant makes a profit of 20% by selling an article. By how much would the profit increase, had he paid 10% less for it and the customer paid 10% more for it?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;20%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;25%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;26.67%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;30%&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;If the cost price of the article is C, then the normal selling price is 1.2C toget a profit of 20%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;However, he buys it for 10% less. So, he buys it for 0.9C.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The customer buys it for 10% more. So, the selling price is 1.1 &amp;times; 1.2C = 1.32C.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the actual profit percentage is (0.42C/0.9C) &amp;times; 100 = 46.67%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The profit percentage will increase by 26.67%.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(524,6,'3','','&lt;p&gt;A book was sold for a certain sum and there was a loss of 20%. Had it been sold for Rs. 36 more, there would have been a gain of 10%. What would be the profit if the book were sold for Rs. 168?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;20%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;25%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;30%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;40%&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;Let the cost price of the book be C. The selling price for 20% loss is 0.8C and 10% profit is 1.1C.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, 1.1C - 0.8C = 36 =&amp;gt; C = Rs.120.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, required profit is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/164.16.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;77&quot; height=&quot;42&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;times; 100 = 40%.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(525,6,'3','','&lt;p&gt;A rickshaw dealer buys 25 buses for Rs. 4000. Of these. 10 are capable of holding 30 persons and the rest are capable of holding up to 50 members. At what price must he sell the buses of first type so that if he sells the second type buses at th of this price, he makes a profit of 55% on his outlay?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 5000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 4500&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 4750&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 5500&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Total cost is Rs.4000 &amp;times; 25 = Rs.100000.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;In order to get 55% profit, total selling price should be 1.55C = Rs.155000.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Let the selling price of first type buses be x. Then the selling price of second type buses will be 7x/5.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total selling price for the first type is 10x + [15 &amp;times; (7x/5)] = 155000 =&amp;gt; x = 155000/31 = Rs.5000.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(526,6,'3','','&lt;p&gt;An apple vendor makes a profit of 20% by selling apples at a certain price. If he charges Rs. 3 higher per apple, he would gain 50%. Find the original price at which he sold an apple.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 15&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 12&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 8&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;RS. 25&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;If the cost price is C, the to get 205 profit, the selling price should be 1.2C and to get 50% profit, the selling price should be 1.5C.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, 1.5C - 0.5C = 0.3C = 3 =&amp;gt; C = Rs.10.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the original selling price is 1.2C = Rs.12.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(527,6,'3','','&lt;p&gt;The profit earned when an article is sold for Rs. 1000 is 14 times the loss incurred when it is sold for Rs. 250. At what price should the article be sold if it is desired to make a profit of 25%?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 350&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 325&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 375&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 400&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Let the cost price be C. So, the loss when sold at Rs. 250 is C - 250 and the profit when it is sold at Rs. 1000 is (1000 - C).&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, according to the question, 1000 - C = 14(C - 250) =&amp;gt; 15C = 4500 =&amp;gt; C = Rs.300.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The final profit should be 25%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the selling price should be (125/100) &amp;times; 300 = Rs.375.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(528,6,'3','','&lt;p&gt;In a certain town, shopkeepers have to buy and sell goods in the range of Rs. 500 to Rs. 999. A shopkeeper in such a town decides not to buy or sell goods for amounts that contain the digit 9 or for amounts that add up to 13 or are a multiple of 13. What is the maximum possible profit he can earn?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 389&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 388&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 387&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 386&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;The cost price should be minimum for maximum profit and it will be Rs. 500.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;He does not buy any good in the range Rs.889 to Rs. 999 because, they contain at least one nine.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the maximum price that he can sell for is Rs. 888.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, his profit will be Rs. 388.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(529,6,'4','','&lt;p&gt;Ravi sold two watches, each costing Rs. 400 each, one at a loss of 30% and the other at a profit of 30%. What is the percent loss (-) or the percent profit (+) that resulted from the transaction?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;9% loss&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1% profit&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;9% profit&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;no profit, no loss&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;If the selling price of two items is same and one is sold at x% profit and the other at x% loss, then the overall loss is x&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;/100%.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(530,6,'4','','&lt;p&gt;Hema sold two watches at Rs. 300 each, one at a loss of 15% and the other at a profit of 15%. What is the percent loss (-) or the percent profit (+) that resulted from the transaction?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2.25% loss&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1% profit&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2.25% profit&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;no profit, no loss&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;If the selling price of two items is same and one is sold at x% profit and the other at x% loss, then the overall loss is x&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;/100%.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(531,6,'4','','&lt;p&gt;I sold two watches, each costing for Rs. 1000 each, one at a loss of 20% and the other at a profit of 20%. What is the percent loss (-) or the percent profit (+) that resulted from the transaction?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1% loss&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1% profit&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2% profit&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;no profit, no loss&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;If the cost price of two items is same and one is sold at x% profit and the other at x% loss, then there is no overall loss or profit.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(532,6,'4','','&lt;p&gt;A loss of 15% was suffered by selling a plot for Rs. 5000. The cost price of the plot was&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 5680.5&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 5921.50&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 5800&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 5882.35&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;Since there is a loss of 15%, the selling price is 0.85x where x is the cost price.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the cost price will be equal to 5000 &amp;times; (100/85) = 5882.35.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(533,6,'4','','&lt;p&gt;A shopkeeper sold an item for Rs. 3000 and made a profit of 50% in the process. Find his profit per cent if he had sold his goods for Rs. 2500.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;20%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;25%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;no profit, no loss&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;His profit percentage in the first case is 50%. So, if the cost price of the article is C, then the selling price is 1.5C.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, 1.5C = 3000 =&amp;gt; C = 3000/1.5 = 2000.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, profit percentage in the second case is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.5.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;90&quot; height=&quot;43&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;times; 100% = = 25%.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(534,6,'4','','&lt;p&gt;The cost price of a cup and a bottle is Rs. 550. If the bottle costs 20% more than the cup, find the cost price of the cup.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;250&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;300&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;275&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;225&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Let the cost of the cup be x. So, the cost of the bottle is 1.24x.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total cost is x + 1.20x = 2.20x = 550 =&amp;gt; x = 250.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, cost of the bottle is 1.20 &amp;times; 250 = Rs.300.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(535,6,'4','','&lt;p&gt;The cost price of a cup and a bottle is Rs. 575. If the bottle costs 30% more than the cup, find the cost price of the cup.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;350&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;325&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;300&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;250&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Let the cost of the cup be x. So, the cost of the bottle is 1.30x.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total cost is x + 1.30x = 2.30x = 575 =&amp;gt; x = 250.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, cost of the bottle is 1.30 &amp;times; 250 = Rs.325.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(536,6,'4','','&lt;p&gt;A tradesman&amp;rsquo;s prices are 30% above C.P. He allows his customers some discount on his bill and makes a profit of 5%. The rate of discount is:&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;19.23%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;25%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;23.35%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;22%&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;His mark-up price is 1.30C where C is the cost price.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Given that his selling price is 1.05C as there is only 5% profit.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the rate of discount is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.8.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;104&quot; height=&quot;45&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;times; 100% = &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.8.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;40&quot; height=&quot;43&quot; /&gt;%&amp;nbsp;= 19.23%.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(537,6,'4','','&lt;p&gt;On selling 55 meters of cloth, a person gained an amount equivalent to the S.P. of 5 meters of cloth. The profit in the deal is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;20%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;70%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;30%&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Let the selling price of 1 meter of cloth be S and its cost price is C.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, 55(S - C) = 5S =&amp;gt; 55C = 50S =&amp;gt; S = 11/10C&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Profit percentage is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.9.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;44&quot; height=&quot;41&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;times; 100% = 10%.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(538,6,'4','','&lt;p&gt;On selling 44 meters of cloth, a person gained an amount equivalent to the S.P. of 12 meters of cloth. The profit in the deal is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;37.5%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;40%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;35%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;30%&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Let the selling price of 1 meter of cloth be S and its cost price is C.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, 44(S - C) = 12S =&amp;gt; 44C = 32S =&amp;gt; S = 21/16C.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Profit percentage is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.10.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;46&quot; height=&quot;39&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;times; 100% = &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.10.3.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;24&quot; height=&quot;41&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;times; 100% = 37.5.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(539,6,'4','','&lt;p&gt;A dishonest dealer claims to sell his goods at cost price, but he uses a weight of 950 gram for the kg weight. His gain percent is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5 5/19%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4 5/19%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;3 3/4%&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Since he uses 950 grams for every 1000 grams sold, his gain is 50 grams for the cost of 950 grams.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, profit percentage is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.11.4.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;36&quot; height=&quot;46&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;times; 100% = 100/19 % = 5 5/19%.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(540,6,'4','','&lt;p&gt;Kishore buys a radio at three-fourth of its value and sells it for 35% more than its value. What will be the profit percent?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;50%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;40%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;60%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;80%&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;Let the original price be Rs. 100.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, cost price is (3/4) &amp;times; 100 = 75.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Selling price is 1.35 &amp;times; 100 = 135.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, profit percentage is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.10.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;46&quot; height=&quot;39&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;times; 100% = &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.12.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;66&quot; height=&quot;43&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;times;100% = 80%.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(541,6,'4','','&lt;p&gt;An article was sold at a loss of 10%. If it were sold for Rs. 24 more, the gain would have been 2%. The cost price of the article is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 208&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 206&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;RS. 200&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;RS. 202&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Let the cost price be C.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If it is sold at 10% loss, then selling price is S&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; = 0.90C.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If it is sold at 2% profit, then selling price is S&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; = 1.02C.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Given S&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; - S&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; = 24 =&amp;gt; 0.12C = 24 =&amp;gt; C = 24/0.12 = Rs.200.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(542,6,'4','','&lt;p&gt;An article was sold at a loss of 25%. If it were sold for Rs. 50 more, the gain would have been 25%. The selling price of the article in the first case is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 150&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;RS. 100&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 75&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 125&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Let the cost price be C.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If it is sold at 25% loss, then selling price is S&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; = 0.75C.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If it is sold at 25% profit, then selling price is S&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; = 1.25C.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Given S&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; - S&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; = 50 =&amp;gt; 0.5C = 50 =&amp;gt; C = 50/0.5 = Rs.100.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the initial selling price is 0.75C = Rs.75.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(543,6,'4','','&lt;p&gt;Listed price of an article is Rs. 100. A customer pays Rs. 76 for it. He was given two successive discounts. If the first discount is 20%, find the second.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;8%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4%&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Final discount is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.15.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;63&quot; height=&quot;46&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;times; 100% = &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.15.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;67&quot; height=&quot;40&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;times; 100% = 24%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If two successive discounts are x% and y%, then effective discount is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.15.3.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;109&quot; height=&quot;42&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, 20 + x - (x/5) = 24 =&amp;gt; 4x/5 = 4 =&amp;gt; x = 20/4 = 5%.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(544,6,'4','','&lt;p&gt;Listed price of an article is Rs. 120. A customer pays Rs. 85.5 for it. He was given two successive discounts. If the first discount is 25%, find the second.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;8%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4%&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Final discount is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.16.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;64&quot; height=&quot;43&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;times; 100% = &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.16.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;81&quot; height=&quot;46&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;times; 100% = 28.75%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If two successive discounts are x% and y%, then effective discount is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.16.3.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;110&quot; height=&quot;33&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, 25 + x - (x/4) = 28.75 =&amp;gt; (3x/4) = 3.75 =&amp;gt; x = (15/3) = 5%.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(545,6,'4','','&lt;p&gt;A single discount equivalent to a discount series of 12%,25% and 50% is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;52%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;55%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;63%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;67%&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;The final price after the discounts is C &amp;times; &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.17.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;320&quot; height=&quot;42&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 0.33C.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the effective discount percentage is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.17.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;73&quot; height=&quot;40&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;times; 100% = 67%.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(546,6,'4','','&lt;p&gt;On selling a certain commodity for Rs 375, there is as much gain as loss on selling it for Rs 325. The C.P of the commodity&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 370&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 350&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 390&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 365&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;If the selling price is S&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; to get x% profit and S&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; to get x% loss, then the cost price C = &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.18.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;53&quot; height=&quot;38&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, C = &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.18.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;74&quot; height=&quot;41&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= Rs.350.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(547,6,'4','','&lt;p&gt;On selling a certain commodity for Rs 693, there is as much gain as loss on selling it for Rs 587. The C.P of the commodity&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 670&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 650&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 690&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 640&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;If the selling price is S&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; to get x% profit and S&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; to get x% loss, then the cost price C = &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.19.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;48&quot; height=&quot;41&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, C = &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.19.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;71&quot; height=&quot;42&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= Rs.640.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(548,6,'4','','&lt;p&gt;Usman decides to sell both his cars. He sells the first car at a loss of 30%. He marks the second car up by 100% and then gives a discount of 50%. What is the percentage loss or gain in the transaction, given that the selling prices of both the cars are the same?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2.5% profit&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;17.35% profit&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5% profit&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10% profit&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Let the cost price of first car be C&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; and that of second car be C&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Selling price of first car is S&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; = 0.7C&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Selling price of second car is 2S&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;(1 - 0.5) = C&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Given S&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; = S&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, C&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; = (C&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;/0.7) = 1.42C&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total profit is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.20.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;117&quot; height=&quot;41&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;times; 100% = &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.20.3.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;126&quot; height=&quot;48&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;times; 100 = -17.35%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, there is 17.35% loss.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(549,6,'4','','&lt;p&gt;A publisher printed 5,000 copies of a book at a cost of Rs. 3,000. He gave 800 copies free to heads of institutions. He allowed a discount of 15% on published price and gave one extra copy when a customer buys 14 copies at a time. He sold all the copies in this scheme. If the published price is Rs. 2.25, find his gain percentage.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;100%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;149.95%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;157.5%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;163.25%&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Total cost is Rs.3000.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total price she got is (800 &amp;times; 0) + [4200 &amp;times; (14/15) &amp;times; 2.25 &amp;times; (85/100)] = Rs.7497 if we assume that each and every customer bought 14 copies and so got one free.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, his profit percentage is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.21.3.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;93&quot; height=&quot;40&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;times; 100 = 149.95%&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(550,6,'4','','&lt;p&gt;There are two consecutive discounts of 25% and 15% on an article. If a person paid Rs. 2200 for that, then what was the original price of the article before the discounts?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 3453.68&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 3333&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 3658&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 3570&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Equivalent discount in case of 2 successive discounts of x% and y% is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.22.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;115&quot; height=&quot;36&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Here, the final discount is 25 + 15 - (375/100) = 36.25 %.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If the original price is C, then discounted price is 0.637C = 2200 =&amp;gt; C = 2200/0.637 = Rs.3453.68.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(551,6,'4','','&lt;p&gt;There are two consecutive discounts of 5% and 15% on a TV. If a person paid Rs. 1270 for that, then what was the original price of the TV before the discounts?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 1573&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 1653&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;RS. 1725&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 1485&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Equivalent discount in case of 2 successive discounts of x% and y% is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.23.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;113&quot; height=&quot;39&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Here, the final discount is 5 + 15 - (75/100) = 19.25 %.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If the original price is C, then discounted price is 0.807C = 1170 =&amp;gt; C = 1170/0.807 = Rs.1573.72.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(552,6,'4','','&lt;p&gt;Vamsi bought 23 kg. of coffee at the rate of Rs. 15 per kg and 17kg. of coffee at the rate of Rs. 20 per kg. He mixed the two varieties and sold the mixture at the rate of Rs. 18 per kg. What was his total gain by doing so?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 135&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 125&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 115&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 105&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Total cost price is C = (23 &amp;times; 15) + (17 &amp;times; 20) = 685.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total selling price is S = 40 &amp;times; 20 = 800.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, gain is equal to S - C = Rs.115.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(553,6,'4','','&lt;p&gt;Prem started a rice business. He bought 30 kg. of rice at the rate of Rs. 35 per kg and 20kg. of rice at the rate of Rs. 43 per kg. He mixed the two varieties and sold the mixture at the rate of Rs. 42 per kg. What was his total gain by doing so?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 185&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 190&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 195&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 175&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Total cost price is C = (30 &amp;times; 35) + (20 &amp;times; 43) = 1910.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total selling price is S = 50 &amp;times; 42 = 2100.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, gain is equal to S - C = Rs.190.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(554,6,'4','','&lt;p&gt;A man buys a watch and sells it at a profit of 30%. If he bought at 20% less and sold it for Rs. 80 less, he would have gained 12.5%. What is the cost price?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 220&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs.200&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 240&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 180&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Let the cost price be C.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;In the first case, selling price is 1.3C.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;In the second case, cost price is 0.8C and the selling price is 1.3C - 80.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Profit in the second case is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.26.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;79&quot; height=&quot;33&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;times; 100% = 12.5%&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;=&amp;gt; (0.5C - 80) = 0.1C =&amp;gt; 0.4C = 80 =&amp;gt; C = Rs.200.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the cost price is Rs. 200.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(555,6,'4','','&lt;p&gt;A man buys an article and sells it at a profit of 40%. If he bought at 10% less and sold it for Rs.50 less, he would have gained 100/9 %. What is the selling price in the first case?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 125&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 175&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 150&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 100&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Let the cost price be C.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;In the first case, selling price is 1.4C.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;In the second case, cost price is 0.9C and the selling price is 1.4C - 50.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Profit in the second case is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.27.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;120&quot; height=&quot;41&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;times; 100% = 100/9% =&amp;gt; (0.5C - 50) = 0.1C =&amp;gt; 0.4C = 50 =&amp;gt; C = Rs.125.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the selling price in the first case is 1.4 &amp;times; 125 = Rs.175.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(556,6,'4','','&lt;p&gt;A man sells 10 articles for Rs. 60 and makes a profit of 50%. Find his gain or loss percent if he sells 4 such articles for Rs. 20.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;20%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;25%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;40%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10%&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Cost price of each article is C, then the selling price is 3C/2 because the profit percentage is 50%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, 10 &amp;times; (3C/2) = 60 =&amp;gt; C = (60/15) = 4.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, cost price of 4 articles is 4 &amp;times; 4 = 16.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, profit percentage is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.28.4.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;65&quot; height=&quot;42&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;times; 100% = (100/4)% = 25%.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(557,6,'4','','&lt;p&gt;A makes an article for Rs. 300 and sells it to B at a profit of 20%. B sells it to C, who sells it to D for Rs. 440 making a profit of 10%. What profit percent did B make?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;20%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;25%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;100/9%&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;Cost price of B is (120/100) &amp;times; 300 = Rs.360.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If C sells it for Rs.440, he would get a profit of 10%. So, if S is the selling price of B, then 1.1S = 440 =&amp;gt; S = 440/1.1 = 400.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Profit percentage for B is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.29.4.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;73&quot; height=&quot;44&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;times; 100% = 100/9%.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(558,6,'4','','&lt;p&gt;A makes an article for Rs. 500 and sells it to B at a profit of 20%. B sells it to C, who sells it to D for Rs. 770 making a profit of 10%. What profit percent did B make?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;20%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;25%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;100/6%&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;Cost price of B is (120/100) &amp;times; 500 = Rs600 .&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If C sells it for Rs.770, he would get a profit of 10%. So, if S is the selling price of B, then 1.1S = 770 =&amp;gt; S = (770/1.1) = 700.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Profit percentage for B is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.30.3.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;79&quot; height=&quot;42&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;times; 100% = 100/6%.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(559,6,'4','','&lt;p&gt;A sold a table to B at a profit of 10%. B sold the same table to C for Rs.429 thereby making a profit of 20%. Find the cost price of the table, if A bought the table from X and it is known that X gained 30% in the transaction&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;320&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;300&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;275&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;250&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;Let cost price be x. There are three phases and 3 profits involved. The final price is Rs.429.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Final price will be x &amp;times; &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.31.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;113&quot; height=&quot;42&quot; /&gt;= 429 =&amp;gt; x = 429 &amp;times; (1000/1716) = Rs.250&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(560,6,'4','','&lt;p&gt;A sold a table to B at a profit of 50%. B sold the same table to C for Rs.990 thereby making a profit of 10%. Find the cost price of the table, if A bought the table from X and it is known that X gained 20% in the transaction&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;500&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;400&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;480&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;250&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Let cost price be x. There are three phases and 3 profits involved. The final price is Rs.990.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Final price will be x &amp;times; &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.32.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;116&quot; height=&quot;43&quot; /&gt; = 990&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;=&amp;gt; x = 990 &amp;times; (1000/1980) = Rs.500&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(561,6,'4','','&lt;p&gt;A man sells a plot of land at 5% profit. If he had sold it at 10% profit, he would have received Rs. 1200 more. What is the selling price of the land?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 20,000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 27,500&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 25,200&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 28,500&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;If the cost price is C, then the selling price to get a 5% profit is 1.05C and 10% profit is 1.1C.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The difference in two cases is 0.05C = 1200 =&amp;gt; C = 1200/0.05 = Rs.24000.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the selling price of the land is (105/100) &amp;times; 24000 = Rs.25,200&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(562,6,'4','','&lt;p&gt;A man sells a plot of land at 15% profit. If he had sold it at 20% profit, he would have received Rs. 3000 more. What is the selling price of the land?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 63,000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 57,000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 65,200&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 68,500&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;If the cost price is C, then the slling price to get a 15% profit is 1.15C and 20% profit is 1.2C.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The difference in two cases is 0.05C = 3000 =&amp;gt; C = 3000/0.05 = Rs.60000.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the selling price of the land is (105/100) &amp;times; 60000 = Rs.63,000&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(563,6,'4','','&lt;p&gt;A man buys two phones for a total cost of Rs. 2000. By selling one for 3/4th of its cost and other for 4/3th of its cost, he makes a profit of Rs. 200 on the whole transaction. Find the cost price of lower priced phone&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 1200&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 800&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 850&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 950&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Let the cost prices of the two phones be x and y. So, x + y = 2000; &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.35.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;64&quot; height=&quot;43&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 2200.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;16x + 9y = 26400; 9x + 9y = 18000 =&amp;gt; 7x = 8400 =&amp;gt; x = 1200.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the cost of lower priced phone is Rs.800.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(564,6,'4','','&lt;p&gt;A man buys two phones for a total cost of Rs. 3000. By selling one for 3/5th of its cost and other for 5/3th of its cost, he makes a profit of Rs. 720 on the whole transaction. Find the cost price of lower priced phone&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 1200&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 1100&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 750&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 950&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Let the cost prices of the two cycles be x and y. so, x + y = 3000; &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.36.3.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;55&quot; height=&quot;47&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 3720.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;25x + 9y = 55800; 9x + 9y = 27000 =&amp;gt; 16x = 28800 =&amp;gt; x = 1800.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the cost of lower priced cycle is Rs.1200.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(565,6,'4','','&lt;p&gt;Two dealers X and Y selling the same model of car mark them under the same selling prices. X gives successive discounts of 25% and 20% and Y gives successive discounts of 30% and 15%. From whom is it more profitable to purchase the car?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;X&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Y&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Same Price&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Data Insufficient&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Effective discount when the individual discounts are x% and y% is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.37.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;111&quot; height=&quot;36&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;For X, the discount is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.37.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;121&quot; height=&quot;46&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 40%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;For Y, the discount is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.37.3.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;121&quot; height=&quot;42&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 40.5%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, it is better to buy the product near Y.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(566,6,'4','','&lt;p&gt;Two dealers X and Y selling the same model of refrigerator mark them under the same selling prices. X gives successive discounts of 20% and 30% and Y gives successive discounts of 40 % and 10%. From whom is it more profitable to purchase the refrigerator?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;X&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Y&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Same Price&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Data Insufficient&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Effective discount when the individual discounts are x% and y% is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.38.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;112&quot; height=&quot;39&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;For X, the discount is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.38.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;122&quot; height=&quot;44&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 44%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;For Y, the discount is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.38.3.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;125&quot; height=&quot;42&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 46%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, it is better to buy the product near y.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(567,6,'4','','&lt;p&gt;The cost of manufacturing an article is made up of materials, labour and overheads in the ratio 1:2:3. If the cost of labour is Rs.600, find the profit percent if the article is sold for Rs.1800.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;33.33%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;25%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;20%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;no profit, no loss&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;Labour cost is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.39.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;67&quot; height=&quot;45&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.39.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;17&quot; height=&quot;41&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;th of the total cost.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total cost is (6/2) &amp;times; 600 = 1800.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, profit percentage is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.39.4.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;91&quot; height=&quot;39&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;times; 100% = 0%.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(568,6,'4','','&lt;p&gt;The cost of manufacturing an article is made up of materials, labour and overheads in the ratio 1:3:6. If the cost of labour is Rs.900, find the profit percent if the article is sold for Rs.3600.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;33.33%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;25%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;20%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;no profit, no loss&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Labour cost is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.40.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;66&quot; height=&quot;43&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= (3/10)th of the total cost.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total cost is (10/3) &amp;times; 900 = 3000.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, profit percentage is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.40.4.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;91&quot; height=&quot;43&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;times; 100% = 20%.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(569,6,'4','','&lt;p&gt;Ashok makes 1000 articles at a cost of 60 paise per article. He fixes the selling price such that if only 500 articles are sold, he would have made a profit of 20% on the outlay. However, 150 articles got spoilt and he was able to sell 850 articles at this price. Find his actual profit percent as the percentage of total outlay assuming that the unsold articles are useless.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;65%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;70%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;75%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;68%&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Total cost is 1000 &amp;times; (60/100) = Rs.600.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;For the profit to be 20%, the selling price should be 1.2C = 1.2 &amp;times; 600 = Rs.720.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, cost of each article will be 720/500 = Rs.1.44 because he assumes only 500 will be sold.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;850 items are sold at that cost, so the total selling price is 850 &amp;times; 1.44 = Rs.1224, since the remaining articles are useless, money from them is 0.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, his final profit percentage is (504/720) &amp;times; 100 = 70%.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(570,6,'4','','&lt;p&gt;A manufacturer estimates that on inspection, 10% of the articles he produces will be rejected. He accepts an order to supply 27,000 articles at Rs. 10 each. He estimates the profit on his outlay including the manufacturing of rejected articles, to be 25%. Find the cost of manufacturing each article.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 7&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 7.20&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 7.50&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 8&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;If he produces 100 articles, only 90 will be accepted.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, in order to supply 27000 articles, he must manufacture 27000 &amp;times; (100/90) = 30000 articles.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The total money he earns is 27000 &amp;times; 10 = 270000.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;His profit ratio is 25%. So, the total cost for him is 270000 &amp;times; (100/125) = Rs.216000.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, his cost of production of each article is 216000/30000 = Rs.7.20 per each article.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(571,6,'4','','&lt;p&gt;The cost of setting up the type of a magazine is Rs. 1500. The cost of running the printing machine is Rs. 100 per 100 copies. The cost of paper, ink and so on is 75 paise per copy. The magazines are sold at Rs. 4 each. 1000 copies are printed, but only 800 copies are sold. What is the sum to be obtained from advertisements to give a profit of 20% on the cost?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 650&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 700&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 725&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 850&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Total cost to print all the magazines is 1500 + [(100/100) &amp;times; 1000] + [(75/100) &amp;times; 1000] = Rs.3250.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;To get a 20% profit, the total return from sales should be 1.2C = 1.2 &amp;times; 3250 = Rs.3900.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Only 800 magazines are sold, so money from the magazines is 800 &amp;times; 4 = Rs.3200.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, money that should come from advertisements is 3900 - 3200 = Rs.700.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(572,6,'4','','&lt;p&gt;A dishonest dealer marks up the price of his goods by 20% and gives a discount of 10% to the customer. He also uses a 800 gram weight instead of a 1 kilogram weight. Find his percentage profit due to these manoeuvres.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;30%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;32%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;35%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;28%&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;He buys 1000 grams for every kilogram and sells 800 grams for every kilogram. So, he saves 200 grams for every 800 grams sold.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, his profit percentage with false weights is (1/4) &amp;times; 100% = 25%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;His price on each good is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.44.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;69&quot; height=&quot;40&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 1.08 times the original price.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, if the original cost is Rs. 100, his selling price is Rs.125 &amp;times; 1.08 = Rs.135.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, his profit percentage is 20%.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(573,6,'4','','&lt;p&gt;A whole-seller allows a discount of 25% on the list price to a retailer. The retailer sells at 10% discount on the list price. If the customer paid Rs. 360 for an article, what profit is made by the retailer?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 40&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 50&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 60&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 80&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Let the marked price be C. Then he sells it at a cost 0.9C and buys it at a cost 0.75C.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the profit percentage is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.45.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;144&quot; height=&quot;47&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The customer bought it for Rs.360. so, 0.9C = 360 =&amp;gt; C = 400.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the profit for the shopkeeper is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.45.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;77&quot; height=&quot;40&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= Rs.60.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(574,6,'4','','Which is the better deal from the below?','Single discount of 40%','Two successive discounts of 20%','Two successive discounts of 30% and 15%','Two successive discounts of 25% and 20%','3','In the case of 30% + 15%, we get maximum discount of 40.5%.','Hard'),(575,6,'4','','&lt;p&gt;A shopkeeper wants to sell 150 articles. If he sells them at Rs. 200 per article, he would be able to sell all the articles. But for every Rs. 5 increase in price, he will be left with one additional unsold article. At what selling price would he be able to maximise his profits (assuming unsold articles remain with him)?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 475&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 450&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 425&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 400&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Since all the articles are already made, the cost price will not change.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The selling price must be made such that the total selling price is maximum.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If the selling price is (200 + 5n), then the number of articles sold are (150 - n).&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the total selling price is S = (200 + 5n)(150 - n).&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;It is maximum when &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.47.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;243&quot; height=&quot;50&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 0&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;=&amp;gt; 10n = 550 =&amp;gt; n = 55.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, in order to get maximum profit, the selling price should be Rs. 475.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(576,6,'4','','&lt;p&gt;A shopkeeper wants to sell 160 articles. If he sells them at Rs. 200 per article, he would be able to sell all the articles. But for every Rs. 20 increase in price, he will be left with two additional unsold articles. At what selling price would he be able to maximise his profits (assuming unsold articles remain with him)?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 880&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 860&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 840&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 900&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Since all the articles are already made, the cost price will not change.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The selling price must be made such that the total selling price is maximum.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If the selling price is (160 + 20n), then the number of articles sold are (160 - 2n).&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the total selling price is S = (160 + 20n)(160 - 2n).&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;It is maximum when &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.48.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;262&quot; height=&quot;43&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 0&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;=&amp;gt; 80n = 2880 =&amp;gt; n = 36.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, in order to get maximum profit, the selling price should be Rs. 880.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(577,6,'4','','&lt;p&gt;A carpenter wants to sell 120 chairs. If he sells them at Rs. 120 per article, he would be able to sell all the chairs. But for every Rs. 20 increase in price, he will be left with one additional unsold chair. At what selling price would he be able to maximise his profits (assuming unsold articles remain with him)?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 1200&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 1240&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 1260&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 1280&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Since all the chairs are already made, the cost price will not change.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The selling price must be made such that the total selling price is maximum.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If the selling price is (120 + 20n), then the number of articles sold are (120 - n).&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the total selling price is S = (120 + 20n)(120 - n).&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;It is maximum when &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.49.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;260&quot; height=&quot;46&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 0&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;=&amp;gt; 40n = 228 =&amp;gt; n = 57.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, in order to get maximum profit, the selling price should be Rs. 1260.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(578,6,'4','','&lt;p&gt;. A shopkeeper makes a profit of x% by selling an object for Rs. 40. Had the cost price and selling price been interchanged, it would have led to a loss of (0.75 &amp;times; x)%. With the latter cost price, what should be the new selling price to get a profit of x%?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 53.33&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 50&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 56.67&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 60&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;His selling price is Rs.40 and he gets x% profit. So, the cost price is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.50.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;128&quot; height=&quot;53&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If the cost price and selling prices are reversed, then the loss is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.50.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;222&quot; height=&quot;57&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 0.75x.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, x = 33%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If the new cost price is Rs. 40, then to get a profit of 33%, the selling price should be 40 &amp;times; (133/100) = Rs.53.33.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(579,6,'4','','&lt;p&gt;A shopkeeper calculates percentage profit on the buying price and another on the selling price. What will be their difference in profits if both claim a profit of 20% on goods sold for Rs. 5000?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 167&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 133&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 150&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 183&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;The profit for the first person is 20% on the buying price.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, to get 20% profit, if his cost price is C, the selling price should be 1.2C.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, 1.2C = 5000 =&amp;gt; C = (5000/1.2) = 4166.67.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, his profit is 5000 - 4166.67 = Rs.833.33.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The profit for the first person is 20% on the selling price.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, to get 20% profit, if his selling price is C, the cost price should be 0.8C.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, his cost price is 0.8 &amp;times; 5000 = Rs.4000.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, his profit is 5000 - 4000 = Rs.1000.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, difference in the profits is Rs.167.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(580,6,'4','','&lt;p&gt;A merchant makes a profit of 20% by selling an article. By how much would the profit increase, had he paid 5% less for it and the customer paid 15% more for it?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;13.16%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;26.32%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;15%&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;If the cost price of the article is C, then the normal selling price is 1.2C to get a profit of 20%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;However, he buys it for 5% less. So, he buys it for 0.95C.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The customer buys it for 15% more. So, the selling price is 1.1 &amp;times; 1.15C = 1.265C.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the actual profit percentage is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.52.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;106&quot; height=&quot;40&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;times; 100% = 33.16%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The profit percentage will increase by 13.16%.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(581,6,'4','','&lt;p&gt;A shopkeeper calculates percentage profit on the buying price and another on the selling price. What will be their difference in profits if both claim a profit of 10% on goods sold for Rs. 5000?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 46&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 42&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 50&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 54&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;The profit for the first person is 10% on the buying price.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, to get 10% profit, if his cost price is C, the selling price should be 1.1C.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, 1.1C = 5000 =&amp;gt; C = (5000/1.1) = 4545.45.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, his profit is 5000 - 4545.45 = Rs.454.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The profit for the first person is 10% on the selling price.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, to get 10% profit, if his selling price is C, the cost price should be 0.9C.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, his cost price is 0.9 &amp;times; 5000 = Rs.4500.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, his profit is 5000 - 4500 = Rs.500.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, difference in the profits is Rs.46.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(582,7,'1','','&lt;p&gt;If two successive discounts are 20% and 40% then its equivalent discount is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;60%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;55%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;52%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;50%&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;If the successive discounts are x% and y%, then the effective discount is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.38.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;112&quot; height=&quot;39&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Here x=20 and y=40.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, effective discount is 20 + 40 - (800/100) = 52%.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(583,7,'1','','&lt;p&gt;If a number is first decreased by x% and then again reduced by x%, then what is the % change?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;x&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;/100 decrease&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;x&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;/100 increase&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;No Change&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Cannot Say&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;The value decreases by x&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;/100%&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(584,7,'1','','&lt;p&gt;If 10 litres of water is removed from a container and replaced with wine, the ratio of water to wine becomes 5:2. How much water was there originally?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;25&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;30&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;35&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;40&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Since there is 10 litres of wine and the ratio of water to wine is 5 : 2, the total amount of water now is (5/2) &amp;times; 10 = 25 litres.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Since 10 litres of water is taken out, the initial amount of water is 35 litres.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(585,7,'1','','&lt;p&gt;What is 20% of 50% of 75% of 70?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5.25&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5.75&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/172.4.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;116&quot; height=&quot;42&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;x 70 = 5.25&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(586,7,'1','','&lt;p&gt;Mr. Banerjee is worried about the balance of his monthly budget. The price of petrol has increased by 40%. By what percent should he reduce the consumption of petrol so that he is able to balance his budget?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;28.57%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;25%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;32.43%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;33.33%&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;If the earlier price is Rs. 100, the new price is Rs. 140. So, an increase of Rs. 40 for every Rs. 140.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The required percentage is (40/100) &amp;times; 100% = 28.57%&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(587,7,'1','','&lt;p&gt;In an election between 2 candidates. Bhiku gets 65% of the total valid votes. If the total votes were 6000. What is the number of valid votes that the other candidate Mhatre gets if 25% of the total votes were declared invalid?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2925&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1575&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1875&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Total number of valid votes is (75/100) &amp;times; 6000 = 4500.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the number of votes that the other candidate gets is (35/100) &amp;times; 4500 = 1575.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(588,7,'1','','&lt;p&gt;A number is mistakenly divided by 5 instead of being multiplied by 5. Find the percentage change in the result due to this mistake&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;94%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;95%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;96%&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;Assume that the number is 100. The result is 500 instead of the correct result 20. So, the error percentage is (480/500) &amp;times; 100% = 96%.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(589,7,'1','','&lt;p&gt;If 65% of x = 13% of y. then find the value of x if y = 2000.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;200&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;400&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;600&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;800&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;It is given that &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/172.8.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;77&quot; height=&quot;43&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;=&amp;gt; y = 5x =&amp;gt; x= 2000/5 = 400.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(590,7,'1','','&lt;p&gt;In a mixture of 80 litres of milk and water, 25% of the mixture is milk. How much water should be added to the mixture so that milk becomes 20% of the mixture?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;20&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;25&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;30&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;The amount of milk will remain at (25/100) &amp;times; 80 = 20 litres. In order that milk be 20% of the mixture, the total amount should be 100 litres. So, 80 - 60 = 20 litres of water is to be mixed.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(591,7,'1','','&lt;p&gt;The price of rice falls by 20%. How much rice can be bought now with the money that was sufficient to buy 20 kg of rice previously?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;24 Kg&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;25 Kg&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;28 Kg&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;30 Kg&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;If the previous price of rice is X, then the new price is (80/100) &amp;times; X = 0.8X.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the number of kg of rice we can buy with 20X is (20x/0.8x) = 25 kg.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(592,7,'1','','&lt;p&gt;At an election, the candidate who got 56% of the votes cast won by 144 votes. Find the total number of voters on the voting list if 80% people cast their vote and there were no invalid votes.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1500&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1200&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1440&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1800&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Let the total number of voters be x. Only 80% of them voted. So, number of persons who voted is (80/100) &amp;times; X= 0.8X&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The difference is 56 - 44 = 12% which is equal to 144.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of persons who voted is (100/12) &amp;times; 144 = 1200 =&amp;gt; 0.8X = 1200 =&amp;gt; X = 1500.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(593,7,'1','','&lt;p&gt;The population of the village of Nava is 10,000 at this moment. It increases by 10% in the first year. However, in the second year, due to immigration, the population drops by 5%. Find the population at the end of the third year if in the third year the population increases by 20%.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;12000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;12540&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;12360&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;12180&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;The population at the end of the third year is 10000 x &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/172.12.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;218&quot; height=&quot;46&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 10000 x &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/172.12.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;85&quot; height=&quot;40&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 12540&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(594,7,'1','','&lt;p&gt;Vicky&amp;rsquo;s salary is 75% more than Asha&amp;rsquo;s. Vicky got a raise of 40% on his salary while Asha got a raise of 25% on her salary. By what percent is Vicky&amp;rsquo;s salary more than Asha&amp;rsquo;s?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;96%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;85%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;90%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;95%&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;If Asha&amp;rsquo;s initial salary is Rs.100, then Vicky&amp;rsquo;s salary will be Rs.175. after the raises, Asha&amp;rsquo;s salary will be Rs.125 and Vicky&amp;rsquo;s will be (140/100) &amp;times; 175 = Rs.245.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the percentage difference is&amp;nbsp;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/172.13.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;171&quot; height=&quot;37&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(595,7,'1','','&lt;p&gt;100 Kg. Potatoes with 98% water content are dried in an oven. The percentage of water decreases to 50 %. What is the weight of potatoes now?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;49 kg&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;51 kg&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4 Kg&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;50 Kg&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Since 98% is water, the remaining 2% will be potato mass.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Mass of dry potato will be equal to (2/100) &amp;times; 100 = 2 kg.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;This mass will remain the same.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Now, in the dried potatoes, 50% is water. So, 50% remaining will be the potato mass which is 2 kg.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total weight of the potatoes now will be 2 &amp;times; (100/50) = 4 kg.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(596,7,'1','','&lt;p&gt;A cow and a calf cost Rs. 2000 and Rs. 1400 respectively. If the price of the cow and that of the calf is increased by 20% and 30% respectively, then the price of 1 cow and 2 calves is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 4800&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs 6000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 6040&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 6100&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;New price of the cow is (120/100) &amp;times; 2000 = Rs.2400.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;New price of the calf is (130/100) &amp;times; 1400 = Rs.1820.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the required price is 2400 + (1820 &amp;times; 2) = 2400 + 3640 = Rs.6040.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(597,7,'1','','&lt;p&gt;I was offered two deals on the same item in two different shops. The first shop owner offered me a discount of 20% percent and the second one offered me two successive discounts of 10%. Which is a better deal?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;First offer&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Second offer&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Both are same&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Data insufficient&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;A single discount of 20% is better than to successive discounts of 10%, because, if the successive discounts are x% and y%, then the effective discount is&amp;nbsp;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/165.38.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;112&quot; height=&quot;39&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(598,7,'1','','&lt;p&gt;A person with some money spends 1/3 for cloths, 1/5 of the remaining for food and 1/4 of the remaining for travel. He is left with Rs. 100/-. How much did he have with him in the beginning?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;200&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;250&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;300&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;350&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Money spent for food is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/172.17.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;80&quot; height=&quot;36&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;of the total income.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Money spent on travel is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/172.17.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;86&quot; height=&quot;37&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;of the total amount.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, remaining amount is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/172.17.3.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;131&quot; height=&quot;38&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;of the total amount.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If his salary is Rs.x, then 2x/5 = 100 =&amp;gt; x = 250.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(599,7,'1','','&lt;p&gt;In an examination, 48% students failed in Hindi and 32% students failed in History. 20% students failed in both the subjects. If the number of students who passed the examination was 880, how many students appeared in the examination if the examination consisted only of these two subjects?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2100&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2200&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2300&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Percentage of students who passed in both the exams is 100 - 48 - 32 + 20 = 40%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, 40% of the students is 880.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the total number of students writing the exam is (100/40) &amp;times; 880 = 2200.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(600,7,'1','','&lt;p&gt;After three successive equal percentage rise in the salary, the sum of 100 rupees tuned into 140 rupees and 49 paise. Find the percentage rise in the salary&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;12%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;13%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;14%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;15%&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Let the rise percentage be r%. There are 3 rises in salary.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/172.19.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;442&quot; height=&quot;40&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;=&amp;gt; r = 12%&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(601,7,'1','','&lt;p&gt;A person saves 6% of his income. Two years later, his income shoots up by 15% but the value of his savings remain the same. Find the percentage hike in his expenditure.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;15.3&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;15&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;15.45&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;14.85&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;His expenditure will always be 94% of the income. Let his initial income be Rs.100. His savings will remain at Rs. 6 throughout.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, initial expenditure is (94/100) &amp;times; 100 = 94 and final expenditure is 115 - 6 = 109.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, percentage hike in expenditure is (15/98) &amp;times; 100%&amp;nbsp;= 15.30%.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(602,7,'2','','&lt;p&gt;I bought 5 pens, 7 pencils and 4 erasers. Raja bought 6 pens, 8 erasers and 14 pencils for an amount which was half more than what I had paid. What percent of the total amount paid by me was paid for the pens?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;50%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;62.5%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;75%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;47.5%&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Let the cost of 1 pen be x and the cost of 7 pencils and 4 erasers included be y.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, 6x + 2y = (3/2).(5x+y)&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;=&amp;gt; 12x + 4y = 15x + 3y&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;=&amp;gt; 3x = y.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the percentage cost of pens is &amp;nbsp;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/173.1.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;56&quot; height=&quot;44&quot; /&gt;% = 500/8% = 62.5%.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(603,7,'2','','&lt;p&gt;David sells his goods 25% cheaper than Robert and 25% dearer than Thomas. How much percentage is Thomas&amp;rsquo; goods cheaper than Robert&#039;s?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;33.33%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;50%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;66.67%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;75%&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Let Thomas&amp;rsquo; goods cost Rs. 100.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Then David&amp;rsquo;s products cost (125/100) &amp;times; 100 = Rs.125 and that of Robert is (75x/100) = 125&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;=&amp;gt; x = 125 &amp;times; (100/75) = Rs.166.67.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, we can see that Thomas&amp;rsquo; goods are 66.67% cheaper than Roberts&amp;rsquo;.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(604,7,'2','','&lt;p&gt;When 60% of a number A is added to another number B, B becomes 175% of its previous value. Then which of the following is true regarding the values of A and B?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;A = B&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;A&amp;gt;B&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;A&amp;lt;B&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Data Sufficient&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;B + 0.6A = 1.75B =&amp;gt; 0.6A = 0.75B =&amp;gt; &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/173.3.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;51&quot; height=&quot;40&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;=&amp;gt; A&amp;gt;B.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(605,7,'2','','&lt;p&gt;In an examination, Mohan obtained 20% more than Susan but 10% less than Rajesh. If the marks obtained by Susan is 1080, find the percentage marks obtained by Rajesh if the full marks is 2000.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;55%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;60%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;65%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;62.5%&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;If the marks obtained by Susan, Mohan and Rajesh be x, y and z respectively.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, x = 1080, y = (120/100) &amp;times; 1080 = 1296 and 0.9z = 1080 =&amp;gt; z = (1080/0.9) = 1200.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So percentage marks of Rajesh is (1200/2000) &amp;times; 100% = 60%.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(606,7,'2','','&lt;p&gt;A man buys a truck for Rs. 300,000. The annual repair cost comes to 2.0% of the price of purchase. Besides, he has to pay an annual tax of Rs. 3000. At what monthly rent must he rent out the truck to get a return of 20% on his net investment of the first year?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 30600&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 30900&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 30700&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 30800&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Total outlay is 1.02 &amp;times; 300000 + 3000 = 309000.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;To get a profit of 15%, the selling price should be 1.2C = 1.2 &amp;times; 309000 = Rs.370800.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the monthly rent should be (370800/12) = Rs.30900.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(607,7,'2','','&lt;p&gt;The entrance ticket at the Minerva theatre in Mumbai is worth Rs. 300. When the price of the ticket was lowered, the sale of tickets increased by 50% while the collections recorded a decrease of 17.5%. Find the deduction in the ticket price.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 145&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 135&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 155&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 165&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;If the increased ticket price is Rs.x, then we can say that the sale ratio in both cases is (100/82.5).&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Sales increased by 50%. Let initial sales be 100. Final sales are 150.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/173.6.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;121&quot; height=&quot;45&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;=&amp;gt; x = 2 &amp;times; 82.5 = Rs.165.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, deduction in ticket price is 300 - 165 = Rs. 135.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(608,7,'2','','&lt;p&gt;A student divided a number by when he required to multiply by . Calculate the percentage of error in his result.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;125%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;400%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;75%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;None of these&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;Dividing the number by 2/3 is the same as multiplying it with 3/2. So, there is no error at all.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(609,7,'2','','&lt;p&gt;Aruna&amp;rsquo;s project report consists of 25 pages each of 60 lines with 75 characters on each line. In case the number of lines is reduced to 55 but the number of characters is increased to 90 per lines, what is the percentage change in the number of pages?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;9.12%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;8.74%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6.67%&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Total number of characters remain the same.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, 25 &amp;times; 60 &amp;times; 75 = x &amp;times; 55 &amp;times; 90 =&amp;gt; x = &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/173.8.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;95&quot; height=&quot;40&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 22.72 pages.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, percentage change in number of pages is (2.28/25) &amp;times; 100% = 9.12%.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(610,7,'2','','&lt;p&gt;After receiving two successive raises. Hursh&amp;rsquo;s salary became equal to times of his initial salary. By how much percent was the salary raised the first time if the second raise was twice as high (in percent) as the first?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;25%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;30%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;15%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;20%&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Let the first raise be x%. Then the second raise is 2x%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the total salary after the hikes will be &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/173.9.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;370&quot; height=&quot;36&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, 2x&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; + 300x = 7 &amp;times; 1250 =&amp;gt; x = 25%.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(611,7,'2','','&lt;p&gt;A company hired a salesman on a monthly salary of Rs. 3,000. In addition to it, the salesman was entitled for 20% commission on the monthly sale. How much sale the salesman should do if he wants his monthly income as Rs. 10,000?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 30000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 35000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 40000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 45000&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;If his monthly income is Rs. 10000, then he gets commissions of Rs. 7000.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, if S is the monthly sale, then the commissions will be 0.2S = 7000 =&amp;gt; S = Rs.35000.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(612,7,'2','','&lt;p&gt;Ravi goes to a shop to buy a sofa set costing Rs. 13,080. The rate of sales tax is 9%. She tells the shopkeeper to reduce the price of the sofa set to such an extent that she has to pay Rs. 13080 inclusive of sales tax. Find the percentage reduction needed in the price of the sofa set to just satisfy her requirement.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;8%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;8.15%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;8.25%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;8.35%&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;The total price including the tax should be Rs. 13080.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, if C is the cost price and 9% is the tax then 1.09C = 13080 =&amp;gt; C = 13080/1.09 = Rs.12000.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the percentage reduction needed is (1080/13080) &amp;times; 100% = 8.25%&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(613,7,'2','','&lt;p&gt;In the university examination last year. Rajesh scored 65% in English and 82% in History. What is the minimum percent he should score in Sociology, which is out of 50 marks (if English and History were for 100 marks each), if he aims at getting 78% overall?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;92%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;94%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;96%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;98%&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;78% out of a total of 250 marks is (78/100) &amp;times; 250% = 195.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the marks he must score in Sociology is 195 - 65 - 82 = 48.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the minimum percentage that he should get is (48/50) &amp;times; 100% = 96%.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(614,7,'2','','&lt;p&gt;Out of two -thirds of the total number of basket-ball matches, a team has won 17 matches and lost 3 of them. What is the maximum number of matches that the team can lose and still win three -fourths of the total number of matches, if it is true that no match can end in a tie?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;3&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Total number of matches is (3/2) &amp;times; 20 = 30.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;To win three-fourth of the matches, the total number of matches that the team needs to win is (3/4) &amp;times; 30 = 22.5 = 23.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, it can still lose another 10 - 23 + 17 = 4 matches.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(615,7,'2','','&lt;p&gt;A&amp;rsquo;s salary is first increased by 25% and then decreased by 20%.The result is the same as B&amp;rsquo;s salary increased by 20% and then reduced by 25%. Find the ratio of B&amp;rsquo;s salary to that of A&amp;rsquo;s&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10 : 9&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1 : 1&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;9 : 10&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;3 : 4&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Let A&amp;rsquo;s salary be Rs.x and B&amp;rsquo;s salary be Rs.y.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, A&amp;rsquo;s salary after the changes is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/173.14.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;241&quot; height=&quot;39&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, B&amp;rsquo;s salary after the changes is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/173.14.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;225&quot; height=&quot;33&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, x = 9y/10 =&amp;gt; y : x = 10 : 9.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(616,7,'2','','&lt;p&gt;A is 50% more than B. C is of A and D is 60% more than C. Now, each of A, B, C and D is increased by 10%. Find what per cent of B is D (after the increase)?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;160%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;150%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;120%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;100%&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Let B be 100. So, A will be 150. C will be (2/3) &amp;times; 150 = 100. D will be 1.6C = 160.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If all these are increased by 10%, then B becomes 110 and D becomes 1.1 &amp;times; 160 = 176.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, D is (176/110) &amp;times; 100% = 160% of B.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(617,7,'2','','&lt;p&gt;To pass an examination, 40% marks are essential. A obtains 10% marks less than the pass marks and B obtains 11.11% marks less than A. What percent less than the sum of A&#039;s and B&amp;rsquo;s marks should C obtain to pass the exam?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;36%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;40%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;41.17%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;43.24%&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;The percentage of marks obtained by A are 40% &amp;times; 0.9 = 36% and the marks obtained by B are 36% &amp;times; (8/9) = 32%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the total of A and B is 36% + 32% = 68% which is 28% more than the pass mark.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, C should obtain (28%/68%) &amp;times; 100% = 41.17% less.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(618,7,'2','','&lt;p&gt;Two numbers X and Y are 20% and 28% less than a third number Z. Find by what percentage is the number Y less than the number X&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;8%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;12%&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;If the number Z is 100, then X and Y are 80 and 72 respectively.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, Y is (8/80) &amp;times; 100 = 10% less than X.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(619,7,'2','','&lt;p&gt;Australia scored a total of x runs in 50 overs. India tied the scores in 20% less overs. If India&amp;rsquo;s average run rate had been 33.33% higher the scores would have been tied 10 overs earlier. Find how many runs were scored by Australia.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;200&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;240&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;250&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Cannot be determined&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;India has scored x runs in 40 overs. So, average run rate is (x/40).&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If the run rate is 33.33% higher, then it is equal to &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/173.18.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;123&quot; height=&quot;40&quot; /&gt; .&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, whatever be the value of x, the result would be the same.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, data is insufficient.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(620,7,'2','','&lt;p&gt;Due to a 25% hike in the price of rice per kilogram, a person is able to purchase 20 kg less for Rs. 400. Find the increased price of rice per kilogram&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 4&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 5&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 6&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 10&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Let the original price be Rs.x. So, the final price will be Rs. 5x/4.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The difference in the quantities for R. 400 is 20 kg.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/173.19.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;304&quot; height=&quot;47&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the new price is Rs.5.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(621,7,'2','','&lt;p&gt;A water tank contains 5% salt by weight. &amp;lsquo;x&amp;rsquo; litres of fresh water is added to 40 litres of tank water, so that the solution contains 2% salt. The value of &amp;lsquo;x&amp;rsquo; is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;40&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;50&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;60&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;75&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;40 litres of tank water contains (5/100) &amp;times; 40 = 2 litres of salt and 38 litres of water.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If fresh water is to be added, then the quantity of salt remains the same.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Final percentage of salt is 2%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the total amount of mixture is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/173.20.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;59&quot; height=&quot;42&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 100 litres.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, 60 litres of fresh water is to be added&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(622,7,'3','','&lt;p&gt;In a town consisting of three localities A, B and C. the population of the three localities A, B and C are in the ratio 9: 8: 3. In locality A, 80% of the people are literate, in locality B, 30% of the people are illiterate. If 90% people in locality C are literate, find the percentage literacy in that town&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;61.5%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;70%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;77.5%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;75%&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Percentage literacy is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/174.1.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;330&quot; height=&quot;40&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 77.5%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The percentage for town B is given for illiterates. Be careful!&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(623,7,'3','','&lt;p&gt;The salary of a person is increased by Rs. 4800 and the rate of tax is decreased by 2% from 12% to 10%. The effect is such that he is now paying the same tax as before. If in both the cases, the standard tax deduction is fixed at 20% of the total income, find the increased salary?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 24000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 26800&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 28800&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 34800&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;If the initial salary is x, then the final salary is (x + 4800).&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Now, the tax is applied on 80% of his income in both cases and the tax is equal.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So,x x [0.8 &amp;times; (12/100)] = [(x + 4800) &amp;times; 0.8 &amp;times; (10/100)]&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;=&amp;gt; 2x = 48000 =&amp;gt; x = Rs.24000.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, his increased salary is 24000 + 4800 = Rs.28800.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(624,7,'3','','&lt;p&gt;On Madagascar Island, there are x dodos in a particular year. 30 dodos in a thousand of the original population die every year and 25 dodos in a thousand of the original population are born every year. In how many years will the population of dodos halve itself?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;200&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;125&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;100&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Indeterminate&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Out of every 1000, 5 dodos die every year.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the entire population will halve itself in 500/5 = 100 years&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(625,7,'3','','&lt;p&gt;Of the adult population in Nagpur, 45% of men and 25% of women are married. What percentage of the total population of adults is married (assume that no man marries more than one woman and vice versa)?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;32.14%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;33.24%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;30%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;25%&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;We can say that 45% of men is equal to 25% of women.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, if the male population is x and female population is y, then 0.45x = 0.25y =&amp;gt; x : y = 5 : 9.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the percent of married population is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/174.4.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;99&quot; height=&quot;38&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;times; 100 = &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/174.4.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;35&quot; height=&quot;55&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;times; 100% = (900/28)% = 32.14%&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(626,7,'3','','&lt;p&gt;The price of raw materials has gone up by 15%, labour cost has also increased from 25% of the cost of raw material to 30% of the cost of raw material. By how much percentage should there be a reduction in the usage of raw materials so as to keep the cost same?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;20%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;25%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;15%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;30%&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;If the initial price of raw materials is Rs. 100, then the price of labour is (25/100) &amp;times; 100 = 25.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The increase prices are Rs.115 and (30/100) &amp;times; 115 = 34.5.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the total cost initially is Rs.125 and finally is 115 + 34.5 = 149.5.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Since the product is constant, the percentage reduction required will be &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/174.5.3.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;89&quot; height=&quot;48&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;times; 100% = 20%.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(627,7,'3','','&lt;p&gt;In the Mock CAT paper, questions were asked in five sections. Out of the total students, 5% candidates cleared the cut-off in all the sections and 5% cleared none. Of the rest, 25% cleared only one section and 20% cleared four sections. If 24.5% of the entire candidates cleared two sections and 300 candidates cleared three sections, find out how many candidates appeared at the Mock CAT?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;900&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1500&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1200&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;Percentage of students who cleared all sections is 5%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Percentage of students who cleared 0 sections is 5%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Percentage of students who cleared 1 section is (9/10) &amp;times; 25% = 22.5%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Percentage of students who cleared 4 sections is (9/10) &amp;times; 20% = 18%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Percentage of students who cleared 2 sections is 24.5%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, percentage of students who cleared 3 sections is 100 - 10 - 18 - 47 = 25%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, 25% of the stents is equal to 300.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, number of students writing the exam is 300 &amp;times; (100/25) = 1200.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(628,7,'3','','&lt;p&gt;A salesman is appointed on the basic salary of Rs. 1200 per month and the condition that for every sales of above Rs. 10,000, he will get 50% of basic salary and 10% of the sales as a reward. This incentive scheme does not operate for the first Rs.10000 of sales. What should be the value of sales if he wants to earn Rs. 7600 in a particular month?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 68000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 76000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 66000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 80000&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;The commission that he wants to earn is 7600 - 1200 = Rs.6400.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Once the sales get above Rs. 10000, he will get 50% of basic salary which is Rs.600.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;He will also get a 10% commission on the sales. So, his sale must be (10/100).x = 5800 =&amp;gt; x = 58000 above the limit of Rs. 10,000.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, his total monthly sale must be Rs. 68000.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(629,7,'3','','&lt;p&gt;In an election of 3 candidates A, B and C, A gets 50% more votes than B. A also beats C by 1,80,000 votes. If it is known that B gets 5 percentage point more votes than C, find the number of voters on the voting list (given 90% of the voters on the voting list voted and no votes were illegal)&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1000000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;900000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;750000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;150000&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;If C gets x% votes, then B got (x + 5)% votes and A got &amp;times;(x + 5)% votes.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, x + x + 5 + 1.5x + 7.5 = 100 =&amp;gt; 3.5x = 87.5 =&amp;gt; x = 87.5/3.5 = 25%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, C got 25% votes, B got 30% votes and A got 45% votes.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The difference between A and C is 20%, which is equal to 1,80,000 votes.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the total number of voters who voted is (100/20) &amp;times; 180000 = 900000.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The total number on voting list is (10/9) &amp;times; 900000 = 10,00,000.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(630,7,'3','','&lt;p&gt;The Congress government promised in 1991 that they would bring down prices in 100 days. They failed to do so and the prices went up by 10% each year for the next five years i.e., from 1992 to 1996. Then BJP got elected and successfully brought down the prices by 10% each year from 1997 onward. Find approximately by what percentage will prices in 1999 be more than those in 1992?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;17.41%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;18.71%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;19.61%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;16.31%&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Let the prices in 1992 be x.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;In 1996, they will be x &amp;times; &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/174.9.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;78&quot; height=&quot;43&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 1.61051x because the prices increased by 10% each year.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;In 1999, they will be 1.61051x &amp;times; &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/174.9.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;74&quot; height=&quot;41&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 1.1741x because the prices decreased by 10% each year.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the percentage increase from 1992 to 1999 will be 17.41%.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(631,7,'3','','&lt;p&gt;When the price of an article was reduced by 15%, the sale of the article is increased by20%. What was the effect on the sales?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2% increase&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2% decrease&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;no Change&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5% increase&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Total sales initially is xy where x is the price of an article and y is the number of items sold.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, final sales will be 0.85x &amp;times; 1.2y = 1.02xy.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, there will be a 2% increase in sales.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(632,7,'3','','&lt;p&gt;In a factory, 60% of the employees are males. Among them 20% are matriculates and the remaining are graduates. Among the females, 40% are matriculates and the remaining are graduates. If the total number of female employees in the factory is 640, how many graduates are there in the factory?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1144&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1148&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1152&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1156&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Since 40% of the employees are females, total number of employees in the factory is (100/40) &amp;times; 640 = 1600.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total number of male employees is (60/100) &amp;times; 1600 = 9600.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of graduates are &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/174.11.3.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;184&quot; height=&quot;43&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 768 + 384 = 1152.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(633,7,'3','','&lt;p&gt;In an examination, Harris got 8 marks less than 80% of the full marks and Ravi got 5 marks more than 70% of the full marks. Harris beats Ravi by 2 marks. The marks scored by Ravi is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;105&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;110&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;75&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;78&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;8 marks less than 80% is 2 more than 5 marks greater than 70%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the difference between 70% and 80% is 8 + 2 + 5 = 15.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the total marks is 150 and 70% of that is (70/100) &amp;times; 150 = 105.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, marks for Ravi is 105 + 5 = 110.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(634,7,'3','','&lt;p&gt;A&#039;s salary is 20% less than B&#039;s salary and B&#039;s salary is 20% more than C&#039;s salary. If the sum of the salaries of A and B is Rs. 5,400 then C&#039;s salary, if he gets a 20% hike in the salary is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 3600&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 4000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 4320&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 4800&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Let the salary of B be x. So, the salary of A is 0.8x and that of C is 1.2x.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, x + 0.8x = 5400 =&amp;gt; x = 5400/1.8 = 3000.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the salary of C is 1.2x = Rs.3600.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If he gets 20% hike, his salary will become 1.2 &amp;times; 3600 = Rs.4320.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(635,7,'3','','&lt;p&gt;A 1 kg gas cylinder runs for 104 hours when the smaller burner on the gas stove is fully opened while it runs for 80 hours when the larger burner on the gas stove is fully opened. Which of these values are the closest to the percentage difference in the usage of gas per hour, between the smaller and the larger burner?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;0.2785%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;0.2835%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;0.2885%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;0.2915%&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Percentage gas usage per hour for small burner is (1/104) &amp;times; 100% = 0.9615%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Percentage gas usage per hour for big burner is (1/80) &amp;times; 100% = 1.25%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, percentage difference is 0.25 + 0.0385 = 0.2885%&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(636,7,'3','','&lt;p&gt;On a shelf, the first row contains 25% more books than the second row and the third row contains 25% less books than the second row. If the total number of books contained in all the rows is 600, then find the number of books in the second row.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;160&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;200&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;240&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;175&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;We can easily see that the number of books in the three shelves are in AP.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the middle shelf will contain 600/3 = 200 books.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(637,7,'3','','&lt;p&gt;The population of a village is 9000. If the number of males increases by 11% and the number of females increases by 20%, then the population becomes 10350. Find the final population of females in the town.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4800&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4200&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4550&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;The percentage of total population increase is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/174.16.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;236&quot; height=&quot;42&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 15%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The percent difference to the total average is 4% for men while it is 5% for women. So, we can say that the ratio of men to women is 5/4.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of women is (4/9) &amp;times; 9000 = 4000 initially and (120/100) &amp;times; 4000 = 4800 finally.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(638,7,'3','','&lt;p&gt;In an election between two candidates, the one who gets 35% of the votes polled is defeated by 15000 votes. The number of votes casted for the winning candidate is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;50000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;33000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;30000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;40000&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;The difference in the ratio is 65% - 35% = 30%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, 30% of votes amount to 15000 votes.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the number of votes that are casted for the winning candidate is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/174.17.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;91&quot; height=&quot;44&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 33000.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(639,7,'3','','&lt;p&gt;In a public sector company, 30% employees opted for pension and 50% employees opted for provident fund. The remaining employees were uncertain. If the difference between those who opted for provident fund and those who were uncertain was 1440, how many married employees opted for the provident fund, if it is known that 60% of the married employees opted for provident fund and 25% of total employees are not married?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4800&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2160&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2400&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;50% applied for provident fund and 20% are uncertain.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, 30% of the employees is 1440.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total number of employees in the organisation is 1440 &amp;times; (100/30) = 4800.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of married employees who opted for provident fund is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/174.18.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;78&quot; height=&quot;40&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;times; 4800 = 2160.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(640,7,'3','','&lt;p&gt;If the radius of a circle is diminished by 10%, the area is diminished by&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;15%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;20%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;19%&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;If the initial radius is r, the final radius is 0.9r.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, ratio of two areas is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/174.19.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;108&quot; height=&quot;44&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the area is diminished by 19%.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(641,7,'3','','&lt;p&gt;At a college, 60% of the students are boys and the rest are girls. Further 15% of the boys and 7.5% of the girls are getting a fee waiver. If the number of those getting a fee waiver is 90, find the total number of students getting 50% concession if it is given that 50% of those not getting a fee waiver are eligible to get half fee concession?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;300&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;330&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;350&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;400&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;If there are x students, then 0.6x are boys and 0.4x are girls.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the total number of students getting a fee waiver is [(15/100) &amp;times; 0.6x] + [(7.5/100) &amp;times; 0.4x] = 90&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;=&amp;gt; 0.12x = 90 =&amp;gt; x = 90/0.12 = 750.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;50% of the remaining 750 - 90 = 660 students are getting half waiver.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, (50/100) &amp;times; 660 = 330 students are getting fee waiver.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(642,7,'4','','&lt;p&gt;If two successive discounts are 30% and 25% then its equivalent discount is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;47.5%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;55%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;52%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;50%&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;If the successive discounts are x% and y%, then the effective discount is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/175.1.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;112&quot; height=&quot;38&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Here x = 30 and y = 25. So, effective discount is 30 + 25 - (750/100) = 47.5%.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(643,7,'4','','&lt;p&gt;If two successive discounts are 45% and 20% then its equivalent discount is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;60%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;55%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;52%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;56%&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;If the successive discounts are x% and y%, then the effective discount is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/175.1.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;112&quot; height=&quot;38&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Here x = 45 and y = 20. So, effective discount is 45 + 20 - (900/100) = 56%.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(644,7,'4','','&lt;p&gt;If a number is first increased by 20% and then again reduced by 20%, then what is the % change?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4% increase&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4% decrease&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;8% increase&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;8% decrease&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;The value decreases by&amp;nbsp;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/175.3.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;143&quot; height=&quot;42&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(645,7,'4','','&lt;p&gt;If a number is first increased by 25% and then again reduced by 25%, then what is the % change?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10% increase&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6.25% decrease&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6.25% increase&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10% decrease&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;The value decreases by&amp;nbsp;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/175.4.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;164&quot; height=&quot;42&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(646,7,'4','','&lt;p&gt;What is 12.5% of 40% of 80% of 160?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6.4&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5.25&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5.75&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6.5&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/175.5.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;126&quot; height=&quot;43&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;times; 160 = 6.4.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(647,7,'4','','&lt;p&gt;What is 30% of 25% of 10% of 40?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;0.5&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;0.25&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;0.6&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;0.3&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/175.6.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;110&quot; height=&quot;41&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;times; 40 = 0.3.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(648,7,'4','','&lt;p&gt;In an election between 2 candidates. Ravi gets 55 % of the total valid votes. If the total votes were 8000. What is the number of valid votes that the other candidate Mouli gets if 20% of the total votes were declared invalid?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2925&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2880&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1875&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Total number of valid votes is (80/100) &amp;times; 8000 = 6400.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the number of votes that the other candidate gets is (45/100) &amp;times; 6400 = 2800.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(649,7,'4','','&lt;p&gt;Total number of valid votes is 80/100&amp;times;8000=6400. So, the number of votes that the other candidate gets is 45/100&amp;times;6400=2800.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2250&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2070&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2160&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2340&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Total number of valid votes is 9000.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Suresh gets 62% and so Ramesh gets 38%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, Suresh will win the election by 62 - 38 = 24%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The difference in the number of votes is (24/100) &amp;times; 9000 = 2160.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(650,7,'4','','&lt;p&gt;A number is mistakenly divided by 10 instead of being multiplied by10. Find the percentage change in the result due to this mistake&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;25%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;98%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;99%&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;Assume that the number is 100. The result is 1000 instead of the correct result 10.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the error percentage is (990/1000) &amp;times; 100% = 99%.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(651,7,'4','','&lt;p&gt;A number is mistakenly divided by 4/3 instead of being multiplied by 3/4. Find the percentage change in the result due to this mistake&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;25%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;93.75%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;98%&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Assume that the number is 100. The result is 400 instead of the correct result 25.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the error percentage is (375/400) &amp;times; 100% = 93.75%.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(652,7,'4','','&lt;p&gt;The price of rice falls by 30%. How much rice can be bought now with the money that was sufficient to buy 21 kg of rice previously?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;24 Kg&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;25 Kg&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;30 Kg&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;28 Kg&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;If the previous price of rice is x, then the new price is (70/100) &amp;times; x = 0.7x.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the number of kg of rice we can buy with 21x is (21x/0.7x) = 30 kg.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(653,7,'4','','&lt;p&gt;The price of rice increases by 40%. How much rice can be bought now with the money that was sufficient to buy 28 kg of rice previously?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;24 Kg&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;16 Kg&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;20 Kg&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;22Kg&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;If the previous price of rice is x, then the new price is (140/100) &amp;times; x = 1.4x.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the number of kg of rice we can buy now with 28x is (28x/1.4x) = 20 kg.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(654,7,'4','','&lt;p&gt;Ashok&amp;rsquo;s salary is 60% more than Susan&amp;rsquo;s. Ashok got a raise of 20% on his salary while Susan got a raise of 25% on her salary. By what percent is Susan&amp;rsquo;s salary less than Ashok&amp;rsquo;s?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;34.89%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;36.61%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;46%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;41.5%&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;If Susan&amp;rsquo;s initial salary is Rs.100, then Ashok&amp;rsquo;s salary will be Rs.160. After the raises, Susan&amp;rsquo;s salary will be Rs.125 and Ashok&amp;rsquo;s salary will be (120/100) &amp;times; 160 = Rs.192.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, Susan&amp;rsquo;s salary is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/175.13.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;212&quot; height=&quot;38&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 34.89% less than Ashok&amp;rsquo;s present salary.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(655,7,'4','','&lt;p&gt;A donkey and a goat cost Rs. 3000 and Rs. 1500 respectively. If the price of the donkey and that of the goat is increased by 10% and 20% respectively, then the price of 1 donkey and 2 goats is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4800&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6900&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6040&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6100&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;New price of the donkey is (110/100) &amp;times; 3000 = Rs.3300.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;New price of the goat is (120/100) &amp;times; 1500 = Rs.1800.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the required price is 3300 + (1800 &amp;times; 2) = 3300 + 3600 = Rs.6900.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(656,7,'4','','&lt;p&gt;A shirt and a trouser cost Rs. 600 and Rs. 200 respectively. If the price of the trouser and that of the shirt is increased by 25% and 30% respectively, then the price of 3 shirts and 1 trouser is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2520&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2590&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2550&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2610&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;New price of the trouser is (125/100) &amp;times; 200 = Rs.250.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;New price of the shirt is (130/100) &amp;times; 600 = Rs.780.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the required price is (780 &amp;times; 3) + 250 = 2340 + 250 = Rs.2590.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(657,7,'4','','&lt;p&gt;I was offered two deals on the same item in two different shops. The first shop owner offered me a discount of 45% percent and the second one offered me two successive discounts of 25% and 20%. Which is a better deal?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;First Offer&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Second Offer&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Both are the same&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Data insufficient&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;A single discount of 45% is better than to successive discounts of 25% and 20% because, if the successive discounts are x% and y%, then the effective discount is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/175.16.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;97&quot; height=&quot;37&quot; /&gt;% = 40%&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(658,7,'4','','&lt;p&gt;I was offered two deals on the same item in two different shops. The first shop owner offered me a discount of 45% percent and the second one offered me two successive discounts of 30% and 20% respectively. Which is a better deal?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;First Offer&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Second Offer&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Both are the same&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Data insufficient&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;If the successive discounts are x% and y%, then the effective discount is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/175.17.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;98&quot; height=&quot;33&quot; /&gt;%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Here x = 30% and y = 20%. So, the effective discount is 30 + 20 - 6 = 44%. So, first deal is better.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(659,7,'4','','&lt;p&gt;After three successive equal percentage rise in the salary, the sum of 200 rupees tuned into 266 rupees and 20 paise. Find the percentage rise in the salary&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;11%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;13%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;12%&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Let the rise percentage be r%. There are 3 rises.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/175.18.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;412&quot; height=&quot;40&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 1.1 =&amp;gt; r = 10%&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(660,7,'4','','&lt;p&gt;After three successive equal percentage rise in the salary, the sum of 500 rupees tuned into 864 rupees. Find the percentage rise in the salary&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;12%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;14%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;20%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;15%&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Let the rise percentage be r%. There are 3 rises.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/175.19.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;386&quot; height=&quot;46&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 1.20 =&amp;gt; r = 20%.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(661,7,'4','','&lt;p&gt;Danny sells his goods 20% cheaper than Ronnie and 10% dearer than Tony. How much percentage is Tony&amp;rsquo; goods cheaper than Ronnie&#039;s?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;40%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;30%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;66.67%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;37.5%&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;Let Tony&amp;rsquo;s goods cost Rs. 100. Then Danny&amp;rsquo;s products cost (110/100) &amp;times; 100 = Rs.110 and that of Ronnie is (80x/100) = 110 =&amp;gt; x = 110 &amp;times; (100/80) = Rs.137.5.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, we can see that Tony&amp;rsquo;s goods are 37.50% cheaper than Ronnie&amp;rsquo;s.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(662,7,'4','','&lt;p&gt;David sells his goods 20% cheaper than Robert and 30% dearer than Thomas. How much percentage is Thomas&amp;rsquo; goods cheaper than Robert&#039;s?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;50%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;60%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;66.67%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;62.5%&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;Let Thomas&amp;rsquo; goods cost Rs. 100. Then David&amp;rsquo;s products cost (130/100) &amp;times; 100 = Rs.130 and that of Robert is (80x/100) = 130 =&amp;gt; x = 130 &amp;times; (100/80) = Rs.162.5.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, we can see that Thomas&amp;rsquo; goods are 62.50% cheaper than Roberts&amp;rsquo;.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(663,7,'4','','&lt;p&gt;When 50% of a number A is added to another number B, B becomes 165% of its previous value. Then which of the following is true regarding the values of A and B?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;A = B&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;A &amp;gt; B&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;A &amp;lt; B&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Data Insufficient&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;B + 0.5A = 1.65B =&amp;gt; 0.5A = 0.65B =&amp;gt; &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/175.22.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;55&quot; height=&quot;43&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;=&amp;gt; A &amp;gt; B.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(664,7,'4','','&lt;p&gt;The entrance ticket for a circus is worth Rs. 200. When the price of the ticket was lowered, the sale of tickets increased by 40% while the collections recorded a decrease of 30%. Find the deduction in the ticket price.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 145&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 135&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 155&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 100&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;If the increased ticket price is Rs.x, then we can say that the sale ratio in both cases is (100/70).&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Sales increased by 40%. Let initial sales be 100. Final sales are 140.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/175.23.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;123&quot; height=&quot;46&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;=&amp;gt; x = 2 &amp;times; 50 = Rs.100.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, deduction in ticket price is 200 - 100 = Rs.100.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(665,7,'4','','&lt;p&gt;Vanaja&amp;rsquo;s project report consists of 30 pages each of 50 lines with 80 characters on each line. In case the number of lines is reduced to 30 but the number of characters is increased to 100 per lines, what is the percentage change in the number of pages?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;33.33%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;8.74%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6.67%&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Total number of characters remains the same.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, 30 &amp;times; 50 &amp;times; 80 = x &amp;times; 30 &amp;times; 100 =&amp;gt; x = &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/175.24.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;93&quot; height=&quot;38&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 40 pages.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, percentage change in number of pages is (10/30) &amp;times; 100% = 33.33%.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(666,7,'4','','&lt;p&gt;A company hired a salesman on a monthly salary of Rs.5000. In addition to it, the salesman was entitled for 25% commission on the monthly sale. How much sale the salesman should do if he wants his monthly income as Rs. 20,000?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 35000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 40000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 45000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 60000&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;If his monthly income is Rs. 20000, then he gets commissions of Rs. 15000.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, if S is the monthly sale, then the commissions will be 0.25S = 15000 =&amp;gt; S = Rs.60000.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(667,7,'4','','&lt;p&gt;Ravi goes to a shop to buy a sofa set costing Rs. 16500. The rate of sales tax is 10%. She tells the shopkeeper to reduce the price of the sofa set to such an extent that she has to pay Rs. 16500 inclusive of sales tax. Find the percentage reduction needed in the price of the sofa set to just satisfy her requirement.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;8%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;8.15%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;9.09%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;8.35%&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;The total price including the tax should be Rs. 16500.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, if C is the cost price and 10% is the tax then 1.1C = 16500 =&amp;gt; C = 16500/1.1 = Rs.15000.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the percentage reduction needed is (1500/16500) &amp;times; 100% = 9.09%&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(668,7,'4','','&lt;p&gt;Ram goes to a shop to buy an Owen set costing Rs. 12000. The rate of sales tax is 20%. She tells the shopkeeper to reduce the price of the Owen set to such an extent that he has to pay Rs. 12000 inclusive of sales tax. Find the percentage reduction needed in the price of the Owen set to just satisfy his requirement.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;8%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;8.15%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;16.67%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;8.35%&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;The total price including the tax should be Rs. 12000.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, if C is the cost price and 20% is the tax then 1.2C = 12000 =&amp;gt; C = (12000/1.2) = Rs.10000.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the percentage reduction needed is (2000/12000) &amp;times; 100% = 16.67%&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(669,7,'4','','&lt;p&gt;A&amp;rsquo;s salary is first increased by 50% and then decreased by 20%.The result is the same as B&amp;rsquo;s salary increased by 20% and then reduced by 50%. Find the ratio of B&amp;rsquo;s salary to that of A&amp;rsquo;s&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2 : 1&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1 : 1&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;9 : 10&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;3 : 4&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Let A&amp;rsquo;s salary be Rs.x and B&amp;rsquo;s salary be Rs.y.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, A&amp;rsquo;s salary after the changes is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/175.28.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;249&quot; height=&quot;41&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, B&amp;rsquo;s salary after the changes is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/175.28.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;246&quot; height=&quot;41&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/175.28.3.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;67&quot; height=&quot;40&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;=&amp;gt; y : x = 2 : 1.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(670,7,'4','','&lt;p&gt;A is 60% more than B. C is 3/4 of A and D is 50% more than C. Now, each of A, B, C and D is increased by 20%. Find what per cent of B is D (after the increase)?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;180%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;150%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;120%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;100%&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Let B be 100. So, A will be 160. C will be (3/4) &amp;times; 160 = 120. D will be 1.5C = 180.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If all these are increased by 20%, then B becomes 120 and D becomes 1.2 &amp;times; 180 = 216.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, D is (216/120) &amp;times; 100% = 180% of B.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(671,7,'4','','&lt;p&gt;A is 20% more than B. C is 4/5 of A and D is 50% more than C. Now, each of A, B, C and D is increased by 25%. Find what per cent of B is D (after the increase)?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;144%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;150%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;120%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;100%&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Let B be 100. So, A will be 120. C will be (4/5) &amp;times; 120 = 96. D will be 1.5C = 144.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If all these are increased by 25%, then B becomes 125 and D becomes 1.25 &amp;times; 144 = 180.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, D is (180/125) &amp;times; 100% = 144% of B.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(672,7,'4','','&lt;p&gt;Two numbers X and Y are 25% and 40% less than a third number Z. Find by what percentage is the number Y less than the number X&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;8%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;20%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;12%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6%&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;If the number Z is 100, then X and Y are 75 and 60 respectively.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, Y is (15/75) &amp;times; 100 = 20% less than X.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(673,7,'4','','&lt;p&gt;Two numbers X and Y are 30% and 50 % more than a third number Z. Find by what percentage is the number X is less than the number Y&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;13.33%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;12.5%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;11.25%&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;If the number Z is 100, then X and Y are 130 and 150 respectively.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, x is (20/150) &amp;times; 100 = 13.33% less than Y.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(674,7,'4','','&lt;p&gt;Due to a 20% hike in the price of rice per kilogram, a person is able to purchase 10 kg less for Rs. 600. Find the original price of rice per kilogram.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 15&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 8&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 12&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 10&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;Let the original price be Rs.x. So, the final price will be Rs. 6x/5.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The difference in the quantities for Rs. 600 is 10 kg.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/175.33.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;212&quot; height=&quot;55&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= Rs.10.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the original price of rice is Rs.10 per kg.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(675,7,'4','','&lt;p&gt;Due to a 10% hike in the price of rice per kilogram, a person is able to purchase 8 kg less for Rs. 440. Find the increased price of rice per kilogram&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 4&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 5.5&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 6&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 10&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Let the original price be Rs.x. So, the final price will be Rs. 11x/10.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The difference in the quantities for Rs. 400 is 20 kg.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/175.34.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;165&quot; height=&quot;53&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 8x =&amp;gt; x = Rs.5.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the new price is Rs.5.50.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(676,7,'4','','&lt;p&gt;The price of raw materials has gone up by 30%, labour cost has also increased from 40% of the cost of raw material to 50% of the cost of raw material. By how much percentage should there be a reduction in the usage of raw materials so as to keep the cost same?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;30%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;35%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;45%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;40%&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;If the initial price of raw materials is Rs. 100, then the price of labour is (40/100) &amp;times; 100 = 40.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The increase prices are Rs.130 and (50/100) &amp;times; 130 = 65.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the total cost initially is Rs.125 and finally is 130 + 65 = 195.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Since the product is constant, the percentage reduction required will be &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/175.35.3.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;77&quot; height=&quot;38&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;times; 100% = 40%(appox).&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(677,7,'4','','&lt;p&gt;A salesman is appointed on the basic salary of Rs. 1500 per month and the condition that for every sales of above Rs. 15,000, he will get 40% of basic salary and 20% of the sales as a reward. This incentive scheme does not operate for the first Rs.10000 of sales. What should be the value of sales if he wants to earn Rs. 8000 in a particular month?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 44500&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 76000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 66000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 80000&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;The commission that he wants to earn is 8000 - 1500 = Rs.6500.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Once the sales get above Rs. 15000, he will get 40% of basic salary which is Rs.600.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;He will also get a 20% commission on the sales. So, his sale must be (20/100).x = 5900 =&amp;gt; x = 29500 above the limit of Rs. 15,000. So, his total monthly sale must be Rs. 44500.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(678,7,'4','','&lt;p&gt;A salesman is appointed on the basic salary of Rs. 2000 per month and the condition that for every sales of above Rs. 8,000, he will get 25% of basic salary and 40% of the sales as a reward. This incentive scheme does not operate for the first Rs.8000 of sales. What should be the value of sales if he wants to earn Rs. 10000 in a particular month?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 26500&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 76000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 66000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 80000&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;The commission that he wants to earn is 10000 - 2000 = Rs.8000.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Once the sales get above Rs. 8000, he will get 25% of basic salary which is Rs.500.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;He will also get a 40% commission on the sales. So, his sale must be (40/100)x = 7500 =&amp;gt; x = 18750 above the limit of Rs. 26750. So, his total monthly sale must be Rs. 44500.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(679,7,'4','','&lt;p&gt;When the price of an article was reduced by 20%, the sale of the article is increased by 25%. What was the effect on the sales?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2% increase&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2% decrease&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;no change&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5% increase&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Total sales initially is xy where x is the price of an article and y is the number of items sold.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, final sales will be 0.8x &amp;times; 1.25y = 1.00xy.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, there will be a no change in sales.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(680,7,'4','','&lt;p&gt;When the price of an article was reduced by 10%, the sale of the article is increased by25%. What was the effect on the sales?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;12.5% increase&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10% decrease&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;12.5% decrease&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;15% increase&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Total sales initially is xy where x is the price of an article and y is the number of items sold.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, final sales will be 0.9x &amp;times; 1.25y = 1.125xy.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, there will be a 12.5% increase in sales.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(681,7,'4','','&lt;p&gt;In a factory, 70% of the employees are males. Among them 30% are matriculates and the remaining are graduates. Among the females, 50% are matriculates and the remaining are graduates. If the total number of female employees in the factory is 600, how many graduates are there in the factory?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1144&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1148&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1280&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1156&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Since 30% of the employees are females, total number of employees in the factory is (100/30) &amp;times; 600 = 2000.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total number of male employees is (70/100) &amp;times; 2000 = 1400.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of graduates are &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/175.40.3.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;193&quot; height=&quot;42&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 1280.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(682,7,'4','','&lt;p&gt;In an examination, Harris got 3 marks less than 60% of the full marks and Ravi got 6 marks more than 50% of the full marks. Harris beats Ravi by 4 marks. The marks scored by Ravi is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;70&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;71&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;72&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;73&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;3 marks less than 60% is 4 more than 6 marks greater than 50%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the difference between 60% and 50% is 3 + 4 + 6 = 13.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the total marks is 130 and 50% of that is (50/100) &amp;times; 130 = 65.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the marks scored by Ravi is 65 + 6=71.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(683,7,'4','','&lt;p&gt;The population of a village is 15000. If the number of males increases by 16% and the number of females increases by 13%, then the population becomes 17750. Find the final population of men in the town.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4500&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10000&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;The percentage of total population increase is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/175.42.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;249&quot; height=&quot;42&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 15%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The percent difference to the total average is 1% for men while it is 2% for women. So, we can say that the ratio of men to women is 2:1.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of men is (1/3) &amp;times; 15000 = 5000 initially.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(684,7,'4','','&lt;p&gt;In an election between two candidates, the one who gets 45% of the votes polled is defeated by 9000 votes. The number of votes casted for the winning candidate is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;50000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;49500&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;30000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;40000&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;The difference in the ratio is 55% - 45% = 10%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, 10% of votes amount to 9000 votes.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the number of votes that are casted for the winning candidate is 55 &amp;times; (9000/10) = 49500.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(685,7,'4','','&lt;p&gt;On Pandora Island, there are x dodos in a particular year. 20 dodos in a thousand of the original population die every year and 25 dodos in a thousand of the original population are born every year. In how many years will the population of dodos double itself?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;200&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;125&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;100&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Indeterminate&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Out of every 1000, 5 dodos increase every year. So, the entire population will double itself in 1000/5 = 200 years.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(686,7,'4','','&lt;p&gt;The population of a village is 14000. If the number of males increases by 10% and the number of females increases by 24%, then the population increases by 16%. Find the initial population of females in the town.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;7000&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;The percentage of total population increase is 16%.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The percent difference to the total average is 6% for men while it is 8% for women. So, we can say that the ratio of men to women is 4:3.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of women is (3/7) &amp;times; 14000 = 6000 initially&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(687,8,'1','','&lt;p&gt;There are three numbers, which are in arithmetic progression, the common difference being 7. If the second number is diminished by 1 and the last number increased by 4, the numbers would be in geometric progression. Find the largest of the three numbers.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;13&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;7&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;20&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Let the numbers be (x - 7), x and (x + 7).&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the numbers (x - 7), (x - 1) and (x + 11) are in GP.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/182.1.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;180&quot; height=&quot;25&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/182.1.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;344&quot; height=&quot;23&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the largest of these numbers is 13 + 7 = 20.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(688,8,'1','','&lt;p&gt;In a number system 12, 20, 24 are in an arithmetic progression. What is the base of the number system?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;7&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;8&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;If the base of the number system is b, then the numbers are (b + 2), 2b and (2b + 4).&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Since they are in AP, 2(2b) = (b + 2) + (2b + 4) =&amp;gt; b = 6.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(689,8,'1','','&lt;p&gt;How many terms are there in the AP 4,7,10,&amp;hellip;133?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;43&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;44&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;45&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;46&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Number of terms in an AP with first term a, last term b and the common difference d is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/182.3.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;91&quot; height=&quot;38&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Here a = 4, b = 133 and d = 3.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, number of terms is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/182.3.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;252&quot; height=&quot;48&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(690,8,'1','','&lt;p&gt;Bobby was appointed to UGC in the pay scale of 70,000-5000-125,000. Find how many years he will take to reach the maximum of the scale&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;11&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;12&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;13&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Number of terms in an AP with first term a, last term b and the common difference d is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/182.4.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;101&quot; height=&quot;40&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Here a = 70000, b = 125000 and d = 5000.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, number of terms is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/182.4.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;299&quot; height=&quot;40&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(691,8,'1','','&lt;p&gt;Find the 1st term of an AP whose 8th and 12th terms are respectively 39 and 59.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;7&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Let a be the first term and d be the common difference.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;a + 7d = 39, a + 11d = 59 =&amp;gt; 4d = 20 =&amp;gt; d = 5.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;a + 35 = 39 =&amp;gt; a = 4.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the first term is a = 4.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(692,8,'1','','&lt;p&gt;A number of squares are given whose perimeters are in GP. Then their sides will be in&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;AP&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;GP&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;HP&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;None&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;In the case of squares, perimeters are proportional to sides and dividing all terms of a GP with a constant will give another GP.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(693,8,'1','','&lt;p&gt;How many terms are identical in the two APs 1,4,7,10&amp;hellip;(120 terms) and 3,5,7,9,&amp;hellip;(130 terms)?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;43&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;58&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;50&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;41&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Every term that is in the form of (2n+1); n=1,2,3&amp;hellip; in the first series is present in the second series. Number of such terms is 58.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Every term that is in the form of (3n); n=1,2,3&amp;hellip; in the second series is present in the first series. Number of such terms is 130/3 = 43.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, number of required terms is min (58, 43) = 43.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(694,8,'1','','&lt;p&gt;Find the 15th term of the sequence 16,14,12,&amp;hellip;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;-80&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;-82&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;-84&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;-86&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/182.8.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;123&quot; height=&quot;23&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Here n = 50; a = 16; d = -2.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/182.8.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;235&quot; height=&quot;20&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(695,8,'1','','&lt;p&gt;A sum of money kept in a bank amounts to Rs. 2240 in 4 years and Rs. 2600 in 10 years at simple Interest. Find the sum.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1500&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1750&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;The sum of money is an AP because the simple interest will be the same each year.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, if &#039;a&#039; is the initial sum and &#039;d&#039; is the interest every annum, then a + 4d = 2240; a + 10d = 2600.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, 6d = 360 =&amp;gt; d = 60 =&amp;gt; a = 2000.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the initial sum is Rs.2000.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(696,8,'1','','&lt;p&gt;The number of terms of the series 64+60+56+â‹¯ such that the sum is 544 is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;16&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;17&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;both 16 and 17&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;either 16 or 17&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Let the number of terms be n.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/182.10.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;325&quot; height=&quot;19&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/182.10.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;535&quot; height=&quot;29&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(697,8,'1','','&lt;p&gt;A man receives 100 for the first week and 8 more each week than the preceding week. How much does he earn by the 20th week?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;3000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;3520&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;3760&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;a = 100; d = 8 and n = 20.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/182.11.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;371&quot; height=&quot;39&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(698,8,'1','','&lt;p&gt;If the fifth term of a GP is 81 and first term is 16, what will be the 4th term of the GP?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;54&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;48&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;27&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;72&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;In a GP with the first term as a and the common ratio as r, the nth term is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/182.12.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;80&quot; height=&quot;25&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/182.12.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;185&quot; height=&quot;35&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/182.12.3.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;208&quot; height=&quot;40&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the fourth term is 54.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(699,8,'1','','&lt;p&gt;The seventh term of a GP is 8 times the fourth term. What will be the first term when its fifth term is 48?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;3&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/182.13.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;150&quot; height=&quot;47&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/182.13.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;211&quot; height=&quot;25&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the first term is 3.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(700,8,'1','','&lt;p&gt;Four geometric means are inserted between 1/8 and 128. Find the third geometric mean.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;8&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;32&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;16&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;If four GMs are inserted, then &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/182.14.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;44&quot; height=&quot;36&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;and &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/182.14.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;64&quot; height=&quot;21&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/182.14.3.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;129&quot; height=&quot;26&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The third GM would be the fourth term and so &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/182.14.4.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;152&quot; height=&quot;38&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(701,8,'1','','&lt;p&gt;A and B are two numbers whose AM is 25 and GM is 7. Which of the following may be a value of A?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;49&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;25&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;24&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;20&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;If the two numbers are a and b, then the AM is (a + b)/2 and the GM is &amp;radic;ab.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, a + b = 50; ab = 49 =&amp;gt; a = 49 or 1.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(702,8,'1','','&lt;p&gt;Jack and Jill were playing mathematical puzzles with each other. Jill drew a square of sides 8 cm and then kept on drawing squares inside the squares by joining the mid points of the squares. She continued this process indefinitely. Jill asked Jack to determine the sum of the areas of all the squares that she drew. If Jack answered correctly then what would be his answer?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;256&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;128&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;64&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;255&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Area if each rectangle is half the area of the receding square.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;All the areas will form an infinite GP with the common ratio 1/2.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Sum of all terms of the GP is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/182.16.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;43&quot; height=&quot;34&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;where a is the first term.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Area of the top square is 8&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; = 256.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Area of all remaining squares is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/182.16.3.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;229&quot; height=&quot;64&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(703,8,'1','','&lt;p&gt;The internal angles of a plane polygon are in AP. The smallest angle is 100&amp;deg; and the common difference is 10&amp;deg;. Find the number of sides of the polygon.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;3&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Sum of all internal angles is 360&amp;deg;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If the polygon has n sides, then &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/182.17.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;332&quot; height=&quot;41&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(704,8,'1','','&lt;p&gt;If 3 times the 3rd term of an AP is equal to 5 times the 5th term, find the 8th term.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;8&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;-8&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;0&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Cannot be determined&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/182.18.1.jpg&quot;