urs to fill the jar to capacity, the first jar will be filled to its capacity in&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;3 hours 3 minutes&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;3 hours&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6 hours&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2 hours 57 minutes&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;It takes 3 minutes for the single amoeba to become two. Then it will be in the same position as the second jar. So, from there, it will take 3 hours to be completely filled.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(728,8,'3','','&lt;p&gt;A number which contains 1000 digits written as follows: 1234&amp;hellip;.101112&amp;hellip;&amp;hellip;. Find the remainder when the above number is divided by 4.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;0&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;3&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;The first 9 digits are single digit numbers.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Next, there are 90 two digit numbers and they take 90 &amp;times; 2 = 180 places. So, there are 811 places remaining.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, number of 3 digit numbers that can be written is 811/3 = 270 and the first digit of the next number.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The 270&lt;sup&gt;th&lt;/sup&gt; 3 digit number is 100 + 269 = 369. The 1000&lt;sup&gt;th&lt;/sup&gt; digit is 3.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the last 2 digits of the number are 9 and 3.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, when we divide the number by 4, the remainder is 93/4 = 23 1/4. So, the remainder is 1.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(729,8,'3','','&lt;p&gt;The average marks of 17 students in a class is A. The marks of students when arranged in ascending or descending order was found to be in A.P. The class teacher found that the students who were ranked 3, 7, 9, 11, 15 had copied in the exam and hence got all of them rusticated. The average of the remainder in the class was B. Then&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;A = B&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;A &amp;gt; B&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;A &amp;lt; B&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Cannot be determined&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;If the terms that are equidistant from the two ends of an AP are removed, then it will have no effect on the mean of the AP.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the mean will remain the same and so A = B.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(730,8,'3','','&lt;p&gt;A and B set out to meet each other from two places 165 km apart. A travels 15 km the first day, 14 km the second day, 13 km the third day and so on. B travels 10 km the first day, 12 km the second day, 14 km the third day and so on. After how many days will they meet?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;7&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Let us assume they meet after n days.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Distance travelled by A in &amp;lsquo;n&amp;rsquo; days is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/184.4.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;281&quot; height=&quot;38&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Distance travelled by B in n days is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/184.4.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;291&quot; height=&quot;34&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total distance that they travel is 165 km.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/184.4.3.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;367&quot; height=&quot;23&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(731,8,'3','','&lt;p&gt;If for an AP having 25 terms, &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/184.5.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;245&quot; height=&quot;22&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;, then the value of &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/184.5.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;108&quot; height=&quot;21&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;60&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;90&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;250&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;300&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;The sum of two terms of an AP which are equidistant from the two ends is equal to twice the AM of the entire AP.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/184.5.3.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;579&quot; height=&quot;27&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/184.5.4.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;291&quot; height=&quot;38&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(732,8,'3','','&lt;p&gt;One side of a staircase is to be closed in by rectangular planks from the floor to each step. The width of each plank is 9 inches and their height are successively 6 inches. 12 inches. 18 inches and so on. There are 24 planks required in total. Find the area in square feet&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;112.5&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;100&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;225&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;156.5&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Total area of the planks is (6 &amp;times; 9) + (12 &amp;times; 9) + (18 &amp;times; 9) + â‹¯.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;There are 24 terms in the series.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/184.6.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;597&quot; height=&quot;54&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(733,8,'3','','&lt;p&gt;The sum of the first terms of the arithmetic progression is equal to half the sum of the next terms of the same progression. Find the ratio of the sum of the first 3n terms of the progression to the sum of its first n terms&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;3: 1&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2: 1&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6: 1&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6: 4&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Given &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/184.7.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;509&quot; height=&quot;43&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/184.7.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;289&quot; height=&quot;30&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/184.7.3.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;224&quot; height=&quot;37&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;and &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/184.7.4.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;258&quot; height=&quot;47&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/184.7.5.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;72&quot; height=&quot;48&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(734,8,'3','','&lt;p&gt;In a certain colony of cancerous cells, each cell breaks into two new cells every hour. If there is a single productive cell at the strait and this process continues for 20 hours, how many cells will the colony have at the end of 11 hours? It is known that the life of an individual cell is 20 hours?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1023&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2047&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4095&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;8191&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Number of bacteria after the end of nth hour is 2 + 4 + 8 + â‹¯ = 2&lt;sup&gt;n&lt;/sup&gt;-1.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, after the end of 11th hour, the number of cells is 2&lt;sup&gt;11&lt;/sup&gt;-1 = 2047.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(735,8,'3','','&lt;p&gt;A student takes a test consisting of 100 questions with differential marking and is told that each question after the first is worth 2 marks more than the preceding question. If the sixth question of the test is worth 11 marks, what is the maximum score that the student can obtain by attempting 85 questions?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;9775&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;7225&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;8000&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;The marks for each question are in AP with the common difference 2.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Let the first term be a.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;T&lt;sub&gt;6&lt;/sub&gt; = a + 5d = a + 10 = 11 =&amp;gt; a = 1.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, in this case, T&lt;sub&gt;n&lt;/sub&gt; = 2n-1; S&lt;sub&gt;n&lt;/sub&gt; = n&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The student answers 85 questions. He will get maximum marks when the student answers the last 85 questions.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, marks obtained is S&lt;sub&gt;100&lt;/sub&gt; - S&lt;sub&gt;15&lt;/sub&gt; = (100)&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; - (15)&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; = 10000 - 225 = 9775.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(736,8,'3','','&lt;p&gt;If the 5th term of an AP is 9 and the 9th term is 5, then what is the sum of 12th, 15th and 18th terms of that AP?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;0&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;-3&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;3&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;8&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;If the mth term of an AP is n and the nth term of an AP is m, then its pth term is given by m + n - p. So, T&lt;sub&gt;n&lt;/sub&gt; = 5 + 9 - n = 14 - n.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The required sum is T&lt;sub&gt;12&lt;/sub&gt; + T&lt;sub&gt;15&lt;/sub&gt; + T&lt;sub&gt;18&lt;/sub&gt; = 42 - 12 - 15 - 18 = -3.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(737,8,'3','','&lt;p&gt;If the tenth term of an AP is 25 and sum of its first four terms is 40, find the sum of first 10 terms.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;120&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;140&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;160&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;180&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Sum of the first four terms is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/184.11.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;367&quot; height=&quot;42&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The 10th term is T&lt;sub&gt;10&lt;/sub&gt; = a + 9d = 25.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the value of a is 7 and the value of d is 2.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, sum of first 10 terms is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/184.11.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;280&quot; height=&quot;41&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(738,8,'3','','&lt;p&gt;Ratio of the 15th term to the 7th term of an AP is 11:5. Find the ratio of the 12th term to the 2nd term.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5: 1&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5: 2&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;7: 1&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;7: 3&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Given &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/184.12.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;489&quot; height=&quot;46&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The required ratio is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/184.12.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;203&quot; height=&quot;44&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(739,8,'3','','&lt;p&gt;Sum of the first 10 terms of an AP is 112 and the sum of the next 10 terms is 362. Find the common difference of the AP.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2.5&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;3&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;3.5&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Each term of the second series exceeds the corresponding term of the first series by 10d.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;For example, T&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt; = a + 2d; T&lt;sub&gt;13&lt;/sub&gt; = a + 12d =&amp;gt; T&lt;sub&gt;12&lt;/sub&gt; - T&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt; = 10d.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The total difference of the two series is 10 &amp;times; 10d = 100d = 362 - 112 = 250.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the value of the common difference is 250/100 = 2.5.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(740,8,'3','','&lt;p&gt;If a, b, c are the pth, qth and rth terms of an AP, then the value of p(b - c) + q(c - a) + r(a - b) is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;0&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;ap + bq + cr&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Not a unique value&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;For any choice of a, b, c, p, q, r the term will always be equal to zero.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(741,8,'3','','&lt;p&gt;If the AM of two numbers is 10 and the GM is 8, then the HM is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;8&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6.4&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;AM, GM and HM form a GP.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/184.15.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;167&quot; height=&quot;43&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(742,8,'3','','&lt;p&gt;If x = 1 + a + a&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; + â‹¯ and y = 1 + b + b&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; + â‹¯ such that |a|&amp;lt;1, |b|&amp;lt;1, then the value of the series 1 + ab + a&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;b&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; + â‹¯ is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/184.16.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;82&quot; height=&quot;50&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/184.16.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;82&quot; height=&quot;44&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/184.16.3.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;80&quot; height=&quot;40&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/184.16.4.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;80&quot; height=&quot;45&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;We can say that &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/184.16.5.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;262&quot; height=&quot;46&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Similarly, &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/184.16.6.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;177&quot; height=&quot;44&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/184.16.7.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;281&quot; height=&quot;47&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(743,8,'3','','&lt;p&gt;A and B play a game of throwing dice alternatively. The first person to throw 6 wins. If A starts the game, what is the probability that A will win the game?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1/6&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5/6&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6/11&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;25/36&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;The probability for success is 1/6 and failure is 5/6.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&#039;A&#039; will win in the following cases:&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;1. A succeeds, P=1/6;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;2. A fails, B fails, A succeeds, P=(5/6) x (5/6) x (1/6);&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;3. A fails, B fails, A fails, B fails, A succeeds, P=(5/6)&lt;sup&gt;4&lt;/sup&gt; x (1/6).&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;As we can see, this is an infinite series with first term a = 1/6 and common ratio r = 25/36.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, probability required is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/184.17.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;150&quot; height=&quot;72&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(744,8,'3','','&lt;p&gt;The number of terms of an AP is even. The sum of all odd terms is 63 and all even terms is 72. If the last term exceeds the first term by 16.5, find the number of terms.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;12&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;18&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;24&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Let there be 2n terms.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The difference between the first term and the last term is (2n - 1)d = 16.5.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Each term in the series of even terms exceed its corresponding term in the series of odd terms by d. There are &#039;n&#039; such terms. So, the difference between the two series is nd = 72 - 63 = 9.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, from the two results we can say that d = 1.5 =&amp;gt; n = 6.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, there are 2n = 12 terms in the AP.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(745,8,'3','','&lt;p&gt;The third term of a GP is 3. The product of the first five terms of the GP is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;81&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;243&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;15&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;27&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;The geometric mean of a GP containing odd number of terms is the middle term.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the product of all the five terms is 3&lt;sup&gt;5&lt;/sup&gt; = 243.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;GM of a group on n terms is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/184.19.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;65&quot; height=&quot;78&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;where a&lt;sub&gt;i&lt;/sub&gt; is the ith term.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(746,8,'3','','&lt;p&gt;Find the average of the series 2,4,6,8&amp;hellip;42.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;20&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;22&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;24&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;23&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Number of terms in the series is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/184.20.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;112&quot; height=&quot;41&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Since there are odd number of terms in an AP, the middlemost term is the average of the series.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, average is T&lt;sub&gt;11&lt;/sub&gt; = a + 10d = 2 + 10(2) = 22.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(747,8,'4','','&lt;p&gt;How many terms are there in the AP 5, 10, 15, &amp;hellip; 200?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;43&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;40&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;45&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;46&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Number of terms in an AP with first term a, last term b and the common difference d is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/185.1.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;97&quot; height=&quot;51&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Here a = 5, b = 200, d = 5.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, number of terms is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/185.1.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;253&quot; height=&quot;42&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(748,8,'4','','&lt;p&gt;How many terms are there in the AP 6, 12, 18, &amp;hellip; 144?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;23&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;24&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;25&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;26&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Number of terms in an AP with first term a, last term b and the common difference d is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/185.2.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;100&quot; height=&quot;42&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Here a = 6, b = 144, d = 6.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, number of terms is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/185.2.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;260&quot; height=&quot;49&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(749,8,'4','','&lt;p&gt;Ravi was appointed as a professor in the pay scale of 60,000-6000-120,000. Find how many years he will take to reach the maximum of the scale&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;11&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;12&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;13&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Number of terms in an AP with first term a, last term b and the common difference d is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/185.3.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;99&quot; height=&quot;40&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Here a = 60000, b = 120000, d = 6000.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, number of terms is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/185.3.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;294&quot; height=&quot;42&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(750,8,'4','','&lt;p&gt;Find the 1st term of an AP whose 14th and 17th terms are respectively 56 and 68.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;7&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Let a be the first term and d be the common difference.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;a + 13d = 56; a + 16d = 68 =&amp;gt; 3d = 12 =&amp;gt; d = 4.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;a + 52 = 56 =&amp;gt; a = 4.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the first term is a = 4.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(751,8,'4','','&lt;p&gt;Find the 1st term of an AP whose 38th and 47th terms are respectively 77 and 95.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;3&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;Let a be the first term and d be the common difference.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;a + 37d = 77; a + 46d = 95 =&amp;gt; 9d = 18 =&amp;gt; d = 2.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;a + 74 = 77 =&amp;gt; a = 3.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the first term is a = 3.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(752,8,'4','','&lt;p&gt;Find the 6th term of an AP whose 14th and 21th terms are respectively 31 and 45.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;14&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;16&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;13&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;15&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;Let a be the first term and d be the common difference.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;a + 13d = 31; a + 20d = 45 =&amp;gt; 7d = 14 =&amp;gt; d = 2.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;a + 26 = 31 =&amp;gt; a = 5.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the sixth term is a + 5d = 5 + 10 = 15.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(753,8,'4','','&lt;p&gt;How many terms are identical in the two APs 2, 4, 6, 8 &amp;hellip; (120 terms) and 4, 8, 12, 16 &amp;hellip; (130 terms)?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;60&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;55&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;53&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;57&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Every term that is in the form of T&lt;sub&gt;2n&lt;/sub&gt;; n=1,2,3&amp;hellip; in the first series is present in the second series.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Number of such terms is 120/2 = 60.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Every term in the second series is present in the first series. Number of such terms is 130.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, number of required terms is min(60, 130) = 60.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(754,8,'4','','&lt;p&gt;Find the 10th term of the sequence 15, 10, 5&amp;hellip;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;-30&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;-32&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;-34&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;-36&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;T&lt;sub&gt;n&lt;/sub&gt; = a + (n-1)d.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Here n = 10, a = 15, d = -5.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;T&lt;sub&gt;50&lt;/sub&gt; = 15 - 9(5) = 15 - 45 = -30.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(755,8,'4','','&lt;p&gt;Find the 20th term of the sequence 81,77,73,69&amp;hellip;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;7&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;T&lt;sub&gt;n&lt;/sub&gt; = a + (n-1)d.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Here n = 20, a = 81, d = -4.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;T&lt;sub&gt;50&lt;/sub&gt; = 81 - 19(4) = 5.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(756,8,'4','','&lt;p&gt;A man receives Rs. 200 for the first week and Rs. 4 more each week than the preceding week. How much does he earn by the 25th week?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6400&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6200&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6600&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;a = 200, d = 4 and n = 25.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/185.10.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;374&quot; height=&quot;47&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(757,8,'4','','&lt;p&gt;If the 7th term of a GP is 128 and first term is 2, what will be the 3rd term of the GP?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;8&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;16&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;32&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;In a GP with the first term as a and the common ratio as r, the nth term is T&lt;sub&gt;n&lt;/sub&gt; = ar&lt;sup&gt;(n-1)&lt;/sup&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, a = 2, ar&lt;sup&gt;6&lt;/sup&gt; = 128 =&amp;gt; r = 2.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;T&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt; = ar&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; =&amp;gt; 2&amp;times;4 = 8.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the 3rd term is 8.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(758,8,'4','','&lt;p&gt;If the fifth term of a GP is 48 and first term is 3, what will be the 4th term of the GP?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;24&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;48&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;36&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;16&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;In a GP with the first term as a and the common ratio as r, the nth term is T&lt;sub&gt;n&lt;/sub&gt; = ar&lt;sup&gt;(n-1)&lt;/sup&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, a = 3, ar&lt;sup&gt;4&lt;/sup&gt; = 48 =&amp;gt; r = 2.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;T&lt;sub&gt;5&lt;/sub&gt; = r x T&lt;sub&gt;4&lt;/sub&gt; =&amp;gt; T&lt;sub&gt;4&lt;/sub&gt; = 48 &amp;times; (1/2) = 24.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the fourth term is 24.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(759,8,'4','','&lt;p&gt;The 7th term of a GP is 16 times the 3rd term. What will be the first term when its fifth term is 32?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;3&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/185.13.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;158&quot; height=&quot;46&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/185.13.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;210&quot; height=&quot;26&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the first term is 2.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(760,8,'4','','&lt;p&gt;The 5th term of a GP is 25 times the 3rd term. What will be the 4th term when its first term is 5?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;125&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;625&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;25&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;3125&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/185.14.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;166&quot; height=&quot;41&quot; /&gt;. And a = 5.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;T&lt;sub&gt;4&lt;/sub&gt; = ar&lt;sup&gt;3&lt;/sup&gt; = 5 &amp;times; 53 = 625.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the fourth term is 625.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(761,8,'4','','&lt;p&gt;Jack and Jill were playing mathematical puzzles with each other. Jill drew an equilateral triangle of area 16 sq. cm. and then kept on drawing triangles inside the triangles by joining the mid points of all the sides. She continued this process indefinitely. Jill asked Jack to determine the sum of the areas of all the triangles that she drew. If Jack answered correctly then what would be his answer?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;21.33&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;19.67&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;32&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;25&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Area of each triangle is 1/4th the area of the preceding triangle.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;All the areas will form an infinite GP with the common ratio 1/4.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Sum of all terms of the GP is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/185.15.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;41&quot; height=&quot;41&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;where a is the first term.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Area of the top triangle is 16 sq.cm.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Area of all triangles is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/185.15.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;273&quot; height=&quot;63&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(762,8,'4','','&lt;p&gt;If 6 times the 6th term of an AP is equal to 4 times the 4th term, find the 10th term.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;0&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;15&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;If aT&lt;sub&gt;a&lt;/sub&gt; = bT&lt;sub&gt;b&lt;/sub&gt; =&amp;gt; T&lt;sub&gt;(a+b)&lt;/sub&gt; = 0.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(763,8,'4','','&lt;p&gt;A ball fell down from 12 meters and each time it bounces half the distance back. What will be the total distance travelled in meters?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;12&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;36&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;48&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;30&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Each time it bounces, it will rise half the height. So, the terms will form an infinite GP with common ratio 2 and each term except the first term will repeat 2 times; one for coming down and the other for going up.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total distance travelled is S = 12 + 6 + 6 + 3 + 3+ â‹¯.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The sum of infinite terms of GP is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/185.17.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;45&quot; height=&quot;45&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/185.17.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;255&quot; height=&quot;64&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;meters.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(764,8,'4','','&lt;p&gt;The sum of an arithmetic progression consisting of 8 terms is 64. The ratio of the sum of even terms to the sum of odd terms is 9: 7. Find the common difference of the progression.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;Sum of all odd terms will be &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/185.18.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;114&quot; height=&quot;44&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Sum of all even terms will be 64 - 28 = 36.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The difference between each even term and its corresponding odd term is the common difference.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, for 4 terms difference will be 4d = 8 =&amp;gt; d = 2.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(765,8,'4','','&lt;p&gt;The sum of an arithmetic progression consisting of 16 terms is 104. The ratio of the sum of even terms to the sum of odd terms is 7: 6. Find the common difference of the progression.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;3&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Sum of all odd terms will be &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/185.19.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;122&quot; height=&quot;42&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Sum of all even terms will be 104 - 48 = 56.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The difference between each even term and its corresponding odd term is the common difference.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, for 8 terms, difference will be 8d = 8 =&amp;gt; d = 1.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(766,8,'4','','&lt;p&gt;If the sum of the first 16 terms of an arithmetic progression equals that of the first 21 terms, then what is the sum of the first 37 terms?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;0&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;37&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;16&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;21&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;If S&lt;sub&gt;m&lt;/sub&gt; = S&lt;sub&gt;n&lt;/sub&gt; =&amp;gt; S&lt;sub&gt;(m+n)&lt;/sub&gt; = 0.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(767,8,'4','','&lt;p&gt;The first term of an arithmetic progression is unity and the common difference is 3. Which of the following will be a term of this AP?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;30&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;31&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;32&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;35&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;The terms of this AP will be of the form 3n + 1.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Only 31 can be written in this form.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(768,8,'4','','&lt;p&gt;The first term of an arithmetic progression is 6 and the common difference is 5. Which of the following will be a term of this AP?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5004&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6006&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5005&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4004&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;The terms of this AP will be of the form 5n + 1.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Only 6006 can be written in this form.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(769,8,'4','','&lt;p&gt;In an infinite geometric progression, each term is equal to 3 times the sum of the terms that follow. If the first term of the series is 6, find the sum of the series?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;8&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;12&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;16&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;The sum of infinite terms of the GP is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/185.23.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;40&quot; height=&quot;42&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, according to the question, if a is the next term, then the previous term is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/185.23.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;25&quot; height=&quot;41&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;and &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/185.23.3.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;236&quot; height=&quot;43&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the sum of the entire series where a = 6 is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/185.23.4.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;162&quot; height=&quot;51&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(770,8,'4','','&lt;p&gt;In an infinite geometric progression, each term is equal to 4 times the sum of the terms that follow. If the first term of the series is 4, find the sum of the series?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;12&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;The sum of infinite terms of the GP is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/185.24.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;40&quot; height=&quot;39&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, according to the question, if a is the next term, then the previous term is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/185.24.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;19&quot; height=&quot;40&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;and &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/185.24.3.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;234&quot; height=&quot;42&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the sum of the entire series where a = 4 is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/185.24.4.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;159&quot; height=&quot;55&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(771,8,'4','','&lt;p&gt;What will be the maximum sum of 60, 58, 56, &amp;hellip;?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;930&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;380&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;400&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;440&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;The maximum value will occur when all the positive terms are exhausted because in this case, the common difference is negative and so, after some terms, the terms will start getting negative.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the maximum sum is 60 + 58 + 56 + â‹¯ + 2 = 2 x [1 + 2 + 3 + â‹¯ + 30] = 2 &amp;times; 30 &amp;times; (31/2) = 930.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(772,8,'4','','&lt;p&gt;What will be the maximum sum of 52, 49, 46, &amp;hellip;?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;477&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;450&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;459&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;440&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;The maximum value will occur when all the positive terms are exhausted because in this case, the common difference is negative and so, after some terms, the terms will start getting negative.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the maximum sum is 52 + 49 + 46 + â‹¯ + 4 + 1 = 3 x [1 + 2 + 3 + â‹¯ + 17] + [18 &amp;times; 1] = 3 &amp;times; 17 &amp;times; (18/2) + 18 = 477.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(773,8,'4','','&lt;p&gt;If the 7th term of an AP is 1/9 and 9th term is 1/7, then find the 6th term&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1/15&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2/21&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;7/36&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5/36&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;T&lt;sub&gt;7&lt;/sub&gt; = 1/9 = 7/63 and T&lt;sub&gt;9&lt;/sub&gt; = 1/7 = 9/63.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, T&lt;sub&gt;n&lt;/sub&gt; = n/63.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, T&lt;sub&gt;6&lt;/sub&gt; = 6/63 = 2/21.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(774,8,'4','','&lt;p&gt;If the 8th term of an AP is 1/6 and 6th term is 1/8, then find the 24th term&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1/3&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1/2&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;14/6&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;14/8&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;T&lt;sub&gt;8&lt;/sub&gt; = 1/6 = 8/48 and T&lt;sub&gt;6&lt;/sub&gt; = 1/8 = 6/48.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, T&lt;sub&gt;n&lt;/sub&gt; = n/48.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, T&lt;sub&gt;24&lt;/sub&gt; = 24/48 = 1/2.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(775,8,'4','','&lt;p&gt;Determine the first term of the geometric progression, the sum of whose first term and third term is 30 and the sum of the second term and fourth term is 90&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;3&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;12&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Sum of first and third terms is a + ar&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; = 30.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Sum of second and fourth terms is ar + ar&lt;sup&gt;3&lt;/sup&gt; = 90 =&amp;gt; 30r = 90 =&amp;gt; r = 3.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, a (1 + r&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; ) = a (1 + 9) = 10a = 30 =&amp;gt; a = 3.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(776,8,'4','','&lt;p&gt;Find the nth term of an AP whose sum of first n terms is S&lt;sub&gt;n&lt;/sub&gt; = 7n&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; + 3n.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5n + 3&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5n - 3&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;14n - 4&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10n - 5&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;T&lt;sub&gt;n&lt;/sub&gt; = S&lt;sub&gt;n&lt;/sub&gt; - S&lt;sub&gt;(n-1)&lt;/sub&gt; = 7n&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; + 3n - [7(n-1)&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; - 3(n-1)] = 14n - 4.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If S&lt;sub&gt;n&lt;/sub&gt; = an&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; + b =&amp;gt; T&lt;sub&gt;n&lt;/sub&gt; = 2an + (b-a).&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(777,8,'4','','&lt;p&gt;Find the nth term of an AP whose sum of first n terms is Sn = 10n&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; + 6n.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5n + 3&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5n - 3&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;20n - 4&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10n - 5&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;T&lt;sub&gt;n&lt;/sub&gt; = S&lt;sub&gt;n&lt;/sub&gt; - S&lt;sub&gt;(n-1)&lt;/sub&gt; = 10n&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; + 6n - [10(n-1)&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; - 6(n-1)] = 20n - 4.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If S&lt;sub&gt;n&lt;/sub&gt; = an&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; + b =&amp;gt; T&lt;sub&gt;n&lt;/sub&gt; = 2an + (b-a).&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(778,8,'4','','&lt;p&gt;There are two jars of equal capacity. In the first jar, there is one amoeba; in the second, there are two. An amoeba reproduces itself in 3 min. If it takes the two amoebas in the second jar 3 hours to fill the jar to capacity, the first jar will be filled to half its capacity in&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;3 hours 3 minutes&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;3 hours&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6 hours&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2 hours 57 minutes&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;It takes 3 minutes for the single amoeba to become two. Then it will be in the same position as the second jar. So, from there, it will take 3 hours to be completely filled. It will be half filled just 3 minutes back, because only then can each amoeba double itself. So, time taken is 3 hours.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(779,8,'4','','&lt;p&gt;A number which contains 1000 digits written as follows: 1234 &amp;hellip;. 101112 &amp;hellip;&amp;hellip;. Find the remainder when the above number is divided by 9.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;7&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;3&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;The first 9 digits are single digit numbers.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Next, there are 90 two digit numbers and they take 90 &amp;times; 2 = 180 places. So, there are 811 places remaining.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, number of 3 digit numbers that can be written is 811/3 = 270 and the first digit of the next number.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The 270th 3 digit number is 100 + 269 = 369. The 1000th digit is 3.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the sum of all the digits of the number is [369 &amp;times; (370/2)] + 3 = 68268.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, when we divide the number by 9, the remainder is (6 + 8 + 2 + 6 + 8)/9 = 30/9 = 3 3/9.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(780,8,'4','','&lt;p&gt;The average marks of 17 students in a class is A. The marks of students when arranged in ascending or descending order was found to be in A.P. The class teacher found that the students who were ranked 3, 7, 9, 11, 14 had copied in the exam and hence got all of them rusticated. The average of the remainder in the class was B. Then&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;A = B&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;A &amp;gt; B&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;A &amp;lt; B&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Cannot be determined&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;If the terms that are equidistant from the two ends of an AP are removed, then it will have no effect on the mean of the AP. The corresponding term for the third term is T&lt;sub&gt;15&lt;/sub&gt; and not T&lt;sub&gt;14&lt;/sub&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the mean in this case will definitely change. Since, T&lt;sub&gt;15&lt;/sub&gt; &amp;gt; T&lt;sub&gt;14&lt;/sub&gt;, we can say that the average will increase because a smaller term is taken out. So, A&amp;lt;B.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(781,8,'4','','&lt;p&gt;A and B set out to meet each other from two places 260 km apart. A travels 15 km the first day, 14 km the second day, 13 km the third day and so on. B travels 11 km the first day, 12 km the second day, 13 km the third day and so on. After how many days will they meet?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;7&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;A and B combined walk 26 kilometres each day.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, they take 260/26 = 10 days to meet.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(782,8,'4','','&lt;p&gt;If for an AP having 25 terms, a&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; + a&lt;sub&gt;11&lt;/sub&gt; + a&lt;sub&gt;15&lt;/sub&gt; + a&lt;sub&gt;25&lt;/sub&gt; = 60, then the value of a&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; + a&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; + â‹¯ + a&lt;sub&gt;25&lt;/sub&gt; is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;60&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;375&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;250&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;300&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;The sum of two terms of an AP which are equidistant from the two ends is equal to twice the AM of the entire AP.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The AM of this AP will be &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/185.36.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;82&quot; height=&quot;37&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/185.36.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;438&quot; height=&quot;27&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/185.36.3.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;298&quot; height=&quot;52&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(783,8,'4','','&lt;p&gt;If for an AP having 17 terms, a&lt;sub&gt;9&lt;/sub&gt; = 10, then the value of a&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; + a&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; + â‹¯ + a&lt;sub&gt;17&lt;/sub&gt; is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;60&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;375&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;250&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;300&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;The AM of this AP will be &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/185.37.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;86&quot; height=&quot;39&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the sum of all the terms is 17 &amp;times; a&lt;sub&gt;9&lt;/sub&gt; = 170.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(784,8,'4','','&lt;p&gt;The sum of the first n terms of the arithmetic progression is equal to half the sum of the next n terms of the same progression. Find the ratio of the sum of the first 3n terms of the progression to the sum of its first 2n terms&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;3: 2&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4: 3&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2: 1&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6: 5&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Each term in the second series exceeds the corresponding term in the first series by nd.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the difference between the two series is S&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; - S&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; = n&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; d.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;But S&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; = (S&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;/2) =&amp;gt; S&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; = 2S&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; =&amp;gt; S&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; = n&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; d.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Each term in the third n term series exceeds the corresponding term in the first series by 2nd.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, S&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt; - S&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; = 2n&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; d =&amp;gt; S&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt; = 3S&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The required ratio is (S&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; + S&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; + S&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt;)/(S&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; + S&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; ) = (1 + 2 + 3)/(2 + 1) = 6:3 = 2:1.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(785,8,'4','','&lt;p&gt;The sum of the first 10 terms of the arithmetic progression is 200 less than the sum of the next 10 terms of the same progression. Find the common difference.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;3&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2.5&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Each term in the second series exceeds the corresponding term in the first series by 10d.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the difference between the two series is S&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; - S&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; = 10 &amp;times; 10d = 100d.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, 100d = 200 =&amp;gt; d = 2.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(786,8,'4','','&lt;p&gt;A student takes a test consisting of 100 questions with differential marking and is told that each question after the first is worth 1 mark more than the preceding question. If the sixth question of the test is worth 10 marks, what is the maximum score that the student can obtain by attempting 60 questions, if he could not answer the last 10 questions?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4320&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;8100&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4590&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;The marks for each question is in AP with the common difference 1. Let the first term be a.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/185.40.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;247&quot; height=&quot;29&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, in this case, &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/185.40.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;166&quot; height=&quot;40&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The student answers 60 questions. He will get maximum marks when the student answers the questions from 31 to 90.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, marks obtained is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/185.40.3.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;391&quot; height=&quot;45&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(787,8,'4','','&lt;p&gt;If the 5th term of an AP is 11 and the 11th term is 5, then what is the sum of 10th, 11th and 14th terms of that AP?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;12&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;13&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;14&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;If the mth term of an AP is n and the nth term of an AP is m, then its pth term is given by m + n - p.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, T&lt;sub&gt;n&lt;/sub&gt; = 5 + 11 - n = 16 - n.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The required sum is T&lt;sub&gt;10&lt;/sub&gt; + T&lt;sub&gt;11&lt;/sub&gt; + T&lt;sub&gt;14&lt;/sub&gt; = 48 - (10 + 11 + 14) = 48 - 35 = 13.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(788,8,'4','','&lt;p&gt;If the 5th term of an AP is 9 and the 9th term is 5, then what is the difference between 8th term and the 17th term of that AP?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;9&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;-9&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;-8&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;8&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;If the mth term of an AP is n and the nth term of an AP is m, then its pth term is given by m + n - p. And the common difference of the AP is -1.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, T&lt;sub&gt;8&lt;/sub&gt; - T&lt;sub&gt;17&lt;/sub&gt; = -9d = 9.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(789,8,'4','','&lt;p&gt;If the tenth term of an AP is 25 and sum of its first four terms is 40, find the sum of first 15 terms.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;345&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;330&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;315&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;300&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Sum of the first four terms is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/185.43.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;365&quot; height=&quot;46&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The 10th term is T&lt;sub&gt;10&lt;/sub&gt; = a + 9d = 25.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the value of a is 7 and the value of d is 2.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, sum of first 15 terms is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/185.43.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;355&quot; height=&quot;49&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(790,8,'4','','&lt;p&gt;If the tenth term of an AP is 19 and sum of its first four terms is 16, find the sum of first 8 terms.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;49&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;64&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;81&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;100&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Sum of the first four terms is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/185.44.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;357&quot; height=&quot;39&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The 10th term is T&lt;sub&gt;10&lt;/sub&gt; = a + 9d = 19.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the value of a is 1 and the value of d is 2.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, sum of first 8 terms is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/185.44.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;224&quot; height=&quot;41&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(791,8,'4','','&lt;p&gt;If a, b, c are the pth, qth and rth terms of an GP, then the value of p&lt;sup&gt;(b-c)&lt;/sup&gt; + q&lt;sup&gt;(c-a)&lt;/sup&gt; + r&lt;sup&gt;(a-b)&lt;/sup&gt; is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;0&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;ap + bq + cr&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Not a unique value&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;For any choice of a, b, c, p, q, r, the term will always be equal to one.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(792,8,'4','','&lt;p&gt;If the AM of two numbers is 4 and the GM is 3, then the HM is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2.25&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;AM, GM and HM form a GP. So, HM = (GM)&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;/(AM) = 9/4 = 2.25.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(793,8,'4','','&lt;p&gt;If |a|&amp;lt;1, |b|&amp;lt;1, then the value of the series 1 + (a+b).a + (a&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; + b&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; ).a&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; + â‹¯ is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/185.47.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;117&quot; height=&quot;54&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/185.47.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;112&quot; height=&quot;49&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/185.47.3.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;109&quot; height=&quot;46&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/185.47.4.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;112&quot; height=&quot;48&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;We can say that &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/185.47.5.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;262&quot; height=&quot;37&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Similarly, &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/185.47.6.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;170&quot; height=&quot;39&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/185.47.7.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;607&quot; height=&quot;53&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(794,8,'4','','&lt;p&gt;The fourth term of a GP is 2. The product of the first seven terms of the GP is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;64&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;128&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;14&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;200&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;The geometric mean of a GP containing odd number of terms is the middle term.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the product of all the seven terms is 2&lt;sup&gt;7&lt;/sup&gt; = 128.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;GM of a group on n terms is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/185.48.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;67&quot; height=&quot;81&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;where a&lt;sub&gt;i&lt;/sub&gt; is the ith term.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(795,8,'4','','&lt;p&gt;If the mth term of an HM is n and the nth term of the HM is m, then the value of (mn)th term is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;0&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;mn&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;m + n&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;The kth term of the corresponding AP is k/mn and so the (mn)th term will be 1.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(796,9,'1','','&lt;p&gt;How many 5-digit numbers greater than 60,000 are possible involving the digits 6, 3, 0, 4 and 6 and using only the digits given?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;12&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;48&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;36&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;24&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;In order to be greater than 60,000, the first digit should be 6 only.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The remaining 4 digits should be filled with the remaining 4 numbers which are 3, 0, 4, 6 (there are two 6&#039;s and one 6 is already used, so only one 6 is available).&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;This can be done in 4! = 24 ways.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(797,9,'1','','&lt;p&gt;In how many ways can we arrange all the letters of the word TRIANGLE?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;80640&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;40320&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;20160&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5040&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;There are 8 different letters. There is no repetition.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;They can be arranged among themselves in 8! = 40320 ways.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(798,9,'1','','&lt;p&gt;In how many ways can the letters of the word TRIANGLE be arranged such that vowels occupy odd places?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;40320&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;840&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5040&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2880&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;There are 4 odd places and 3 vowels.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So 3 vowels are arranged in these 4 places in &lt;sup&gt;4&lt;/sup&gt;P&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt; ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Now, there will be 5 places blank and they can be filled with 5 consonants in 5! ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of ways to arrange is 4! x 5! = 24 x 120 = 2880 ways.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(799,9,'1','','&lt;p&gt;In how many ways can the letters of the word TRIANGLE be arranged such that all vowels are always together?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4320&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;720&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;8040&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;120&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;The vowels will always be together. So, let us treat them as a single group. Now, there are 6 letters to be arranged instead of 8 because the vowels are one group. They can be arranged in 6! = 720 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Now, within the group of vowels, the 3 letters can be arranged within themselves because the word TRNGIAEL is different from TRNGIEAL. This can be done in 3! = 6 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the total number of arrangements is 720 x 6 = 4320.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(800,9,'1','','&lt;p&gt;In how many ways can the letters of the word TRIANGLE be arranged such that A will immediately follow E and E will immediately follow I?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4320&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;720&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;8040&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;120&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;The vowels will always be together. So, let us treat them as a single group. Now, there are 6 letters to be arranged instead of 8 because the vowels are one group. They can be arranged in 6! = 720 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Now, within the group of vowels, the 3 letters cannot be arranged within themselves because there is a fixed order among the vowels that is to be maintained.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the total number of arrangements is 720.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(801,9,'1','','&lt;p&gt;In how many ways can the letters of the word TRIANGLE be arranged such that no two vowels are together?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;7200&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;14400&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;3600&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;28800&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;In this case, no two vowels should be together. The best way to proceed is to arrange the consonants first. 5 consonants can be arranged themselves in 5! = 120 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;There will be 6 gaps in between these consonants that we can use to place the vowels in. This will ensure that no two vowels will be together. 3 vowels can be arranged in 3 paces in &lt;sup&gt;6&lt;/sup&gt;P&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt; = 120 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of arrangements is 120 &amp;times; 120 = 14400 ways.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(802,9,'1','','&lt;p&gt;In how many ways can the letters of the word TRIANGLE be arranged such that the word always start with T and end with E?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;360&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;720&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2880&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1440&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;The word should always start with T and end with E.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, there are only 6 blank spaces to be filled.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;We can fill these 6 spaces in 6! = 720 ways.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(803,9,'1','','&lt;p&gt;In how many ways can a 5 letter word be formed from the letters of the word TRIANGLE if T is never included in the word?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1260&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2520&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5040&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;720&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Since T is never included, we shall find the required 5 letters from the remaining 7 letters in &lt;sup&gt;7&lt;/sup&gt;P&lt;sub&gt;5&lt;/sub&gt; = 2520 ways.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(804,9,'1','','&lt;p&gt;In how many ways can a 5 letter word be formed from the letters of the word TRIANGLE if T is always included in the word?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;720&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4200&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5040&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2520&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Since T is always included, first arrange T in one place in 5 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Now for the remaining 4 places, there are 7 letters which can be used.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;They can be arranged in &lt;sup&gt;7&lt;/sup&gt;P&lt;sub&gt;4&lt;/sub&gt; = 840 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of ways is 5 &amp;times; 840 = 4200&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(805,9,'1','','&lt;p&gt;In how many ways can a 5 letter word be formed from the letters of the word TRIANGLE if T is never included and E is always included in the word?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;900&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1800&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2520&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5040&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Since E is always included, first arrange E in one place in 5 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Since T is never included, we shall find the required 4 letters from the remaining 6 letters in &lt;sup&gt;6&lt;/sup&gt;P&lt;sub&gt;4&lt;/sub&gt; = 360 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total number of ways to arrange them is 5 &amp;times; 360 = 1800 ways.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(806,9,'1','','&lt;p&gt;In how many ways can letters of the word SUCCESS be arranged?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;3600&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;900&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;720&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;43200&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;There are 8 letters where S is repeated 3 times and C is repeated 2 times.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of ways of arranging them is&amp;nbsp;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/192.11.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;146&quot; height=&quot;43&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(807,9,'1','','&lt;p&gt;In how many ways can 9 letters be posted in 4 letter boxes?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4&lt;sup&gt;9&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;9&lt;sup&gt;4&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;&lt;sup&gt;9&lt;/sup&gt;P&lt;sub&gt;4&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;&lt;sup&gt;9&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;4&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;For each of the letter, it can be posted in 4 letter boxes.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;More than one letter can be posted in the same letter box.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, for 9 letters, total number of choices is 4 &amp;times; 4 &amp;times; &amp;hellip; &amp;times;&amp;nbsp;4 (9 times ) = 4&lt;sup&gt;9&lt;/sup&gt;.&lt;sup&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(808,9,'1','','&lt;p&gt;In an office, 4 posts have fallen vacant. In how many ways can a selection out of 31 candidates be made if one candidate is always excluded and another candidate is always included?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;&lt;sup&gt;30&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;&lt;sup&gt;30&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;4&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;&lt;sup&gt;29&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;4&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;&lt;sup&gt;29&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;One candidate is always included and the other is always excluded.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, there are 3 vacancies and 29 candidates that can be considered.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the total number of ways of selecting them is &lt;sup&gt;29&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(809,9,'1','','&lt;p&gt;A question paper is divided into two groups such that the first group contains 4 questions and the second group contains 5 questions. One question must be selected from each group. In how many ways can this be done?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;20&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;9&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;80&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;15&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;One question can be selected from the first group in &lt;sup&gt;4&lt;/sup&gt;P&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; = 4 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;One question can be selected from the second group in &lt;sup&gt;5&lt;/sup&gt;P&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; = 5 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of ways to solve the paper is 4 &amp;times; 5 = 20 ways.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(810,9,'1','','&lt;p&gt;Eight chairs are numbered 1 to 8. Two women and three men wish to occupy one chair each. First the women choose the chairs marked from 1 to 4 and later the men choose the chairs from amongst the remaining. The number if possible arrangements is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;&lt;sup&gt;6&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt; x &lt;sup&gt;4&lt;/sup&gt;P&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;&lt;sup&gt;6&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt; x &lt;sup&gt;4&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;&lt;sup&gt;6&lt;/sup&gt;P&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt; x &lt;sup&gt;4&lt;/sup&gt;P&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;&lt;sup&gt;6&lt;/sup&gt;P&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt; x &lt;sup&gt;4&lt;/sup&gt;P&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;For the women, only the first four chairs are available. So, they can be arranged in &lt;sup&gt;4&lt;/sup&gt;P&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;After the ladies are seated, there are 6 vacant chairs in all and 3 men are arranged in these 6 chairs in &lt;sup&gt;6&lt;/sup&gt;P&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt; ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of ways required is &lt;sup&gt;4&lt;/sup&gt;P&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; &amp;times; &lt;sup&gt;6&lt;/sup&gt;P&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(811,9,'1','','&lt;p&gt;A student has to answer 10 out of 13 questions in an examination paper such that he must choose at least 4 from the first 5 questions. The number of choices available to the student is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;96&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;82&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;90&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;286&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Case 1: choosing 4 from first 5.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;In this case, 6 are to be chosen from the remaining 8 questions.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of ways is &lt;sup&gt;5&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;4&lt;/sub&gt; + &lt;sup&gt;8&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;6&lt;/sub&gt; = 5 + 28 = 33&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Case 2: choosing 5 from first 5.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;In this case, 5 are to be chosen from the remaining 8 questions.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of ways is &lt;sup&gt;5&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;5&lt;/sub&gt; + &lt;sup&gt;8&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;5&lt;/sub&gt; = 1 + 53 = 57.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of choices is 33 + 57 = 90 ways.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(812,9,'1','','&lt;p&gt;The number of ways in which a team of 11 players can be selected from a pool of 22 players while always including 2 players and always excluding 4 players is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;&lt;sup&gt;16&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;11&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;&lt;sup&gt;16&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;9&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;&lt;sup&gt;16&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;5&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;&lt;sup&gt;20&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;9&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Since two players are always included, number of vacant positions is 9.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Out of the remaining 20 players, four players are not at all in consideration. So, total number of players available for selection are 16.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total number of ways is &lt;sup&gt;16&lt;/sup&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;9&lt;/sub&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(813,9,'1','','&lt;p&gt;The number of ways of arranging 5 players to throw a cricket ball so that the youngest may not throw first is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;119&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;96&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;24&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;23&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;For the first throw, there are 4 choices.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;For the remaining 4 throws, we can arrange them in 4! ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of ways is 4 &amp;times; 4! = 96.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(814,9,'1','','&lt;p&gt;The letters of the word PROMISE are arranged such that no two vowels come together. The total number of arrangements is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;60&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1440&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;120&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;140&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;First arrange 4 consonants in 4! ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;This will leave 5 blank spaces in which to pot the 3 vowels. This can be done in &lt;sup&gt;5&lt;/sup&gt;P&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt; = 60 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of ways is 24 &amp;times; 60 = 1440.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(815,9,'1','','&lt;p&gt;If words are formed by using only 4 letters of the word PHYSICS, in how many of them will the letter Y occur?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;240&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;288&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;480&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;780&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Y is always present. So, it can be arranged in 4 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Now, for the remaining 3 places, 3 letters can be selected from 6 available letters in &lt;sup&gt;6&lt;/sup&gt;P&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt; = 120 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of ways is 4 &amp;times; 120 = 480 ways.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(816,9,'2','','&lt;p&gt;In a chess competition involving some boys and girls of a school, every student had to play exactly one game with every other student. It was found that in 45 games both the players were girls, and in 190 games both were boys. The number of games in which one player was a boy and the other was a girl is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;200&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;216&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;235&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;256&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Let there be m boys and n girls in the competition.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The number of games in which both players are girls is nC2 = 45(given).&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, nC2 = 10C2 =&amp;gt; n = 10.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The number of games in which both players are girls is mC2 = 190 (given).&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, mC2 = 20C2 =&amp;gt; m = 20.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, if one of the players is a boy and the other is a girl, then the number of games possible is mn = 20 &amp;times; 10 = 200.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(817,9,'2','','&lt;p&gt;In how many ways can the letters of the word TRIANGLE be arranged such that A will follow E but need not be immediately?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;40320&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5040&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;20160&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10080&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;In this case, first arrange the other 6 letters excluding A and E in the available 8 places in 8P6 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;There will be 3 blank places left. We have a specific order for the vowels. So, the first blank is filled with I and the second with E. This can be done only in 1 way.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of ways to arrange is 8P6 = 20160.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(818,9,'2','','&lt;p&gt;In how many ways can the letters of the word EQUATION be arranged such that two and only two of the consonants are together?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;21600&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10800&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5040&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2520&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;There are 3 consonants but only two must be together.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, first 2 consonants from the entire pool and then group them together. The consonants can be arranged among themselves. This can be done in 3C2 &amp;times; 2! ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Now, we must make sure that the remaining consonant is never together with this group.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, arrange 5 vowels in 5! ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;This will give 6 gaps in between them in which you can place the two consonant elements in 6P2 = 30 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of arrangements is 6 &amp;times; 120 &amp;times; 30 = 21600 ways.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(819,9,'2','','&lt;p&gt;n how many ways can 5 persons, from a group of 8 persons, be arranged for a photograph if Mrs. A refuses to be involved if Mr. B is included in the photograph?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5040&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4320&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2160&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2520&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Here there are 2 cases to be considered.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Case 1: if Mr. B is included in the photograph&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;In this case first Mr. B can chose his place in 5 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Now, Mrs. A will not be included in the photograph.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the remaining 4 places will be filled by the remaining 6 persons in 6P4 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of ways in this case is 5 &amp;times; 6P4 = 1800.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Case 2: if Mr. B is not included in the photograph&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;In this case there is no problem at all.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, 5 places will be filled by the remaining 7 persons in 7P5 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of ways in this case is 7P5 = 2520.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of ways is 1800 + 2520 = 4320 ways.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(820,9,'2','','&lt;p&gt;In how many ways can 5 persons, from a group of 8 persons, be arranged for a photograph if Mrs. A will be included in the photograph if and only if Mr. A is included in the photograph?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2460&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4920&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1230&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5040&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Here there are 2 cases to be considered.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Case 1: if Mr. A is included in the photograph&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;In this case first Mr. A can chose his place in 5 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Now, Mrs. A may or may not be included in the photograph.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the remaining 4 places will be filled by the remaining 7 persons in 7P4 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of ways in this case is 5 &amp;times; 7P4 = 4200.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Case 2: if Mr. A is not included in the photograph&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;In this case Mrs. A will not be considered at all.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, 5 places will be filled by the remaining 6 persons in 6P5 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of ways in this case is 6P5 = 720.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of ways is 4200 + 720 = 4920 ways.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(821,9,'2','','&lt;p&gt;In how many ways can letters of the word SUCCESS be arranged such that the two C&amp;rsquo;s are never together?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;600&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;150&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;300&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;225&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Since the two C&amp;rsquo;s are never together, leave them out and arrange the other 5 characters. S has repeated 3 times. This can be done in &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/193.6.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;51&quot; height=&quot;37&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Now, there will be 6 gaps in between them and since the two C&amp;rsquo;s are identical, it is enough if we just select 2 places to fill the 2 C&amp;rsquo;s. This can be done in 6C2 = 15 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the total number of ways in which this can be done is 20 &amp;times; 15 = 300 times.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(822,9,'2','','&lt;p&gt;In how many ways can 7 identical black balls and 6 identical blue balls be arranged linearly such that no two blue balls are together?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;8C6&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;8P6&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;8C6 x 7!&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;8C6 x 7!&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;For a group of identical items, there will be no arrangement.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;First place 7 black balls in 7C7 = 1 way.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Now there will be 8 gaps in between the black balls and 6 blue balls can be arranged in these 8 gaps in 8C6 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of ways is 8C6.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(823,9,'2','','&lt;p&gt;The total number of natural numbers less than 1000 and divisible by 5 formed with ( 0, 1, 2, &amp;hellip;. ,9) such that each digit does not occur more than once in each number is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;150&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;152&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;154&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;None&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Total number of 1 digit numbers is 1.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;For 2 digit numbers:&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;(a) if units digit is 0, since there is no repetition, the tens digit has 9 choices available.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;(b) if units digit is 5, since there is no repetition, the tens digit has 8 choices available since 0 cannot be in the tens place for 2 digit numbers.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total number of 2 digit numbers is 9 + 8 = 17.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;For 3 digit numbers:&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;(a) if units digit is 0, since there is no repetition, the tens digit and hundreds digit can be filled by the remaining 9 digits in 9P2 = 72 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;(b) if units digit is 5, since there is no repetition, the hundreds digit has 8 choices available since 0 cannot be in the hundreds place for 3 digit numbers. Now, tens place also has 8 choices available to it since 2 digits are already used. So total number of choices is 8 x 8=64&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total number of 2 digit numbers is 72 + 64 = 136 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total number of required numbers is 1 + 17 + 136 = 154.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(824,9,'2','','&lt;p&gt;In terms of all words containing the letters of the word ZENITH, what is the rank or order of the word ZENITH in the dictionary?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;600&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;614&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;613&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;617&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Write the word in alphabetical order. Here it is EIHNTZ&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Now strike the first letter of the word ZENITH which is z. now the number of words in this case is n x m! where n is the number of letters which are not stricken and before the letter to be stricken out. m denotes the total number of letters not stricken off. After the process is repeated with all the letters, add 1 finally to get the rank.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;For Z, n = 5 and m = 5, so number of words is 5 x 5!&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;For E, n = 0 and m = 4, so number of words is 0 x 4!&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;For N, n = 2 and m = 3, so number of words is 2 x 3!&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;For I, n = 0 and m = 2, so number of words is 0 x 2!&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;For T, n = 1 and m = 1, so number of words is 1 x 1!&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;For H, n = 0 and m = 0, so number of words is 0 x 0!&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, rank of ZENITH is 5 x 5! + 2 x 3! + 1 x 1! + 1 = 600 + 12 + 2 = 614.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(825,9,'2','','&lt;p&gt;In how many ways can 10 persons be seated across a circular table such that the same person never has the same two neighbours?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10!&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10!/2&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;9!&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;9!/2&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;10 persons can be arranged in a circular table in (10 - 1)! = 9! ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;In these combinations, in two of them, the neighbours will be the same. In one of these, the arrangement is in clockwise orientation and in the other, the arrangement is in anti-clockwise orientation. So, the total number of arrangements in which the same person never has the same two neighbours is (9!/2) ways.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(826,9,'2','','&lt;p&gt;There are 4 letters and 4 addressed envelopes corresponding to them. The number of ways in which the letters can be placed in the envelopes so that exactly one letter is in the wrong envelope is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;9&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;18&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;0&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;If I put letter number 1 in envelope 2, then it means that letter number 2 is not put in envelope 2. So, it is impossible to place the letters so that exactly one letter is in the correct envelope.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(827,9,'2','','&lt;p&gt;There are 4 letters and 4 addressed envelopes corresponding to them. The number of ways in which the letters can be placed in the envelopes so that no letter is in the correct envelope is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;9&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;18&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;0&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Every letter must go to the wrong envelope.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Number of ways in which this can be done if there are n letters is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/193.12.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;201&quot; height=&quot;39&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Here n = 4.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, number of ways is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/193.12.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;271&quot; height=&quot;41&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(828,9,'2','','&lt;p&gt;7 speakers are to address a meeting. Of them B wants to speak before A and C wants to speak before B, though not immediately. In how many ways can the program be drafted?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;840&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;35&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;14&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5040&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;In this case, first arrange the speakers other than A, B and C in the available 7 places in 7P4 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;There will be 3 blank places left. We should not disturb the order of appearance of A, B and C. So, the first blank is filled with C, the second with B and third with A. This can be done only in 1 way.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of ways to arrange is 7P4 = 840.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(829,9,'2','','&lt;p&gt;The number of ways in which the letters of the word MULTIPLE be arranged without changing the order of the vowels is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;3360&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;20160&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6720&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;13440&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;In this case, first arrange the consonants in the available 8 places in 8P5 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;There will be 3 blank places left. We should not disturb the order of vowels. So, the first blank is filled with U, the second with I and third with E. This can be done only in 1 way.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of ways to arrange is 8P5 = 6720.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(830,9,'2','','&lt;p&gt;There are 2 cars, one of which holds a maximum of five persons and the other a maximum of four. In how many ways can a group of 8 persons go to an excursion in these cars?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;8400&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;126&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;124&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6400&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;There are 2 cases here.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Case 1: select 4 members for the bigger car. From, 8 persons, this can be done in 8C4 = 70 ways. The remaining 4 persons will travel in the smaller car.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Case 2: select 5 members for the bigger car. From, 8 persons, this can be done in 8C5 = 56 ways. The remaining 3 persons will travel in the smaller car.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total number of ways is 70 + 56 = 126 ways.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(831,9,'2','','&lt;p&gt;If a regular polygon has 9 diagonals, what is the number of its sides?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;7&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;8&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;9&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Let the number of sides for a regular polygon be n.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;We can combine these n points in pairs and get nC2 different straight lines. Out of these, n are sides.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, number if diagonals is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/193.16.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;134&quot; height=&quot;40&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Here &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/193.16.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;88&quot; height=&quot;35&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So n(n-3) = 18 =&amp;gt; n = 6.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(832,9,'2','','&lt;p&gt;The number of different ways in which any number of items among 7 pencils, 6 books and 5 pens can be given away is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;336&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;334&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;335&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;210&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;For the pencils, there are 8 ways to give them away. We can chose to give either 0 or 1 or 2 or 3 or 4 or 5 or6 or 7 pencils. Similarly we have 7 choices with respect to books and 6 choices with respect to pens.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of choices available is 8 &amp;times; 7 &amp;times; 6 = 336.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Out of these, in one of the choices, we give away 0 pencils, 0 books and 0 pens.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of ways to give away is 336 - 1 = 335 ways.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(833,9,'2','','&lt;p&gt;The number of products that can be formed with 10 prime numbers taking two or more at a time is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2&lt;sup&gt;10&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2&lt;sup&gt;10&lt;/sup&gt; - 1&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2&lt;sup&gt;10&lt;/sup&gt; - 11&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2&lt;sup&gt;10&lt;/sup&gt; - 10&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Number of products formed by taking two primes is 10C2.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Number of products formed by taking 3 primes is 10C3.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;We can take any number of primes from 2 to 10.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of ways is 10C2 + 10C3 + 10C4 + â‹¯ + 10C10 = 2&lt;sup&gt;10&lt;/sup&gt; - 10C0 - 10C1 = 2&lt;sup&gt;10&lt;/sup&gt;-11.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(834,9,'2','','&lt;p&gt;The number of distinct positive divisors of 2&lt;sup&gt;5&lt;/sup&gt; x 3&lt;sup&gt;6&lt;/sup&gt; x 7&lt;sup&gt;3&lt;/sup&gt; is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;90&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;168&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;166&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;167&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;We can see that a divisor of the number 2&lt;sup&gt;5&lt;/sup&gt; &amp;times; 3&lt;sup&gt;6&lt;/sup&gt; &amp;times; 7&lt;sup&gt;3&lt;/sup&gt; will be of the form 2&lt;sup&gt;a&lt;/sup&gt; &amp;times; 3&lt;sup&gt;b&lt;/sup&gt; &amp;times; 7&lt;sup&gt;c&lt;/sup&gt; where the possible values for a are (0,1,2,3,4,5), for b are (0,1,2,3,4,5,6) and for c are (0,1,2,3).&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, a divisor will be formed if we pick all the three values. Number of choices to pick a value for a is 6, for b is 7 and for c is 4.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;This can be done in 6 &amp;times; 7 &amp;times; 4 = 168 ways.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(835,9,'2','','&lt;p&gt;Ram is having 127 coins of one rupee. He puts it in different bags, so that he can hand over the cash of any denomination required between Rs. 1 to Rs. 127. What is the least no. of bags required?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;11&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;13&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;15&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;7&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;If 2&lt;sup&gt;(m-1)&lt;/sup&gt; &amp;le; n &amp;lt; 2&lt;sup&gt;m&lt;/sup&gt;, then the number of bags that are required is m.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Here n = 127 &amp;lt; 2&lt;sup&gt;7&lt;/sup&gt;, so the number of bags required is 7.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(836,9,'3','','&lt;p&gt;In a dark room, there is a box containing 3 white balls, 4 black balls, 7 yellow balls, 6 blue balls, and 5 red balls. What is the least number of balls to be chosen so as to ensure a pair of same colour balls has been drawn?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;22&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;14&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;12&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;If a particular colour is not specified, Then answer is (total number of different colours + 1).&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Here, it will be 5 + 1 = 6.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The first ball drawn may be white, second may be black, 3rd may be yellow and 4th may be red and the 5th one may be red. However, the 6th ball must have at least one of these colours and so a pair will be formed.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(837,9,'3','','&lt;p&gt;In a dark room, there is a box containing 3 white balls, 4 black balls, 7 yellow balls, 6 blue balls, and 5 red balls. What is the least number of balls to be chosen so as to ensure a pair of RED balls has been drawn?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;22&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;14&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;12&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;If a particular colour is specified, Answer will be (sum of balls of all other colours + 2).&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If we want red balls, then in the worst case, all the first 3 balls may be white, the next 4 balls may be black, the next 7 may be yellow and the next 6 may be blue. Now that all other colour balls are exhausted, the next 2 balls should really be a red pair.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, answer will be 3 + 4 + 7 + 6 + 2 = 22&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(838,9,'3','','&lt;p&gt;In how many ways can 6 boys and 6 girls be arranged for a photograph such that neither 2 boys nor 2 girls are adjacent?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6! x 6!&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5! x 6!&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2 x 6! x 6!&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6!&amp;nbsp;x (6!/2)&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;There cannot be any two boys or two girls who are close to each other. So, the best way to arrange them is to alternate them.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The series will look like this BGBGBGBGBGBG or GBGBGBGBGBGB.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;In both these cases, 6 places are fixed for boys and 6 places are fixed for girls.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of ways o0f arranging them is 2 &amp;times; 6! &amp;times; 6!.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(839,9,'3','','&lt;p&gt;A computer has 5 terminals and each terminal is capable of four distinct positions including the positions of rest. What is the total number of signals that can be made?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1024&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;624&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1023&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;625&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;For each of the terminals, it can be connected to 4 distinct positions.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Each of the terminals is independent of the other.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, for 5 terminals, total number of choices is 4 &amp;times; 4 &amp;times; 4 &amp;times; 4 &amp;times; 4 = 1024.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;In one of these choices, all the five terminals are connected to rest positions and so would not work.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So total number of signals is 1024 - 1 = 1023.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(840,9,'3','','&lt;p&gt;Out of 10 consonants and 4 vowels how many words can be formed each containing 6 consonants and 3 vowels?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10C6 x 4C3&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10C6 x 4C3 x 9!&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10C6 x 4C3 x 10!&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;None&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;6 consonants can be selected from 10 consonants in 10C6 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;3 vowels can be selected from 4 vowels in 4C3 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Now we need to arrange these 9 letters to form a word. This can be done in 9! ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the total number of words that can be formed is 10C6 &amp;times; 4C3 &amp;times; 9!.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(841,9,'3','','&lt;p&gt;A team of 12 men is to be formed out of n persons. It is found that A and B are three times as often together as C, D and E are. Then the value of n is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;32&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;23&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;9&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;None&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;A team of n persons can be formed from 12 candidates in nC12 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If A and B are in the group, then the remaining 10 places can be filled from remaining (n-2) candidates in (n-2)C10 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If C, D and E are in the group, then the remaining 9 places can be filled from remaining (n-3) candidates in (n-3)C9 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Given &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/194.6.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;371&quot; height=&quot;43&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(842,9,'3','','&lt;p&gt;In how many ways can you answer one or more questions out of 6 questions each having an alternative?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;728&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;729&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;128&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;127&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;If each question has two parts (a) and (b), then we have 3 choices with respect to each question.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;We can leave it or answer part (a) or answer part (b).&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;For six questions, the total number of choices is 3&lt;sup&gt;6&lt;/sup&gt; = 729.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Out of them, one choice is where we do leave all the questions.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the required number of choices is 729 - 1 = 728.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(843,9,'3','','&lt;p&gt;There are 12 points in a plane such that 6 of them are collinear and all the other points are non-collinear. Then the number of triangles that can be formed is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;220&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;200&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;189&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;256&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Total number of triangles that can be formed from 12 non collinear points is 12C3.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;For the first set of 6 collinear points, the total number of triangles is 0 instead of 6C3.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of triangles possible is 12C3 - 6C3 = 220 - 20 = 200.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(844,9,'3','','&lt;p&gt;There are 12 points in a plane such that 6 of them are collinear and all the other points are non-collinear. Then the number of straight lines that can be formed is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;52&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;66&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;67&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;44&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Total number of straight lines that can be formed from 12 non collinear points is 12C2.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;For the first set of 6 collinear points, the total number of straight lines is 1 instead of 6C2.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of straight lines possible is 12C2 - 6C2 + 1 = 66 - 15 + 1 = 52.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(845,9,'3','','&lt;p&gt;In a cross word puzzle 20 words are to be guessed of which 8 words have each an alternative solution. The number of possible solutions is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;(2 x 8)&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;20C16&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;20C8&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;None&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;For the 12 words, there will be only 1 correct solution for each one. So, they can be filled in 112 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;For the 8 words with alternatives, each position has 2 correct choices. So the total number of ways to fill these positions is 2&lt;sup&gt;8&lt;/sup&gt; ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total number of ways to solve the entire puzzle is 1&lt;sup&gt;12&lt;/sup&gt; &amp;times; 2&lt;sup&gt;8&lt;/sup&gt; = 256 = (2&amp;times;8)&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(846,9,'3','','&lt;p&gt;A person hosts a dinner to 10 persons. They have to be seated around a circular table which can accommodate 6 persons and another straight table which can accommodate 4 persons. The number of ways in which this can be done is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10P6 &amp;times; 4P4 &amp;times; 5! &amp;times; 3!&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10P6 &amp;times; 4P4 &amp;times; 5! &amp;times; 4!&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10C6 &amp;times; 4C4 &amp;times; 5! &amp;times; 3!&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10C4 &amp;times; 5! &amp;times; 4!&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;Of the 10 guests, select 4 of them and arrange them near the straight table. This can be done in 10C4 &amp;times; 5! &amp;times; 4! Ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Now the remaining 6 guests will be arranged near a circular table in (6-1)! = 5! ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of arrangements is 10C4 &amp;times; 5! &amp;times; 4!.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(847,9,'3','','&lt;p&gt;9 articles are to be placed in 9 boxes, one in each box. Three of them are too big for 5 of the boxes. The number of possible arrangements is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;17280&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1728&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;720&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2880&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;Here, some boxes cannot hold some articles. First fill these articles in the other boxes.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;3 articles can be arranged in the remaining 4 boxes in 4P3 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Now there are 6 remaining balls and 6 remaining boxes. These can be filled in 6! ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of ways is 6! &amp;times; 4P3 = 120 &amp;times; 24 = 2880&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(848,9,'3','','&lt;p&gt;20 people are to travel by a double-decker bus which can carry 9 in the lower deck and 11 in the upper deck. In how many ways can the people be seated in 4 keep themselves in the lower deck and 5 keep in the upper deck is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;(11!)&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; x 9!&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;11P5 x 6P6&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/194.13.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;64&quot; height=&quot;41&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;none&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;First select people for the two sides.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The 9 persons with preferences go to their preferred sides.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Out of the remaining 11 persons, pick 5 of them and send them to the lower deck where there are 4 persons already. This can be done in 11C5 ways. (We can also pick 6 of them and send them to the upper deck where there are 5 persons already. This can be done in 11C6&amp;nbsp;ways. This does not make any difference because 11C5 = 11C6). The remaining 6 persons now go to the upper deck.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Now, arrange the persons either side in 9! ways for lower deck and 11! ways for upper deck.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of arrangements is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/194.13.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;409&quot; height=&quot;49&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(849,9,'3','','&lt;p&gt;The results of 21 football matches (win, lose, draw) are to be predicted. The number of different forecasts that contain 19 wins is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;210&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;640&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;840&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1260&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;First select the 19 matches in which wins are forecasted. This can be done in 21C19 = 210 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;In the remaining 2 games, there are 2 choices (either draw or loss) for each game.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of forecasts is 210 &amp;times; 2 &amp;times; 2 = 840.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(850,9,'3','','&lt;p&gt;Given 5 different green dyes, 4 different blue dyes and 3 different red dyes, the number of combinations of dyes that can be chosen by taking at least one green and one blue dye is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;248&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;120&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;3720&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;465&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;For each green dye, there are two choices. You can either use it or not use it. For 5 different green dyes, total number of choices is 2&lt;sup&gt;5&lt;/sup&gt; = 32. Since you should use at least one green dye, the choice where you do not use any dye will not be there. So, total valid choices for green dyes is 31.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;For each blue dye, there are two choices. You can either use it or not use it. For 4 different blue dyes, total number of choices is 2&lt;sup&gt;4&amp;nbsp;&lt;/sup&gt;= 16. Since you should use at least one blue dye, the choice where you do not use any dye will not be there. So, total valid choices for blue dyes is 15.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;For each red dye, there are two choices. You can either use it or not use it. For 3 different red dyes, total number of choices is 2&lt;sup&gt;3&lt;/sup&gt; = 8. There are no conditions in this case. So, total valid choices for red dyes is 8.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of ways of choosing is 31 &amp;times; 15 &amp;times; 8 = 3720.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(851,9,'3','','&lt;p&gt;The citizens of planet Pandora are 7 fingered and have thus developed their decimal system in base 7. A certain street in Pandora contains 1000 (in base 7) buildings numbered 1 to 1000. How many 2s are used in numbering these buildings?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;192&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;300&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;147&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;84&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;All the numbers from 1 to 1000 in base 7 are written down. We only have 7 different digits to work with. We want the total count of 2&amp;rsquo;s.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Case 1: only one 2 is present&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Now, select one place out of 3 available places for 2 in 3C1=3 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The remaining 2 places can be filled with 6 different digits in 6 &amp;times; 6 = 36 ways because repetition is allowed and if the house with number 2 is considered to be 002, then the hundreds place can also have the value 0.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of such numbers is 3 &amp;times; 36 = 108 and number of 6&amp;rsquo;s in these numbers is 108.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Case 2: two 2&amp;rsquo;s are present&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Now, select two places out of 3 available places for 2 in 3C 2 = 3 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The remaining place can be filled with 6 different digits in 6 ways because repetition is allowed and if the house with number 2 is considered to be 002, then the hundreds place can also have the value 0.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of such numbers is 3 &amp;times; 6 = 18 and number of 2&amp;rsquo;s in these numbers is 18 &amp;times; 2 = 36.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Case 3: three 2&amp;rsquo;s are present&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;There is only such number 222. So, number of 2&amp;rsquo;s in these numbers is 3.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total number of 2&amp;rsquo;s is 108 + 36 + 3 = 147.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(852,9,'3','','&lt;p&gt;Given a cube of edge length n units, with paint on all its faces, and then is cut into smaller cubes of edge length 1 unit each, then find the number of small cubes with zero coloured faces.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;8&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;(n - 2)&lt;sup&gt;3&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;12(n - 2)&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6(n - 2)&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Total number of smaller cubes that the bigger cube is broken to will be n&lt;sup&gt;3&lt;/sup&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Only those cubes that have at least one face that is one of the faces of the bigger cube will be coloured.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of cubes without any coloured faces = number of inner cubes = (n-2)&lt;sup&gt;3&lt;/sup&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Only those cubes which form the vertices have paint on three faces.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Since a cube has 8 vertices, number of cubes having paint on three sides is 8.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Those cubes that form part of the edges (not including those cubes part of the vertices)&amp;nbsp;will have paint on 2 sides.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, each edge has (n - 2) such cubes and there are 12 such edges.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, number of cubes with paint on 2 sides is 12(n - 2).&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Those cubes that form part of the outer face (not including those cubes part of the vertices) will have paint on 1 sides.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, each edge has (n-2)&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; such cubes and there are 6 such edges.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, number of cubes with paint on 2 sides is 6(n-2)&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(853,9,'3','','&lt;p&gt;There are 27 balls out of them 1 is heavy. Find the minimum number of times the balls have to be weighed for finding out the heavy ball?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;3&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;13&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;In this question, divide the number of balls into 3 equal sized groups.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Then weigh two sets of balls. There may be 2 cases.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Case 1: if one set of balls weigh more than the other set, then the heavier set has the heavier ball.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Then, divide the balls of the heavier set into three groups again.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Case 2: if both sets are of equal weight, then the third set has the heavier ball.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Then, divide the third set into three groups.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Repeat this process until we can separate the heavier ball.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Trick: If there are n balls such that 3&lt;sup&gt;(m-1)&lt;/sup&gt; &amp;lt; m &amp;le; 3&lt;sup&gt;m&lt;/sup&gt;, then the number of trails required is m. Here, m = 27 = 3&lt;sup&gt;3&lt;/sup&gt;. So, number of trials required is 3.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(854,9,'3','','&lt;p&gt;How many three-digit natural numbers are there so that unit&amp;rsquo;s digit is always less than ten&amp;rsquo;s and the tens digit is always less than hundred&amp;rsquo;s digit?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;172&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;84&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;120&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;144&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Here all the three digits are different and the unit&amp;rsquo;s digit is the smallest of the three. For the three places, there is a particular order is to be followed.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Since unit&amp;rsquo;s digit can also be 0, it is enough if we select 3 numbers from the 10 available digits in 10C3 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Once the numbers are selected, we just fill the places according to the given rule and this can be done only in 1 way.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of required ways is 10C3 = 120&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(855,9,'3','','&lt;p&gt;A single Badminton tournament is held in which 20 men participate. It is a knockout tournament, a player is eliminated as soon as he loses a match. How many matches should be played in the entire tournament to have one clear winner?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;20&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;19&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;15&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;In a strict knockout tournament, if there are n initial players, to have a clear winner, (n - 1) players are to be knocked out and so, there will be (n - 1) matches held.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;In this case, n = 20.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of matches held is 19.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(856,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;The number of ways in which a team of 8 students can be selected from a pool of 15 students while always including 2 students is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;15C8&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;13C6&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;13C8&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;15C6&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Since two players are always included, number of vacant positions is 6.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of players available for selection for these 6 positions is 13.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total number of ways is 13C6.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(857,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;The number of ways in which a team of 8 students can be selected from a pool of 15 students while always excluding 2 students is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;15C8&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;13C6&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;13C8&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;15C6&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Since two players are always excluded, number of vacant positions is 8 but the total number of students available for selection for these 8 positions is 13.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total number of ways is 13C8.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(858,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;The number of ways in which a team of 8 students can be selected from a pool of 15 students while always including 2 students and always excluding 2 students is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;13C8&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;11C6&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;11C8&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;13C6&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Since two students are always included, number of vacant positions is 6.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Out of the remaining 13 students, 2 players are not at all in consideration. So, total number of students available for selection are 11.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total number of ways is 11C6.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(859,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;In how many ways can 7 persons be seated across a circular table?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;7!&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;7!/2&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6!&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6!/2&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;7 persons can be arranged in a circular table in (7-1)! = 6! ways.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(860,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;How many one-one functions can be made from the set A which contains 4 elements to the set B which contains 9 elements?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4&lt;sup&gt;9&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;9&lt;sup&gt;4&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;9P4&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;9C4&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;For each of the element in A, it can be mapped to one and only one element of B. More than one element in A cannot be related to the same element in B.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, for 5 elements, total number of functions possible is 9 &amp;times; 8 &amp;times; 7 &amp;times; 6 = 9P4.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(861,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;How many 5-digit numbers are possible involving the digits 2, 3, 0, 4 and 4 and using only the digits given?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;12&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;48&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;36&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;24&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;The ten thousandths digit cannot be 0. So, there are 4 options for this place.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;For the remaining 4 positions, the remaining 4 digits can be arranged in 4! ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Now, if we make that 5-digit number, 4 will be repeated twice.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of ways is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/195.6.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;86&quot; height=&quot;42&quot; /&gt; .&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(862,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;How many functions can be made from the set A which contains 5 elements to the set B which contains 3 elements?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;3&lt;sup&gt;5&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5&lt;sup&gt;3&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5P3&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5C3&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;For each of the element in A, it can be mapped to any element of B. so, the total choices available is 3.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;More than one element in A can be related to the same element in B.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, for 5 elements, total number of functions possible is 3 &amp;times; 3 &amp;times; 3 &amp;times; 3 &amp;times; 3 = 3&lt;sup&gt;5&lt;/sup&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(863,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;In how many ways can we arrange all the letters of the word MATHEMATICS?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;11!&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/195.8.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;43&quot; height=&quot;49&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/195.8.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;39&quot; height=&quot;48&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/195.8.3.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;38&quot; height=&quot;43&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;There are 11 letters out of which 3 letters are repeated twice.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;They can be arranged among themselves in &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/195.8.4.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;38&quot; height=&quot;47&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;ways.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(864,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;In how many ways can we arrange all the letters of the word ALLAHABAD?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;9!&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/195.9.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;37&quot; height=&quot;45&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/195.9.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;40&quot; height=&quot;44&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/195.9.3.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;21&quot; height=&quot;35&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;There are 9 letters out of which 1 letter is repeated 4 times and another letter is repeated 2 times.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;They can be arranged among themselves in &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/195.9.4.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;44&quot; height=&quot;47&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;ways.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(865,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;In how many ways can the letters of the word ALLAHABAD be arranged such that vowels occupy odd places?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;600&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;300&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;150&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;900&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;There are 5 odd places and 1 vowel which has repeated itself 4 times. So, it is enough f we select the places for the vowel.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So 4 places can be selected in 5C4 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Now, there will be 5 places blank and they can be filled with 5 consonants, where there is one repetition in &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/195.10.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;26&quot; height=&quot;44&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of ways to arrange is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/195.10.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;108&quot; height=&quot;38&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;ways&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(866,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;How many telephone connections can be allotted with 8 digits form the numbers 0, 1, 2 ...9?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10&lt;sup&gt;8&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10!&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10C8&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10P8&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;There can be repetition and the starting number can be zero. So, number of choices available are 10 for each position.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Since there are 8 positions, total number of choices will be 10&lt;sup&gt;8&lt;/sup&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(867,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;How many 4 digit numbers greater than 7000 can be formed out of the digits 3, 5, 7, 8, 9?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;24&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;48&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;72&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;50&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;For the thousands position, there are only 3 possibilities 7,8,9. So, thousands place can be filled in 3 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Now, for the remaining 3 positions, we can arrange from a pool of 4 digits in 4P3 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of ways is 3 &amp;times; 4P3 = 72.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(868,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;The chief ministers of 17 states meet to discuss the hike in oil price at a round table. In how many ways can they seat themselves if the Kerala and Bengal chief ministers choose to sit together?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;15! X 2!&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;17! X 2!&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;16! X 2!&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;16!&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Since 2 persons want to sit together, make them a group. Now, within the group, they can be arranged among themselves in 2! = 2 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;There are 16 elements to be seated around a table. This can be done in (16-1)! = 15!.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of required ways is 15! x 2&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(869,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;In how many ways the word ARRANGE be arranged such that the 2 &amp;lsquo;r&amp;rsquo;s come together?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;400&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;440&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;360&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;320&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Make the 2 r&amp;rsquo;s into a group. Now, since all the elements of the group are identical, there will be no arrangement within the group.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Now, there will be 6 elements, out of which one element is repeated 2 times.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of ways of arrangements is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/195.14.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;58&quot; height=&quot;32&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;ways.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(870,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;If there are 50 stations on a railway line, how many different kinds of single first class tickets may be printed to enable a passenger to travel from one station to other?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2500&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2450&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2400&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2350&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;A person can get into the train a t any one of the 50 stations and can get out at any of the remaining 49 stations.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of tickets required is 50 &amp;times; 49 = 2450.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(871,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;The total number of sitting arrangements of 7 persons in a row if 3 persons sit together in a particular order is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5!&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6!&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2! x 5!&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2! x 6!&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Three persons will always be together. So, let us treat them as a single group. Now, there are 5 persons to be arranged instead of 7 because the three persons are one group. They can be arranged in 5! ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Now, within the group, the 3 persons cannot be arranged within themselves because there is a fixed order among them.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the total number of arrangements is 5!.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(872,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;If all the permutations of the letters of the word MOTHER are written in a dictionary the rank of this word will be&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;309&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;310&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;308&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;311&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Write the word in alphabetical order. Here it is EHMORT.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Now strike the first letter of the word which is M. now the number of words in this case is n.m! where n is the number of letters which are not stricken and before the letter to be stricken out. m denotes the total number of letters not stricken off. After the process is repeated with all the letters, add 1 finally to get the rank.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;For M, n = 2 and m = 5, so no.of words is 2 x 5!&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;For O, n = 2 and m = 4, so no.of words is 2 x 4!&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;For T, n = 3 and m = 3, so no.of words is 3 x 3!&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;For H, n = 1 and m = 2, so no.of words is 1 x 2!&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;For E, n = 0 and m = 1, so no.of words is 0 x 1!&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;For R, n = 0 and m = 0, so no.of words is 0 x 0!&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, rank of MOTHER is (2 x 5!) + (2 x 4!) + (3 x 3!) + (1 x 2!) + 1 = 240 + 48 + 18 + 2 + 1 = 309.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(873,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;In how many ways can you make a choice of 7 questions out of a 10 question set?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10C7&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10P7&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;7! x 10C7&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;7!&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;It is enough if we select the 7 questions that we intend to answer. We need not arrange them.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of ways required is 10C7.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(874,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;In a paper from 2 groups of 5 questions each, you have to answer any 6 questions attempting at least 2 questions from each group. This is possible in ________ number of ways.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;50&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;100&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;200&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;150&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;There are 3 possibilities to answer 6 questions.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Case 1: 2 from group 1 and 4 from group 2. This can be done in 5C2 &amp;times; 5C4 = 10 &amp;times; 5 = 50.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Case 2: 3 from group 1 and 3 from group 2. This can be done in 5C3 &amp;times; 5C3 = 10 &amp;times; 10 = 100.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Case 3: 4 from group 1 and 2 from group 2. This can be done in 5C2 &amp;times; 5C4 = 10 &amp;times; 5 = 50.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of ways is 50 + 100 + 50 = 200.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(875,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;A party of 6 is to be formed from 10 men and 7 women so as to include 3 men and 3 women. In how many ways the party can be formed if two particular women refuse to join it?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4200&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;600&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;3600&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1200&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;3 men from 10 men can be selected in 10C3 = 120 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Since 2 women refuse to be part of the committee, 3 women must be selected from the remaining 5 women in 5C3 = 10 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of ways is 120 &amp;times; 10 = 1200.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(876,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;The number of distinct positive divisors of 16200 is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;90&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;60&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;45&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;96&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;16200 expressed in terms of prime factorisation is 2&lt;sup&gt;3&lt;/sup&gt; &amp;times; 3&lt;sup&gt;4&lt;/sup&gt; &amp;times; 5&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;We can see that a divisor of the number 2&lt;sup&gt;3&lt;/sup&gt; &amp;times; 3&lt;sup&gt;4&lt;/sup&gt; &amp;times; 5&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; will be of the form 2&lt;sup&gt;a&lt;/sup&gt; &amp;times; 3&lt;sup&gt;b&lt;/sup&gt; &amp;times; 5&lt;sup&gt;c&lt;/sup&gt; where the possible values for a are (0,1,2,3), for b are (0,1,2,3,4) and for c are (0,1,2).&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, a divisor will be formed if we pick all the three values. Number of choices to pick a value for a is 4, for b is 5 and for c is 3.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;This can be done in 4 &amp;times; 5 &amp;times; 3 = 60 ways.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(877,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;The number of distinct even positive divisors of 16200 is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;90&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;60&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;45&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;96&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;16200 expressed in terms of prime factorisation is 2&lt;sup&gt;3&lt;/sup&gt; &amp;times; 3&lt;sup&gt;4&lt;/sup&gt; &amp;times; 5&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;We can see that a divisor of the number 2&lt;sup&gt;3&lt;/sup&gt; &amp;times; 3&lt;sup&gt;4&lt;/sup&gt; &amp;times; 5&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; will be of the form 2&lt;sup&gt;a&lt;/sup&gt; &amp;times; 3&lt;sup&gt;b&lt;/sup&gt; &amp;times; 5&lt;sup&gt;c&lt;/sup&gt; where the possible values for a are (0,1,2,3), for b are (0,1,2,3,4) and for c are (0,1,2).&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The requirement is that the divisor should be even. So, the power for 2 can take only the values a=1,2,3. If a=0, then the divisor will be odd. So, the number of choices to pick a value for a is 3, for b is 5 and for c is 3.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;This can be done in 3 &amp;times; 5 &amp;times; 3 = 45 ways.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(878,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;There are 4 balls of different colours and 4 boxes of colours same as those of the balls. The number of ways in which the balls, each in a box could be placed such that a ball does not go to the box of its own colour is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;0&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;24&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;9&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;Every ball must go to the wrong colour box.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Number of ways in which this can be done if there are n balls is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/195.23.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;190&quot; height=&quot;39&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Here n = 4.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, number of ways is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/195.23.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;229&quot; height=&quot;40&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(879,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;There are 4 balls of different colours and 4 boxes of colours same as those of the balls. The number of ways in which the balls, each in a box could be placed such that only one ball does not go to the box of its own colour is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;0&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;24&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;9&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;If we deliberately put red ball into a box of blue colour, then it means that we cannot put the blue ball into the blue box.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, it is never possible to put one ball wrong.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, answer is zero.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(880,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;The results of 21 football matches (win, lose, draw) are to be predicted. The number of different forecasts that contain at least 19 wins is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;210&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;640&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;840&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1890&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;First select the 19 matches in which wins are forecasted. This can be done in 21C19 = 210 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;In the remaining 2 games, there are 3 choices (either win, draw or loss) for each game.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of forecasts is 210 &amp;times; 3 &amp;times; 3 = 1890.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(881,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;The total number of products that can be formed with 10 prime numbers taking one or more at a time is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2&lt;sup&gt;10&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2&lt;sup&gt;10&lt;/sup&gt; - 1&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2&lt;sup&gt;10&lt;/sup&gt; - 11&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2&lt;sup&gt;10&lt;/sup&gt; - 10&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Number of products formed by taking one prime is 10C1.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Number of products formed by taking two primes is 10C2.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Number of products formed by taking 3 primes is 10C3.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;We can take any number of primes from 2 to 10.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of ways is 10C1 + 10C3 + 10C4 + â‹¯ + 10C10 = 2&lt;sup&gt;10&lt;/sup&gt; - 10C0 = 2&lt;sup&gt;10&lt;/sup&gt;-1.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(882,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;The number of different sums that are greater than one rupee that can be formed using the following coins -1 rupee, 50 paisa, 25 paisa, 10 paisa, 5 paisa- is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;32&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;31&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;15&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;Since the sum should be greater than 1 rupee, the 1 rupee coin should be used. There is no choice otherwise.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;With each and every other coin, we have two choices. We can either use it or not use it.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, for 5 different coins, total number of choices is 2 &amp;times; 2 &amp;times; 2 &amp;times; 2 &amp;times; 1 = 16.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;But in one of these choices, We do not use any other coin and the sum would be exactly one rupee which is not valid.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So total number of sums that can be made is 16 - 1 = 15.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(883,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;If a regular polygon has 10 sides, what is the number of its diagonals?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;35&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;45&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;21&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Let the number of sides for a regular polygon be n.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;We can combine these n points in pairs and get nC2 different straight lines. Out of these, n are sides.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, number if diagonals is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/195.28.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;129&quot; height=&quot;49&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Here n = 10. So, number of diagonals is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/195.28.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;80&quot; height=&quot;41&quot; /&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(884,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;The number of ways in which the letters of the word FLOWER be arranged without changing the order of the vowels is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;720&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;180&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;360&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;270&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;In this case, first arrange the consonants in the available 6 places in 6P4 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;There will be 2 blank places left. We should not disturb the order of vowels. So, the first blank is filled with O and the second with E. This can be done only in 1 way.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of ways to arrange is 6P4 = 360.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(885,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;The number of ways in which the letters of the word FLOWER be arranged without changing the positions of the vowels is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;96&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;48&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;72&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;144&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;In this case, vowels should remain in their places always i.e., 3rd and 5th positions always. Similarly, consonants should remain in their positions always.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total number of ways to arrange the vowels is 2! = 2.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total number of ways to arrange the consonants is 4! = 24.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of ways required is 48.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(886,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;The number of ways in which the letters of the word EQUATION be arranged without changing the positions of the vowels is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;720&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;180&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;360&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;270&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;In this case, vowels should remain in their places always i.e., 1st, 3rd, 4th, 6th and 7th positions always. Similarly, consonants should remain in their positions always.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total number of ways to arrange the vowels is 5! = 120.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total number of ways to arrange the consonants is 3! = 6.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of ways required is 120 &amp;times; 6 = 720.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(887,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;In order to pass Class XII examination minimum marks have to be secured in each of 6 subjects. In how many ways can a pupil fail?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;32&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;64&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;31&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;63&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;A student fails if he does not pass in even one subject.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;For every subject, he has two choices, either he will pass or he will fail.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, for 6 subjects, total number of choices is 2&lt;sup&gt;6&lt;/sup&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;In one of these choices, he will pass in all subjects and so is not required.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of ways to fail is 2&lt;sup&gt;6&lt;/sup&gt; - 1 = 63 ways.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(888,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;A committee is to be formed of 4 teachers and 3 students out of 10 teachers and 20 students. If a particular student is always excluded and another particular teacher is always included, then the number of ways in which this can be done is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10C3 x 19C2&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;9C4 x 20C3&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;9C3 x 19C3&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;9C4 x 19C3&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;For the 3 student posts, we need to select from remaining 19 students. This can be done in 19C3 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;One teacher post is already fixed. For the 3 teacher posts, we need to select from remaining 9 students. This can be done in 9C3 ways.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(889,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;From 7 men and 4 women a committee of 5 is to be formed. In how many ways can this be done to include at least one woman?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;441&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;440&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;420&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;435&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Total number of committees that can be formed is 11C5.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total number of committees in which there is no female member is 7C5.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of committees in which there is at least one female member is 11C5 - 7C5 = 462 - 21 = 441.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(890,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;Out of 6 members belonging to party &amp;lsquo;A&amp;lsquo; and 4 to party &amp;lsquo;B&amp;lsquo; in how many ways a committee of 5 can be selected so that members of party &amp;lsquo;A&amp;lsquo; are in a majority?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;180&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;186&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;185&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;184&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Members belonging to party A can be in majority in these cases.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Case 1: 3 from A and 2 from B. number of ways is 6C3 &amp;times; 4C2 = 20 &amp;times; 6 = 120.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Case 2: 4 from A and 1 from B. number of ways is 6C4 &amp;times; 4C1 = 15 &amp;times; 4 = 60.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Case 3: 5 from A and 0 from B. number of ways is 6C5 = 6.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of ways is 120 + 60 + 6 = 186.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(891,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;The number of ways in which 10 candidates A&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt;, A&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;, A&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt;,&amp;hellip;, A&lt;sub&gt;10&lt;/sub&gt; can be ranked, if A&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; is always above A&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;, is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;9!&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10!&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10P9&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10P8&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;First arrange the remaining 8 candidates in the 10 positions in 10P8.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Now, there will be 2 places that are free for A1 and A2. We cannot arrange them because the order is already determined.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of ways is 10P8.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(892,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;How many numbers greater than 50,000 be formed with the digits (1, 1, 5, 9, 0) ?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;24&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;12&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;18&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;36&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;The initial digit can only be either 5 or 9. So, the total number of ways to fill this digit is 2.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The remaining 4 digits can be filled with 4 numbers in &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/195.37.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;23&quot; height=&quot;47&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;ways because 1 is repeated twice.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the total number of ways is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/195.37.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;73&quot; height=&quot;35&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;ways.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(893,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;The number of different words that can be formed by using all the letters if the word NINETEEN in which no two E&amp;rsquo;s come together is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/195.38.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;40&quot; height=&quot;46&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/195.38.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;59&quot; height=&quot;43&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/195.38.3.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;57&quot; height=&quot;43&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/195.38.4.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;56&quot; height=&quot;43&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;First arrange all the remaining 5 letters. Here N is repeated 3 times. So, this can be done in &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/195.38.5.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;24&quot; height=&quot;42&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Now, there will be 6 blank places in between them. We have to fill 3 E&amp;rsquo;s in these 6 places in 6C3 ways because all the items are identical.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of ways is &lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/Question%20Images/195.38.6.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;62&quot; height=&quot;47&quot; /&gt; .&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(894,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;A letter lock has 5 rings each marked with four different letters. The number of all possible unsuccessful attempts to open the lock is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;625&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1024&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;624&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1023&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;Each ring has 4 choices. So for 5 rings, the total number of choices that can be created is 4&lt;sup&gt;5&lt;/sup&gt; = 1024 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Out of all these combinations, only one choice will open the lock.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the total number of choices is 1024 - 1 = 1023 ways.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(895,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;In how many ways can a collection of 30 books be divided into two groups of 10 and 20 books, if the larger group always contains a particular book?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;29C29&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;29C20&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;29C10&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;29C29 x 29C20&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Out of the remaining 29 books, select 19 books for the larger group in 29C19 ways. The remaining 10 books automatically go to the smaller group.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the total number of ways required is 29C19 = 29C10.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;(we can also select 10 books for the small group in &amp;nbsp;ways. Now, the remaining 19 books go to the larger group)&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(896,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;The number of triangles that can be formed by joining the vertices of a decagon are&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;120&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;720&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;80&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1000&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;The total number of triangles that can be made from 10 non collinear points is 10C3 = 120.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(897,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;A single Badminton tournament is held in which 35 men participate. It is a knockout tournament, a player is eliminated as soon as he loses a match. How many matches should be played in the entire tournament to have 2 clear winners?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;34&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;33&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;20&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;17&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;In a strict knockout tournament, if there are n initial players, to have 2 clear winners, (n - 2) players are to be knocked out and so, there will be (n - 2) matches held.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;In this case, n = 35.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of matches held is 33.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(898,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;There are 15 points in a plane of which 4 points are on one straight-line and another 5 points are on another straight-line. The two lines are parallel and no three of the remaining 6 points are collinear. Find the number of triangles that can be formed by joining these 15 points.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;441&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;455&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;213&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Data Insufficient&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Total number of triangles that can be formed from 15 non collinear points is 15C3.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;For the first set of 4 collinear points, the total number of triangles is 0 instead of 4C3.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Similarly, for the second set of 5 collinear points, the total number of triangles is 0 instead of 5C3.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of triangles possible are 15C3 - 4C3 - 5C3 = 455 - 4 - 10 = 441.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(899,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;There are 15 points in a plane of which 4 points are on one straight-line and another 5 points are on another straight-line. The two lines are parallel and no three of the remaining 6 points are collinear. Find the number of straight lines that can be formed by joining these 15 points.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;91&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;92&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;93&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;90&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Total number of straight lines that can be formed from 15 non collinear points is 15C2.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;For the first set of 4 collinear points, the total number of straight lines is 1 instead of 4C2.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Similarly, for the second set of 5 collinear points, the total number of straight lines is 1 instead of 5C2.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of straight lines possible is 15C2 - 4C2 - 5C2 + 2 = 105 - 6 - 10 + 2 = 91.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(900,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;How many three-digit natural numbers are there so that unit&amp;rsquo;s digit is less than ten&amp;rsquo;s as well as hundred&amp;rsquo;s digit (no repetition is allowed)?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;300&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;360&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;320&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;240&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;Here all the three digits are different and the unit&amp;rsquo;s digit is the smallest of the three.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Since unit&amp;rsquo;s digit can also be 0, it is enough if we select 3 numbers from the 10 available digits in 10C3 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Once the numbers are selected, we just fill the unit&amp;rsquo;s digit with the lowest digit among the three. For the remaining two places, the two digits can be arranged in 2! = 2 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the total number of arrangements is 2 &amp;times; 10C3 = 240 ways.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(901,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;How many three-digit natural numbers are there so that unit&amp;rsquo;s digit is always greater than ten&amp;rsquo;s and the tens digit is always greater than hundred&amp;rsquo;s digit?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;172&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;84&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;120&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;144&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Here all the three digits are different and the unit&amp;rsquo;s digit is the smallest of the three. For the three places, there is a particular order is to be followed.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Since hundred&amp;rsquo;s digit cannot be 0, it is required that we select 3 numbers from the remaining 9 available digits in 9C3 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Once the numbers are selected, we just fill the places according to the given rule and this can be done only in 1 way.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of required ways is 9C3 = 84&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(902,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;There are 243 balls out of them 1 is heavy. Find the minimum number of times the balls have to be weighed for finding out the heavy ball?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;8&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;13&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;In this question, divide the number of balls into 3 equal sized groups.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Then weigh two sets of balls. There may be 2 cases.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Case 1: if one set of balls weigh more than the other set, then the heavier set has the heavier ball.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Then, divide the balls of the heavier set into three groups again.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Case 2: if both sets are of equal weight, then the third set has the heavier ball.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Then, divide the third set into three groups.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Repeat this process until we can separate the heavier ball.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Trick: If there are n balls such that 3&lt;sup&gt;(m-1)&lt;/sup&gt; &amp;lt; m &amp;le; 3&lt;sup&gt;m&lt;/sup&gt;, then the number of trails required is m. Here, m = 243 = 3&lt;sup&gt;5&lt;/sup&gt;. So, number of trials required is 5.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(903,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;Given a cube of edge length n units, with paint on all its faces, and then is cut into smaller cubes of edge length 1 unit each, then find the number of small cubes with one coloured face.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;8&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;(n-2)&lt;sup&gt;3&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;12(n-2)&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6(n-2)&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;Total number of smaller cubes that the bigger cube is broken to will be n&lt;sup&gt;3&lt;/sup&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Only those cubes that have at least one face that is one of the faces of the bigger cube will be coloured.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of cubes without any coloured faces = number of inner cubes = (n-2)&lt;sup&gt;3&lt;/sup&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Only those cubes which form the vertices have paint on three faces.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Since a cube has 8 vertices, number of cubes having paint on three sides is 8.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Those cubes that form part of the edges (not including those cubes part of the vertices) will have paint on 2 sides.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, each edge has (n - 2) such cubes and there are 12 such edges.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, number of cubes with paint on 2 sides is 12(n - 2).&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Those cubes that form part of the outer face (not including those cubes part of the vertices and edges&amp;nbsp;) will have paint on 1 side.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, each edge has (n - 2)&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; such cubes and there are 6 such edges.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, number of cubes with paint on 1 sides is 6(n - 2)&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(904,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;Given a cube of edge length n units, with paint on all its faces, and then is cut into smaller cubes of edge length 1 unit each, then find the number of small cubes with two coloured faces.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;8&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;(n-2)&lt;sup&gt;3&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;12(n-2)&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6(n-2)&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Total number of smaller cubes that the bigger cube is broken to will be n&lt;sup&gt;3&lt;/sup&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Only those cubes that have at least one face that is one of the faces of the bigger cube will be coloured.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of cubes without any coloured faces = number of inner cubes = (n-2)&lt;sup&gt;3&lt;/sup&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Only those cubes which form the vertices have paint on three faces.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Since a cube has 8 vertices, number of cubes having paint on three sides is 8.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Those cubes that form part of the edges (not including those cubes part of the vertices) will have paint on 2 sides.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, each edge has (n - 2) such cubes and there are 12 such edges.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, number of cubes with paint on 2 sides is 12(n - 2).&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Those cubes that form part of the outer face (not including those cubes part of the vertices and edges&amp;nbsp;) will have paint on 1 sides.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, each edge has (n - 2)&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; such cubes and there are 6 such edges.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, number of cubes with paint on 1 sides is 6(n - 2)&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(905,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;Given a cube of edge length n units, with paint on all its faces, and then is cut into smaller cubes of edge length 1 unit each, then find the number of small cubes with three coloured faces.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;8&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;(n-2)&lt;sup&gt;3&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;12(n-2)&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6(n-2)&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Total number of smaller cubes that the bigger cube is broken to will be n&lt;sup&gt;3&lt;/sup&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Only those cubes that have at least one face that is one of the faces of the bigger cube will be coloured.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of cubes without any coloured faces = number of inner cubes = (n - 2)&lt;sup&gt;3&lt;/sup&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Only those cubes which form the vertices have paint on three faces.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Since a cube has 8 vertices, number of cubes having paint on three sides is 8.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Those cubes that form part of the edges (not including those cubes part of the vertices)&amp;nbsp;will have paint on 2 sides.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, each edge has (n - 2) such cubes and there are 12 such edges.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, number of cubes with paint on 2 sides is 12(n - 2).&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Those cubes that form part of the outer face (not including those cubes part of the vertices and edges)&amp;nbsp;will have paint on 1 side.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, each edge has (n-2)&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; such cubes and there are 6 such edges.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, number of cubes with paint on 1 sides is 6(n - 2)&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(906,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;In a dark room, there is a box containing 8 white balls, 12 black balls, 14 yellow balls and 5 red balls. What is the least number of balls to be chosen so as to ensure a pair of balls of same colour has been drawn?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;17&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;36&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;12&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;If a particular colour is not specified,&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Then answer is (total number of different colours + 1).&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Here, it will be 4 + 1 = 5.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The first ball drawn may be white, second may be black, 3rd may be yellow and 4th may be red. However, the 5th ball must have at least one of these colours and so a pair will be formed.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If a particular colour is specified,&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Answer will be (sum of balls of all other colours + 2).&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If we want red balls, then in the worst case, all the first 8 balls may be white, the next 12 balls may be black and the next 14 may be yellow. Now that all other colour balls are exhausted, the next 2 balls should really be a red pair.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, answer will be 8 + 12 + 14 + 2 = 36&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(907,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;In a dark room, there is a box containing 8 white balls, 14 black balls, 12 yellow balls and 5 red balls. What is the least number of balls to be chosen so as to ensure a pair of RED balls has been drawn?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;17&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;36&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;12&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;If a particular colour is not specified,&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Then answer is (total number of different colours + 1).&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Here, it will be 4 + 1 = 5.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The first ball drawn may be white, second may be black, 3rd may be yellow and 4th may be red. However, the 5th ball must have at least one of these colours and so a pair will be formed.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If a particular colour is specified,&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Answer will be (sum of balls of all other colours + 2).&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;If we want red balls, then in the worst case, all the first 8 balls may be white, the next 12 balls may be black and the next 14 may be yellow. Now that all other colour balls are exhausted, the next 2 balls should really be a red pair.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, answer will be 8 + 12 + 14 + 2 = 36&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(908,9,'4','','&lt;p&gt;If all the numbers from 1 to 1000 are written side by side, how many 6s are used in numbering these buildings?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;192&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;300&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;147&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;84&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;All the numbers from 1 to 1000 are written down.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;We want the total count of 6&amp;rsquo;s.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Case 1: only one 6 is present&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Now, select one place out of 3 available places for 6 in 3C1 = 3 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The remaining 2 places can be filled with 9 different digits in 9 &amp;times; 9 = 81 ways because repetition is allowed and if the house with number 2 is considered to be 002, then the hundreds place can also have the value 0.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of such numbers is 3 &amp;times; 81 = 243 and number of 6&amp;rsquo;s in these numbers is 243.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Case 2: two 6&amp;rsquo;s are present&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Now, select two places out of 3 available places for 6 in 3C2 = 3 ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;The remaining place can be filled with 9 different digits in 9 ways because repetition is allowed and if the house with number 2 is considered to be 002, then the hundreds place can also have the value 0.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total number of such numbers is 3 &amp;times; 9 = 27 and number of 6&amp;rsquo;s in these numbers is 27 &amp;times; 2 = 54.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Case 3: three 6&amp;rsquo;s are present&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;There is only such number 666. So, number of 6&amp;rsquo;s in these numbers is 3.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total number of 6&amp;rsquo;s is 243 + 54 + 3 = 300.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(909,10,'1','&lt;p&gt;Direction: Following table shows the population of 8 different cities A, B, C, D, E, F, G and H and ratio of Male and Females among them and the ratio of literate to illiterate in the total population. Answer the given questions based on this table.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%201%20-%201%20-%20Ex%201/212.1.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;418&quot; height=&quot;180&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the total number of Female population in city C and city F?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6375642&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6375742&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6375842&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6475742&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Total female population from C is 4627340 x (7/10) = 3239138.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total female population from F is 8625386 x (4/11) = 3136504.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, total population required is 3239138 + 3136504 = 6375642.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(910,10,'1','&lt;p&gt;Direction: Following table shows the population of 8 different cities A, B, C, D, E, F, G and H and ratio of Male and Females among them and the ratio of literate to illiterate in the total population. Answer the given questions based on this table.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%201%20-%201%20-%20Ex%201/212.1.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;418&quot; height=&quot;180&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the total number of Male population in city E and illiterate population in city H?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4748760&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4749760&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4747760&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4745760&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Total male population in city E is 5201265 x (8/15) = 2774008.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total illiterate population in city H is 2469740 x (4/5) = 1975752.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the required population is 2774008 + 1975752 = 4749760.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(911,10,'1','&lt;p&gt;Direction: Following table shows the population of 8 different cities A, B, C, D, E, F, G and H and ratio of Male and Females among them and the ratio of literate to illiterate in the total population. Answer the given questions based on this table.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%201%20-%201%20-%20Ex%201/212.1.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;418&quot; height=&quot;180&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the difference between total Male population and the total Literate population from A, B and D?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1816809&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1816909&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1816709&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1817709&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Total male population from A, B, D is [7731375 x (2/5)] + [3889305 x (4/9)] + [6241532 x (6/11)] = 3092550 + 1728580 + 3404472 = 8225602.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total literate population from A, B, D is [7731375 x (1/5)] + [3889305 x (2/3)] + [6241532 x (4/11)] = 1546275 + 2592870 + 2269648 = 6408793.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the required difference is 8225602 &amp;ndash; 6408793 = 1816809&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(912,10,'1','&lt;p&gt;Direction: Following table shows the population of 8 different cities A, B, C, D, E, F, G and H and ratio of Male and Females among them and the ratio of literate to illiterate in the total population. Answer the given questions based on this table.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%201%20-%201%20-%20Ex%201/212.1.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;418&quot; height=&quot;180&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the ratio of Literate population from city B to the Male population from G?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1297935 : 1243568&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1297935 : 1234568&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1279935 : 1234568&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1279935 : 1243568&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Literate population from B is 3889305 x (2/3) = 2592870.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Male population from G is 3108920 x (4/5) = 2487136.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the required ratio is 2592870: 2487136 = 1297935: 1243568&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(913,10,'1','&lt;p&gt;Direction: Following table shows the population of 8 different cities A, B, C, D, E, F, G and H and ratio of Male and Females among them and the ratio of literate to illiterate in the total population. Answer the given questions based on this table.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%201%20-%201%20-%20Ex%201/212.1.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;418&quot; height=&quot;180&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;The female population of city B and E is approximately what percent of its Literate population?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;104%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;108%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;96%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;92%&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Total female population of B and E is [3889305 x (5/9)] + [5201265 x (7/15)] = 2160725 + 2427257 = 4587982.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total male population of B and E is [3889305 x (1/3)] + [5201265 x (3/5)] = 1296435 + 3120759 = 4417194.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the required ratio is (4587982/4417194) x 100% = 103.86 = 104%.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(914,10,'1','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the table carefully to answer the following questions. Number (in lakhs) of items manufactured by six companies over the years.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%201%20-%201%20-%20Ex%201/212.2.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;525&quot; height=&quot;162&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the ratio of the number of items manufactured by Company S in the year 2010 to that of those manufactured by Company Q in the year 2013?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;103 : 47&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;47 : 103&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;113 : 57&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;57 : 113&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;The required ratio is 51.5: 23.5 = 103: 47.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(915,10,'1','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the table carefully to answer the following questions. Number (in lakhs) of items manufactured by six companies over the years.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%201%20-%201%20-%20Ex%201/212.2.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;525&quot; height=&quot;162&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the approximate per cent increase in the number of items manufactured by Company R in the year 2013, from the previous year?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;31.50%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;33.50%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;30.50%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;29.50&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;The number increased from 38.7 lakhs to 50.9 lakhs from 2012 to 2013. So, the percentage increase is [(50.9 &amp;ndash; 38.7)/38.7] x 100% = [12.2/38.7] x 100% = 31.52%&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(916,10,'1','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the table carefully to answer the following questions. Number (in lakhs) of items manufactured by six companies over the years.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%201%20-%201%20-%20Ex%201/212.2.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;525&quot; height=&quot;162&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the average number of items manufactured by all companies together in the year 2014?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;3925000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;39250000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;3975000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;39750000&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Total number of items produced in 2014 is 53 + 35.7 + 42.6 + 26.5 + 36.2 + 41.5 = 235.5 lakhs.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the average production is 235.5/6 lakh = 39.25 lakhs&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(917,10,'1','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the table carefully to answer the following questions. Number (in lakhs) of items manufactured by six companies over the years.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%201%20-%201%20-%20Ex%201/212.2.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;525&quot; height=&quot;162&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;The number of items manufactured by Company T in the year 2010 is approximately what per cent of the total number of items manufactured by it in all the years together?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;24%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;32%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;20%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;28%&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Total number of items produced by T is 28.3 + 41.5 + 50.8 + 24.1 + 30.4 + 36.2 = 211.3 lakhs. Items produced by T in 2010 is 41.5 lakhs.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the percentage required is (41.5/211.3) x 100% = 19.64%.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(918,10,'1','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the table carefully to answer the following questions. Number (in lakhs) of items manufactured by six companies over the years.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%201%20-%201%20-%20Ex%201/212.2.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;525&quot; height=&quot;162&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;How many more items need to be manufactured by Company S in the year 2013 to make the ratio of the number of items manufactured by Company S to that of those manufactured by Company U in the year 2013 as 54: 83?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;250000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;25000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;50000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;500000&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;The ratio given is 54: 83 = 27: 41.5. Since U already produces 41.5 lakh items, S must produce 27 lakh items. It is already producing 26.5 lakhs. So, it must produce another 50,000 units.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(919,10,'1','&lt;p&gt;Direction: Following table shows the run scored by different batsman in five ODI matches in a series. Answer given questions based on this table.&lt;/p&gt;\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%201%20-%201%20-%20Ex%201/212.3.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;370&quot; height=&quot;140&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the average runs scored by batsman in all five matches together?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;50.6&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;54.6&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;52.6&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;48.6&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Runs scored by all the batsmen in all the matches together is 1518. There are 30 innings in all. So, average runs scored by a batsman in five matches together is 1518/30 = 50.6&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(920,10,'1','&lt;p&gt;Direction: Following table shows the run scored by different batsman in five ODI matches in a series. Answer given questions based on this table.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%201%20-%201%20-%20Ex%201/212.3.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;370&quot; height=&quot;140&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the difference between total runs scored by all six batsman in match M2 and total run scored by them in match M3?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;53&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;51&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;43&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;57&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Total runs scored in M2 is 41 + 28 + 65 + 55 + 47 + 36 = 272. Total runs scored in M3 is 25 + 48 + 114 + 61 + 34 + 43 = 325. So, the difference is 325 &amp;ndash; 272 = 53.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(921,10,'1','&lt;p&gt;Direction: Following table shows the run scored by different batsman in five ODI matches in a series. Answer given questions based on this table.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%201%20-%201%20-%20Ex%201/212.3.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;370&quot; height=&quot;140&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Run scored by batsman &#039;F&#039; in match M1 is what percentage of total run scored by batsman &#039;D&#039; in all five matches together&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;23.40%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;25.60%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;27.20%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;28.30%&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Total run scored by batsman D in all the matches is 34 + 55 + 61 + 18 + 27 = 195. Batsman F scored 53 runs in M1. So, the required percentage is 53/195 x 100 = 27.17% ~ 27.20%&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(922,10,'1','&lt;p&gt;Direction: Following table shows the run scored by different batsman in five ODI matches in a series. Answer given questions based on this table.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%201%20-%201%20-%20Ex%201/212.3.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;370&quot; height=&quot;140&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Runs scored by batsmen &#039;C&#039; in match M5 is approximately how much percentage more/less than run scored by &#039;E&#039; in match M1?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;133.30%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;233.30%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;57.14%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;42.85%&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;C scores 42 runs in M5 and E scores 98 marks in M1. So, the required percentage is [(98-42)/98] x 100% = 400/7% = 57.14%.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(923,10,'1','&lt;p&gt;Direction: Following table shows the run scored by different batsman in five ODI matches in a series. Answer given questions based on this table.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%201%20-%201%20-%20Ex%201/212.3.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;370&quot; height=&quot;140&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is percentage rise/fall in runs scored by batsman &#039;A&#039; in match M2 compare to run scored by him in match M1?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;11%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;13%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;9%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;15%&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Runs scored by A in M1 and M2 are 37 and 41 respectively. So, required percentage is [(41-37)/37] x 100% = 400/37% = 10.81%&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(924,10,'1','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the table carefully to answer the questions that follow. The table gives the total number of employees working in various organizations over the years.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%201%20-%201%20-%20Ex%201/212.4.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;471&quot; height=&quot;162&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the average number of employees working in the Organization E over the given years?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;330&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;335&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;340&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;345&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Total number of employees in organization E over the years is 195 + 264 + 318 + 374 + 396 + 430 = 1977. So, the average number of employees is 1977/6 = 329.5 or approx. 330&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(925,10,'1','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the table carefully to answer the questions that follow. The table gives the total number of employees working in various organizations over the years.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%201%20-%201%20-%20Ex%201/212.4.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;471&quot; height=&quot;162&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;The number of employees working in Organization C in the year 2012 is approximately what percent of the tot