stions that follow: The line diagram shows the cost of production and profit of six companies for the year 2011-12. (The figures are in &#039;Lakhs&#039;). Revenue = Cost of Production + Profit.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%203%20-%204%20-%20DPPS/235.13.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;482&quot; height=&quot;290&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;The profit of company C is what percentage of the revenue of company F?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;20%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;25%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;30%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;35%&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Revenue for company F = profit + cost = 19 + 6 = 25. So, the required percentage is 5/25 x 100% = 20%.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(1304,12,'4','&lt;p&gt;Direction: Study the given graph carefully and answer the questions that follow: The line diagram shows the cost of production and profit of six companies for the year 2011-12. (The figures are in &#039;Lakhs&#039;). Revenue = Cost of Production + Profit.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%203%20-%204%20-%20DPPS/235.13.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;482&quot; height=&quot;290&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;The revenue of company C is how many times of company E&#039;s profit?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5.5&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5.25&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5.75&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Revenue for company C = profit + cost = 18 + 5 = 23. So, it is 23/4 = 5.75 times the profit of E.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(1305,12,'4','&lt;p&gt;Direction: Study the given graph carefully and answer the questions that follow: The line diagram shows the cost of production and profit of six companies for the year 2011-12. (The figures are in &#039;Lakhs&#039;). Revenue = Cost of Production + Profit.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%203%20-%204%20-%20DPPS/235.13.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;482&quot; height=&quot;290&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Which company has the maximum percentage of profit?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;C&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;D&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;E&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;F&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;D has the maximum percentage which is [6/(16 + 6)] x 100 = 27.27 %.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(1306,12,'4','&lt;p&gt;Direction: Study the given graph carefully and answer the questions that follow: The line diagram shows the cost of production and profit of six companies for the year 2011-12. (The figures are in &#039;Lakhs&#039;). Revenue = Cost of Production + Profit.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%203%20-%204%20-%20DPPS/235.13.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;482&quot; height=&quot;290&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the average profit of the last five companies (B, C, D, E and F)?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 500&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 5,000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 50,000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 500,000&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;Average profit is (4 + 5 + 6 + 4 + 6)/5 x 100000 = Rs. 500,000.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(1307,12,'4','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the following graph carefully and answer the questions below it.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%203%20-%204%20-%20DPPS/235.14.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;482&quot; height=&quot;290&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the average number of students (Males and Females) passed out from all the colleges together?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;38000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;48000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;42000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;51000&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Reqd. average = (15 + 22&amp;middot;5 + 17&amp;middot;5 + 20 + 27&amp;middot;5 + 35 + 25 + 30 + 7&amp;middot;5 + 10)/5 = 42000.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(1308,12,'4','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the following graph carefully and answer the questions below it.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%203%20-%204%20-%20DPPS/235.14.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;482&quot; height=&quot;290&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;The number of females passed out from college C is approximately what per cent of the total number of females passed out from all the colleges together?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;28&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;30&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;36&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;25&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Required % = 35/115 &amp;times; 100% = 30&amp;middot;43% ~ 30% .&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(1309,12,'4','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the following graph carefully and answer the questions below it.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%203%20-%204%20-%20DPPS/235.14.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;482&quot; height=&quot;290&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the difference between the total number of students passing out from college A and the total number of students passing out from college E?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;20500&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;21000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10500&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;20000&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;Reqd. difference = (15 + 22&amp;middot;5) &amp;ndash; (7&amp;middot;5 + 10) thousand = (37&amp;middot;5 &amp;ndash; 17&amp;middot;5) thousands = 20000.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(1310,12,'4','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the following graph carefully and answer the questions below it.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%203%20-%204%20-%20DPPS/235.14.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;482&quot; height=&quot;290&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the respective ratio of the total number of males to the total number of females passed out from all the colleges together?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;19 : 23&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;18 : 25&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;23 : 19&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;25 : 18&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Reqd. ratio = (15 + 17.5 + 27.5 + 25 + 10.0)/(22.5 + 20 + 35 + 30 + 7.5) = 95 : 115 = 19 : 23.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(1311,12,'4','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the following graph carefully and answer the questions below it.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%203%20-%204%20-%20DPPS/235.14.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;482&quot; height=&quot;290&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;The number of males passing out from colleges A and B together is what per cent of the number of females passing out from colleges C and D together?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;45&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;40&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;35&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;50&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;Reqd. % = (15 + 17&amp;middot;5)/ (35 + 30) &amp;times; 100% = 32&amp;middot;5/65 &amp;times; 100% = 50%.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(1312,12,'4','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the following graph carefully and answer the questions that follow. The bar diagrams show the production of T.Vs and AC (In thousands) by 5 different brands and the line graphs show the percentage of exported T.V and AC&amp;rsquo;s.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%203%20-%204%20-%20DPPS/235.15.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Average T.V production by all the companies is&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;50000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;51600&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;53200&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;58900&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Total TV production by all the companies is 60 + 40 + 63 + 42.6 + 60.4 = 266,000. There are 5 companies. So, average TV production will be 266000/5 = 53200.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(1313,12,'4','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the following graph carefully and answer the questions that follow. The bar diagrams show the production of T.Vs and AC (In thousands) by 5 different brands and the line graphs show the percentage of exported T.V and AC&amp;rsquo;s.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%203%20-%204%20-%20DPPS/235.15.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the average number of AC&#039;s exported by Sony, Onida and Philips?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;12438&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;12408&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;12468&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;12498&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Number of AC&amp;rsquo;s exported by Sony is 25/100 x 50,000 = 12,500. Number of AC&amp;rsquo;s exported by Onida is 22/100 x 58,800 = 12,936. Number of AC&amp;rsquo;s exported by Philips is 22/100 x 54,400 = 11,968. So, total ACs exported by the 3 companies is 12500 + 12936 + 11968 = 37404. So, average required is 37404/3 = 12468.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(1314,12,'4','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the following graph carefully and answer the questions that follow. The bar diagrams show the production of T.Vs and AC (In thousands) by 5 different brands and the line graphs show the percentage of exported T.V and AC&amp;rsquo;s.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%203%20-%204%20-%20DPPS/235.15.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the respective ratio between T.Vs exported by Samsung and Onida and AC&#039;s exported by Sony and Taxla?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1225: 1677&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1243: 1677&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1677: 1225&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1677: 1243&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Number of TVs exported by Samsung and Onida are (40000 x 22/100) + (63000 x 25/100) = 8800 + 15750 = 24500. Number of ACs exported by Sony and Taxla are (50,000 x 25/100) + (52600 x 40/100) = 12500 + 21040 = 33540. So, the required ratio is 2450: 3354 = 1225: 1677&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(1315,12,'4','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the following graph carefully and answer the questions that follow. The bar diagrams show the production of T.Vs and AC (In thousands) by 5 different brands and the line graphs show the percentage of exported T.V and AC&amp;rsquo;s.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%203%20-%204%20-%20DPPS/235.15.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Total T.V produced by Sony, Samsung and Onida is how much more than T.V produced by Taxla and Philips?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;72000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;60000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;61320&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;60580&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Total TVs produced by Sony, Samsung and Onida is 60 + 40 + 63 = 163,000. Total TVs produced by Taxla and Philips is 42.6 + 60.4 = 103,000. So, the required difference is 60,000.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(1316,12,'4','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the following graph carefully and answer the questions that follow. The bar diagrams show the production of T.Vs and AC (In thousands) by 5 different brands and the line graphs show the percentage of exported T.V and AC&amp;rsquo;s.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%203%20-%204%20-%20DPPS/235.15.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;AC&#039;s exported by Taxla and Philips is approximately what per cent more/less than the TV&#039;s exported by Sony and Samsung?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;15%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;20%&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Number of ACs exported by Taxla and Philips is (40/100 x 52600) + (22/100 x 54,400) = 21040 + 11968 = 33008. Number of ACs exported by Sony and Samsung is (60,000 x 38/100) + (22/100 x 40,000) = 22800 + 8800 = 31600. So, the required percentage is [33008 &amp;ndash; 31600]/31600 x 100% = 1408/316 = 4.5% or 5% approximately.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(1317,12,'4','&lt;p&gt;Direction: Following line graph shows the ratio of imports to exports of two companies over the years.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%203%20-%204%20-%20DPPS/235.16.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;In how many of the given years were the imports more than the exports in case of company - A?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;3&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Imports will be greater than exports if the ratio is greater than 1. In the case of company A, it is more than 1 3 times. So, number of years required is 3.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(1318,12,'4','&lt;p&gt;Direction: Following line graph shows the ratio of imports to exports of two companies over the years.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%203%20-%204%20-%20DPPS/235.16.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;If the imports of company-B in year 2011 were Rs. 51.688 lakh, then what were the exports of company-B in the same year?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;64.26 lakh&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;67.54 lakh&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;71.36 lakh&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;73.84 lakh&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;The ratio of imports to exports in the year 2011 for company B is 0.7. Since imports is Rs. 51.688 lakh, the exports will be 51.688/0.7 = 73.84 lakhs.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(1319,12,'4','&lt;p&gt;Direction: Following line graph shows the ratio of imports to exports of two companies over the years.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%203%20-%204%20-%20DPPS/235.16.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;If the exports of company-A and Company-B were equal to 84 lakh in year 2014, then what will be the difference between imports of company-B and imports of company-A in that year ?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;9.6 lakh&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;8.4 lakh&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;7.2 lakh&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6.8 lakh&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;The exports of company A and company B in the year 2014 are each equal to Rs. 84 lakhs. So, imports for company A in 2014 is 84 x 1.2 = Rs. 100.8 lakhs So, imports for company B in 2014 is 84 x 1.1 = Rs. 92.4 lakhs So, the required difference is 100.8 &amp;ndash; 92.4 = Rs. 8.4 lakhs.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(1320,12,'4','&lt;p&gt;Direction: Following line graph shows the ratio of imports to exports of two companies over the years.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%203%20-%204%20-%20DPPS/235.16.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;If the exports of company-A in year 2009 and exports of company-B in year 2013 were equal, then the imports of company B in 2012 is approximately what percentage of imports of company-A in 2009?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;60%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;75%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;90%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;96%&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Let the value of the exports be I. Then, the value of imports of company A in 2009 will be 1.3I and that of B in the year 2012 will be 0.8I. So, the required percentage is 0.8/1.3 x 100% = 61.5% or approx. 60%&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(1321,12,'4','&lt;p&gt;Direction: Following line graph shows the ratio of imports to exports of two companies over the years.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%203%20-%204%20-%20DPPS/235.16.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;In year 2010, if the export of company-B is increased by 100% and import is increased by 200%. Then what will be the new ratio of import to export of company-B in that year?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;0.8&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1.2&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1.15&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1.35&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;The initial values of imports and exports will be 0.9Z and Z respectively. The final values will be 2.7Z and 2Z respectively. So, the new ratio will be 2.7/2 = 1.35&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(1322,13,'1','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Following pie-chart shows the population of six states and the table shows the ratio of males to females in each of the six states. Total Population in all the 6 states is 3 crore. Answer the questions given below based on this information.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%201%20-%20Ex%201/242.1.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;574&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%201%20-%20Ex%201/242.1.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;224&quot; height=&quot;141&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the total population of AP and Orissa taken together?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;100 lakh&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;80 lakh&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;120 lakh&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;110 lakh&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;The total percentage of people living in the two states is 26.67 + 6.67 = 33.33%. So, the total population will be 33.33 x 300/100 lakhs = 100 lakh = 1 crore.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(1323,13,'1','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Following pie-chart shows the population of six states and the table shows the ratio of males to females in each of the six states. Total Population in all the 6 states is 3 crore. Answer the questions given below based on this information.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%201%20-%20Ex%201/242.1.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;574&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%201%20-%20Ex%201/242.1.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;224&quot; height=&quot;141&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the difference between the total male population of TN and Kerala taken together and female population of Karnataka and Chhattisgarh taken together?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;11 Lakh&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10 Lakh&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;15 Lakh&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;12.5 Lakh&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Total male population of TN is 5/7 x 23.33/100 x 300 lakh = 50 lakh. Total male population of Kerala is 1/3 x 10/100 x 300 lakh = 10 lakh. Total female population of Chhattisgarh is 5/8 x 13.34/100 x 300 lakh = 25 lakh. Total female population of Karnataka is 2/5 x 20/100 x 300 lakh = 24 lakh. So, the required value is 50 + 10 &amp;ndash; 25 &amp;ndash; 24 = 11 lakhs.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(1324,13,'1','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Following pie-chart shows the population of six states and the table shows the ratio of males to females in each of the six states. Total Population in all the 6 states is 3 crore. Answer the questions given below based on this information.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%201%20-%20Ex%201/242.1.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;574&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%201%20-%20Ex%201/242.1.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;224&quot; height=&quot;141&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the average male population of all the states?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;20 lakh&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;25 Lakh&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;27.33 Lakh&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;23.33 Lakh&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Total male population in AP is 3/5 x 26.67/100 x 300 lakh = 48 lakh Total male population of TN is 5/7 x 23.33/100 x 300 lakh = 50 lakh. Total male population of Kerala is 1/3 x 10/100 x 300 lakh = 10 lakh. Total male population of Chhattisgarh is 3/8 x 13.34/100 x 300 lakh = 15 lakh. Total male population of Karnataka is 3/5 x 20/100 x 300 lakh = 36 lakh. Total male population of Orissa is 1/4 x 6.67/100 x 300 lakh = 5 lakh. So, total male population is 48 + 50 + 10 + 15 + 36 + 5 = 164 lakhs. So, the average male population is 164/6 = 27.33 lakh&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(1325,13,'1','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Following pie-chart shows the population of six states and the table shows the ratio of males to females in each of the six states. Total Population in all the 6 states is 3 crore. Answer the questions given below based on this information.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%201%20-%20Ex%201/242.1.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;574&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%201%20-%20Ex%201/242.1.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;224&quot; height=&quot;141&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Total average population of females is approximately how much percent less than total average population of female?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;17%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;15%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;16.5%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;18%&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Total male population is 164 lakh. So, the total female population is 300 &amp;ndash; 164 = 136 lakh. The average male population is 164/6 = 27.33 lakh. The average female population is 136/6 = 22.67 lakh. So, the required percentage is [27.33 &amp;ndash; 22.67]/26.67 x 100 = 17.05 %&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(1326,13,'1','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Following pie-chart shows the population of six states and the table shows the ratio of males to females in each of the six states. Total Population in all the 6 states is 3 crore. Answer the questions given below based on this information.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%201%20-%20Ex%201/242.1.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;574&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%201%20-%20Ex%201/242.1.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;224&quot; height=&quot;141&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the number of females in AP?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;35 Lakh&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;32 Lakh&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;30 Lakh&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;32.5 Lakh&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;The total female population in AP is 2/5 x 26.67/100 x 300 lakh = 2/5 x 80 = 32 lakh&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(1327,13,'1','&lt;p&gt;Directions: The following Pi &amp;ndash; chart represents the breakup of Bobby&#039;s monthly expenses. Study the graph carefully and answer the questions that follow.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%201%20-%20Ex%201/242.2.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;If Bobby spent Rs. 3000 more on others and Rent together then he spent on Food and Transport, find his monthly expense on Gym.&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 9,000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 4,500&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 6,000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 4,000&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Percentage spent on others and rent is 15 + 15 = 30%. Percentage spent on Food and transport is 8 + 12 = 20%. So, the difference between the two is 10% which is equal to Rs. 3000. So, his total monthly salary is 3000 x 100/10 = Rs. 30,000 and so, his spending on Gym is 30 x 30,000/100 = Rs. 9000.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(1328,13,'1','&lt;p&gt;Directions: The following Pi &amp;ndash; chart represents the breakup of Bobby&#039;s monthly expenses. Study the graph carefully and answer the questions that follow.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%201%20-%20Ex%201/242.2.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Find the central angle (in degrees) made by Rent, Transport and Gym together?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;216&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;205&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;180&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;195&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Total percentage of Rent, Transport and Gym is 15 + 12 + 30 = 57%. All the items together make a 360 angle at the center. So, the required angle is 360 x 57/100 = 205 degrees.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(1329,13,'1','&lt;p&gt;Directions: The following Pi &amp;ndash; chart represents the breakup of Bobby&#039;s monthly expenses. Study the graph carefully and answer the questions that follow.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%201%20-%20Ex%201/242.2.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Bobby spent 25 % of his expenditure on education, to buy some educational material which amounted to Rs. 1500. Find his expenditure on Food?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 2500&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 2400&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 3000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 3600&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;25% of education is equal to 25/100 x 20% = 5%. So, 5% of his salary is equal to Rs. 1500. So, his monthly salary is 1500 x 100/5 = Rs. 30,000 So, his expenditure on food is 8% = 30000 x 8/100 = Rs. 2400.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(1330,13,'1','&lt;p&gt;Directions: The following Pi &amp;ndash; chart represents the breakup of Bobby&#039;s monthly expenses. Study the graph carefully and answer the questions that follow.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%201%20-%20Ex%201/242.2.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;As price dropped, Bobby&#039;s expenditure on Food, dropped by 10%. As a result of this, expenditure on others increased from Rs. 12,000 to Rs. 12,640. So the current expense on Food is approximately what percentage of current expenses on others, if we assume that all other expenses remain the same?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;25%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;36%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;40%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;45%&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;According to the question, 10% drop in food which is 8% is Rs. 640. So, z x 10/100 x 8/100 = 640 =&amp;gt; z = Rs. 80,000 where z is the total expenses per month. So, the present expenditure on food is 9/10 x 8% = 7.2% and that on others is 12640 x 100/80000 = 15.8% So, the required percentage is 7.2/15.8 x 100 = 45.6% ~ 45%.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(1331,13,'1','&lt;p&gt;Directions: The following Pi &amp;ndash; chart represents the breakup of Bobby&#039;s monthly expenses. Study the graph carefully and answer the questions that follow.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%201%20-%20Ex%201/242.2.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;If Bobby increased his savings, which is currently 15 % of his income, by 20 % and reduced his expenses by 10 %, then his savings would be what percent of his expenses?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;23.5%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;21.5%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;22.5%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;25.5%&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;If his salary is Rs. 100, then his savings will be Rs. 15 and expenses will be Rs. 85. His savings increase by 20% and expenses reduce by 10%. So, his savings become 15 x 120/100 =Rs. 18 and expenses will be 85 x 9/10 = Rs. 76.5 So, the required percentage is 18/76.5 x 100 = 23.5%&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(1332,13,'1','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the following Charts carefully and answer the questions given below.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%201%20-%20Ex%201/242.3.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%201%20-%20Ex%201/242.3.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Female Lecturers are approximately what percent of the Female Professors in the university?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;168%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;146%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;73%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;60%&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Total number of female professors is 14/100 x 35/100 x 2000 = 98. Total number of female lecturers is 15/100 x 55/100 x 2000 = 165. So, the required percentage is 165/98 x 100% = 168.36%&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(1333,13,'1','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the following Charts carefully and answer the questions given below.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%201%20-%20Ex%201/242.3.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%201%20-%20Ex%201/242.3.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is respective ratio of the total number of Female Assistant Professors and Associate Professors to the total number of Male Senior Lecturers and Teaching Assistants in the university?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;36 : 31&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;31 : 36&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4 : 5&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5 : 4&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Total number of female assistant professors is 16/100 x 60/100 x 2000 = 192. Total number of female associate professors is 17/100 x 40/100 x 2000 = 136. So, total number of females is 192 + 168 = 360. Total number of male senior lecturers is 18/100 x 25/100 x 2000 = 90. Total number of male teaching assistants is 20/100 x 55/100 x 2000 = 220. So, total number of females is 90 + 220 = 310. So, the ratio required is 36: 31.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(1334,13,'1','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the following Charts carefully and answer the questions given below.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%201%20-%20Ex%201/242.3.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%201%20-%20Ex%201/242.3.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;The total number of male Associate professors are approximately what per cent of the total number of teachers in the university?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6.4%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;7.2%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;8%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5.6%&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Percentage of male associate professors in the university is 40/100 x 16 = 6.4%.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(1335,13,'1','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the following Charts carefully and answer the questions given below.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%201%20-%20Ex%201/242.3.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%201%20-%20Ex%201/242.3.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the respective ratio of the number of Male professors to the number of Male lecturers in the university?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;182 : 135&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;182 : 165&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;98 : 135&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;98 : 165&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;Number of male professors in the university is 14/100 x 65/100 x 2000 = 182. Number of male lecturers in the university is 15/100 x 45/100 x 2000 = 135. So, the required ratio is 182: 135.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(1336,13,'1','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the following Charts carefully and answer the questions given below.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%201%20-%20Ex%201/242.3.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%201%20-%20Ex%201/242.3.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the difference between the number of Female senior lecturers and the number of Male professors?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;88&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;78&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;82&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;82&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Number of male professors in the university is 14/100 x 65/100 x 2000 = 182. Number of female senior lecturers in the university is 18/100 x 75/100 x 2000 = 270. So, the required difference is 270 &amp;ndash; 182 = 88.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(1337,13,'1','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the following pie-charts carefully to answer the questions that follow. The pie diagram shows the distribution of students from different states in a college and the table gives the ratio of boys and girls belonging to a particular state in the college.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%201%20-%20Ex%201/242.4.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%201%20-%20Ex%201/242.4.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;224&quot; height=&quot;120&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the total number of boys from states A and E together?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1320&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1280&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1240&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1200&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Number of boys from the state A is 8/13 x 26/100 x 4000 = 16 x 40 = 640. Number of boys from the state E is 2/3 x 27/100 x 4000 = 18 x 40 = 720. So, the total number of boys required is 640 + 720 = 1360.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(1338,13,'1','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the following pie-charts carefully to answer the questions that follow. The pie diagram shows the distribution of students from different states in a college and the table gives the ratio of boys and girls belonging to a particular state in the college.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%201%20-%20Ex%201/242.4.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%201%20-%20Ex%201/242.4.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;224&quot; height=&quot;120&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Girls from state C is what percent less than the Boys of State B?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;20%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;22.72%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;23.33%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;24.72%&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Total number of girls form state C is 17/30 x 15/100 x 4000 = 8.5 x 40 = 340. Total number of boys from state B is 11/18 x 18/100 x 4000 = 11 x 40 = 440. So, the required percentage is [11 &amp;ndash; 8.5]/11 x 100% = 2.5/11 x 100% = 22.72%&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(1339,13,'1','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the following pie-charts carefully to answer the questions that follow. The pie diagram shows the distribution of students from different states in a college and the table gives the ratio of boys and girls belonging to a particular state in the college.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%201%20-%20Ex%201/242.4.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%201%20-%20Ex%201/242.4.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;224&quot; height=&quot;120&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the difference between the total number of boys and total number of girls in the college?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;480&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;470&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;520&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;510&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Number of boys from state A is 8/13 x 26/100 x 4000 = 16 x 40 = 640. Number of boys from state B is 11/18 x 18/100 x 4000 = 11 x 40 = 440. Number of boys from state C is 13/30 x 15/100 x 4000 = 6.5 x 40 = 260. Number of boys from state D is 5/14 x 14/100 x 4000 = 5 x 40 = 200. Number of boys from the state E is 2/3 x 27/100 x 4000 = 18 x 40 = 720. So, total number of boys is 640 + 440 + 260 + 200 + 720 = 2260. So, the total number of girls will be 4000 &amp;ndash; 2260 = 1740. So, the required difference is 2260 &amp;ndash; 1740 = 520.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(1340,13,'1','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the following pie-charts carefully to answer the questions that follow. The pie diagram shows the distribution of students from different states in a college and the table gives the ratio of boys and girls belonging to a particular state in the college.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%201%20-%20Ex%201/242.4.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%201%20-%20Ex%201/242.4.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;224&quot; height=&quot;120&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the total number of students from the states C and D together?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1160&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1120&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1200&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1080&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Total percentage of students from the two states is 15 + 14 = 29%. So, the required number of students is 29/100 x 4000 = 29 x 40 = 1160.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(1341,13,'1','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the following pie-charts carefully to answer the questions that follow. The pie diagram shows the distribution of students from different states in a college and the table gives the ratio of boys and girls belonging to a particular state in the college.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%201%20-%20Ex%201/242.4.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%201%20-%20Ex%201/242.4.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;224&quot; height=&quot;120&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the average of total students from state A and boys from state D?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;620&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;640&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;630&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;610&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Total students from state A is 26/100 x 4000 = 26 x 40 = 1040. Total number of boys form state D is 5/14 x 14/100 x 4000 = 5 x 40 = 200. So, the required average is [1040 + 200]/2 = 1240/2 = 620. * Here there are only two groups. So, in order to find the average, we divide by 2.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(1342,13,'2','&lt;p&gt;Direction: Read the following Pi chart carefully and answer the questions that follows.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%202%20-%20Ex2/243.1.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;602&quot; height=&quot;314&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Percentage distribution of the number of items sold by the shopkeepers during seven months.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%202%20-%20Ex2/243.1.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;301&quot; height=&quot;263&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the ratio of the number of items sold by company A in December to those sold in November by the company C?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2 : 3&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;7 : 8&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;18 : 7&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;3 : 2&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Number of items sold by company A in December is 9/100 x 2/9 x 25 lakh = 50,000. Number of items sold by company C in November is 10/100 x 3/10 x 25 lakh = 75,000. So, the ratio required is 2: 3.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(1343,13,'2','&lt;p&gt;Direction: Read the following Pi chart carefully and answer the questions that follows.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%202%20-%20Ex2/243.1.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;602&quot; height=&quot;314&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Percentage distribution of the number of items sold by the shopkeepers during seven months.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%202%20-%20Ex2/243.1.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;301&quot; height=&quot;263&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;If 75% of the items sold by company B in September are at discount rate, how many Items sold without discount?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;31250&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;62500&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;125000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;25000&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Total number of items sold by company B in September is 5/16 x 16/100 x 25 lakh = 125,000. 75% items are sold on discount. So, number of items not sold on discount is 25/100 x 125000 = 31,250.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(1344,13,'2','&lt;p&gt;Direction: Read the following Pi chart carefully and answer the questions that follows.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%202%20-%20Ex2/243.1.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;602&quot; height=&quot;314&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Percentage distribution of the number of items sold by the shopkeepers during seven months.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%202%20-%20Ex2/243.1.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;301&quot; height=&quot;263&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the total number of Items sold by all companies in August and January together in lakhs?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6.75&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;7.75&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;8.75&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6.5&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;The percentage of items sold in August and January together is 15 + 20 = 35%. So, number of items is 35/100 x 25 lakhs = 8.75 lakhs.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(1345,13,'2','&lt;p&gt;Direction: Read the following Pi chart carefully and answer the questions that follows.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%202%20-%20Ex2/243.1.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;602&quot; height=&quot;314&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Percentage distribution of the number of items sold by the shopkeepers during seven months.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%202%20-%20Ex2/243.1.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;301&quot; height=&quot;263&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the respective ratio of Items sold by company A and company B in September together sold by company B and C in November together?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;9 : 5&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5 : 9&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;8 : 5&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5 : 8&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Number of items sold by A and B together in September is 9/16 x 16/100 x 25 lakh = 225,000. Number of items sold by C and B together in November is 5/10 x 10/100 x 25 lakh = 125,000. So, the ratio required is 225: 125 = 9: 5.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(1346,13,'2','&lt;p&gt;Direction: Read the following Pi chart carefully and answer the questions that follows.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%202%20-%20Ex2/243.1.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;602&quot; height=&quot;314&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Percentage distribution of the number of items sold by the shopkeepers during seven months.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%202%20-%20Ex2/243.1.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;301&quot; height=&quot;263&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is number of total Items sold by company A in August, company B in October and company C in December together in thousands?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;475&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;575&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;675&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;375&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Total number of items sold by company A in August is 7/15 x 15/100 x 25 lakh = 175,000. Total number of items sold by company B in October is 8/16 x 24/100 x 25 lakh = 300,000. Total number of items sold by company C in December is 4/9 x 9/100 x 25 lakh = 100,000. So, the total amount of sales is 175 + 300 + 100 = 575,000.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(1347,13,'2','&lt;p&gt;Directions: The following pie-chart shows the distribution of the number of computers of different models produced by a Company in 2010 and 2014.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%202%20-%20Ex2/243.2.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;602&quot; height=&quot;314&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%202%20-%20Ex2/243.2.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;602&quot; height=&quot;314&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the difference in the central angle (in degrees) made by computers of Model D, E and F in the year 2010 and 2014?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;7.2&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5.4&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;3.6&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;10.8&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Percentage of models D, E, F in 2010 is 11 + 13 + 16 = 40%. Percentage of models D, E, F in 2014 is 11 + 14 + 13 = 38%. So, the difference in percentages is 40 &amp;ndash; 38 = 2% So, the difference in central angle will be 2 x 360/100 = 7.2 degrees&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(1348,13,'2','&lt;p&gt;Directions: The following pie-chart shows the distribution of the number of computers of different models produced by a Company in 2010 and 2014.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%202%20-%20Ex2/243.2.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;602&quot; height=&quot;314&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%202%20-%20Ex2/243.2.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;602&quot; height=&quot;314&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the percentage increase in the number of Model F computers produced by the company from 2010 to year 2014?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;187%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;146%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;173%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;150%&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Number of model F computers produced in 2010 is 24000 x 13/100 = 13 x 240 = 3120. Number of model F computers produced in 2014 is 56000 x 16/100 = 16 x 560 = 8960. So, the required percentage increase is [8960 &amp;ndash; 3120]/3120 x 100% = 5840/3120 x 100% = 187.17%&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(1349,13,'2','&lt;p&gt;Directions: The following pie-chart shows the distribution of the number of computers of different models produced by a Company in 2010 and 2014.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%202%20-%20Ex2/243.2.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;602&quot; height=&quot;314&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%202%20-%20Ex2/243.2.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;602&quot; height=&quot;314&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the ratio of the number of computers of model H in the year 2010 to the number of computers of model G in the year 2014?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2 : 7&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2 : 3&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;3 : 8&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;3 : 2&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Number of model H computers produced in 2010 is 24000 x 10/100 = 10 x 240 = 2400. Number of model G computers produced in 2014 is 56000 x 15/100 = 15 x 560 = 8400. The required ratio is 24: 84 = 2: 7.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(1350,13,'2','&lt;p&gt;Directions: The following pie-chart shows the distribution of the number of computers of different models produced by a Company in 2010 and 2014.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%202%20-%20Ex2/243.2.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;602&quot; height=&quot;314&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%202%20-%20Ex2/243.2.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;602&quot; height=&quot;314&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;The number of computers of Model D in the year 2014 is what percentage of the number of Model C computers in the year 2010?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;150%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;130%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;140%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;160%&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;Number of model C computers produced in 2010 is 24000 x 17/100 = 17 x 240 = 4080. Number of model D computers produced in 2014 is 56000 x 11/100 = 11 x 560 = 6160. So, the required percentage is 6160/4080 x 100% = 160% approximately.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(1351,13,'2','&lt;p&gt;Directions: The following pie-chart shows the distribution of the number of computers of different models produced by a Company in 2010 and 2014.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%202%20-%20Ex2/243.2.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;602&quot; height=&quot;314&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%202%20-%20Ex2/243.2.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;602&quot; height=&quot;314&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;The number of computers of Model B in the year 2014 is how much more than the number of same-model computers in 2010? (Approximate value)&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2160&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2250&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2130&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2150&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Number of computers of model B in 2010 is 12/100 x 24000 = 240 x 12 = 2880. Number of computers of model B in 2014 is 9/100 x 56000 = 560 x 9 = 5040. So, the required difference is 5040 &amp;ndash; 2880 = 2160.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(1352,13,'2','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the following Pie&amp;ndash;chart carefully and answer the following questions. The Pie chart shows the percentage distribution of total population among different cities in a state.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%202%20-%20Ex2/243.3.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;577&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%202%20-%20Ex2/243.3.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;333&quot; height=&quot;198&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the total population from city C, F and H?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1.26 million&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1.24 million&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1.16 million&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1.22 million&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;C, F and H occupy a percentage of 14 + 11 + 17 = 42%. So, the total population of these cities is 42/100 x 3 million = 1.26 million.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(1353,13,'2','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the following Pie&amp;ndash;chart carefully and answer the following questions. The Pie chart shows the percentage distribution of total population among different cities in a state.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%202%20-%20Ex2/243.3.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;577&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%202%20-%20Ex2/243.3.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;333&quot; height=&quot;198&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the total number of male population in city A, D, G in lakhs?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4.9&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5.1&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5.2&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Male population in city A is 5/8 x 16/100 x 3 million = 3 Lakhs. Male population in city D is 1/4 x 8/100 x 3 million = 0.6 Lakhs. Male population in city G is 5/13 x 13/100 x 3 million = 1.5 Lakhs. So, total male population required is 3 + 0.6 + 1.5 = 5.1 lakhs.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(1354,13,'2','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the following Pie&amp;ndash;chart carefully and answer the following questions. The Pie chart shows the percentage distribution of total population among different cities in a state.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%202%20-%20Ex2/243.3.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;577&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%202%20-%20Ex2/243.3.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;333&quot; height=&quot;198&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the ratio of male population in city B to female population in city E?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;27 : 20&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;20 : 27&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2 : 3&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;3 : 2&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Male population in city B is 3/5 x 9/100 x 3 million = 1.62 Lakhs. Female population in city E is 1/3 x 12/100 x 3 million = 1.2 Lakhs. So, the required ratio is 1.62: 1.2 = 162: 120 = 27: 20.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(1355,13,'2','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the following Pie&amp;ndash;chart carefully and answer the following questions. The Pie chart shows the percentage distribution of total population among different cities in a state.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%202%20-%20Ex2/243.3.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;577&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%202%20-%20Ex2/243.3.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;333&quot; height=&quot;198&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the total number of female population in city F, G and H in lakhs?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;7.2&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;7.5&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;7.4&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;7&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Female population in city F is 6/11 x 11/100 x 3 million = 1.8 Lakhs. Female population in city G is 8/13 x 13/100 x 3 million = 2.4 Lakhs. Female population in city H is 10/17 x 17/100 x 3 million = 3 Lakhs. So, total male population required is 3 + 1.8 + 2.4 = 7.2 lakhs.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(1356,13,'2','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the following Pie&amp;ndash;chart carefully and answer the following questions. The Pie chart shows the percentage distribution of total population among different cities in a state.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%202%20-%20Ex2/243.3.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;577&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%202%20-%20Ex2/243.3.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;333&quot; height=&quot;198&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;The number of male population in city D, E and F is what percent of total number of population in these three cities?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;48&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;52&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;44&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;46&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;The cities D, E, F comprise of 8 + 12 + 11 = 31% of the total population. So, the total population of D, E, F is 31/100 x 3 million = 9.3 lakhs. Male population in city D is 1/4 x 8/100 x 3 million = 0.6 Lakhs. Male population in city E is 2/3 x 12/100 x 3 million = 2.4 Lakhs. Male population in city F is 5/6 x 11/100 x 3 million = 1.5 Lakhs. So, total male population in these cities is 0.6 + 2.4 + 1.5 = 4.5 lakhs. So, the required percentage is 4.5/9.3 x 100% = 48.38%&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(1357,13,'2','&lt;p&gt;Direction: Study the following information to answer the given questions: Percentage of students in various courses of Engineering like Electronics, IT, CSE, Mechanical, Mining and Civil Engineering.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%202%20-%20Ex2/243.4.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;602&quot; height=&quot;314&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%202%20-%20Ex2/243.4.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;602&quot; height=&quot;314&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;How many girls are there in the courses PCB and MEC together?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;600&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;550&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;500&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;575&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Total number of girls in PCB is 10/100 x 2500 = 250. Total number of girls in MEC is 14/100 x 2500 = 350. So, the total number of girls required is 250 + 350 = 600.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(1358,13,'2','&lt;p&gt;Direction: Study the following information to answer the given questions: Percentage of students in various courses of Engineering like Electronics, IT, CSE, Mechanical, Mining and Civil Engineering.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%202%20-%20Ex2/243.4.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;602&quot; height=&quot;314&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%202%20-%20Ex2/243.4.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;602&quot; height=&quot;314&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;For which pair of courses is the number of boys highest?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;PCMB&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;PCM&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;MEC&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;HEC&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Number of boys in PCM is (20/100 x 4000) &amp;ndash; (24/100 x 2500) = 800 &amp;ndash; 600 = 200. Number of boys in PCB is (10/100 x 4000) &amp;ndash; (10/100 x 2500) = 400 &amp;ndash; 250 = 150. Number of boys in MEC is (16/100 x 4000) &amp;ndash; (14/100 x 2500) = 640 &amp;ndash; 350 = 290. Number of boys in CEC is (14/100 x 4000) &amp;ndash; (15/100 x 2500) = 560 &amp;ndash; 375 = 185. Number of boys in HEC is (18/100 x 4000) &amp;ndash; (17/100 x 2500) = 720 &amp;ndash; 425 = 295. Number of boys in PCMB is (22/100 x 4000) &amp;ndash; (20/100 x 2500) = 880 &amp;ndash; 500 = 380. So, the highest number of boys are in PEMB&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(1359,13,'2','&lt;p&gt;Direction: Study the following information to answer the given questions: Percentage of students in various courses of Engineering like Electronics, IT, CSE, Mechanical, Mining and Civil Engineering.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%202%20-%20Ex2/243.4.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;602&quot; height=&quot;314&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%202%20-%20Ex2/243.4.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;602&quot; height=&quot;314&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;In how many courses is the number of girls more than 400?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;3&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Number of girls in PCM is (24/100 x 2500) = 600 Number of girls in PCB is (10/100 x 2500) = 250. Number of girls in MEC is (14/100 x 2500) = 350. Number of girls in CEC is (15/100 x 2500) = 375. Number of girls in HEC is (17/100 x 2500) = 425. Number of girls in PCMB is (20/100 x 2500) = 500. So, the number of girls is more than 400 in 3 courses.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(1360,13,'2','&lt;p&gt;Direction: Study the following information to answer the given questions: Percentage of students in various courses of Engineering like Electronics, IT, CSE, Mechanical, Mining and Civil Engineering.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%202%20-%20Ex2/243.4.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;602&quot; height=&quot;314&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%202%20-%20Ex2/243.4.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;602&quot; height=&quot;314&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the ratio of the number of boys in MEC to the number of girls in HEC?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;58 : 85&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;85 : 58&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;12 : 17&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;17 : 12&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Number of boys in MEC is (16/100 x 4000) &amp;ndash; (14/100 x 2500) = 640 &amp;ndash; 350 = 290. Number of boys in HEC is (17/100 x 2500) = 425. So, the required ratio is 58: 85.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(1361,13,'2','&lt;p&gt;Direction: Study the following information to answer the given questions: Percentage of students in various courses of Engineering like Electronics, IT, CSE, Mechanical, Mining and Civil Engineering.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%202%20-%20Ex2/243.4.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;602&quot; height=&quot;314&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%202%20-%20Ex2/243.4.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;602&quot; height=&quot;314&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the total number of students in PCM and PCMB together?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1680&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1640&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1560&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1720&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Total percentage of students in PCM and PCMB is 20 + 22 = 42%. So, the total number of students required is 42/100 x 4000 = 1680.&lt;/p&gt;','Medium'),(1362,13,'3','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Five different companies A, B, C, D and E make two products I and II. The total number of products produced by these five companies is 80 thousand. The cost of production of each product is Rs. 4000. The percentage distribution of the total production by these companies is given in the following pie-chart and the table shows the ratio of production of Product I to that of Product II and the percentage profit earned by these companies on each of these products.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%203%20-%20Ex%203/244.1.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;617&quot; height=&quot;321&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%203%20-%20Ex%203/244.1.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;541&quot; height=&quot;140&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the total profit earned by Company B on Product II?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs 77.6 lakhs&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs 72.4 lakhs&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs 76.8 lakhs&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs 74.4 lakhs&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Total number of products produced by company B is 54/360 x 80,000 = 12,000. Out of them, number of product II that are produced is 4/5 x 12,000 = 9,600. Since the cost of production is Rs. 4000 and the profit percentage is 20% on each item, profit on each item produced is 20/100 x 4000 = Rs. 800. So, total profit earned on the product is 800 x 9600 = Rs. 76.8 lakhs.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(1363,13,'3','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Five different companies A, B, C, D and E make two products I and II. The total number of products produced by these five companies is 80 thousand. The cost of production of each product is Rs. 4000. The percentage distribution of the total production by these companies is given in the following pie-chart and the table shows the ratio of production of Product I to that of Product II and the percentage profit earned by these companies on each of these products.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%203%20-%20Ex%203/244.1.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;617&quot; height=&quot;321&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%203%20-%20Ex%203/244.1.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;541&quot; height=&quot;140&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the total cost of production of Product I by companies A and B together?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 15.6 crore&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 17.28 crore&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 17.84 crore&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 16.24 crore&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Total number of product I that is produced by company A is 72/360 x 2/5 x 80,000 = 6400. Total number of product I that is produced by company B is 54/360 x 1/5 x 80,000 = 2400. Total number of product I that is produced by company C is 90/360 x 3/5 x 80,000 = 12000. Total number of product I that is produced by company D is 36/360 x 2/5 x 80,000 = 3200. Total number of product I that is produced by company E is 108/360 x 4/5 x 80,000 = 19200. So, total number of products manufactured is 6400 + 2400 + 12000 + 3200 + 19200 = 43,200. So, total cost of manufacture is 4000 x 43200 = Rs. 17.28 crore.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(1364,13,'3','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Five different companies A, B, C, D and E make two products I and II. The total number of products produced by these five companies is 80 thousand. The cost of production of each product is Rs. 4000. The percentage distribution of the total production by these companies is given in the following pie-chart and the table shows the ratio of production of Product I to that of Product II and the percentage profit earned by these companies on each of these products.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%203%20-%20Ex%203/244.1.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;617&quot; height=&quot;321&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%203%20-%20Ex%203/244.1.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;541&quot; height=&quot;140&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the total of the profit earned by Company E on production of Product I and the profit of Company C on production of Product II?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs 1.75 crore&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs 2.15 crore&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs 2 crore&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs 2.1 crore&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Total number of product I that are produced by company E is 4/5 x 108/360 x 80,000 = 19,200. Since the cost of production is Rs. 4000 and the profit percentage is 20% on each item, total profit on all the items produced is 20/100 x 4000 x 19200 = Rs. 153.6 lakh. Total number of product II that are produced by company C is 2/5 x 90/360 x 80,000 = 8,000. Since the cost of production is Rs. 4000 and the profit percentage is 15% on each item, total profit on all the items produced is 15/100 x 4000 x 8000 = Rs. 48 lakh. So, the total profit is 153.6 + 48 = Rs. 201.6 lakh ~ Rs. 2 crore.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(1365,13,'3','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Five different companies A, B, C, D and E make two products I and II. The total number of products produced by these five companies is 80 thousand. The cost of production of each product is Rs. 4000. The percentage distribution of the total production by these companies is given in the following pie-chart and the table shows the ratio of production of Product I to that of Product II and the percentage profit earned by these companies on each of these products.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%203%20-%20Ex%203/244.1.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;617&quot; height=&quot;321&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%203%20-%20Ex%203/244.1.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;541&quot; height=&quot;140&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the ratio of the cost of production of Product I by Company D to the cost of production of Product II by Company B?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5 : 18&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;7 : 18&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1 : 3&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1 : 2&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Since the cost of production is the same for all the products, the required ratio is the same as the ratio of the number of items produced. Number of items of product I by company D is 2/5 x 36/360 x 80,000 = 3200. Number of items of product II by company B is 4/5 x 54/360 x 80,000 = 9600. So, required ratio is 1: 3.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(1366,13,'3','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Five different companies A, B, C, D and E make two products I and II. The total number of products produced by these five companies is 80 thousand. The cost of production of each product is Rs. 4000. The percentage distribution of the total production by these companies is given in the following pie-chart and the table shows the ratio of production of Product I to that of Product II and the percentage profit earned by these companies on each of these products.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%203%20-%20Ex%203/244.1.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;617&quot; height=&quot;321&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%203%20-%20Ex%203/244.1.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;541&quot; height=&quot;140&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;The total cost of production for Company E is what per cent of the total cost of production for Company C?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;150%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;120%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;80%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;75%&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Since the cost of production is the same for all the products, the required ratio is the same as the ratio of the number of items produced. So, the ratio of products produces is 108: 90 = 6: 5. So, the required percentage is 6/5 x 100% = 120%.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(1367,13,'3','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the following Pie charts carefully and answer the questions given below.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%203%20-%20Ex%203/244.2.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%203%20-%20Ex%203/244.2.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%203%20-%20Ex%203/244.2.3.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the total expenditure of C on Electronic and Social Media?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;32 Lakh&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;34.5 Lakh&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;33.5 Lakh&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;30 Lakh&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Total percentage of expenditure for party C on electronic and print media is 9 + 14 = 23%. The total expenditure for party C is 15/100 x 800 lakh = Rs. 120 lakh. So, the required expenditure is 23/100 x 150 = Rs. 34.5 lakhs.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(1368,13,'3','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the following Pie charts carefully and answer the questions given below.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%203%20-%20Ex%203/244.2.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%203%20-%20Ex%203/244.2.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%203%20-%20Ex%203/244.2.3.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the ratio of expenditure on Travelling for F to that of B on Electronic Media?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;143: 168&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;134: 186&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;168: 143&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;134: 168&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Total expenditure on travel for party F is 13/100 x 11/100 x 800 lakh = Rs. 11.44 lakh. Total expenditure on Electronic media for party B is 14/100 x 12/100 x 800 lakh = Rs. 13.44 lakh. So, the required ratio is 11.44: 13.44 = 286: 336 = 143: 168.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(1369,13,'3','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the following Pie charts carefully and answer the questions given below.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%203%20-%20Ex%203/244.2.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%203%20-%20Ex%203/244.2.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%203%20-%20Ex%203/244.2.3.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the average expenditure (in Rs. Lakh) of party A on Food, Advertising and Rallies?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;16.426&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;16.423&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;16.42&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;16.4&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;The total percentage of expenditure required for party A is 15 + 16 + 13 = 44%. So, the total expenditure for party A will be 44/100 x 14/100 x 800 lakh = Rs. 49.28 lakh. So, the average spending required will be 49.28/3 = 16. 4267 lakhs.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(1370,13,'3','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the following Pie charts carefully and answer the questions given below.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%203%20-%20Ex%203/244.2.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%203%20-%20Ex%203/244.2.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%203%20-%20Ex%203/244.2.3.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;The total expenditure of party D on Social Media and Advertising is what percent more or less than the total expenditure of party G on Food and Hoardings?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;46.52%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;49.21%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;44.36%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;48.35%&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;The total percentage of expenditure required for party D is 12 + 16 = 28%. So, total expenditure for party D is 28/100 x 17/100 x 800 = Rs. 38.08 lakh The total percentage of expenditure required for party G is 17 + 12 = 29%. So, total expenditure for party G is 29/100 x 11/100 x 800 = Rs. 25.52 lakh So, the required percentage is [38.08 &amp;ndash; 25.52]/25.52 x 100% = 12.56/25.52 x 100% = 49.21%.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(1371,13,'3','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the following Pie charts carefully and answer the questions given below.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%203%20-%20Ex%203/244.2.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%203%20-%20Ex%203/244.2.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%203%20-%20Ex%203/244.2.3.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the difference between the expenditure of party C on Food to that of party F on print media?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;968000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;977000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;986000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;954000&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Expenditure of party C on Food is 15/100 x 15/100 x 800 lakh = Rs. 18 lakh. Expenditure of party F on Print Media is 8/100 x 13/100 x 800 lakh = Rs. 8.32 lakh. So, the required difference is 18 &amp;ndash; 8.32 = Rs. 9.68 lakh.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(1372,13,'3','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the following information carefully and answer the questions given below. The total number of newspaper readers from six different cities is 80 thousand. Following pie-chart shows the percentage distribution of readers among these cities and the table gives the ratio of male to female readers and the ratio of Hindi to English newspaper readers.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%203%20-%20Ex%203/244.3.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;616&quot; height=&quot;322&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%203%20-%20Ex%203/244.3.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;378&quot; height=&quot;140&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the average number of Hindi newspaper readers from all the six cities together?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6400&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;7200&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;8000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5600&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Number of Hindi newspaper readers from city A is 2/3 x 18/100 x 80,000 = 9600.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Number of Hindi newspaper readers from city B is 1/4 x 20/100 x 80,000 = 4000.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Number of Hindi newspaper readers from city C is 4/11 x 22/100 x 80,000 = 6400.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Number of Hindi newspaper readers from city D is 2/5 x 10/100 x 80,000 = 3200.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Number of Hindi newspaper readers from city E is 5/7 x 14/100 x 80,000 = 8000.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Number of Hindi newspaper readers from city F is 9/16 x 16/100 x 80,000 = 7200.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Number of Hindi newspaper readers from all the cities is 9600 + 4000 + 6400 + 3200 + 8000 + 7200 = 38400.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Average number of Hindi newspaper readers from all the cities is 38400/6 = 6400.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(1373,13,'3','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the following information carefully and answer the questions given below. The total number of newspaper readers from six different cities is 80 thousand. Following pie-chart shows the percentage distribution of readers among these cities and the table gives the ratio of male to female readers and the ratio of Hindi to English newspaper readers.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%203%20-%20Ex%203/244.3.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;616&quot; height=&quot;322&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%203%20-%20Ex%203/244.3.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;378&quot; height=&quot;140&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the total number of males from City F who read English newspapers&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5400&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5600&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5000&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Data insufficient&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Total number of newspaper readers in city F is 16/100 x 80,000 = 16 x 800 = 12800. The required number of males from city F who read English newspapers is 3/4 x 9/16 x 12800 = 5400.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(1374,13,'3','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the following information carefully and answer the questions given below. The total number of newspaper readers from six different cities is 80 thousand. Following pie-chart shows the percentage distribution of readers among these cities and the table gives the ratio of male to female readers and the ratio of Hindi to English newspaper readers.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%203%20-%20Ex%203/244.3.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;616&quot; height=&quot;322&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%203%20-%20Ex%203/244.3.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;378&quot; height=&quot;140&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;The total number of male readers from City C who read Hindi newspapers is what percentage of the total number of female readers from City A who read English newspapers?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;150%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;163.5%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;175%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;135.5%&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Total number of newspaper readers in city C is 22/100 x 80,000 = 22 x 800 = 17600.&lt;br /&gt;The required number of males from city C who read Hindi newspapers is 6/11 x 4/11 x 12800 = 3491.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Total number of newspaper readers in city A is 18/100 x 80,000 = 18 x 800 = 14400.&lt;br /&gt;The required number of females from city A who read English newspapers is 4/9 x 1/3 x 14400 = 2134.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;So, the required percentage is 3491/2134 x 100% = 163.5%.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(1375,13,'3','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the following information carefully and answer the questions given below. The total number of newspaper readers from six different cities is 80 thousand. Following pie-chart shows the percentage distribution of readers among these cities and the table gives the ratio of male to female readers and the ratio of Hindi to English newspaper readers.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%203%20-%20Ex%203/244.3.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;616&quot; height=&quot;322&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%203%20-%20Ex%203/244.3.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;378&quot; height=&quot;140&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the ratio of the total number of female readers from City C to the total number of Hindi newspaper readers from City D?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;3 : 4&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5 : 2&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2 : 5&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4 : 3&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Total number of female readers from city C is 22/100 x 5/11 x 80,000 = 10 x 800 = 8,000. Total number of Hindi newspaper readers from city D is 10/100 x 2/5 x 80,000 = 4 x 800 = 3,200. So, the required ratio is 8000: 3200 = 5: 2.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(1376,13,'3','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the following information carefully and answer the questions given below. The total number of newspaper readers from six different cities is 80 thousand. Following pie-chart shows the percentage distribution of readers among these cities and the table gives the ratio of male to female readers and the ratio of Hindi to English newspaper readers.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%203%20-%20Ex%203/244.3.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;616&quot; height=&quot;322&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%203%20-%20Ex%203/244.3.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;378&quot; height=&quot;140&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;The total number of English newspaper readers from cities A, E, F together is what percentage of the total number of newspaper readers (both Hindi and English) from City B?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;95%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;85%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;100%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;115%&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Total number of newspaper readers from city B is 20/100 x 80,000 = 16,000. Total number of English newspaper readers from city A is 18/100 x 1/3 x 80,000 = 4800. Total number of English newspaper readers from city E is 14/100 x 2/7 x 80,000 = 3200. Total number of English newspaper readers from city F is 16/100 x 9/16 x 80,000 = 7200. So, total number of English newspaper readers from these cities is 4800 + 3200 + 7200 = 15200. So, the required percentage is 15200/16000 x 100% = 95%.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(1377,13,'3','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the following Pi&amp;ndash;charts and answer questions that follow.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%203%20-%20Ex%203/244.4.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%203%20-%20Ex%203/244.4.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;If the total global production of asbestos is 3.6 lakh metric tons, find the production of asbestos in Warangal?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5400 metric tons&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;3600 metric tons&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;7200 metric tons&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;9000 metric tons&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Total global production is 3.6 lakh tons. So, production in India will be 20/00 x 3.6 lakh = 72000 tons. So, production in Andhra Pradesh will be 30/100 x 72000 = 21600 tons. So, production in Warangal will be 25/100 x 21600 = 5400 tons.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(1378,13,'3','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the following Pi&amp;ndash;charts and answer questions that follow.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%203%20-%20Ex%203/244.4.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%203%20-%20Ex%203/244.4.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Tirumala produces what percent of asbestos from the asbestos produced globally?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;0.6%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1.2%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1.5%&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;0.9%&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;If the total production of asbestos is 100, then 20% out of it or 20 will be produced in India. 30% of the 20, which is 6 will be produced in Andhra Pradesh. So, the amount produced by Tirumala is 10% of 6, or 0.6. So, the percentage required is 0.6%.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(1379,13,'3','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the following Pi&amp;ndash;charts and answer questions that follow.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%203%20-%20Ex%203/244.4.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%203%20-%20Ex%203/244.4.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;If China produced 400,000 metric tons asbestos, find the asbestos produced by Vishakhapatnam?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4800 metric tons&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;7200 metric tons&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6000 metric tons&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;3600 metric tons&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Total production of asbestos globally is 400,000 x 100/25 = 16 lakh tons. So, production in India will be 20/00 x 4 lakh = 80000 tons. So, production in Andhra Pradesh will be 30/100 x 80000 = 24000 tons. So, production in Vishakhapatnam will be 20/100 x 24000 = 4800 tons.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(1380,13,'3','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the following Pi&amp;ndash;charts and answer questions that follow.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%203%20-%20Ex%203/244.4.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%203%20-%20Ex%203/244.4.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Production of asbestos in Australia is how many times that of the asbestos produced by Orissa?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4.8&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;4&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Total steel produced by Orissa is 10/100 x 20z/100 = 0.02z where z is the total global production. The amount produced by Australia will be 10z/100 = 0.1z. So, the required multiple is 0.1/0.02 = 5.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(1381,13,'3','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the following Pi&amp;ndash;charts and answer questions that follow.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%203%20-%20Ex%203/244.4.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%203%20-%20Ex%203/244.4.2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;576&quot; height=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;If Japan produces 90,000 metric tons asbestos, find the total asbestos produced by Russia and Karnataka together?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2.1 lakh metric tons&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2.4 lakh metric tons&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;1.35 lakh metric tons&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2 lakh metric tons&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Japan produces 15% of the global amount and so, the total amount of asbestos produced will be 90,000 x 100/15 = 600,000 = 6 lakh tons. So, share of Russia is 30% = 30/100 x 6 lakh = 1.8 lakh tons. Share of India will be 20/100 x 6 lakh = 1.2 lakh tons. So, share of Karnataka will be 25/100 x 1.2 lakhs = 0.3 lakh tons. So, total amount produced by Russia and Karnataka together is 1.8 + 0.3 = 2.1 lakh tons.&lt;/p&gt;','Hard'),(1382,13,'4','&lt;p&gt;The following pie diagram shows the expenditure incurred on the preparation of a book by a publisher, under various heads. Study the diagram carefully and answer following questions:&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%204%20-%20DPPS/245.1.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;578&quot; height=&quot;382&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the angle of pie diagram showing the expenditure incurred on paying the royalty?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;15 degrees&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;24 degrees&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;48 degrees&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;54 degrees&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;Angle representing royalty D = (15 &amp;times; 360/100) degrees = 54 degrees.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(1383,13,'4','&lt;p&gt;The following pie diagram shows the expenditure incurred on the preparation of a book by a publisher, under various heads. Study the diagram carefully and answer following questions:&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%204%20-%20DPPS/245.1.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;578&quot; height=&quot;382&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;The marked price of a book is 20% more than the C.P. If the marked price of the book be Rs 30, what is the cost of paper used in a single copy of the book?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 6&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 5&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs 4.50&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs 6.50&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;C.P. of a book = Rs (100&amp;times;30/120) = Rs 25. Cost of paper = Rs (20&amp;times;25/100) = Rs 5.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(1384,13,'4','&lt;p&gt;The following pie diagram shows the expenditure incurred on the preparation of a book by a publisher, under various heads. Study the diagram carefully and answer following questions:&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%204%20-%20DPPS/245.1.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;578&quot; height=&quot;382&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Which two expenditures together will form an angle of 108 degrees at the centre of the pie diagram?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;A and E&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;B and E&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;A and D&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;D and E&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Angle A = (20&amp;times;360/100) degrees =72 degrees.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Angle B = (25&amp;times;360/100) degrees = 90 degrees.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Angle C = (30&amp;times;360/100) degrees = 108 degrees.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Angle D = (10&amp;times;360/100) degrees = 36 degrees.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Angle E = (15&amp;times;360/100) degrees = 54 degrees.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Thus, A and D together will form an angle of 108 degrees.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(1385,13,'4','&lt;p&gt;The following pie diagram shows the expenditure incurred on the preparation of a book by a publisher, under various heads. Study the diagram carefully and answer following questions:&lt;/p&gt;\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%204%20-%20DPPS/245.1.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;578&quot; height=&quot;382&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;If the difference between two expenditures be represented by 18 degrees in the pie diagram, these expenditures are:&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;B and E&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;A and C&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;B and D&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;None of these&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;These expenditures are A and B; B and C; D and E; and A and E. because 180 = 5%.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(1386,13,'4','&lt;p&gt;Direction: Study the following pie-chart and answer the questions given below: Preferences of students among six beverages in terms of degree of angle in the pie &amp;ndash;chart. Total No. of students = 6800&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%204%20-%20DPPS/245.2.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;581&quot; height=&quot;414&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the difference between the total number of students who prefer Beverage A and C together and the total number of students who prefer beverage D and F together?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;959&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;955&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;952&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;954&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Difference of corresponding angles = (122.4 + 21.6)&lt;sup&gt;0&lt;/sup&gt; - (79.2 + 14.4)&lt;sup&gt;0&lt;/sup&gt; = 50.4&lt;sup&gt;0&lt;/sup&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Required difference = 50.4&lt;sup&gt;0&lt;/sup&gt;/360&lt;sup&gt;0&amp;nbsp;&lt;/sup&gt;x 6800 = 952 students.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(1387,13,'4','&lt;p&gt;Direction: Study the following pie-chart and answer the questions given below: Preferences of students among six beverages in terms of degree of angle in the pie &amp;ndash;chart. Total No. of students = 6800&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%204%20-%20DPPS/245.2.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;581&quot; height=&quot;414&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the ratio of the number of students who prefer beverage F and the number of students who prefer beverage A?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;3 : 11&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;3 : 13&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;6 : 11&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;5 : 11&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Required Ratio = 21.6 : 79.2 = 3 : 11.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(1388,13,'4','&lt;p&gt;Direction: Study the following pie-chart and answer the questions given below: Preferences of students among six beverages in terms of degree of angle in the pie &amp;ndash;chart. Total No. of students = 6800&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%204%20-%20DPPS/245.2.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;581&quot; height=&quot;414&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;The number of student who prefer beverage E and F together is what per cent of the total of students?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;18&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;14&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;26&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;24&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;Required percentage = 18% + 6% = 24%.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(1389,13,'4','&lt;p&gt;Direction: Study the following pie-chart and answer the questions given below: Preferences of students among six beverages in terms of degree of angle in the pie &amp;ndash;chart. Total No. of students = 6800&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%204%20-%20DPPS/245.2.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;581&quot; height=&quot;414&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;The number of students who prefer beverage C are approximately what percent of the number of students who prefer Beverage D?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;7&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;12&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;18&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;22&lt;/p&gt;','2','&lt;p&gt;Required percentage = 4/34 &amp;times; 100 = 11.76%&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(1390,13,'4','&lt;p&gt;Direction: Study the following pie-chart and answer the questions given below: Preferences of students among six beverages in terms of degree of angle in the pie &amp;ndash;chart. Total No. of students = 6800&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%204%20-%20DPPS/245.2.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;581&quot; height=&quot;414&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;How many students prefer beverage B and beverage E together?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2312&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2313&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2315&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;2318&lt;/p&gt;','1','&lt;p&gt;Number of students who prefer beverages B and E together = 34/100 &amp;times; 68000 = 2312.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(1391,13,'4','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the following pie-chart and answer the following questions. Percentagewise distribution of teachers in six different universities. Total number of teachers = 6400&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%204%20-%20DPPS/245.3.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;580&quot; height=&quot;402&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;The number of teachers in University B is approximately what per cent of the total number of teachers in University D and University E together?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;55&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;59&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;49&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;45&lt;/p&gt;','3','&lt;p&gt;Required percentage is 17/[6+29] x 100% = 1700/35% = 48.57% = 49%.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(1392,13,'4','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the following pie-chart and answer the following questions. Percentagewise distribution of teachers in six different universities. Total number of teachers = 6400&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%204%20-%20DPPS/245.3.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;580&quot; height=&quot;402&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;If twenty five per cent of the teachers in University C are females, what is the number of male teachers in University C?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;922&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;911&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;924&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;912&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;Number of teachers in University C is 19 x 64 = 1216. Number of male teachers in University C = 1216 x 0.75 = 912.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(1393,13,'4','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the following pie-chart and answer the following questions. Percentagewise distribution of teachers in six different universities. Total number of teachers = 6400&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%204%20-%20DPPS/245.3.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;580&quot; height=&quot;402&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;The difference between the total number of teachers in University A, University B and University C together and the total number of teachers in University D, University E and University F together is exactly equal to the number of teachers of which University?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;University A&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;University B&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;University C&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;University D&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;Difference = (D + E + F) % &amp;ndash; (A + B + C) % = (53 &amp;ndash; 47) = 6%. So, 6% of 6400 = 384. Hence, University of D is equal to 6%.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(1394,13,'4','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the following pie-chart and answer the following questions. Percentagewise distribution of teachers in six different universities. Total number of teachers = 6400&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%204%20-%20DPPS/245.3.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;580&quot; height=&quot;402&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;If one-thirty sixth of the teachers from University F are professors and the salary of each professor is Rs. 96000, what will be the total salary of all the professors together from University F?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 307.2 lakh&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 307.2 lakh&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 3.072 lakh&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;Rs. 3.072 lakh&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;Number of teachers in University F = 18 x 64 = 1152. Number of professors in University F = 1152/36 = 32. &amp;there4; Total Salary of professors in University F = 32 x&amp;nbsp;96000 = 30.72 lakh.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(1395,13,'4','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the following pie-chart and answer the following questions. Percentagewise distribution of teachers in six different universities. Total number of teachers = 6400&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;tinymce/uploaded/DI%20-%20Chapter%204%20-%204%20-%20DPPS/245.3.1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;580&quot; height=&quot;402&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;What is the average number of teachers in University A, University C, University D and University F together?&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;854&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;3546&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;3456&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;864&lt;/p&gt;','4','&lt;p&gt;Average is [(11 + 19 + 6 + 18)/4] x 64 = 54 x 16 = 864.&lt;/p&gt;','Easy'),(1396,13,'4','&lt;p&gt;Directions: Study the following pie-charts carefully and answer the questions given below: Discipline-wise Breakup of the Number of candidates appeared in Interview and Discipline wise