Easy'),(2190,21,'1','','Statements: Some cats are dogs. All zebras are cats.\nConclusions:\nI. All zebras are dogs.\nII. Some zebras being dogs is a possibility.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow','2','All zebras are cats. Only some cats are dogs. So, we cannot conclusively say that those cats which are zebras are dogs. So, conclusion I is wrong.\nSecond conclusion is correct only because of the word â€˜possibilityâ€™.','Easy'),(2191,21,'1','','Statements: No gadget is a mobile. All mobiles are cells.\nConclusions:\nI. No cell is a gadget.\nII. All cells being gadgets is a possibility.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow','3','He did not say that all cells are mobiles. So, there will be some cells which are not mobiles. Some gadgets which are not mobiles may be included in this category. So, conclusion I may be wrong. \nSecond conclusion is conclusively wrong because we know that mobiles, which are not gadgets, are cells.','Easy'),(2192,21,'1','','Statements: All circles are rhombuses. Some rhombuses are rectangles.\nConclusions:\nI. All rectangles being rhombuses is a possibility.\nII. All circles being rectangles is a possibility.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow','4','If rectangles is a subset of rhombuses, then still some rhombuses will be rectangles and so, there is a chance that this might happen. So, conclusion I is right, but only because of the inclusion of the word â€˜possibilityâ€™.\nSince circles is a subset of rhombuses, expanding on the hypothesis above, we can see that there is a possibility of all circles being rectangles. So, conclusion II is right, but only because of the inclusion of the word â€˜possibilityâ€™.','Easy'),(2193,21,'1','','Statements: All districts are states. All states are countries.\nConclusions:\nI. All those countries which are states are also districts.\nII. All districts are countries.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow','2','States is a bigger set than districts and so, conclusion I is NOT right.\nDistricts is a subset of states, which in turn is a subset of countries. So, all districts will be countries and conclusion II is right.','Easy'),(2194,21,'1','','Statements: No boat is a ship. Some ships are vessels.\nConclusions:\nI. All vessels being ships is a possibility.\nII. No vessel is a boat.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow','1','If all vessels are ships, then some ships are still vessels. So, conclusion I is right, just because of the word â€˜possibilityâ€™.\nSome vessels, which are not ships, may be boat and so, conclusion II is wrong.','Easy'),(2195,21,'1','','Statements: Some lions are tigers. Some cheetahs are lions.\nConclusions:\nI. No tiger is a cheetah.\nII. All cheetahs being tigers is a possibility.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow','2','There can be some lions, who are both cheetahs and tigers. So, statement I is wrong.\nIf all cheetahs are tigers, then there may be some tigers who are not cheetahs but lions and also some cheetahs that are lions. So, conclusion II is valid, but only because of the word â€˜possibilityâ€™.','Easy'),(2196,21,'1','','Statements: Some animals are humans. No animal is an alien.\nConclusions:\nI. No alien is a human.\nII. Some humans are definitely not animals.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow','3','Since only some animals are humans, there may be some animals which are not humans and these may be aliens. So, conclusion I is wrong.\nIf we consider that all humans are animals, the statement some animals are humans is still true and so conclusion II may NOT always be right.','Easy'),(2197,21,'1','','Statements: Some gases are liquids. All liquids are solids. \nConclusions:\nI. All gases being solids is a possibility.\nII. All such gases which are not solids can never be liquids.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow','4','Solids is a bigger set than liquids and may well include all the gases. So, conclusion I is right, only because the word â€˜possibilityâ€™ is included.\nSince liquid is a subset of solids, gases that are not solids can never be liquids. So, conclusion II is also right.','Easy'),(2198,21,'1','','Statements: All lengths are widths. Some widths are volumes.\nConclusions: \nI. All lengths are volumes.\nII. All volumes being lengths is a possibility.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow','2','Since only some widths are volumes, there may be some widths, which are lengths, which are not volumes. So, conclusion I is wrong.\nWidths is a bigger set than lengths. If we consider that the volumes is a subset of lengths, then also only some volumes will be lengths. So conclusion II may be right, but only because the word â€˜possibilityâ€™ is used.','Easy'),(2199,21,'1','','Statements: No house is an apartment. Some buildings are apartments. \nConclusions:\nI. No house is a building. \nII. All buildings are houses.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow','3','Some buildings, which are not apartments, can be houses and so, conclusion I is wrong.\nSome buildings which are apartments can never be houses and so, conclusion II is wrong.','Easy'),(2200,21,'1','','Statements: Some goals are points. All runs are points. \nConclusions: \nI. All runs being goals is a possibility. \nII. No run is a goal.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow','1','If we consider that the runs is a subset of goals, then there is every chance that the two statements are still satisfied. So, conclusion I is right because of the inclusion of the word â€˜possibilityâ€™.\nSome goals which are charts can also be runs. So conclusion II is wrong.','Easy'),(2201,21,'1','','Statements: Some pencils are markers. All markers are highlighters.\nConclusions:\nI. No highlighter is a pencil. \nII. All markers being pencils is a possibility.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow','2','Conclusion I is wrong, because those pencils, which are also markers are also highlighters.\nIf markers is a subset of pencils, then all markers are pencils, but still only some pencils are markers. So, Conclusion II is right.','Easy'),(2202,21,'1','','Statements: Some engineers are educators. Some educators are scientists.\nConclusions:\nI. Some engineers are scientists.\nII. Some educators are engineers.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow','2','There is every chance that the educators who are scientists may not be engineers. So, conclusion I is wrong.\nSince some engineers are educators, some educators will be engineers. So conclusion II is right.','Easy'),(2203,21,'1','','Statements: Some pens are sharpeners. All sharpeners are erasers.\nConclusions:\nI. At least some pens are erasers.\nII. All erasers being pens is a possibility.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow','4','Since all sharpeners are erasers, those sharpeners which are pens are also erasers. So, conclusion I is right.\nErasers is a bigger group than sharpeners. It may even include all the pens which are not sharpeners. So, conclusion II is also right, but only because of the presence of the word â€˜possibilityâ€™.','Easy'),(2204,21,'1','','Statements: All consumers are angels. All angels are good.\nConclusions:\nI. All consumers are good.\nII. No angels can be a consumer.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow','1','Since every consumer is an angel, he will be good. So, conclusion I is right.\nConsumers are a subset under angels. So, some angels will be consumers. So conclusion II is wrong.','Easy'),(2205,21,'1','','Statements: Some caps are shirts. All shirts are trousers.\nConclusions:\nI. All shirts which are caps are trousers.\nII. Some shirts are caps.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow','4','Since some caps are shirts, we can be sure that some shirts are caps. So, conclusion II is right.\nEvery shirt, even if is a cap or not, will be a trouser. So, conclusion I is also right.','Easy'),(2206,21,'1','','Statements: Some eyes are ears. Some ears are hands. \nConclusions:\nI. No hand is an eye.\nII. Some eyes are hands.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Either conclusion I or conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow','3','Some eyes which are ears may also be hands. In such a case, conclusion II is valid. In all other cases, no hand will be an eye and so, conclusion I is valid.\nWe cannot say for sure, which case it is we are referring to.\nSo, either conclusion I or conclusion II follows.','Easy'),(2207,21,'1','','Statements: Some papers are bulletins. No bulletin is a magazine.\nConclusions:\nI. All magazines being papers is a possibility.\nII. All bulletins being papers is a possibility.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Either conclusion I or conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow','4','Some of the papers which are not bulletins can be magazines. In the special case that magazines is a subset of paper, we can say that all magazines are papers. So, conclusion I can occur and hence is true.\nIf we take the bulletins to be a subset of papers, then also some papers will be bulletins, because it is a superset and all bulletins will be papers. So, conclusion II can occur and hence is true.\nIn this case, both conclusions are true only because of the presence of the word â€˜possibilityâ€™.','Easy'),(2208,21,'1','','Statements: Some cows are buffalos. No buffalo is a fox.\nConclusions:\nI. No fox is a cow. \nII. Some cows are foxes.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Either conclusion I or conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow','3','We do not know for sure whether some cows are foxes or not. But, one thing we know for sure is that, if we take a fox out, it will either be a cow or will not be a cow. So, we can say that in all cases, either conclusion I or conclusion II follows.','Easy'),(2209,21,'1','','Statements: All goats are sheep. All sheep are grass eaters.\nConclusions:\nI. Some sheep are goats.\nII. All grass eaters are goats.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Either conclusion I or conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow','1','Sheep is a bigger set than goats and so, some sheep are goats. So, conclusion I is right.\nGrass eaters is a bigger set than goats and so, only some grass eaters are goats. So, conclusion II is wrong.','Easy'),(2210,21,'2','','Statements: All cats are dogs. No dog is a zebra. All zebras are horses.\nConclusions:\nI. No horse is a dog.\nII. No cat is a zebra.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow','2','Dogs is a bigger set than cats. Since the second statement says that no dog is an apartment, we can safely say that no cat will also be apartment either. So, conclusion II is right.\nIt is given that all zebras are horses. So, there may be some horses which are not zebras. Some of these horses which are not zebras may be dogs. So, conclusion I is wrong.','Medium'),(2211,21,'2','','Statements: All cats are dogs. No dog is an elephant. All elephants are jackals.\nConclusions:\nI. All cats being jackals is a possibility. \nII. All elephants being cat is a possibility.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow','3','Since cats is a subset of dogs and since no dog is an elephant, we can say that no elephant will be a cat. So, conclusion II is wrong.\nConclusion I is also wrong, because the facts that no dog is an elephant and all elephants are jackals combine to make the possibility very difficult.','Medium'),(2212,21,'2','','Statements: Some clubs are spades. All clubs are hearts. No heart is a ace.\nConclusions:\nI. All hearts can never be clubs. \nII. All aces being clubs is a possibility.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow','3','All clubs are hearts does not limit the chance of all hearts to be clubs. So, conclusion I is wrong.\nSince no heart is a ace and all clubs are hearts, we can directly say that no ace will be an club. So, conclusion II is wrong.','Medium'),(2213,21,'2','','Statements: Some jacks are queens. All jacks are kings. No king is a ace.\nConclusions:\nI. No jack is a ace.\nII. At least some queens are kings.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow','4','Since no king is a ace and all jacks are kings, we can directly say that no jack will be a ace. So, conclusion I is right.\nAll jacks are kings. So, some jacks, which are queens, will also be kings. So, conclusion II is right.','Medium'),(2214,21,'2','','Statements: No gold is silver. All silvers are platinum. No platinum is a radium.\nConclusions:\nI. No gold is platinum.\nII. No gold is an radium.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow','3','Silver and gold are disjoint sets. Since all silvers are platinum, there may be some platinum which are not silvers and these may include gold. So, conclusion I is wrong.\nAs we have seen in conclusion I, some platinum may be gold and of the remaining gold, some may be radium. We cannot say for sure that this is not possible. So, conclusion II is also wrong.','Medium'),(2215,21,'2','','Statements: No music is video. All videos are document. No document is an picture.\nConclusions:\nI. No pictures are videos. \nII. All music being document is a possibility.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow','4','All videos are document. So, document is a bigger set than videos. Since no document is an picture, we can safely say that no pictures are videos. So, conclusion I is wrong.\nMusic and video are disjoint sets. We know that all videos are document. We cannot rule out the chance that all music are document. So, conclusion II is also correct, only because it includes the word â€˜possibilityâ€™. Otherwise, that possibility is so rare that we can ignore it.','Medium'),(2216,21,'2','','Statements: All men are women. No woman is a boy. All boys are girls.\nConclusions:\nI. No man is a boy.\nII. Some girls are women.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow','1','From the first statement, it is clear that mans is a subset of women. So, we can safely say that no man is a boy because no woman is a boy. So, conclusion I is correct.\nGirls is a bigger set that contains boys within it. Since no woman is a boy, the chance of some girls being women is very little. So, we can say that conclusion II is wrong. Conclusion II would have been right, if the conclusion has included the word â€˜possibilityâ€™.','Medium'),(2217,21,'2','','Statements: All Chemistry are Physics. All Maths are Physics. Some Physics are Biology.\nConclusions:\nI. Some Maths are Chemistry. \nII. Some Biology are Maths.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow','3','All men are human beings and all women are human beings but no man is a woman. Similar argument in this case would lead us to conclude that conclusion I is wrong. If there are no words like possibility or maybe, then we have to be very sure to say that the conclusion is correct.\nAll Maths are Physics. So, there may be some Physics which are not Maths. Some Physics which are Biology, may be those ones which are not Maths. So, conclusion II is not always correct. So, conclusion II is also wrong.','Medium'),(2218,21,'2','','Statements: All Blues are Greens. All Reds are Blues. All Oranges are Greens.\nConclusions:\nI. All Oranges are Blues.\nII. All Reds are Greens.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow','2','Oranges and Blues are subsets of Greens and there is every chance that some Blues may not be Oranges. So, conclusion I is wrong.\nReds is a subset of Blues which in turn is a subset of Greens. So, we can safely say that all Reds are Greens. So, conclusion II is right.','Medium'),(2219,21,'2','','Statements: Some clouds are ashes. Some ashes are particles. All particles are elements.\nConclusions:\nI. No particle is a cloud.\nII. Some elements are ashes.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow','2','Since every particle is included in the set of elements, some ashes, which are particle, are also elements and so, conclusion II is always right.\nSome clouds which are ashes, may be particles. If this happens, they will also be elements since all particles are elements. So, conclusion II is not always right and so, conclusion II is wrong.','Medium'),(2220,21,'2','','Statements: No A is B. Some B are C. All C are D.\nConclusions:\nI. No D is A.\nII. Some D are B.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow','2','Since all C are D, the set of D will include those C which are B. So, some D would always be B and so, conclusion II is right.\nThere are some C which are not B. If some of them are A, then since all C are D, these C would be D. This would contradict conclusion I. so, conclusion I is NOT always right.','Medium'),(2221,21,'2','','Statements: All apples are berry. All berry are grape. No grape is guava.\nConclusions:\nI. No apple is guava.\nII. Most grape are berry.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow','1','From the first two statements, we can say that all apples are grape. So, no apple will be guava. So, conclusion I is right.\nBerry may be a tiny subset of the set grape. In this case, we can safely say that conclusion II is NOT right.','Medium'),(2222,21,'2','','Statements: Some fruits are mangoes. Some mangoes are red. All red are vegetables.\nConclusions:\nI. No fruit is red.\nII. Some fruits are red.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Either conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow','3','Since some fruits are mangoes and some mangoes are red, we cannot be sure about the redness of the fruits. Any given fruit has only two choices. It will either be red or not be red. \nIn these cases, we can say that either conclusion I or conclusion II follows.','Medium'),(2223,21,'2','','Statements: All nuts are fruits. Some fruits are berries. No berry is a vegetable.\nConclusions:\nI. All vegetables being nuts is a possibility.\nII. At least some fruits are nuts.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Either conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow','4','There is a chance that none of the nuts, which are fruits, are berries. In such a case, all of them may be vegetables. So, conclusion I is right, but only because if the word â€˜possibilityâ€™.\nSince all nuts are fruits, we can say for sure that some fruits are nuts. So, conclusion II is right.','Medium'),(2224,21,'2','','Statements: All stars are bottles. Some bottles are papers. No paper is a calendar.\nConclusions: \nI. All stars being papers is a possibility.\nII. No calendar is a bottle.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Either conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow','1','Since bottles is a bigger set than stars, there is a possibility that only bottles which are stars are papers and remaining all bottles are not paper. So, conclusion I is right, but only because if the word â€˜possibilityâ€™.\nSome bottles which are not paper may be calendars and in this case, statement II is NOT right.','Medium'),(2225,21,'2','','Statements: All almonds are cashews. Some cashews are grapes. No grape is a fruit.\nConclusions:\nI. At least some fruits are cashews.\nII. No fruit is an almond.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow','3','All the cashews which are not grapes, may not be fruits. In such a case, conclusion I is wrong.\nSome of the cashews which are not grapes, may be fruits. This cashew group may even include some almonds. In such a case, conclusion II is wrong.','Medium'),(2226,21,'2','','Statements: All rings are circles. All squares are rings. No ellipse is a circle. \nConclusions:\nI. Some rings being ellipses is a possibility.\nII. At least some circles are squares.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Either conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow','2','Squares is a subset of rings, which in turn is a subset of circles. Since no ellipse is a circle, we can surely say that no ring and no square can be an ellipse. So, conclusion I is wrong, even when there is the word possibility.\nSince circles is a bigger set that includes squares, conclusion II will be true.','Medium'),(2227,21,'2','','Statements: 50% eyes are ears. 15% ears are noses. 99% noses are mouths.\nConclusions:\nI. Some eyes are noses.\nII. Some eyes are mouths.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow','3','We cannot surely say that some eyes are either noses or mouths. So, neither conclusion is correct.','Medium'),(2228,21,'2','','Statements: All A are Z. All Z are X. All Y are A.\nConclusions:\nI. All A are Y.\nII. All Y are X.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Either conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow','2','Y is a subset of A, which is a subset of Z, which is a subset of X.\nWe cannot for surely say that all A are Y. so, conclusion I is NOT right.\nSince Y will be a subset of X, conclusion II is right.','Medium'),(2229,21,'2','','Statements: Some books are pens. Some pens are pencils. Some pencils are buttons.\nConclusions:\nI. Some buttons are pens.\nII. Some pencils are books.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow','3','There is every chance that each and every pencil which is a pen is not a button. In such cases, conclusion I is wrong.\nSimilarly, there is every chance that each and every book which is a pen is not a pencil. In such cases, conclusion I is wrong.','Medium'),(2230,21,'3','','Statements: No Bat is Cat. Some Rats are Cats. All Mats are Rats.\nConclusions:\nI. No Mat is Bat.\nII. Some Mats are Cats.\nIII. No Cat is Mat.\nIV. Some Bats are Rats.','Only Either III follows','Only either II or III follows','Only I follows','None of these','2','Since only some Rats are Cats, some Mats may not be Cats. Some of these Mats can be Bats. So, conclusion I is not valid.\nThose Rats, which are Cats, may or may not include Mats. If we take a particular Mat, then only one of the two options holds true. The Mat is either a Cat or not a Cat. So, either conclusion II or III is valid.\nSince no Bat is a Cat, no Cat can be a Bat. So, conclusion IV will be wrong.\nSo, the correct answer is conclusion II or III.','Hard'),(2231,21,'3','','Statements: All Lions are Tigers. All Cheetahs are Tigers. Some Tigers are Foxes.\nConclusions:\nI. No Lion is Fox.\nII. Some Cheetahs are not Foxes.\nIII. Some Lions are Cheetahs.\nIV. All Foxes are Lions.','Only I and II follows','Only III and IV follows','Only II or IV follows','None of these','4','Lions and Cheetahs can either be joint sets or disjoint sets (e.g. Men, Women, and Humans). So, we cannot conclusively say that no Lion is Tiger. So, conclusion I is not always valid.\nIf all those Tigers, which are Foxes, are Cheetahs, then conclusion II is not valid.\nLions and Cheetahs can be disjoint sets. In such cases, conclusion III is wrong.\nThose Foxes, which are Tigers, need not necessarily include all the Lions. So, conclusion IV is not always valid.\nSo, no conclusion is correct.','Hard'),(2232,21,'3','','Statements: Some Cars are Goals. Some Goals are Animals. Some Animals are Flies.\nConclusions:\nI. Some Flies are Cars.\nII. Some Flies are not Animals.\nIII. No Goal is Fly. \nIV. No Car is Fly.','Only I or II follows','Only II or III follows','Only III or IV follows','None of these.','4','Those Animals, which are Goals and also flies, may never be Cars. So, there is no surety that some flies are Cars. So, conclusion I is not always right.\nIf all flies are Animals, then also, some Animals are flies. In this case, conclusion II is not valid.\nSome Animals, which are Goals, can be flies. Similarly, some Cars, which are Goals, can be Animals and so can be flies. So, conclusion III and IV are wrong.\nSo, no conclusion is right.','Hard'),(2233,21,'3','','Statements: All Mails are Browsers. Some Mails are Letters. Some Browsers are Pins.\nConclusions:\nI. Some Pins are Mails.\nII. Some Browsers are Letters.\nIII. Some Pins are Letters.\nIV. All Mails are Pins.','Either I or IV follows','Either I or IV &amp; II follow','Only II follows','None of these.','3','Those Browsers, which are Pins, may not be Mails and so, conclusion I is not always valid.\nSince all Mails are Browsers, those Letters which are Mails, will also be Browsers. So, conclusion II is always valid.\nSince some Mails are Letters, some Browsers will also be Letters. There is every possibility that these Browsers may not be Pins. So, conclusion III is not always valid.\nSome Mails, which are Browsers, may not be Pins and so, conclusion IV is not always valid.\nSo, only conclusion II is valid.','Hard'),(2234,21,'3','','Statements: Some Animals are Mammals. All Mammals are Humans. No Human is Plant.\nConclusions:\nI. Some Animals are not Plants.\nII. Some Animals are not Humans.\nIII. All Animals are Humans.\nIV. No Animal is Plant.','Only I follows','I &amp; either II or III follow','Only IV follows','None of these','2','Since some Animals are mammals and all mammals are boxes, some Animals will be boxes. These Animals will never be plants and so, conclusion I is always valid.\nAs seen above, some Animals will be Humans. So, any Animal selected will either be a Human or not a Human. So, at any time, only one of conclusion II or III is valid. So, either II or III follows.\nSome Animals will be Humans. Those Animals, which are not Humans can be plants and so, conclusion IV is not always valid.\nSo, the correct answer is conclusion I and either II or III will follow.','Hard'),(2235,21,'3','','Statements: Some streets are roads. Some roads are lanes. Some lanes are highways.\nConclusions:\nI. Some roads are not streets.\nII. No highway is street.\nIII. Some streets are not roads.\nIV. Some lanes are not roads','Only II follows','Only IV and III follow','Either I or III follows','None of these','4','If roads is a subset of streets, then some streets are roads is valid and every road will be a street, contradicting conclusion I. so, conclusion I is NOT always valid.\nThere can be some streets, which are roads and also lanes. There is a possibility that some of these lanes, which are also roads, are highways. So, conclusion II is NOT always right.\nSame argument as for conclusion I will result in deciding that both conclusion III and conclusion IV are not always right.\nSo, no conclusion is always valid.','Hard'),(2236,21,'3','','Statements: Some boards are books. All books are notes. All pointers are notes.\nConclusions:\nI. Some books are not boards.\nII. All notes are boards.\nIII. Some pointers are books.\nIV. Some pointers are boards.','Only I follows','Only II follows','Only III or IV follows','None of these','4','Some boards are books. There is a chance that boards is a bigger set for which, books is a subset. In that case, conclusion I is not valid.\nSince some boards are books and all books are notes, we can say that only some boards will be notes and some notes will be boards. So, conclusion II is not valid.\nThere is a chance that pointers and books are completely disjoint subsets of notes. In such case, conclusion III is not valid. e.g. for this case is all men are humans and all women are humans, but still no man is a woman.\nWe cannot conclusively say that conclusion IV will be valid, because there is every chance that boards and pointers are disjoint sets.\nSo, NO conclusion is valid.','Hard'),(2237,21,'3','','Statements: Some tables are chairs. No bed is table. Some chairs are beds. \nConclusions:\nI. Some chairs are not tables.\nII. All chairs are either tables or bed\nIII. Some chairs are both tables and beds.\nIV. All chairs are tables.','Only I and IV follow','Only either II or III follow','Either II or III &amp; I follow','None of these','4','Some tables are chairs only means that some chairs will be tables and so, conclusion I and IV is NOT valid always. One out of conclusion I and IV will be true always, but we cannot say which conclusion will be true until we see the particular instance.\nSince no bed can be a table, we can surely say that conclusion III is wrong.\nThere may be some chairs which are neither tables, nor beds. In those cases, conclusion II is not valid.\nSo, no conclusion is always valid.','Hard'),(2238,21,'3','','Statements: All birds are animals. Some animals are humans. All humans are monsters.\nConclusions:\nI. Some humans are not birds.\nII. Some birds are humans.\nIII. Some animals are not monsters.\nIV. All animals are monsters.','Either I or II follows','Either III or IV follows','Either I or II and either III or IV follow','None of these','3','Those animals, which are humans will either include a particular bird or not. So, in each and every case, we can say that one out of conclusions I and II will follow. We cannot determine which conclusion will follow until we know the particular context.\nSimilarly, if we take an animal, which is a human, it will surely be a monster. If we pick an animal which is not a human, then it may not be a monster. So, only one statement out of conclusion III and IV will be true.\nSo, either I or II and either III or IV will follow.','Hard'),(2239,21,'3','','Statements: Some leaves are fruits. All branches are fruits. Some roots are branches.\nConclusions:\nI. Some roots are fruits.\nII. Some branches are leaves.\nIII. No leaf is branch.\nIV. Some leaves are roots.','Either II or III and I follow','Only I follows','Only either II or III follows','None of these','1','All those branches, which are roots, will be fruits. So, conclusion I is valid always.\nIf we take a particular leaf, it will either be a branch, in which case it will be a fruit: or it will not be a branch and so not a fruit. These are the only possible choices. So, for any leaf, either conclusion II or III will hold true in all cases.\nThere is a chance that those leaves which are fruits, are not branches and so, no leaf is a root. So, conclusion IV is NOT always right.\nSo, only either II or III follows.','Hard'),(2240,21,'3','','Statements: All clubs are hearts. Some hearts are spades. No spade is card.\nConclusions:\nI. Some hearts are clubs.\nII. Some spades are clubs.\nIII. Some clubs are cards.\nIV. No club is a card.','Only I follows','Only I and either III or IV follow','Either III or IV follows','None of these','2','Since all clubs are hearts, some hearts will be clubs and so, conclusion I is valid.\nOnly some hearts will be clubs. We cannot be very sure that some of the hearts which are spades belong from this group. So, conclusion II is not valid.\nIf all the clubs belong to those hearts which are spades, then no club can be a card. In all the other cases, some clubs will be cards. We cannot conclusively say whether the first case will hold or the second case will hold in a particular instance. We can only say that one of the cases will hold each and every time.\nSo, either conclusion III or conclusion IV will be true.\nSo, the correct answer is I and either III or IV.','Hard'),(2241,21,'3','','Statements: Some nuts are fruits. No fruit is a berry. All berries are flowers.\nConclusions:\nI. Some nuts are berries.\nII. Some fruits are flowers.\nIII. No fruit is a flower.\nIV. Some nuts are flowers.','Only I and II follows','Either II or III follows','Either III or IV follows','None of these','2','There is every possibility that no nut can be a berry and so, conclusion I is NOT valid always.\nSince all berries are flowers, there can be some flowers which are not berries. These flowers can either be fruits or not be fruits. So, either conclusion II or conclusion III is valid.\nThere is every possibility that no nut can be a berry and so, no nut is a flower.  So, conclusion IV is NOT valid always.\nSo, only either II or III follows.','Hard'),(2242,21,'3','','Statements: All cats are dogs. Some cats are zebras. Some dogs are animals.\nConclusions:\nI. Some dogs are zebras.\nII. Some animals are zebras.\nIII. Some animals are cats.\nIV. No dog is zebra.','Only I follows','Only I and IV follow','Only I and III follow','None of these','1','All cats are dogs. So, some cats, which are also flowers, will be zebras. So, conclusion I is always valid and conclusion IV is never valid.\nSome dogs can be zebras. There is a chance that none of these dogs are animals. Then, conclusion II is not valid \nThose animals, which are also dogs, may not be cats. So, conclusion III is not always valid.\nSo, only conclusion I follows.','Hard'),(2243,21,'3','','Statements: All pins are staplers. Some staplers are sharpeners. Some sharpeners are erasers.\nConclusions:\nI. Some staplers are erasers.\nII. Some sharpeners are pins.\nIII. Some pins are erasers.\nIV. Some erasers are sharpeners.','Only I and II follow','Only II and IV follow','Only IV follows','None of these','3','There is every chance that not even one of the sharpeners, which are also erasers, is a stapler. So, conclusion I is not always right.\nThere is every chance that those staplers, which are also sharpeners, will not include even one pin. So, in this case, conclusion II is not valid.\nWe can see that whenever conclusion I is wrong, conclusion III will also be wrong.\nSince some sharpeners are erasers, some erasers will be sharpeners. So, conclusion IV is always valid. \nSo, only IV follows.','Hard'),(2244,21,'3','','Statements: Some oranges are apples. All apples are guavas. No guava is a banana.\nConclusions:\nI. Some guavas are oranges.\nII. No apple is a banana.\nIII. Some oranges are bananas.\nIV. Some apples are bananas.','Only I and II follow','Only I and either II or IV follow','Only III and either II or IV follow','None of these','1','Since all apples are guavas, some guavas will be apples. So, conclusion I is valid.\nSince all apples are guavas and no guava is a banana, no apple can be a banana. So, conclusion II is valid and conclusion IV is WRONG.\n There is a chance that those oranges which are not apples, may also not be bananas. In those cases, conclusion III is NOT valid.\nSo, only I and II are always valid.','Hard'),(2245,21,'3','','Statements: Some events are celebrations. No goal is a point. Some celebrations are points.\nConclusions:\nI. Some celebrations are not goals.\nII. Some goals are events.\nIII. No goal is a celebration.\nIV. No point is an event.','Only I follows','Only ! &amp; III follow','Only  III or IV follows','None of these','1','Those celebrations which are points can never be goals. So, conclusion I is valid.\nWe cannot say anything conclusively about conclusion II because we do not know the nature of the set GOALS. So, conclusion II is not valid\nOnly some celebrations are points. Those celebrations which are not points can be goals and so, conclusion III is NOT valid.\nThere can be some celebrations which are both points and events and so, conclusion IV is not always valid.\nSo, only conclusion I is valid.','Hard'),(2246,21,'3','','Statements: All cameras are tube lights. No pen is a bulb. Some bulbs are cameras.\nConclusions:\nI. Some pens are tube lights.\nII. No pens are tube lights.\nIII. Some tube lights are cameras.\nIV. All tube lights are cameras.','Only I and II follow','Either I or II and III follow','Only III and IV follow','None of these','2','Some bulbs are cameras. The remaining cameras are not bulbs. There are two choices here. Those cameras may include some pens or do not include any pens. So, only one conclusion between I and II is correct.\nSince all cameras are tube lights, some tube lights will surely be cameras. So, conclusion III is right.\nSince all cameras are tube lights, tube lights is a bigger set than cameras. So, conclusion IV is NOT always right.\nSo, the correct answer is Either I or II and III.','Hard'),(2247,21,'3','','Statements: Some fruits are vegetables. All flowers are plants. All plants are fruits.\nConclusions:\nI. Some plants are vegetables.\nII. Some fruits are flowers.\nIII. All flowers are fruits.\nIV. No flowers are vegetables.','Only I and II follow','Only II and III follow','Only III and IV follow','None of these','2','Flowers is a subset of Plants, which in turn is a subset of Fruits.\nOnly some fruits are vegetables. We cannot be sure if the group of fruits includes those which are flowers or not. So, conclusion I is NOT RIGHT.\nSince flowers is a subset of fruits, conclusion II and conclusion III are both valid.\nSome flowers, which are fruits, may be vegetables and so, conclusion IV is WRONG.\nSo, only conclusions II and II follow.','Hard'),(2248,21,'3','','Statements: All stockings are slippers. Some socks are shoes. All shoes are stockings.\nConclusions:\nI. Some socks are stockings.\nII. Some socks are slippers.\nIII. All shoes are slippers.\nIV. All shoes are socks.','Only I and II follow','Only III and IV follow','Only IV does not follow.','None of these','3','Since some socks are shoes and all shoes are stockings, those socks, which are shoes, will be stockings. So, conclusion I is correct.\nThose socks which are stockings, will also be slippers because all the stockings are slippers. So, conclusion II is valid.\nSince all shoes are stockings, which in turn are slippers, we can say that all shoes are slippers. So, conclusion III is valid.\nWe cannot conclusively say that all shoes are socks. There may be a case where only some shoes are socks. So, conclusion IV does not follow.\nSo, only conclusion IV does not follow.','Hard'),(2249,21,'3','','Statements: Some books are papers. All plates are records. Some records are books.\nConclusions:\nI. Some plates are books.\nII. Some records are papers.\nIII. Some papers are plates.\nIV. Some books are records.','Only I follows','Only II and III follow','Only IV follows','None of these','3','There is a chance that only those records which are not plates can be books. So, conclusion I is NOT right.\nThere is a chance that only those books which are not records can be papers. So, conclusion II is NOT right.\nWe cannot conclusively say that some papers are plates. So, conclusion III is wrong.\nSince some records are books, some books will be records. So, conclusion IV will be correct.\nSo, only conclusion IV follows.','Hard'),(2250,21,'4','','Statements: Some ants are bats. No bat is cat. Some cats are ants.\nConclusions:\nI. Some ants that is bats is cats.\nII. Some cats that is ants is bats.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow.','3','Conclusion I and II are both wrong because, anything that is bats will never be cats.','Medium'),(2251,21,'4','','Statements: Some goat is mat. Some mat is sky. Some sky is goat.\nConclusions:\nI. Some goat which is mat is sky.\nII. Some sky is neither goat nor mat.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow.','3','We cannot say for sure that some goat which is mat is sky. There is every chance that goat which is mat will not be sky. So, conclusion I is wrong.\nWe cannot conclusively support statement II also. So, both are wrong.','Medium'),(2252,21,'4','','Statements: All lions are panthers. All panthers are fighters. No panther is a cheetah.\nConclusions:\nI. No cheetah is a fighter.\nII. At least some fighters are lions.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow.','2','Fighters is a bigger set than panthers and so, may include some elements which are not panthers. This may include cheetahs. So, conclusion I is NOT right.\nFighters is a bigger set which has lions as a subset and so, some fighters are lions. So, conclusion II is right.','Medium'),(2253,21,'4','','Statements: Some brochures are mails. All brochures are flyers. No flyer is a card.\nConclusions:\nI. No mail is a card.\nII. All mails being flyers is a possibility.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow.','2','There may be some mails which are not brochures and flyers and which may be cards. So, conclusion I is wrong.\nFlyers is a bigger set than brochures and may well include all the mails which are not brochures. So, conclusion II is right, but only because of the inclusion of the word â€˜possibilityâ€™.','Medium'),(2254,21,'4','','Statements: Some colours are paints. All colours are varnishes. No varnish is a dye.\nConclusions:\nI. Some varnishes are paints.\nII. No dye is a colour.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow.','4','Varnishes include even those colours which are paints and so, conclusion I is valid.\nSince every colour is a varnish and no varnish is a dye, we can safely say that no dye is a colour. So, conclusion II is also valid.','Medium'),(2255,21,'4','','Statements: All As are Bs. No B is a C. All Cs are Ds.\nConclusions:\nI. No D is an A.\nII. All Ds being As is a possibility.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow.','3','D is a bigger set than Cs and may include some Bs, among whom some may be As, also. So, conclusion I is NOT right.\nSince Ds contain some Cs, which can never be a B or A, conclusion II is wrong, even though the word â€˜possibilityâ€™ is included.','Medium'),(2256,21,'4','','Statements: All Doctors are Engineers. No Engineer is a surgeon. All surgeons are professionals.\nConclusions:\nI. No Doctor is a surgeon.\nII. At least some surgeons are Doctors.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow.','1','Since no Engineer is a surgeon, no Doctor can be a surgeon. So, conclusion I is correct.\nSince no surgeon can be a Doctor, conclusion II is wrong.','Medium'),(2257,21,'4','','Statements: No plant is a flower. Some flowers are fruits.\nConclusions:\nI. All fruits being flowers is a possibility.\nII. No fruit is a plant.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow.','1','If all fruits are flowers, then some flowers are still fruits. So, conclusion I is right, just because of the word â€˜possibilityâ€™.\nSome fruits, which are not flowers, may be plant and so, conclusion II is wrong.','Easy'),(2258,21,'4','','Statements: Some strikers are defenders. All strikers are mid-fielders. All mid-fielders are keepers.\nConclusions:\nI. Some strikers are not keepers.\nII. All mid-fielders being defenders is a possibility.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow.','2','Conclusion I is wrong, since strikers is a subset of mid-fielders, which itself is subset of keepers. So, all strikers will be keepers.\nThere is a chance that all defenders are strikers, in such a case, still some strikers are defenders. The set of defenders can also include all the mid-fielders. So, conclusion II is right, but only because of the presence of the word â€˜possibilityâ€™.','Medium'),(2259,21,'4','','Statements: Some stores are shops. All stores are groceries. All groceries are markets.\nConclusions:\nI. All shops can never be markets.\nII. Any shop which is a store is a market.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow.','2','There is a chance that all shops are stores, in such a case, still some stores are shops. Since the set markets includes the set stores, in this case, all the shops can be markets. So, conclusion I is NOT right.\nEvery store is a market. So, all those shops which are stores are also markets. So, conclusion II is right.','Medium'),(2260,21,'4','','Statements: All goats are donkeys. No donkey is horse. All horses are cows.\nConclusions:\nI. All those cows if they are donkeys are also goats.\nII. No goat is horse.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow.','2','Conclusion 1 is wrong. No cow can be a donkey because, cows are a subset of horses. \nSince goat is a subset of donkeys and no donkey is a horse, we can say that no goat is a horse. So, conclusion II is right.','Medium'),(2261,21,'4','','Statements: No cash is a cheque. All cheques are drafts.\nConclusions:\nI. No draft is a cash.\nII. All drafts are cash.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow.','3','He did not say that all drafts are cheques. So, there will be some drafts which are not cheques. Some cash which are not cheques may be included in this category. So, conclusion I may be wrong. \nSecond conclusion is conclusively wrong because we know that cheques, which are not cash, are drafts. So, all drafts can never be cash.','Easy'),(2262,21,'4','','Statements: All marks are ranks. All ranks are scores.\nConclusions:\nI. All scores are marks.\nII. All marks are scores.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow.','2','Scores is a bigger set then ranks and ranks is a bigger set than marks and so, conclusion I is NOT right.\nMarks is a subset of ranks, which in turn is a subset of scores. So, all marks will be scores and conclusion II is right.','Easy'),(2263,21,'4','','Statements: No island is a peninsula. Some lands are peninsulas. \nConclusions:\nI. No island is a land. \nII. All lands are islands.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow.','3','Some lands, which are not peninsulas, can be islands and so, conclusion I is wrong.\nSome lands which are peninsulas can never be islands and so, conclusion II is wrong.','Easy'),(2264,21,'4','','Statements: Some fingers are nails. Some nails are boards. \nConclusions:\nI. No board is a finger.\nII. Some fingers are boards.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Either conclusion I or conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow.','3','Some fingers which are nails may also be boards. In such a case, conclusion II is valid. In all other cases, no board will be a finger and so, conclusion I is valid.\nWe cannot say for sure, which case it is we are referring to.\nSo, either conclusion I or conclusion II follows.','Easy'),(2265,21,'4','','Statements: All mats are cats. All cats are rats.\nConclusions:\nI. Some cats are mats.\nII. All rats are mats.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Either conclusion I or conclusion II follows.','Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow.','1','Cats is a bigger set than mats and so, some cats are mats. So, conclusion I is right.\nRats is a bigger set than mats and so, only some rats are mats. So, conclusion II is wrong.','Easy'),(2266,21,'4','','Statements: Some goals are keepers. All runs are goals.\nConclusions:\nI. All runs are keepers.\nII. Some runs are keepers.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Either conclusion I or conclusion II follows.','3','All runs are goals. Only some goals are keepers. So, we cannot conclusively say that those goals which are runs are keepers. So, conclusion I is wrong.\nSecond conclusion is also not correct because all the runs may be goals which are not keepers.','Easy'),(2267,21,'4','','Statements: Some fans are lights. All tubes are lights. \nConclusions: \nI. All tubes being fans is a possibility. \nII. No tube is a fan.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Either conclusion I or conclusion II follows.','1','If we consider that the tubes is a subset of fans, then there is every chance that the two statements are still satisfied. So, conclusion I is right because of the inclusion of the word â€˜possibilityâ€™.\nSome fans which are charts can also be tubes. So conclusion II is wrong.','Easy'),(2268,21,'4','','Statements: All letters are phones. All phones are sticks.\nConclusions:\nI. All phones are letters.\nII. All letters are sticks.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Either conclusion I or conclusion II follows.','2','Phones is a bigger set than letters and so, conclusion I is NOT right.\nLetters is a subset of phones, which in turn is a subset of sticks. So, all letters will be sticks and conclusion II is right.','Easy'),(2269,21,'4','','Statements: All parabolas are circles. All ellipses are parabolas. No ellipse is a hyperbola. \nConclusions:\nI. Some parabolas being ellipses is a possibility.\nII. At least some hyperbolas are ellipses.','Only conclusion I follows.','Only conclusion II follows.','Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows.','Either conclusion I or conclusion II follows.','2','Ellipses is a subset of parabolas, which in turn is a subset of hyperbolas. Since no ellipse is a hyperbola, we can surely say that no parabola and no ellipse can be an ellipse. So, conclusion I is wrong, even when there is the word possibility.\nSince hyperbolas is a bigger set that includes ellipses, conclusion II will be true.','Medium');

